<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR TO SEEK DEATH PENALTY FOR DRAGGING DEATH OF CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Jackson County
prosecutor said Friday that he would seek the death penalty against
a Kansas City man charged the dragging death of a 6-year-old boy
last week in Independence.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prosecutor Bob Beaird's announcement came hours after a grand
jury upgraded charges against 34-year-old Kim L. Davis to include
first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week prosecutors charged Davis with second-degree murder in
the Feb. 22 death of Jake Robel. The boy was dragged after he
became entangled by a seat belt during the theft of his mother's
sport-utility vehicle. Since then, Beaird said, ``We have studied
all the files and I have personally talked to a number of
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's harshest murder charge fits, Beaird said.
</P>
<P>
   Second-degree murder provides for a life sentence; first-degree
murder is punishable by death or life without parole. It requires
proof that a killer acted with deliberation, defined as ``cool
reflection, no matter how brief.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the grand jury indicted Davis for first-degree
murder, along with second-degree robbery, kidnapping and armed
criminal action.
</P>
<P>
   The armed criminal action charge replaces an earlier count of
child abuse. It is based on the concept that Davis used the
sport-utility vehicle as a weapon to kill Jake.
</P>
<P>
   Davis pleaded not guilty in his previous arraignment. He is to
be arraigned on the grand jury charges on March 15. Beaird said he
would file grounds for the death penalty at that hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The case began just after Christy Robel of Independence parked
her Chevrolet Blazer in front of a sub shop at 3010 S. Missouri
291. She went into the eatery and left her keys in the ignition and
her son, Jake, strapped in a seat belt in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records:
</P>
<P>
   Davis tried to shove the boy from the Blazer before stealing it,
and Robel ran outside and tried to grab her son. Jake became
tangled in his seat belt outside the closed rear door, and Robel
screamed at Davis as he drove off with her son. Jake also screamed
as he died. Davis did not stop until motorists captured him after a
high-speed chase that covered five miles.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said the upgraded charges had nothing to do with tears he
shed at a previous news conference dealing with the case. That was
because he had met with the family just before the news briefing,
he said. He also met with them Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're caught in a terrible tragedy,'' Beaird said. ``If you
talk to them, it's pretty hard not to be moved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
