<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-CAMPAIGN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS 2000 LAUNCHES AD CAMPAIGN TO ENCOURAGE PARTICIPATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mom is a waitress
with no choice other than to bring her toddler to work at the
diner. He bothers the customers. The boss is not happy. A voice
intones:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Next year, billions of dollars will be spent for day care.
Will you get your share?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, the TV commercial implies, can be ``yes'' _ but only
if mom fills out her Census 2000 form.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the less subtle messages being beamed at
Americans as the government makes a glitzy $100 million media pitch
to increase participation in the Census.
</P>
<P>
   Many 30-second spots are airing in prime time to encourage
Americans to fill out the forms that will be mailed to 118 million
households beginning March 13. Census workers began delivering
forms to rural residents Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the Census has resorted to paid,
professional advertising, an effort to reverse a historical decline
in the number of people who mail the forms back.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 50 versions of the ads aimed at such
audiences as working moms, African-Americans, Hispanics and
American Indians. Languages include Spanish, Vietnamese, Polish and
even Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   The spots are slick and well-made. Most are warm and fuzzy, with
an emphasis on smiles, children and community. But the motivation
is self interest. The ads talk about education, health care and job
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top reason is, crudely stated, `What's in it for me?' ''
said Jennifer Marks, chief of the publicity office for Census 2000.
``Part of the message is: `Fill out the Census and you may get this
school or whatever. If you don't fill out the Census this is what
you'll get, which is nothing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The decennial Census is required by the Constitution and
determines Congressional district boundaries and therefore
political representation. But it also influences how and where $185
billion in federal money will be spent next year, as well as
countless millions by state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The ads were produced by a consortium headed by the Young &AMP;
Rubicam Inc. agency of New York, whose clients include AT&AMP;T, Ford
Motor Co. and the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Kirkpatrick of Kansas City's Bernstein-Rein advertising
agency, and a former employee of Young &AMP; Rubicam, was impressed by
the scope of the government's ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an incredible amount of production money being
spent,'' said Kirkpatrick, who is creative director for
Bernstein-Rein's Wal-Mart account. ``To do that volume of
commercials, I'd say is unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 the mail-in response rate to the Census was about 75
percent. By 1990 it had dropped to 65 percent, and there are fears
it could drop even lower this year.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau estimates each percentage point drop costs about $25
million in door-to-door follow-up by Census workers. So officials
are hoping the advertising investment will actually save money by
boosting mail response.
</P>
<P>
   In previous counts the Census Bureau relied upon free
advertising services, which meant spots on late-night TV or obscure
channels. A professional paid campaign is putting the ads in prime
time during popular network shows, sports events and on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Ads aimed at African-Americans emphasize empowerment. Ads aimed
at American Indians feature a powwow dance as the announcer urges
the audience ``to unite as one tribe.'' Ads aimed at
Asian-Americans promote close family relationships. A spot aimed at
a Puerto Rican audience depicts children playing musical chairs.
One boy appears left out, but is all smiles when he finds a place
to sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take is that it will have the (intended) effect and that
people will come away from this with a more positive feeling about
the Census,'' Kirkpatrick said after viewing a sampling of the ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The total Census ad budget of $167 million also includes radio,
print and outdoor advertising. Other venues include schools and
ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Brochures distributed in schools include activity sheets and
quizzes about the Census and are designed to deliver a message to
parents through their children. To allay fears, the brochures
underscore privacy by reminding that ``Not even the president of
the United States can find out your answers!''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball stars Barry Bonds of the San Francisco Giants, Derek
Jeter of the New York Yankees and Ivan Rodriguez of the Texas
Rangers taped public service announcements that will appear on TV
and scoreboards in most ballparks through May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to steal an extra base, meet a wall head-on or
stand against a 100 mph fastball,'' outfielder Bonds proclaimed in
one spot. ``So why should I be afraid to fill out the Census? Your
answers are confidential.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
