<SLUG> BC-BIRTH-PARENTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH MOM AND DAD ARE HOSPITALIZED AT BABY'S BIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ This may be the rare
case where having a baby was just as hard on Dad as it was on Mom.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the same time that Jonna Brandel of Overland Park, Kan., was
in labor Thursday night at Research Medical Center, her husband,
Joe, was two floors below her undergoing emergency surgery to
remove his appendix.
</P>
<P>
   Their medical adventures began that morning when Jonna went into
labor. The Brandels drove to Research but were told it was too soon
for Jonna to enter the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, while Jonna was having contractions, Joe, 30, was
having abdominal cramps. Friends he spoke to on the phone teased
him that he was having sympathy pains. But Joe's cramps turned out
to be more than psychosomatic. Thursday evening Jonna's parents,
John and Barbara Thompson of Kansas City, brought a chicken and
mashed potato dinner to their house. Jonna ate; Joe was too sick to
take a bite.
</P>
<P>
   Around 9:30 p.m., Joe was feeling so bad that he asked to be
taken to an emergency room. His father-in-law drove him to
Research. About a half-hour later, it was Jonna's turn. Her mother
drove her to Research.
</P>
<P>
   While Jonna was in labor, she received periodic reports from the
doctors about Joe's condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried,'' she said. ``But it was hard to pay attention.
I was preoccupied by what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Joe was out of surgery and ready to witness the
birth of their first child early Friday morning, the Brandels'
daughter, Jordan, was already born.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very disappointed,'' Jonna, 31, said Friday. ``They
brought him up as soon as possible, but the baby came fast. He said
he was sorry he missed the delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, mother and daughter were doing fine. And father?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of green and nauseous,'' Jonna said. ``He was asleep
most of the day'' _ in an adjoining room.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on their conditions, the Brandels plan to go home
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping,'' Jonna said, but Joe ``is the one in
question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
