<SLUG> BC-GOVERNORS-POLL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GOVERNOR'S RACE IS TOO CLOSE TO CALL, POLLS FIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Another statewide
race in Missouri, another dead heat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A poll commissioned by The Kansas City Star shows that the
governor's race is a tossup, with Republican Jim Talent leading
Democrat Bob Holden by 36 percent to 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's margin of error is plus or minus 4 points, meaning
the race is too close to call. The survey covered 628 registered
Missouri voters who said they voted regularly in state elections.
Calls were made Feb. 25 to 28.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, by Mason-Dixon Polling &AMP; Research Inc., revealed a
giant wild card: 30 percent of the voters had not made up their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many voters are not familiar with either candidate and remain
undecided,'' said J. Bradford Coker, Mason-Dixon's managing
director.
</P>
<P>
   In another poll this week, Mason-Dixon said Missouri's U.S.
Senate race between Republican John Ashcroft and Democrat Mel
Carnahan also was close. Ashcroft led 47 percent to 44 percent,
within the poll's margin of error. Nine percent were undecided, an
indication that Ashcroft and Carnahan, with their long public
careers in Missouri, are better known than Talent and Holden.
</P>
<P>
   In the governor's race, 21 percent said they knew nothing about
Talent, a four-term U.S. House member from St. Louis County. He sat
in the Missouri House from 1982 to 1992, serving as minority leader
his last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 29 percent of Missourians said they didn't recognize
Holden's name. A Kansas City native, he is the state treasurer and
served three terms in the Missouri House in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Talent, Michelle Dimarob, said another reason
for the high undecided quotient was the Senate race's high profile
in Missouri and nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of like the quiet, sleeping giant,'' she said of
the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   In the Holden camp, aide Richard Martin said the poll's results
did not surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew this would be a close race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that Talent held his biggest lead, 42 percent to
33 percent, in the St. Louis area.
</P>
<P>
   Holden's biggest edge was in the Springfield area, which he
represented in the House. Holden led 38 percent to 30 percent
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
