<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-FARM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS URGE AID IN THE LIMITING OF WHAT THEY CALL PRICE
DISCRIMINATION BY MEAT PROCESSORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two organizations
representing family farmers have called on U.S. Secretary of
Agriculture Dan Glickman to aggressively use his administrative
powers to limit what they call price discrimination by large
meat-processing companies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The request came during a news conference Friday at the Catholic
Chancery for the Diocese of Kansas City-St. Joseph. Members of
Catholic Charities also participated in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   John Crabtree, with the Center for Rural Affairs, said Glickman
could improve the situation by issuing administrative rules that
clearly defined what pricing practices were illegal. Crabtree said
he believed some processors' pricing violated the U.S. Packers and
Stockyards Act by paying independent producers less on the open
market than they pay for the same quality livestock from farmers
with whom they have contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Kremer, former president of the Missouri Farmers Union and
a hog farmer in Osage County, Mo., said that without such rules,
many small family livestock farmers would go out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Kremer pointed out that prices for hogs reached historic lows a
year ago. He lost about $70 a hog at those prices. Prices have
rebounded to about 38 cents a pound now, still only a break-even
price, he said. He said retail pork prices never reflected those
rock-bottom farm prices.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Agriculture Department said representatives
of the department had been communicating with the Center for Rural
Affairs and were looking at various possibilities to address its
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The general counsel for the American Meat Institute, a trade
organization of the meat-processing industry, said federal
legislation already spelled out what was legal and what was not in
pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act allows legal price discrimination for lots of reasons,
and buying volume is one reason to give somebody a different
price,'' said Mark Dott of the institute. ``In those circumstances
when the department thought the rules were not being followed, it
has brought a case. There is some current litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kremer pointed out that a bill had been introduced in the
Missouri General Assembly that would mirror the Packers and
Stockyards Act but allow the state to act against pricing
discrimination. He said it was hoped such state laws might pressure
the Agriculture Department or Congress to act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
