A6557 &Cx1f; kan-z
a k BC-GREENSPAN-OUTLOOK-KAN     03-04 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-OUTLOOK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED CHIEF'S OUTLOOK IS INEXPLICABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan made an odd observation when ruminating
recently on the economy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenspan implied that a recent surge in productivity was not an
altogether good thing because it tended to boost demand even more
than supply, and thus may be inflationary.
</P>
<P>
   By his reasoning, accelerating productivity drives stock prices
higher by feeding expectations of higher profits. Rising stock
prices enhance the ``wealth effect'' that supercharges consumers,
whose expanding net worth makes them want to buy more stuff.
</P>
<P>
   This view is odd for a couple of reasons. One of the first
things Econ 101 students learn is that rising productivity is an
unalloyed good. It's what makes economic growth possible without
the bugbear of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity has increased more than 3 percent annually the past
couple of years, which is remarkable given the maturity of the
expansion. More incredibly, productivity soared at a 5 percent
annual rate last quarter, and many economists expect this estimate
to be revised upward to 6 percent or higher next week.
</P>
<P>
   While many analysts would jubilantly claim this the best
economic news possible, Greenspan sees a dark lining in this silver
cloud, which may portend several more interest-rate increases by
the Fed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Another odd aspect of Greenspan's remarks is his apparent
perception of a rising stock market, which definitely isn't the
case. Even when the major indices were climbing last year, the
market's narrow leadership masked the fact that most stocks were in
the doldrums. While the Nasdaq is up so far this year, the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 and Dow Jones industrial average are listing badly.
The Dow's January-February swoon was one of its worst ever.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the stocks that still are rising are for the most
part the dot-com mania darlings that are impervious to the rate
increases the Fed is engineering in the name of cooling the stock
market. These companies use relatively little credit capital and
instead get most of their money from equity investors.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the confusing situation: The Fed chairman appears to
be one of the few economists in the world who perceives strong
productivity gains as a threat to society's well-being. In the name
of fighting an inflationary threat few others can discern, he wants
to halt the rise of stocks that really aren't rising while pushing
policies that won't affect the stocks whose prices are rising.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Join the club. None of this makes any sense, unless
Fed policy-makers responsible for tightening the screws are simply
looking to get even with market participants for not behaving as
the Fed wants them to behave. To be sure, these inexplicable
policies will continue to depress Old Economy stock prices and
eventually even bring the New Economy dot-com wonders back to
Earth. Meanwhile, the overall economy will slide inexorably into
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Expansions don't die of old age, it's said, but are killed by
policy miscalculations. Even as strong as the economy is, the Fed
certainly has the power to end this record run of prosperity.
That's a given. The compelling question at this point is whether
this is what the Fed really wants to do. And if so, why?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
