r s BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN     03-04 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S RUSH WON'T BE RUSHED BACK IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ JaRon Rush doesn't know exactly when he'll
play, how long he'll play or how well he'll play today at No.1
Stanford. But he knows after a 24-game, 84-day suspension, he's as
anxious as he is excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty excited, but I'm also pretty nervous,'' said Rush,
suspended Dec. 10 for violating NCAA rules. ``The team is starting
to play well, and I don't want to mess with the chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard. I had given up on the season. I thought I
wasn't coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush's reprieve came Monday when the NCAA appeals committee
reduced his 29-game suspension to nine games. He was on the Bruins'
bench Thursday night at Cal when they turned a 19-point deficit
into an 83-62 victory. He has no regrets about returning against
the nation's No.1 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to play calm,'' Rush said. ``There's no pressure
on me, and there's no pressure on the team. We're going against the
top-ranked team in the country. Everybody thinks they're going to
blow us out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins need Rush, who averaged 11.3 points and 4.7 rebounds
in three games before the suspension. They need his energy, they
need his tenacity, they need his fouls - especially against
Stanford's deep bench - and they need his rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll add more fire,'' forward Jason Kapono said. ``He plays
with great heart and passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Steve Lavin hasn't decided on Rush's role or his
playing time. He could play 10 minutes if the game is close or 20
if it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to stay with the regular rotation, which has been
irregular,'' Lavin said. ``I don't anticipate him being the first
or second guy off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way, he kind of blends in. He's not coming in with our
backs to the wall where he'd be seen as the savior. Things have
fallen in line, so his return is kind of ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Big swing: Lavin called Thursday's 19-point comeback the most
memorable since the Bruins rallied from 16 down to defeat Iowa
State in the 1997 Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 19 down, you still believe you have a chance,''
Lavin said. ``What we kept saying in the timeouts was we were
taking their best shot, but if we could whittle (the deficit) to 10
or below, we cold crawl back in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our energy at halftime was the best it's been all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Comeback II? Unlikely: Even the Bruins' best game might not be
enough to stay within single-digits of Stanford, which beat USC by
43 points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal has won 13 consecutive games by an average of 25.4
points, and it's on pace to set the NCAA record for field goal
defense. Opponents are shooting only 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a runaway, but it's very unlikely they'll let
youback in the game,'' Lavin said. ``We can't afford to dig a deep
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Stanford beat UCLA by 48 points, the worst loss
in school history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
