<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-REPUBLICAN-VOTERS-     03-04 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REPUBLICAN-VOTERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PRESIDENTIAL PRIMARY CHALLENGES LOYALTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add art advisory.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 36 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ko) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTCHESTER, N.Y. _ The Odyssey Diner here is one of those
old-fashioned political hangouts, where establishment pols, mostly
Republicans, gather at the counter or in a side room to hash things
out over the famous cheesecake and coffee courtesy of the affable
Doukases, who have run the place for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the stiff competition among the Republican candidates and
the approach of the New York primary on Tuesday have enlivened the
discourse here, even among the Doukas family. They unwittingly
served up an example of the split among Republican voters in this
336-year-old town of mansions and Cape Cod-style homes when it
comes to Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   George Doukas, the proprietor, scoffed at the televised face of
McCain as he spoke in a television news report while Doukas played
backgammon. Doukas firmly declared his commitment to Bush, aligning
himself with the county Republican establishment, including this
Westchester County town's supervisor, James Cavanaugh, who is the
newly anointed county party leader and a firm Bush man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bush has the better chance of winning,'' said Doukas,
65, who owns the diner with his family. ``He seems to have done a
good job in Texas and has a good record there.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as the Republican Party as a whole has not united
behind Bush, neither have the Doukases. Standing a few feet away at
the register, Doukas's wife, Angela, 61, just as firmly declared
her commitment to McCain, of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he lost in South Carolina he made that speech and what he
said stuck in my heart,'' she said. ``He said we will go forth, but
he congratulated Bush even though they fought so much. It just
showed what a strong gentleman he is.''
</P>
<P>
   While far from being a scientific sounding, 28 interviews with
registered Republicans over two days here and in the two
self-governing villages this town encompasses _ Tuckahoe and
Bronxville _ suggested an electorate tuned to the primary campaign
but sometimes ambivalent about the choices a few days before the
Tuesday primary.
</P>
<P>
   There was hope for McCain in people willing to buck the
conventional wisdom and even to risk domestic bliss for their man.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can take comfort, too, in the likes of Mr. Doukas and
William Carlson, a 69-year-old semiretired sales representative who
said he was turned off by reports of McCain's negative campaigning
by telephone. Besides, Carlson said, Bush stands firm on
conservative principles and served as governor of a large, ``tough
state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done a lot of good things in Texas,'' Carlson said.
``He has used the death penalty a lot, and I think we need more of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many people could articulate policy positions of the
candidate they favored. The more common requests of any candidate
were lower taxes, keep the economy cruising, do something to
improve access to health care, but few could explain what their
candidate might do to achieve such goals.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's post-New Hampshire primary surge entranced some who
otherwise would have supported Bush because he was so far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is still an open race,'' said Kevin Scully, an
Internet entrepreneur from Bronxville. ``I didn't think of McCain
before, when Bush was the primary candidate, but now I'm starting
to get serious about thinking of McCain. I'm still not able to
clearly get his message, but I will be paying more attention now.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin L. Cooperman, 53, a physiotherapist, said he thought Bush
was ``spending too much time attacking, and I don't like those
tactics.'' This comment came a day before the Bush campaign began
broadcasting radio advertisements and disseminating fliers
questioning McCain's record on financing for breast cancer
research.
</P>
<P>
   While favoring McCain, he said both candidates had disappointed
him by not fully explaining how they would improve the delivery of
health insurance, particularly for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman also said he would be tempted to vote Democratic in a
contest between Gore and Bush. He voted for President Clinton in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   How such sentiments will translate in the voting booth remains
anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanaugh, the party leader, acknowledged McCain's draw. ``I am
not the least bit dismissive of McCain's challenge,'' he said. ``He
is making a strong challenge, and there are people who are enamored
of him. I am not saying Bush has it in the bag. We all have to work
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   For the undecided and even those with a bent, the race could
hardly be described as the same-old, same-old. ``With all these
choices, it's hard to keep up,'' said Robert Frederick, a
38-year-old computer scientist who said he planned to spend the
next few days reading about the candidates before deciding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a fiscal conservative but sort of moderate on social
issues,'' Frederick said. ``Bush and McCain both say they are
fiscal conservatives, and it's hard to keep up on where they stand
on things like abortion, which I think they both oppose, but then
they may have said things like it's OK in certain cases, or
something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pro-choice and think the Democrats have done good with the
economy,'' he said. ``Where does that leave me?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 0015EST &QL; 
