<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NORTHEAST-SMOG-1STLD-     03-04 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHEAST-SMOG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT UPHOLDS EPA RULES TO REDUCE SMOG IN THE NORTHEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert 2 grafs, bgng More than ... after 6th graf to add
names of states affected)  
(ko) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what clean air advocates called a watershed ruling, a federal
appeals court on Friday upheld rules limiting pollution from
Midwestern states that causes unacceptable levels of smog in
Northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-to-1 ruling, a panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia Circuit in Washington upheld the Environmental
Protection Agency rule requiring the control of smog-causing
chemicals that move from several states, among them Indiana, Ohio
and West Virginia, to states like New York and parts of New
England. Coal-burning power plants are the primary source of one of
those chemicals, nitrogen oxide.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling limits the amount of nitrogen oxide that states can
emit into the atmosphere. In some cases, the new limit may require
power plants to reduce their emissions to one-quarter or one sixth
of what had been allowed, said Peter Lehner, chief of the
environmental protection bureau of the New York attorney general's
office. They can chose to limit emissions as they wish, but are
expected to focus on power plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision means that we again can move forward to bring
cleaner, healthier air to more than 138 million people living in
the eastern half of the United States,'' Carol Browner, the EPA's
administrator, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The agency had issued regulations on emissions in October 1998,
but their implementation was delayed by litigation over them.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations are expected to take effect by 2003 for some
plants and by 2005 for others. The rules originally applied to 22
states;  &UR; Fri &LR; day's ruling said further review was necessary to
determine how the regulations applied to Wisconsin, Missouri and
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the reductions in emissions would come in six
states: Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio, Pennsylvania and West
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to New York, the other states affected are Alabama,
Connecticut, Delaware, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts, New
Jersey, North Carolina, Rhode Island, South Carolina, Tennessee and
Virginia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The total amount of air pollution, especially in the summer,
will be dramatically less,'' Lehner said, predicting that people
would be able to notice reductions in smog and would see some
relief from asthma and other respiratory diseases, which are
worsened by air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   He said that while the current regulations focused on summertime
smog the controls might also be necessary in winter and that that
should reduce acid rain and particulate pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extraordinarily big step toward getting year-round
controls,'' he said. Many other lawsuits have been filed to control
year-round pollution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Hawkins, senior attorney at the Natural Resources Defense
Council, an environmental advocacy group involved in the suit, said
Ohio, one of the worst polluters, experienced a higher rate of
hospital admissions in smoggy periods than New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the states that are the biggest polluters of other
states are also the biggest polluters of their own citizens,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the lawyer representing the Midwest Ozone Group, a
coalition of utility and coal companies that fought the
regulations, were not returned last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a massive attack by industry on the EPA effort, but
the court upheld that effort, a joint effort by the EPA, many of
the states suffering from transporting pollution and environmental
organizations,'' Hawkins said. Judges Stephen Williams and Judith
Rogers sided with the EPA. Judge David Sentelle dissented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
