<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PINOCHET-1STLD-WRITET     03-04 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-780&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED EMOTIONS IN CHILE AS PINOCHET RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert `muted' in lede graf.)  
(js) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Gen. Augusto Pinochet received a muted hero's
welcome from the Chilean military high command as he returned home
Friday from his long exile and house arrest in London to salutes,
brassy martial music and a low flying air force helicopter
entourage.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of Chilean society displayed its lingering
divisions, as thousands of detractors and supporters took to the
streets of Santiago in competing demonstrations that vented the
political hatreds of the past.
</P>
<P>
   After a 16-month legal tug-of-war, Britain dropped extradition
proceedings against the 84-year-old former dictator on Thursday,
saying he was too ill to face charges for human rights violations
during his 17-year rule of Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of people who disappeared under Pinochet's regime
cried again for their lost loved ones in candle-lit vigils.
Thousands of others rallied to hail the man they say saved Chile
from civil war and the clutches of communism. And while no serious
violence and few arrests were reported, it was hardly a day of
reconciliation. Parts of Santiago looked as if they were under
siege, with police on patrol in armored trucks mounted with water
canon.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet spent his first day back in Chile in Santiago's
Military Hospital, where he underwent medical tests while
sharpshooters were stationed on the building's roof. Local
newspaper and television reports suggested on Friday that he may
spend much of the next several days in the hospital or in seclusion
in army facilities or his Santiago residence. He is expected to
keep a low profile at least through the March 11 presidential
inauguration of Ricardo Lagos, the first Socialist party member to
hold the presidency since Pinochet's overthrow of Salvador Allende
in a violent 1973 coup.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Christian Democratic-Socialist coalition
government and the military high command are discussing ways to
avert demonstrations by pro- or anti-Pinochet demonstrators at the
inaugural festivities. Pinochet apparently has not been involved in
the talks, which reportedly included discussions of how to remove
the former dictator from his position as senator for life in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be improper to organize this as if it were a party,''
Interior Minister Raul Troncoso told reporters, straining to
explain the ambiguities surrounding his government's attitude
toward Pinochet's return..
</P>
<P>
   Chile's uneasy, decade-long transition to civilian democracy was
on display even before the Chilean air force aircraft that brought
Pinochet home touched the ground Friday morning. The military
ordered journalists removed from the arrival area, until President
Eduardo Frei personally intervened by calling Gen. Ricardo
Izurieta, chief commander of the army, to complain that Chile's
democratic image would be sullied by the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   There were no speeches at the arrival ceremony, which was open
only to 450 family members, friends and former senior officials who
served in Pinochet's Cabinet. The politicians who attended went to
pains to say they had come as personal friends and not as
representatives of their political parties.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet smiled and nodded in gratitude as he was received with
a warm hug by Izurieta, who replaced the former dictator as head of
the army in 1998. Then, as a 50-member military band played several
scores said to be the former dictator's favorites, all the
commanders of the armed forces personally greeted him on the
airport tarmac before a national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Television commentators expressed surprise that Pinochet looked
as fit as he did in his pressed blue suit, white shirt and violet
tie as he walked to a helicopter with the help of a cane. The
general had been released by British Home Secretary Jack Straw on
the grounds that he was mentally and physically unfit to stand
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinochet is in perfect shape as anyone can see,'' complained
Mireya Garcia, secretary-general of the Family Members of the
Disappeared, as she and 1,500 other human rights activists marched
outside the La Moneda presidential palace Friday. ``All humanity
should feel cheated by this sham.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a fleet of helicopters escorted Pinochet to the
hospital, flying low through the smoggy skies, traffic halted as
pedestrians and drivers sought to witness the historic arrival.
Office workers scurried from their desks to balconies and windows,
and more than 5,000 people waving Chilean flags and banners
declaring the general the country's savior gathered around the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my greatest happiness,'' said Lucia Varas, a
69-year-old housewife, who carried a poster emblazoned with
Pinochet's portrait in full military uniform. ``He brought us
tranquility and progress. His kidnapping defamed our sovereignty.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When a few young Communist Party activists taunted the crowd
outside the hospital on Avenida Providencia, dozens of young
Pinochet supporters began running toward them and screamed: ``Kill
them, Kill them. Throw out the pigs.'' Some plastic water bottles
were thrown before the police broke up the melee.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, 1,500 human rights activists and leftist protesters
carrying pictures of people who were executed and disappeared
during the Pinochet rule marched from the presidential palace
through downtown Santiago to the central court building. There they
called for the removal of Pinochet's senatorial immunity so he can
stand trial on charges of torture and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assassins, assassins,'' they chanted, as they stopped a few
minutes in front of the executive offices of the army and navy,
pointing their fingers and shaking their fists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel nothing but indignation and bitterness,'' said Monica
Monsalve, the 30-year-old daughter of a railroad labor leader who
was executed in 1973. ``We were so hopeful there would be justice
for all the victims.'' As her voice trailed off, she added, ``Maybe
we can still get some justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty criminal complaints have been filed against Pinochet in
Chilean courts, but appeals and counter-appeals are likely to take
months if not years before he can ever stand trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
