<HEADER>
A6590 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-TEX     03-04 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS CHANGE THEIR FOCUS AFTER BEATING COYOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For most of this season, the Stars chased the Phoenix
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed them in the Pacific Division until after the
All-Star break, when they led them. But it always has been the
Coyotes they compared themselves with.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-1 come-from-behind victory against Phoenix last night at
America West Arena mightjust have changed the object of their
pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can catch St. Louis,'' Stars winger Grant Marshall said of
the Western Conference-leading Blues. ``We can catch any team if we
play the way we're capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory did more than extend the Stars' lead in the division
to seven points. The victory positioned them nine points behind St.
Louis and only three behind Detroit for the second-best record in
the West. They have a chance to further trim that with the Red
Wings in town tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the 80s now point-wise and there areother teams in
the 80s now, too,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We've spent
the whole season looking behind us. ... Maybe, we can start looking
ahead a little bit now and chasing other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of last night, the Stars were chasing the pace of the
game. The Coyotes led 1-0 through two periods, although that
eventually meant absolutely nothing. Phoenix has allowed 33 goals
in their past 10 games, with 18 of those coming in the third
period. The Coyotes coughed up four third-period goals on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the guys were talking about it, I didn't hear it,'' Stars
center Aaron Gavey said.
</P>
<P>
   The talk in the locker room was score one early, and Marshall
accommodated, taking a pass from Gavey and going five-hole on
Coyotes backup Bob Essensa 85 seconds in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the next goal of the game was real crucial for us,''
Stars center Mike Modano said. ``You go down 2-0 it's a different
game. But 1-1, boom, boom we score two more quick ones like we did
in Detroit and we took the wind out of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall got them started. Modano kept them going.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock juggled his lines betweeen periods, double shifting
Modano. He responded by assisting on the Stars final three goals,
including Langenbrunner's game winner at 6:36 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey made it 3-1 at 9:27, a pretty wrist shot that went top
shelf on Essensa.
</P>
<P>
   And Brenden Morrow sent most of the crowd of 15,840 to the exits
when he scored at 11:07 to make it 4-1. The Stars threw 19 shots at
the Coyotes in the third period, after getting 17 in the first two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as the third goes on I feel I guess stronger and I
feel better as the opportunities increase a little bit,'' Modano
said.
</P>
<P>
   The four-goal third period wasn't even the Stars biggest at
America West Arena this season.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, the Stars scored five third-period goals for a 6-4
come-from-behind victory. The victory last night gave the Stars a
season sweep in Phoenix this season. Not to mention a stranglehold
on the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock said it's a hard game to make assumptions on
because of who was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were missing key players. The Coyotes were without
winger Keith Tkachuk (ankle), center Jeremy Roenick (flu),
defenseman Teppo Numminen (hip) and goalie Sean Burke (groin). The
Stars were without defensemen Richard Matvichuk (hamstring) and
Sylvain Cote (emergency), along with center Joe Nieuwendyk
(shoulder) and winger Jere Lehtinen (ankle).
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes took a 1-0 lead at 4:11 of the second period on a
goal by Mike Alatalo. They came within a split second of making it
2-0 nine minutes later. Phoenix winger Dallas Drake tipped the puck
into the empty net, but the referee waved the goal off because the
whistle had already blown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two periods I don't even know if the white team was
even out there,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody had to guess whether they were in the third when the
Stars effectively stopped playing with the Coyotes and started
playing with the Blues and Red Wings. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
