<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CELTICS-RAPTORS-BOS     03-04 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-RAPTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS FALL TO RAPTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Add two more names to the list of people who don't
view the Celtics in a positive light: referees Joe Crawford and Jim
Kinsey. The men in green may have left the city of negativity, but
their luck didn't change north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they discovered that the sight of officials signaling
technical fouls offends the senses just as much as a chorus of
FleetCenter boos and the sound of constant criticism. Friday night
at the Air Canada Centre, a tough work week on the court and in
postgame press conferences ended with the ejections of coach Rick
Pitino and Antoine Walker.
</P>
<P>
   As the Celtics' most vocal supporter (Pitino) and leading scorer
(Walker) spent the final quarter in the visitors' locker room, the
chances for a comeback dimmed. Although the Celtics pulled within 5
(100-95) with 4 minutes 12 seconds remaining, they lost to the
Raptors, 114-104. The site of the Celtics' season-opening triumph
became just another disappointing stop on the team's slow, sub-.500
march to the end of the season. The loss extended the Celtics'
losing streak to four and pushed them 12 games below .500. Even
keep-the-encouragement-coming Pitino sounded resigned to the
Celtics' fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 20 years, my friends have kidded me about how
lucky I am,'' said Pitino. ``I guess my luck has run out when
Muggsy Bogues goes 4 for 4 from the 3-point line. But I liked the
way our guys hung in there and hustled. It wasn't a great game for
a few of our players, but the other guys picked it up and gave it
their all.''
</P>
<P>
   Practicing what he preaches, Pitino was full of positive
reinforcement for his players as he paced the sideline. The Celtics
entered halftime trailing by 7 (57-50) but did not give up as they
struggled to keep the Raptors' lead under 10 during the third. When
two Walker free throws brought the Celtics within 9 (80-71) with
1:38 left in the third, Pitino shouted ``Here we go, Celts. Here we
go.''
</P>
<P>
   But the enthusiasm and Pitino's sideline presence did not last
long. As the final minute ticked off the clock, Pitino was assessed
two technicals and tossed from the game by Kinsey. The coach had
argued that Kenny Anderson was tripped by Bogues as he was handling
the ball late in the third. (``You don't fall by osmosis.'') The
point guard went down and turned over the ball, allowing Dell Curry
to convert on the other end. Pitino felt he deserved the technical,
but not the ejection.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the fourth quarter started, Boston trailed by 13
(86-73). And it was not long before Walker joined his coach.
Fighting for a defensive rebound, Walker felt Kevin Willis went
over his back and deserved a foul. The forward took his case up
with the Crawford and lost. The referee served up two technicals
and a second Celtic ejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to take (the ejection) personally,'' said
Walker. ``Maybe he wanted to kick somebody out and he picked me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino and Walker stuck around long enough to watch Bogues
tie a career high with 24 points (6 for 6 from the floor), Vince
Carter chip in 30, and Tracy McGrady prove his worth with a
24-point, 3-block, 2-steal performance. With McGrady, Carter,
Bogues, and a well-executed half-court offense (29 team assists),
the Raptors never trailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's positive to go out of town with the wins we got, rather
than the team struggling,'' said Toronto coach Butch Carter, whose
team starts a five-game West Coast trip Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Watching his team play ineffectively in the first quarter,
Pitino inserted the second unit. After falling behind early in the
opening stanza and taking a 12-point deficit into the second
quarter, Boston turned its fortunes around behind the play of
substitutes Tony Battie, Eric Williams, and Doug Overton. In the
first three minutes, the Celtics went on an 11-2 run to cut the
lead to 3. Battie contributed a basket and a steal to the run, and
Williams added 3 points and a blocked shot.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the second period, the Celtics cut the lead to 1.
First, a 3-pointer by Williams brought the Celtics nearly even
(46-45). Then, a dunk by Battie narrowed the margin to 48-47 with
4:29 left. The Boston bench outscored the starters, 34-16, in the
first half, but despite battling after intermission, it wasn't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Williams finished with a season-high 22 points to lead the
Celtics, while Anderson dropped in 17. Danny Fortson started and
produced a double-double with 11 points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   And despite two technicals, an ejection, and the loss, Pitino
remained positive as he headed back to the city of negativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love our attitude,'' said Pitino. ``I just think we really
have to go to work in the summertime. The summer can't be
Margaritaville. The attitude, the team chemistry, the team values
are all there, but we've got to go to work on our games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
