<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, March 4.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 9 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VIGILANTE (Yekaterinburg, Russia) _ Here at the
crossroads of Asia and Europe, the supply lines of opium and heroin
out of Central and South Asia run into big population centers near
the frontier of the drug trade. A group of tough guys who have
organized themselves as a foundation called City Without Drugs, are
leading a brutal civic campaign to take the streets of
Yekaterinburg back from the drug dealers and the corrupt police who
are widely believed to be protecting them. By Patrick Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-CRIME-RATES (New York) _ With the city's stunning drop in
crime in the 1990s, many New Yorkers have come to assume that
aggressive police tactics and crime reductions are inextricably
linked. But a look at other cities suggests that large reductions
in crime can be achieved with less reliance on the kinds of
confrontational law enforcement measures New York has used. Some
cities, notably San Diego and Boston, have recorded as big or even
larger drops in violence through strategies that rely on close
cooperation between the police and the community. By Fox
Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ It is really quite impressive, all
this outrage about the anti-Catholic views of Bob Jones University.
Until campaign workers for Sen. John McCain began alerting
Michigan's Roman Catholics three weeks ago, it is questionable
whether there were enough Roman Catholics upset by anything
emanating from Bob Jones University to fill an old-fashioned
confessional. By Peter Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EASTCHESTER, N.Y. _ The Odyssey Diner here is one of those
old-fashioned political hangouts, where establishment pols, mostly
Republicans, gather at the counter or in a side room to hash things
out over the famous cheesecake and coffee courtesy of the affable
Doukases, who have run the place for 27 years. But the stiff
competition among the Republican candidates and the approach of the
New York primary on Tuesday have enlivened the discourse here, even
among the Doukas family. They unwittingly served up an example of
the split among Republican voters in this 336-year-old town of
mansions and Cape Cod-style homes when it comes to Gov. George W.
Bush and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 38 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-SENATE (Washington) _ At one level, John McCain has been
a model of conservative Republican orthodoxy in his 13 years in the
Senate, with a voting record close to that of Jesse Helms, who sets
the standard for Senate conservatives. McCain's career gets an 85
from the American Conservative Union, a 9 from the liberal
Americans for Democratic Action and an 89 from the National Right
to Life Committee. Helms, the dean of Senate conservatives, gets 99
from the ACU, 3 from the ADA and 99 from Right to Life. But a
Senate career is more than just showing up to vote. And a review of
McCain's record shows that, by subtler measures, his interests,
even passions, are hardly ideological. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 34 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ After a series of twists in their
favor, Republicans have improved their chances of keeping control
of the House in this year's elections, according to party leaders,
analysts and strategists from both parties. The defection of one
House Democrat, the decision of another to retire from his swing
district and the fact that fewer Republican seats will be as tough
to defend as anticipated have all contributed to the Republican
turnaround. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
