<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NBA-WORLD (Paris) _ After the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, when
millions of non-Americans were hypnotized by the artistry of Magic
Johnson, Michael Jordan and the rest of the Dream Team, the
National Basketball Association started pushing harder to make its
logo, and the superstars that populate its universe, household
images worldwide. By and large, it has succeeded. But if the NBA is
hurting a bit on the home court, many assumptions about global
growth have been cast into doubt, too. Sales of jerseys, balls and
backboards are flat, as is television audience growth, and
magazines about the NBA draw fewer readers than they used to. There
is no crisis, but the figures partly reflect the impact of the
owners' lockout that canceled 464 games last season, and they also
underscore the challenge of keeping fans who are an ocean apart
from spending their sports money elsewhere. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MACHINES-HUMANS (Undated) _ Recent advances in airplane design
have energized a debate among designers and industrial
psychologists about how machines should relate to their human
operators. Two different approaches _ one that is fully automated,
the other that relies on human judgment _ illustrate the knotty
issues facing researchers and designers in a variety of fields.
Highly automated machines now automatically administer drugs to
hospital patients, produce sophisticated semiconductors and operate
complex power plants, transforming technicians from machine
operators into supervisory controllers. How the human masters are
best kept ``in the loop'' so they know what the machines are doing
will ultimately affect hundreds of millions of people's lives. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
