<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PHILIPMORRIS-1ST     03-04 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PHILIPMORRIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STRATEGY AT PHILIP MORRIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to make `disease' plural in 2nd sentence.)  
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, March 4:
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, the nation's largest cigarette maker, is battling
to rehabilitate its image as part of a pariah industry. After
decades of denials, Philip Morris publicly admitted last fall that
smoking is addictive and causes cancer and other fatal diseases.
This week Steven Parrish, a senior vice president of Philip Morris,
said the company was willing to discuss some federal regulation of
tobacco. Parrish also expressed his belief, at a conference
sponsored by the National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse,
that nicotine is an addictive drug, although not a drug as defined
by the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act.
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason to be deeply skeptical of Philip Morris'
new stance. After all, the tobacco industry has long been
duplicitous while fighting to maintain its right to sell a
dangerous product. But that longstanding strategy may be crumbling
under the pressure of public denunciations and new legal threats
against the cigarette manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to rule this spring on whether the
Food and Drug Administration has regulatory authority over tobacco
under the existing federal act. Meanwhile, a Florida jury is
expected soon to decide punitive damages against the industry in a
class-action lawsuit brought on behalf of injured smokers.
Regardless of how either case is resolved, Philip Morris and other
tobacco companies will remain under intense political and
litigation pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris' shift may reflect a pragmatic judgment that it
will eventually have to accept some form of regulation and that
opening the door to negotiations now could produce a better outcome
for the company than total resistance. The company says it is
willing to work with federal regulators to define and develop a
``safer'' cigarette, remove harmful ingredients from cigarettes and
keep tobacco out of the hands of teen-agers, even if that means
fewer adults smoke in the future. But the company remains
deliberately vague about the kinds of regulations and enforcement
it will accept.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some things are changing. The company is no longer trying
to get immunity against civil lawsuits in exchange for regulation,
as was part of a 1997 proposed deal with the state attorneys
general. It is clearly worried that mounting public anger will lead
to tighter marketing restrictions, even for adults. Now that Philip
Morris is willing to talk, those concerned about the death toll
from smoking need to press Congress vigorously to give the FDA
unquestioned authority over tobacco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
