<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TUITION-1STLD-WR     03-04 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TUITION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SKEWED TUITION TAX BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite 3rd graf for syntax.)  
(DW) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, March 4:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved an unfair education bill this week that
would give tax breaks mostly to upper-income families with children
in private schools. President Clinton vetoed a similar proposal in
1998, and he should veto this legislation when it reaches his desk.
The centerpiece of the bill, introduced by Sens. Paul Coverdell,
R-Georgia, and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., would allow families with
annual incomes of up to $150,000 to deposit up to $2,000 a year per
child in after-tax dollars into education savings accounts. The
interest earned on the accounts would be tax-free, and the money
could be used to pay for private school tuition and other
educational expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The current law allows families to set aside up to $500 a year
per child, but limits the use of the money to college costs. An
expansion to $2,000 that would include elementary and secondary
school costs would largely give affluent families a federal subsidy
for tuition they already currently pay.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme is estimated to cost the federal government $1.2
billion over five years, yet little of that would benefit
low-income families, which are not likely to have the money to set
aside and would receive a minimal tax break even if they did.
</P>
<P>
   This measure would siphon off federal revenue that could be
better spent improving public schools that educate 90 percent of
American students. It does not reduce class sizes or improve
teacher quality. Nor would it offer meaningful aid to low-income
students who might want to attend private schools, since the
subsidy is too small to cover full tuition expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders, who contend that education is one of
their top priorities, pushed hard for this idea because it is
relatively inexpensive. But it is still a wasteful tax giveaway
that offers no educational benefits and should be rejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
