<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-REW     03-04 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORRY SPARKS LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The campaign started a tad late, and wouldn't you
know it, the debates are over, and those CNN trucks have already
packed up and left downtown L.A. Is it too late for Robert Horry to
declare his candidacy?
</P>
<P>
   For sixth man of the year, if nothing else?
</P>
<P>
   It could be a hard sell in a deep field, but Horry's late push
merits at least a few ``ayes'' at the party convention.
</P>
<P>
   For certain, he could have won a popularity vote Friday night at
Staples Center, as he played a key role in the Los Angeles Lakers'
107-92 rout of the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal led the way with 31 points, and Kobe Bryant
pitched in 22, but it was Horry whose 14-point burst provided the
needed cushion to push the Lakers' winning streak to 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great for us,'' Bryant said of Horry's hot play the
last few weeks. ``Like I've said, I think Robert's the key to this
team, because he does so many things for us, defensively, and
offensively when he's hitting his shots, keeping the floor spread.
It keeps our bench in attack mode.''
</P>
<P>
   That was clear as Horry made his first five shots of the night,
scored 12 points in the second quarter alone and completed his
usual potpourri of contributions with four assists, four rebounds
and a big blocked shot of Austin Croshere in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   All that, and several scraps for loose balls, produced a
familiar, yet new cheer among the home crowd: ``Hor-ry!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't count, because they didn't do it like they used to
to do with Eddie (Jones). They didn't get as loud,'' Horry joked.
``But I appreciate when fans realize you're having a good game,
they acknowledge you, and I'm happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the Lakers, who won their eighth in a row at home,
maintained their 1-game lead over Portland and avenged a January
loss to the Pacers, who snapped their previous 16-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson has often said Horry could be the Lakers' key
man off the bench, but his game went wayward in January after
breaking his nose and playing with an awkward plastic mask. Jackson
said he had to ``nurse'' Horry through that period, but he's been
their best bench performer during the current winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert played real well,'' Jackson said. ``When you have a
player that brings attack or ability to score from the outside at
that position, in this offense it means you have to play the whole
floor, and you don't have a place to help from (defensively). And
that makes it even more valuable for Shaq, to have that spacing out
there. It makes the whole offense kind of click a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, with the No. 1 winning percentage in the NBA, have
now beaten the second (Portland) and third (Indiana) teams in the
same week. And in both cases, it took a big bench effort to
compensate for an off night by O'Neal (13 for 28 on Friday) and
Glen Rice (3 for 10, eight points).
</P>
<P>
   This one was put away surprisingly early. A 15-0 first-quarter
run gave the Lakers a lead they never relinquished, and they took a
56-39 lead by halftime, capitalizing on 11 Pacers turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana never recovered, as Reggie Miller went just 7 for 17 (22
points), and Jalen Rose 4 for 15 (3 points). The Pacers shot just
39.5 percent against a stiff Lakers defense.
</P>
<P>
   Horry helped there too. But about that key-to-the-team stuff ...
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jackson) has been saying that ever since day one,'' Horry
said. `I appreciate the vote of confidence, but I don't want that
pressure on me. I think the whole team is the key, not just one
player.''
</P>
<P>
   So forget that sixth-man-of-the-year candidacy too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let a couple good games make y'all put me somewhere that
I don't need to be right now, you know what I'm saying?'' Horry
said of the suggestion. ``I'm just going and doing what I need to
do. ... I'm just trying to play a little bit aggressive. My
confidence was never gone, even though they weren't falling. You've
got to still shoot the ball, and that's just the way I've been
playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 0248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
