<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6632 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CHILE-U.S.-REVIEW-NYT     03-04 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-U.S.-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S STILL A LOT TO LEARN ABOUT THE PINOCHET YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(EDS: Please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets) 
(bl) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as a jet whisked Gen. Augusto Pinochet home to Chile last
week from Britain, ending the prospect of his trial in a foreign
land, a determined alliance of human rights advocates and victims
of his military regime redoubled their efforts to gather new
details of atrocities committed when he ruled Chile in the 1970s
and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt goes on wherever his junta's victims are scattered _ in
Chile, the United States, Spain and elsewhere _ accelerated by the
Internet. The general's critics in Chile feel that large gaps still
exist in what is known about the Pinochet years, and that filling
them represents the key to achieving reconciliation and redemption
for their country's reconstituted democracy.
</P>
<P>
   With the general now home, each new fact to emerge also gives
hope to critics who want to place him in the dock in Chile; to do
that, they will have to get an appeals court to revoke an immunity
granted when he stepped down as president in 1990. For Americans,
the Chileans' quest does something else: it raises questions about
one of the largest gaps in knowledge, involving America's own role
in the Pinochet years.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton has launched an ambitious
project to declassify U.S. records relating to abuses during the
Pinochet era. For more than a year, U.S. government agencies that
worked with Chile have been reviewing their files and slowly
revealing the degree of U.S. knowledge about the contours and
gruesome details of the machinery that killed democracy for a
generation of Chileans. So far, 6,900 documents have been released
and can be seen on the Internet (www.state.gov/foia); thousands
more are due in June.
</P>
<P>
   The broad outlines of U.S. efforts to oust Chile's Socialist
president, Salvador Allende, emerged in Senate intelligence
committee hearings in the 1970s, but the full extent of U.S.
involvement with the junta that replaced him in a 1973 coup remains
shrouded in secrecy. A number of the documents now surfacing were
released in earlier years, but in a form so heavily censored that
their meanings were distorted.
</P>
<P>
   A handful describe Operation Condor, a plan by U.S.-backed
military regimes in Chile, Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay, Brazil and
Bolivia to track down and kill leftists, union organizers and
opposition figures. Others describe campaigns of state terror and
the arrest of thousands of political activists. One State
Department cable forwards a request from the Chilean military days
after it seized power, seeking somebody who could help set up
concentration camps for political prisoners. (Washington sent
blankets instead.)
</P>
<P>
   A declassified Defense Intelligence Agency report describes how
Chilean agents created public fear to win support for the junta's
brutality: intelligence agents took hostages and kidnapped an
extreme rightist, and a far-right group that once received funds
from the CIA planted bombs and blamed Marxists.
</P>
<P>
   Among these documents are two internal State Department
inquiries in 1976 that blame Chile's military for the deaths of two
Americans, Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi, who were arrested and
executed. The inquiries suggest a possible CIA role in the slaying
of Horman, which was dramatized in the 1982 movie ``Missing.'' The
CIA has not released its records on the killings, saying it will do
so in June, but strongly denies responsibility for Horman's death.
</P>
<P>
   Another document the State Department declassified, titled
``Declaration of an Agent of the DINA'' (the most feared branch of
the secret police), is a confession by a government killer, Juan
Rene Munoz Alarcon. It details the location of mass graves for
leftists _ 345 people at two spots in Santiago, another 112 at
Colonia Dignidad, a secretive German colony in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz also describes the workings of a death squad, naming the
artillery captain who heads it, and its cooperation with security
services in Argentina and Uruguay to hunt down leftist activists _
``all of it permitted by the president of the republic, who is the
direct chief of this entire area.'' He names CIA officials in
Santiago, saying they were ``very important.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his wrenching confession, Munoz says he knows his
honesty will cost him his life, and in a note at the bottom we
learn that he was indeed assassinated two months later.
</P>
<P>
   One 1978 memo from Robert Pastor, a National Security Council
official in the Carter administration, to Zbigniew Brzezinski, then
head of the National Security Council, involves an investigation
into the killing in 1976 of Chile's former defense minister,
Orlando Letelier, and Ronni Moffitt, his American aide, in
Washington in a three-country operation attributed to Condor.
</P>
<P>
   The memo quotes George Landau, then the U.S. ambassador to
Chile, as saying there was no way the colonel who orchestrated the
killing would have done so without informing Pinochet, ``with whom
he had breakfast almost every single day.''
</P>
<P>
   If such pages from Chile's grim past are important to Chile's
victims, they also hold lessons for Americans: Facing questions in
Congress about the assassinations, Pastor notes that Landau had
spoken to ``many people in the State Department'' and was
``prepared to offer a sanitized version of this to Senator ((Edward
M.)) Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the years, the secrecy suggested by Landau's offer to
``sanitize'' the truth has not completely ended. While the State
Department has been the most forthcoming in releasing its records,
other agencies have held out. Key files remain classified,
including CIA documents on Horman and the agency; FBI and Defense
Department documents on Teruggi, and many records about Letelier
case.
</P>
<P>
   Another gap in the public record involves Henry Kissinger, the
impresario of foreign policy in the Nixon and Ford years. He has
declared his papers personal and had them sealed until five years
after his death.
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Archive, a group that has pressed to open
the Chile files, has listed scores of documents not yet made public
on covert efforts to foment a coup while Allende was in office.
Hundreds more, including 175 cables sent from Santiago to
Washington the day after the coup in which Allende died, were sent
by President Richard M. Nixon's' library to the review panel, but
have not been made public. Peter Kornbluh of the National Security
Archive and others argue that given the long history of
Washington's support for Latin American militaries, Americans need
to understand what happened in Chile. ``It's really about the
American public's right to know what was done in their name,
without their knowledge,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-CHILE-U.S.-REVIEW-NYT     03-04 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-U.S.-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S STILL A LOT TO LEARN ABOUT THE PINOCHET YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(EDS: Please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets) 
(bl) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
