</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICS-POLITICS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXING GOD AND POLITICS AND GETTING BURNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forty years and 10 presidential elections ago, John
F. Kennedy felt compelled to journey to a hostile conference of
Protestant church leaders in Houston to plead that he would never
serve as a vassal of the pope if he were elected the nation's first
Catholic president.
</P>
<P>
   It was an ignominious moment for many of Kennedy's fellow
American Catholics as the candidate, a decorated war veteran, had
to pass Protestant muster and deal with the dregs of
anti-immigrant, anti-Catholic bigotry rooted in the nativist
prejudices of the 19th century Know-Nothing movement, when native
born Protestants demanded voting, citizenship and education curbs
on the alarming waves of Catholic immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In weathering the fire and winning the election, Kennedy gently
cautioned the nation to oppose any attempt to distort the
presidency by ``making it an instrument of one religious group.''
His words survive as a prescription for all the nimble campaigners
who have followed him through the risky, often treacherous field
where politics and religion overlap.
</P>
<P>
   This year, spurred by an unexpectedly contentious Republican
primary, the nation is witnessing a 180-degree turn on the historic
Kennedy confrontation. This time, it is a worried Protestant
candidate from Texas, Gov. George W. Bush, who is now daily seeking
out Catholic forums and photo ops, replete with church banners and
