not be an instrument of a dominant religious group _ evangelical
Protestantism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that a neat little parallel _ a nervous George Bush
trying to reassure Catholics?'' observed Kate O'Beirne, the
Washington editor for The National Review. She is less amused by
Sen. John McCain's wielding of the religion issue in his
tooth-and-claw nomination struggle with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rare Catholic who even cares about Bob Jones
University,'' O'Beirne said of the South Carolina evangelical
college that McCain has strategically lambasted as an anti-Catholic
bastion happily visited by Bush. ``It's shameless Catholic
baiting,'' said O'Beirne, predicting a backlash of sorts against
McCain among the significant blocs of Catholic voters expected to
turn out this week in the mammoth Super Tuesday primary showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Whether McCain wins or loses, it is clear he has let a
red-white-and-blue genie out of the bottle and its recorking seems
unlikely during the general election campaign this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, fairly leering in delight, are recording every sling
and arrow exchanged in the Republican primary. And for good reason.
It was only six years ago that the Newt Gingrich revolution in the
House alarmed Democrats with the fact that a Catholic majority of
voters had shifted for the first time in decades from Democrats to
Republicans on the House ballot. Before that, Catholics had split
their ticket, voting, say, for President Ronald Reagan but then
returning to their lunch-pail party roots.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans' painful disarray over the role of the
religious right _ a bloc that Reagan first tucked masterfully into
the GOP fold _ is giving Capitol Hill Democrats new hope. In the
House, the McCain attack has caused Democrats to revive an earlier,
largely overlooked flap in which charges of anti-Catholicism marred
a bipartisan attempt to choose a new chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Democrats, hoping to sting Republicans in open
floor debate, quickly offered broadside resolutions condemning Bob
Jones University as segregationist and _ 40 years after Kennedy _
even anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one question of value that will outlast the
primaries,'' promised Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who runs his
party's Senate political operation. ``People are going to want to
be heard on this, the possible alienation of Catholics just when
many thought they were part of the Establishment,'' the senator
added, contending that Bush would be tarred with the issue into the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, think that McCain ``went one day too far'' with
his attack, in the words of Scott Appleby, a history professor at
Notre Dame University. He noted that McCain used the word ``evil''
in a follow-up attack on the Rev. Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson,
two politico-evangelical stalwarts, but then quickly had to retract
it.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby, the director of the Cushwa Center for the Study of
American Catholicism, feels McCain ``is failing to tap into a
deeper level'' of Catholic fear that is more a relic of history
than descriptive of modern Catholics, who are not monolithic voters
unless faced by an appalling instance of anti-Catholic bigotry.
Bush just does not fill the bill, Appleby thinks.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, too, that it was only after McCain was
defeated in South Carolina and headed for states with broader, more
diverse voter blocs, that he threw down the religious glove and
singled out Robertson and Falwell as ``agents of intolerance,''
betting that the muscle of the religious right has withered since
Reagan blended it into a coalition with post-Kennedy, blue-collar
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, McCain first denied, then confirmed that his
campaign phone-blitzed Catholic voters with reminders of Bush's Bob
Jones appearance and of the school's policy against interracial
dating, which it reversed Friday, and its history of anti-Catholic
polemics, including descriptions of the Vatican as running a
``Satanic system.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was, in some sense, merely stealing from the religious
attack playbook of the Bush campaign in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was some of the worst of American politics I've seen,'' the
political columnist Mark Shields said of attacks by pro-Bush
organizations on McCain, in which some observers sensed wisps of
anti-Semitism and other insults to pluralism.
</P>
<P>
   The key question is how the McCain initiative will play out
Tuesday in states like Ohio and New York, where there are
significant numbers of voters who consider themselves Catholic.
Will the bloc fears of the old post-immigration generation revive?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, as other states, Catholics may be increasingly uneasy
about the Bob Jones reports, says John C. Green, director of the
Bliss Institute of Applied Politics at the University of Akron. But
he emphasizes that Protestant evangelicals also see the issue as an
attack on them and not, as McCain insists, solely on two performers
on the nation's politico-religion circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, exit polls in Virginia and interviews with many voters
who identify themselves as religious conservatives suggest that
McCain's remarks are mobilizing support for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the issue of religion, as ever in American history,
is putting as much fresh life into primary day as into the Bush
campaign. ``The running joke here,'' Green said, ``is whether
Governor Bush will join the Knights of Columbus by primary day.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Quinn, a veteran New York political speechwriter and
historical novelist, said: ``McCain is blowing on some old embers
and causing some smoke, but no real fire. I don't think George Bush
is seen as anti-Catholic.'' Still, Quinn admitted he was intrigued
by how much the Catholic vote might resonate Tuesday with Kennedy's
trial by dogma before the Protestant prelates.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect of McCain's attacks on the religious right were
``politically disastrous,'' in the view of Shields. ``He failed to
distinguish the followers from the leadership, implying they'd been
bamboozled,'' he said. ``And in politics you never blame the
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond questions of strategic advantage in the electoral wars,
there lies the large gray area where voters' impressions of
personal and civic morality overlap. There, the rancorous butting
of politics and religion itself can become an issue as much as a
spectacle for the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Green of the University of Akron sounded decidedly unalarmed
about this instance of boundary crossing. Whether in the year 2000
or 1900, ``this is what campaigns do: they look for appeals that
will work and look for groups that will move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that this election cycle ``has an unusual amount of
explicit references to religion.'' He pointed to the early and
emphatic statements of Christian faith from Bush, Vice President Al
Gore and many of their rivals. He thinks this may be due to voters,
who are looking beyond the booming economy to wonder whether a
rapidly changing culture, regularly troubled by news of its own
lack of control, as seen in a lurid ongoing melange of shootings
and scandal-ridden leaders, demands more avowedly moral politics
and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly are out there now on the stump. They are talking
beliefs and charging hypocrisy, looking for advantage while
promising the high road to voters already sensing the risk, amid
the spectacle of once more mixing politics and religion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
