<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, March 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TEENS (Tokyo) _ For years, the United States has urged the
Japanese to loosen up, to spend more and to be freer in the way
they live. More and more, Japanese teen-agers are running with the
ball, rejecting the staid, studious behavior of the past in ways
that are disconcerting even for a government that has been
investigating ways of makeing childhood less regimented. By Howard
W. French.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN-HEIST (Kabul, Afghanistan) _ If the Taliban are
anything, they are holier-than-thou. And that's what made the big
heist so embarrassing. In the cold predawn of Jan. 13, thieves made
off with more than $200,000 in cash from Kabul's main money bazaar.
They met no opposition from the Taliban soldiers who stand watch
over the deserted bazaar at night. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   BHOPAL-LAWSUIT (New York) _ Warren M. Anderson, chairman of the
Union Carbide Corp. during the 1984 chemical disaster at Bhopal,
India, has apparently gone into hiding to avoid a summons to appear
in a Manhattan federal court as part of civil proceedings against
him and the company, say lawyers who have hired a private
investigator to locate Anderson. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE-FLOODS (Dateline TK) _ On the delay in getting aid to
flood victims in Mozambique. By Rachel Swarms.
</P>
<P>
   UNESCO-REFORM (United Nations) _ In the family of U.N. agencies,
UNESCO has long been the spoiled child. The top jobs were
invariably cushy and easy to get with a little political pull. When
a new director general with new ideas, Koichiro Matsuura of Japan,
was elected last fall, he thought he knew quite a bit about how bad
things were. ``But I discovered once I was inside that the
mismanagement was much more serious than I had anticipated,'' he
said in an interview. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-EMIGRES (Cali, Colombia) _ After four decades of civil
conflict and a proliferation of guns and gangs, the forces driving
Colombians to abandon their country are perhaps especially acute in
this city of 2 million people, best known for its ruthless drug
cartels. But the phenomenon is national, with people of every class
leaving from small towns and rural areas as well as large cities.
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PINOCHET-ASSESS (Santiago, Chile) _ When Gen. Augusto
Pinochet traveled to London 16 months ago on a diplomatic passport,
he was still a powerful force on the Chilean political scene. But
when he returned home on Friday _ benefiting from a British
decision that he was too infirm to stand trial in Spain on charges
of gross human rights violations during his 17 years in power _ he
was a shadow of his former self. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ENVIRONMENT (Mexico City) _ After five years of pressure
from an environmental movement that is every day more
transnational, the government on Thursday canceled plans with
Mitsubishi Corp. of Japan to build a gigantic salt plant on the
shores of a lagoon where gray whales give birth. It was a decision
Mexico never expected to make when the battle began, back in the
early stages of the country's broad opening to foreign commerce
under the 1994 North American Free Trade Agreement. By Julia
Preston.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-VIETNAM-WAR (Toronto) _ Next month's 25-year anniversary
of the fall of Saigon and the presidential campaign of Sen. John
McCain are reopening a long forgotten fissure between two groups of
Canadian fiftysomethings: the roughly 25,000 American draft dodgers
still living here, and the almost equal number of Canadians who
volunteered to fight in Vietnam. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CORRUPTION (Beijing) _ The revelation of several
high-level corruption cases has caused tensions within the
government. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOBJONES (Greenville, S.C.) _ The impression one is most likely
to gain on entering the campus of Bob Jones University is that it
is a very long way from the typical American college. Young men
wear neckties. Young women wear skirts with hemlines at the knee or
ankle. No one is smoking. And a visitor is nearly always addressed
as ``Sir.'' By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   EPISCOPALIAN-RIFT (Pawleys Island, S.C.) _ An unusual alliance
has developed between conservative Episcopalians in the United
States and like-minded heads of some Anglican churches overseas,
who share a perception that the Episcopal Church has come to rely
less on Scripture than on ideas from secular American culture,
especially on issues of human sexuality. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-FAMILY (Scranton, Pa.) _ Married 12 years, in love for 22,
Barbara and Charlie Smith have created 17 children, and there are
times when Mrs. Smith has sensed disdain laced into the curiosity
of people who were in wonder at their feat. The Smith family
recently ended a harrowing stretch of homelessness, in which the
children had to be parceled out in this ultimately generous city,
and they feared for their own solidarity. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-VOICES (New York) _ None of the facts have changed in the
year since Amadou Diallo died in his doorway: four white police
officers, 41 bullets and one unarmed black man. But in
neighborhoods from one end of the city to the other, away from the
daily protests over the slain man and the political posturing, New
Yorkers' attitudes about the police have begun a subtle shift. By
Ginger Thompson and C.J. Chivers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-RDP (Los Angeles) _ After an extraordinary five-week
roller coaster of contests, the Republican presidential contenders
head into Tuesday _ the most consequential and climactic primary
day of the 2000 campaign _ with Sen. John McCain determined to at
long last crack Gov. George W. Bush's hold on party loyalists. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-FOREIGN-POLICY (Washington) _ North Korea is just one
example of the differences in both substance and style between John
McCain and George Bush when they talk about foreign policy. They
come to their conclusions much as they run their campaigns: one by
instinct, the other by committee. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GAMBLING (Los Angeles) _ Nevada's gambling halls might be
about to face some significant competition right on their doorstep.
Californians, who account for about one-third of the visitors to
Nevada, will vote on Tuesday on a proposal to allow a broad
expansion of casino-style gambling on American Indian reservations
in their own state. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS (Los Angeles) _ Cowboys have long been a
vanishing breed in California, but when it comes to campaign
finance, this is still the wild, wild west. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ADS (Los Angeles) _ So many groups are elbowing for
television time to broadcast their positions on one of the 20
initiatives and referendums on the California ballot, that they are
all but drowning out the political advertising by the presidential
candidates. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-RULES-ASSESS (Washington) _ The peculiarities of the
California election law could conceivably precipitate a credentials
fight at Philadelphia this summer. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL BRIEFS (Undated) _ California senator's outlook is
sunny; Los Angeles DA is biding his time; Taking advantage of a
governor's woes. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GUARD (Washington) _ Since the scaling back of the
military that followed the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, the
Guard and Reserves have played a larger role in U.S. military
operations than ever before. For the Army, the increased reliance
has been the unintended consequence of a deliberate decision made
after the Vietnam War to put critical support units, from engineers
to civil affairs specialists, in the Guard and Reserve. By Steven
Lee Myers. (Part of an occasional series.)
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-RULE-CHANGE (Washington) _ Spurred by election-year
politics and complaints from employers scrambling to find enough
workers to help them keep the boom alive, the House voted 422-0 on
Wednesday to purge the Social Security laws of a relic of the
Depression. For decades, the provision has reduced the benefits of
workers ages 65 through 69 for every dollar they earned over
$17,000. At the time it was enacted, the law was designed to move
older workers aside in favor of younger ones. By Peter T. Kilborn
with Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIC-FOOD (Washington) _ More than two years after the
Federal government's first effort to define and regulate organic
food failed to win public approval, the Department of Agriculture
is announcing much tougher rules that prohibit the use of
genetically modified ingredients in products carrying the organic
label, as well as the use of irradiation to decontaminate them or
the application of sewage sludge when the crops are grown. By
Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Stony Brook, N.Y.) _ Breast beating in New York. By
Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A rerun of that '70s show. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
