<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6638 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MCCAIN-RELIGION-REVIE     03-04 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-RELIGION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THE RELIGIOUS RIGHT VS. McCAIN: IS IT ABOUT MONEY OR ABORTION?  
 (With CATHOLICS-POLITICS-REVIEW)  
 (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bile between Sen. John McCain and the religious right
involves both God and Mammon.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition and the National Right to Life
Committee, which ran radio ads against McCain in New Hampshire and
South Carolina, tangled with the Arizona Republican before he began
his presidential bid. They battled over McCain's legislation to
overhaul campaign financing. Money, not abortion, is still the
religious right's real beef with him, McCain says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoyed a cordial relationship for many years until this,''
McCain said, referring to his campaign finance bill and his
anti-abortion voting record in the Congress. ``It's turned into a
jihad because they believe this will destroy their impact on the
political process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exclusively about money,'' agrees Sen. Russ Feingold,
D-Wis., McCain's co-sponsor of legislation that would ban the
unrestricted political donations known as soft money. ``John and I
have tried to turn off their money spigot and they find that very
threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   One provision of the McCain-Feingold bill would have placed
restrictions on issue advertising 60 days before an election, a
hindrance to the election-related activities of many ideological
groups, including the Christian Coalition and the National Right to
Life Committee. These groups and others spend millions of dollars
and flood the airwaves near election day with ads targeting foes or
friends on specific issues including abortion, the environment and
health care. Unlike candidates, parties and political action
committees, the groups can collect and spend unlimited amounts and
aren't required to disclose their contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Groups on the left, including the American Civil Liberties
Union, also opposed the provision as interfering with free speech.
Although the issue ad restrictions were stripped out of the Senate
bill voted on last year, a similar provision passed the House. And
the Senate bill's ban on soft money, the large, unrestricted
donations to the political parties, is also anathema to the
National Right to Life Committee and its allies. (Republican Party
committees have given lots of soft money to the group.)
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Johnson, legislative director of the National Right to
Life Committee, said his group's board decided to endorse Gov.
George W. Bush and run ads against McCain mainly because of
``substantive concerns about his record on right to life issues.''
He cited McCain's comments that he would not seek to repeal Roe vs.
Wade. But Johnson said McCain's campaign reform proposal was
certainly a factor, too. ``We are strongly opposed to certain
components of his proposal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fault lines between leaders of conservative groups and
anti-abortion lawmakers over the issue of political money were
exposed last year. As the House prepared to vote on its version of
McCain's bill, the Christian Coalition, the American Conservative
Union and the National Right to Life Committee warned anti-abortion
congressmen that their votes on campaign finance would be counted
against them in ratings compiled by conservative, anti-abortion
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Writing anti-abortion House colleagues, Gene Taylor, a
Mississippi Democrat, called the warning an ``obvious attempt to
target and intimidate those of us who believe that our campaign
system is in need of an overhaul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
