<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6649 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BAYWATCH-OVERTIME-LAD     03-04 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYWATCH-OVERTIME-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFEGUARDS' OVERTIME COST LOS ANGELES COUNTY $1.3 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ It's not exactly ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County lifeguards, the models for the popular TV
show, may have been too tired to rescue swimmers last year because
some worked as much as 105 hours of overtime a month, according to
a new audit.
</P>
<P>
   County Auditor-Controller Alan Sasaki found lifeguards cost the
county $1.3 million in overtime and may not have been ``physically
alert and mentally capable of performing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifeguard Capt. Steve Moseley said public safety was never
jeopardized, and the overtime ensured the most experienced
lifeguards were on duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never put someone out in a lifeguard tower who we
thought was in any way unable to fulfill their job,'' Moseley said.
``We would never compromise public safety on someone's belief that
they were entitled to an overtime shift.''
</P>
<P>
   The audit found that a group of 20 permanent lifeguards had
worked 7,138 hours of overtime, or between 50 and 105 hours of
overtime a month each.
</P>
<P>
   An average permanent lifeguard earns $58,900 a year, but if one
worked 50 to 105 hours of overtime a month, he or she would make
$87,784 to $119,556 a year. The high end is more than county
supervisors and superior court judges, who only make $117,912
annually.
</P>
<P>
   County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky requested the audit in
December after receiving a complaint that the Los Angeles County
Fire Department's Lifeguard Division was spending too much money on
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint alleged that permanent lifeguards, who earn an
average of $31.35 an hour for regular pay and $48.14 an hour for
overtime, were working the extra hours rather than temporary and
part-time lifeguards who make $23.95 an hour straight time and
$36.15 an hour overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The audit found the overtime cost taxpayers nearly $1.3 million
in 1999, up from about $1 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned they were paying overtime to their
higher-paid employees and, as a result, spending more than they
needed to,'' Yaroslavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem we've had in the city and county. If this kind
of abuse is taking place at this small scale, it raises the
possibility it is taking place on a larger scale in our bigger
departments.''
</P>
<P>
   The overtime problem worsened after the Lifeguard Division was
transferred from the Department of Beaches and Harbors to the Fire
Department. The department's policy allows only permanent
lifeguards to fill in - working overtime - because officials say
they are more experienced than temporary ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we use permanent personnel, we can guarantee their level
of training,'' Moseley said.
</P>
<P>
   Lifeguard officials cited the extensive use of defibrillators as
the key reason why more experienced personnel are needed. Those
machines require an emergency medical technician certification and
four hours of special training.
</P>
<P>
   However, auditors noted that a significant number of part-time
lifeguards are EMT certified and require only the four-hour
training to be certified in these positions.
</P>
<P>
   The audit recommended that the Fire Department re-evaluate its
overtime policy, establish rules on the number of hours that can be
worked and monitor overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Chief P. Michael Freeman said using a group of well-trained
temporary lifeguards to fill vacancies rather than training a large
number of part-time lifeguards is the best way to reduce overtime.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
