<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AFGHANISTAN-HEIST-2TA     03-04 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHANISTAN-HEIST-2TAKES-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEFT UNDER THE TALIBAN? PERISH THE THOUGHT. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KABUL, Afghanistan _ If the Taliban are anything, they are
holier-than-thou. And that's what made the big heist so
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   In the cold predawn of Jan. 13, thieves made off with more than
$200,000 in cash from Kabul's main money bazaar. The brigands were
methodical in their noisy work, dismantling the metal shutters and
jimmying the locks on 10 stores. They met no opposition from the
Taliban soldiers who stand watch over the deserted bazaar at night.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, come morning, those guards, like the money, were gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to have been an inside job,'' said a currency
trader, Haji Amanullah, who lost $165,000. This was not, he quickly
realized, the most prudent answer to give about the Islamic
fundamentalists who control most of the country. So he hastened to
amend: ``I'm not saying the Taliban did this. I completely trust
the Taliban. It was probably done by people in the clothing of the
Taliban, impostors from the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamentably, with all its other woes, Afghanistan's forlorn
capital is suffering a mini-crime wave, a rare circumstance in
recent years. Chopping off a robber's hands and feet has generally
deterred those inclined toward banditry.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the money bazaar been hit twice, several homes have
been burgled in the last two months by armed ruffians who work in
the wee hours, seemingly untroubled by a 9 p.m. curfew enforced at
the Taliban militia's checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, our enemies have become active in Kabul,
infiltrating people into the city for the purpose of besmirching
our reputation,'' said Mullah Ghulam Haider, a white-bearded judge
who dispenses the Taliban's stern wrath on criminals. ``Our
security forces will leave no stone unturned until we catch these
people and end this rash of robbery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban are notoriously tough on rule breakers, meting out
severe punishments for murder, adultery, homosexuality, improper
dress, watching television or listening to music. And while many
Afghans complain about Islamic strictures that seem medieval, they
have praised the Taliban for eliminating crime.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a doctor who was stabbed and his money taken,'' said
Muhammad Naseem, a jeweler. ``If someone comes into this shop and
says, `Stick your hands up,' how can I resist? The Taliban have
forbidden people to have guns.''
</P>
<P>
   As is the case everywhere, people say they do not want to point
a finger at anyone _ and then they point and point. Not all the
Taliban are pure of heart, many allege.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an implausible theory. Afghanistan is notable for
fluid loyalties and vendible comradeship. Much of the militia's
battlefield success is owed to cash gifts paid to local warlords
who then joined the movement and brought along their troops.
Taliban trained in religious schools have become mixed together
with Ali-come-latelies less devoted to Islamic uprightness. It is
hard to vouch for partisans who have been purchased.
</P>
<P>
   There are other hypotheses, too, including the sociological ones
that lay the blame on poverty. ``Unemployment leads to crime,''
said Abdul Qadir, a money trader. ``People do not have enough to
eat these days. What do you expect them to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Deprivation is certainly rife. War has been a constant in
Afghanistan for 21 straight years. The economy capsized long ago.
Good research is impossible in such mayhem, but experts believe the
average annual income to be less than $175.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the scene of the great $200,000 heist _ the money
bazaar known as Sarai Shahzadah, or House of the Prince _ is an
excellent location to observe many of the peculiarities of the
present-day economy _ the impact of the war, the injunctions of
Islam, the desperation of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the crime victim, Amanullah, after initially
naming the Taliban as suspects in taking his $165,000, was not
finished in his heedful exoneration of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy with the Taliban,'' he said. ``I have been
personally assured that their supreme leader, Mullah Muhammad Omar,
is sorry for my loss, and if the money is not recovered, the
Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan will stand liable for the full
amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanullah is a tall man who was wearing a white skull cap, a
black leather jacket and an expensive watch, a gift from his
brother, a carpet dealer in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are elated with the Taliban,'' he again emphasized. ``They
have our full trust.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sarai Shahzadah has 225 small storefronts on three levels. While
it is Kabul's financial hub, it looks like a cheap motel. In the
courtyard, hundreds of small-timers try to get in on the action,
hectically trading tiny sums of dollars, Afghanis, Pakistani rupees
and German marks, hoping to go home with $1 profit for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no work in Kabul,'' said Shams Muhammad, 30, a textile
engineer. ``This bazaar is full of engineers, teachers and doctors.
We stand here all day, exchanging currency for people who come by,
making a few cents on every transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The amateur traders may be short of wealth, but they are not
wanting for sheer bulk of cash. By necessity, they carry around
foot-high stacks of paper money.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre bit of banking, Afghanistan's currency is printed
by the Taliban's remaining opposition, the government of
Burhanuddin Rabbani, who unceremoniously fled Kabul in 1996. Most
nations still recognize the old government, which faces high costs
in keeping up its end of the civil war and prints excessive amounts
of cash to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as such things always go, the more money that is
manufactured the less it is worth. Ten years ago, the Afghani was
trading at about 50 to $1; five years ago 3,000 to $1; last year
40,000 to $1; now, about 54,000 to $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thieves were wise to steal dollars,'' joked Amin Khustai,
the amiable president of the bazaar. ``Can you imagine the weight
of so many Afghanis?''
</P>
<P>
   Out came the calculators. Using notes worth 5,000 Afghanis _ the
second highest denomination _ the equivalent of $200,000 would tip
the scale at 24 tons.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the use of the incredible shrinking Afghani
is the fact that two types are in circulation, the other being
leftovers that were printed by a second opposition figure, the now
self-exiled Abdul Rashid Dostum. In some cities, like Kabul, these
alternate bills are worthless. In others, like Dostum's one-time
redoubt Mazar-i-Sharif, they fetch about half value.
</P>
<P>
   To an untrained eye, the Rabbani and Dostum currencies look
identical. But with money so dear, few eyes can afford to be
untrained. As each bill is inspected at the point of purchase, all
but the smallest of transactions seems to require the time it would
take to authenticate a painting.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Afghani remains the common currency of the
street, though with its value in free fall, merchants quickly try
to convert the bills to another currency. Besides, Afghanis take up
too much space. Big pockets are needed just to buy a bottle of jam.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There are few private banks in Afghanistan. According to the
Taliban, Koranic law prohibits the payment of interest. ``In Islam,
banks may loan a customer money for a specific project, but only if
there is an arrangement to share in both the profits and losses,''
said Abdul Manan Deobandi, the third deputy governor of the
national bank.
</P>
<P>
   Most people with a sizable amount of cash keep it with a
currency trader like the recently looted Amanullah. He is one of
the bazaar's leading figures, though his shop, one of the nicer
ones, is but a single narrow room with a badly cracked teller's
window.
</P>
<P>
   It is a busy place, with tea always brewing on a small stove.
Men enter with their armfuls of Afghanis, placing them on an old
table, unburdening themselves as if they had been hauling a cord of
wood. Amanullah records deposits by hand in a ledger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is safe here in the bazaar,'' he said proudly,
momentarily forgetting his robbery.
</P>
<P>
   He was reminded of that unfortunate incident, and this pleased
him greatly, for it gave him another chance to mention his support
of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taliban provide excellent security,'' he said. ``We are
very, very happy with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
