<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, March 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exceptionally mild air for early March will spread from the
Plains to the Eastern States during the next few days. Meanwhile, a
series of Pacific disturbances will keep much of the West unsettled
with valley showers and mountain snow.
</P>
<P>
   Record-setting warmth will envelop most of the Missouri and
northern Mississippi Valleys on Sunday. Increasing breezes from the
south will combine with plentiful sunshine to boost afternoon
readings above 70 degrees in these regions. Elsewhere in the Plains
and Mississippi Valley, it will be mainly dry and mild although
isolated showers will occur in the increasingly humid air across
central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A tandem of low pressure areas will promote inclement weather in
most of the Southwest. Rain will be locally heavy near a front in
southern California, especially where moist winds ascend the
sloping terrain of the San Gabriel and San Bernardino mountains.
Farther east, intermittent snow will occur from the southern Sierra
to the mountains of northern Arizona and Utah. Showers will dampen
many valleys of the interior Southwest. Drier air will reach the
coast from Washington to northern California as offshore winds
develop.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will be a bit cooler than Saturday as gusty winds
from the northwest develop in the wake of a cold front. Clouds and
a few flurries will occur from the Adirondacks to northern New
England, particularly early Sunday. Elsewhere, ample sunshine will
prevail from the Middle Atlantic States to the Southeast with
afternoon temperatures a bit above the seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: March Contrasts
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a heavy wet snowstorm blanketed much of western and
northern Kansas. By Saturday afternoon, temperatures will surge
into the 70s in the same region. Spectacular contrasts like this
are the signature of the third month. The strengthening March sun
steadily warms the equatorial regions while arctic air lingers over
Canadian tundra. Storms in the atmosphere mix air masses in an
effort to eliminate temperature differences. In March, these storms
can draw warm tropical air toward the north as easily as they bring
the last vestiges of winter south.
</P>
</TEXT>
