<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-ART-NY     03-04 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY TO CURTAIL TOURS OF RESERVES SERVING OVERSEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Increasingly concerned about a backlash to its
growing reliance on the National Guard and Reserve, the Army has
decided to limit overseas deployments of these units in
peacekeeping and other military operations to a maximum of six
months, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's decision will shorten the time these troops have to
be away from home, which Pentagon and Army officials hope will ease
the strain that a rising number of calls to active duty have had on
reservists, their families and, especially, their employers.
</P>
<P>
   The new limit is the first significant step by the Army to
recognize that its greater reliance on the Guard and Reserve _ like
that of all the other armed services _ has so intensified the
burden on its citizen-soldiers that it threatens to undermine their
willingness to join or stay in those units.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to continue to rely on this part of the force,''
said Charles L. Cragin, the assistant secretary of defense for
reserve affairs, ``and therefore we have to look at things we can
do to make it easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the scaling back of the military that followed the fall of
the Berlin Wall in 1989, the Guard and Reserves have played a
larger role in American military operations than ever before. There
are now three simultaneous presidential mobilizations of reservists
_ for Bosnia, Kosovo and the continuing containment of Iraq _ and
there is no end in sight to any of them. The president still has
the authority to call up troops for Haiti, too, but the American
military has largely ended its presence there.
</P>
<P>
   For the Army, the increased reliance has been the unintended
consequence of a deliberate decision made after the Vietnam War to
put critical support units, from engineers to civil affairs
specialists, in the Guard and Reserve. It was a response by the
Army's chief of staff at the time, Gen. Creighton Abrams, to
President Johnson's decision not to call up the reserves during the
Vietnam War for fear of generating greater opposition to it.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, whenever Army units conduct an overseas operation,
at least some reservists go along. Moreover, with the tempo of
peacekeeping operations having increased through the 1990s, Army
leaders say they now have no choice but to turn even more to the
564,000 members of its Guard and Reserve to ease the burden on its
active force of 479,000, despite the strains that has placed on
reservists who must set aside their civilian lives, including
college educations or jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy has raised questions _ in the Pentagon and,
just as important, on Capitol Hill _ about the structure of today's
Army and its budget if it cannot meet its worldwide missions
without relying so heavily on the Guard and Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, two of the Army's 10 active divisions, the 10th
Mountain and the 1st Mechanized Infantry, classified themselves
unready for war because so many of their troops were committed to
Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   This helps explain why Army officials defend their increased
reliance on the Guard and Reserve for a greater share of
peacekeeping as a way to let the Army focus on the Pentagon's
stated strategy, which is to fight and win two major regional wars
nearly at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Integration is the right thing to do,'' said P.T. Henry, the
Army's assistant secretary for reserve affairs, referring to the
service's plans to incorporate more and more Guard and Reserve
units into continuing operations. ``The benefit is that we can
share the load. We're willing, in knowing that, to pick up the
attending consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army's decision to shorten overseas rotations is one of a
series of steps the Pentagon has taken to address what officials
acknowledge are the new burdens being placed on the nation's
citizen-soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's chief of staff, Gen. Erik K. Shinseki, is expected to
announce the decision on Tuesday at a ceremony handing over command
of the American sector of NATO's peacekeeping operation in Bosnia
to the 49th Armored Division of the Texas National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter rotation will not apply to the 700 men and women
from the 49th, including its headquarters company and aviation,
engineering, communications and military police units, who will
serve in Bosnia for nearly eight months. The call-up of the 49th is
the largest single deployment of Guard troops since the Persian
Gulf war in 1990 and 1991. The 49th will be the first unit to take
command of an overseas operation since the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Cold War, in fact, the Guard and Reserves were
underused, Pentagon officials say. They were literally held in
reserve for ``the big one,'' which never came. With President
Johnson adamant about not turning to the Guard and Reserves,
joining them was a way to avoid being drafted for the war in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The increased reliance on the Guard and Reserves has brought
some political fallout, especially on Capitol Hill, where lawmakers
echo the complaints of reservists about the strains the deployments
have created and question the Army's intent to rely more heavily on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, inside as well as outside the Pentagon, have
questioned whether the Defense Department would ever have to
actually fight two nearly simultaneous regional wars, which has
been the policy since 1993. Modifying this policy, they argued,
would allow the Pentagon to ease training requirements on the
active force, freeing troops for missions the Army is conducting _
and requiring less use of the Guard and Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   After reducing the Army to 479,000 soldiers today from 770,000
in 1989, Army officials argue that the force is now not configured
to carry out what the Pentagon calls ``operations other than war''
and still spend enough time preparing to fight major wars. The
phrase ``operations other than war'' refers to unanticipated
missions, like those in Somalia, Haiti, Bosnia and now Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could argue that the Army is well structured for the most
stressing threat to our vital interests, potentially presented by
two nearly simultaneous major theater wars,'' said Col. Blair Ross,
an Army officer who serves in the Department of Defense's strategy
office, ``but that it is not as well structured for some of the
day-to-day requirements of engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-ART-2N     03-04 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-GUARD-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: of engagement.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The growth in Army operations other than war has led to calls
for increasing the total number of active troops, something that
Army leaders have echoed, but that the Department of Defense
opposes, citing the expense and the difficulties in recruiting
enough soldiers today.
</P>
<P>
   Critics on Capitol Hill, including Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchinson,
R-Texas, complain that the real problem is the number of
peacekeeping missions to which President Clinton has committed
American troops. Hutchinson said an increased reliance on the Guard
and Reserves should not become a routine policy because of the
impact such deployments have on reservists and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army's effort to ease the burden of these deployments is
encouraging,'' she said, ``yet fails to address the underlying
problems caused by deployments that are not in our national
interest and appear to have no end.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the trend appears likely to continue _ and even
grow.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Pentagon report, the Reserve Component Employment Study
2005, predicted that five years from now there would still be at
least two peacekeeping missions like Bosnia and Kosovo. The report
also called on the services to do more to use the Guard and
Reserves, including giving them a significant role in defending the
nation against possible terrorist attacks and the national missile
defense system the Pentagon is planning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered the services
to remove ``all structural barriers'' to integrating Guard and
Reserve units into active-duty operations. It may be one of his
lasting legacies as secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Since the peacekeeping mission in Bosnia began in 1995, more
than 33,000 of the 150,000 troops who have served there _ 22
percent _ have belonged to the Guard and Reserves many of them in
specialties that exist primarily in the Army's Reserve components,
such as public affairs, medics, transportation and psychological
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the 49th's headquarters company represents a
further expansion of the Guard's role in Bosnia. The Army has
already scheduled deployments in Bosnia of headquarters units of
the 29th Infantry Division from Virginia and the 28th Infantry
Division from Pennsylvania, as well as combat brigades from North
Carolina, Oklahoma, Georgia, Idaho and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Army and Pentagon officials say they have not yet fully measured
the long-term ramifications of an increased reliance on the Guard
and Reserves. They hope that steps like the Army's will assuage
some of the concerns. In recent years, the Pentagon has also
offered new benefits to reservists, including expanded dental care
and access to government rates on airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's decision to shorten rotations for its Guard and
Reserve units applies only to operations other than war. In the
event of a conflict, the Army will still be able to mobilize its
Guard and Reserve units and send them overseas for the 270 days
allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   The policy brings the Army closer in line to the other services.
Air National Guard and Air Force Reserve units, for example,
generally deploy no more than three months, though some individual
commanders and specialists serve as long as six.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Army officials described the shift as a matter of fairness,
since active Army units generally deploy from their home posts for
only six-months. They concede that over time the policy could
increase the number of Guard and Reserve units called to serve, but
added that shortening deployments could ease the impact on
individual reservists, especially with their civilian employers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Army limited deployments of doctors, nurse
anesthetists and dentists to 90 days after more than a third of the
doctors ordered to Bosnia from 1995 to 1998 quit the Reserve rather
than risk being called away from their civilian practices again.
Officials said they realized that most doctors could not afford to
be away from their patients more than 90 days without risking their
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Robert J. St. Onge Jr., the Army's deputy chief of
staff for operations and plans, said the demands of rising
deployments also affected soldiers on active duty. Like their Guard
and Reserve counterparts, the active-duty soldiers faced repeated
tours and months away from home, something officials believe has
eroded morale and hurt recruiting and retention of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, however, is that members of the Guard and
Reserves sign up for military duty expecting to serve 39 days a
year _ one weekend a month and two weeks each summer _ not for 270
days. And expectations have been slow to change.
</P>
<P>
   St. Onge recalled hearing a radio advertisement for the New
Jersey National Guard recently that extolled the benefits of
joining, including extra pay and college grants. ``I kept waiting
to hear the shoe drop: `And you can serve in exotic places,''' he
said. ``It never came.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing use of the Guard and Reserve has challenged many
assumptions about the Army, from its strategies to its structure to
its budget. ``The whole dynamic has changed,'' St. Onge said. ``And
frankly, if it goes south, we're going to have to look at a new way
of doing business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
