<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EPISCOPALIAN-RIFT-ART     03-04 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPALIAN-RIFT-ART-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPISCOPAL CHURCH RIFT WIDENS WITH BISHOP CONSECRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Pa., England)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAWLEYS ISLAND, S.C. _ In this pleasant coastal community, a
place of lush golf resorts and second homes, there is little to
evoke Rwanda, a densely populated East African nation, the site of
a devastating ethnic conflict in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the two places have a link, a spiritual one, which became
abruptly apparent a month ago in an event that sent shock waves
among the world's Anglican churches, whose 73 million members
include those in the Episcopal Church in the United States. The
Rev. Charles H. Murphy III, 52, rector of All Saints Episcopal
Church, whose stately campus here occupies a swath of land near the
Waccamaw River, was consecrated a bishop by the head of the
Anglican Province of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   In the same ceremony, which took place in Singapore, another
Episcopal priest, the Rev. John H. Rodgers Jr., retired dean of
Trinity Episcopal School for Ministry in Ambridge, Pa., was also
consecrated a bishop, under the authority of the Anglican Province
of Southeast Asia. Within days, both men returned to the United
States, with plans to minister to conservatives in the Episcopal
Church who feel alienated from the church's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, conducted with no warning to Episcopal Church
leaders, vividly showed an unusual alliance that has developed
between conservative Episcopalians in the United States and the
like-minded heads of some Anglican churches overseas, who share a
perception that the Episcopal Church has come to rely less on
Scripture than on ideas from secular American culture, especially
on issues of human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a crisis of leadership in the American church,''
Murphy said in an interview here last week, a few hours before he
was to fly to Rwanda, for a meeting with his new boss, Archbishop
Emmanuel Kolini. While there are divisive debates within the
Episcopal Church over such questions as whether to ordain gay men
and lesbians as priests, Murphy said, ``Human sexuality issues are
a symptom of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative congregations in this country have already
requested his ``oversight'' as a bishop, he said. But, he added,
Kolini asked that he take no action now, and instead wait for
guidance after the heads of the 38 Anglican church provinces
worldwide hold a long-scheduled meeting in Portugal on March 23.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the heads of two of those provinces to create bishops
to minister within the areas of sister churches, as happened in
Singapore on Jan. 29, is remarkable. In secular terms, it would be
as if the governor of one state appointed a judge to administer
justice in another.
</P>
<P>
   After the consecrations, the Episcopal Church's top official,
the Presiding Bishop Frank T. Griswold III, declared in a letter to
American bishops that he was ``appalled'' by the event, and ``even
more so'' by the accusations that the church was in a crisis, which
he said was not true.
</P>
<P>
   Griswold could not be reached for comment this week because he
was away from his office, but in an earlier interview in February,
he said he would go to Portugal to ``share a very different story
about the Episcopal Church'' with his fellow primates, the heads of
the Anglican churches.
</P>
<P>
   The consecrations in Singapore have also reverberated across the
Atlantic, to England, where Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey,
the spiritual leader of the Church of England and first among
equals among Anglican bishops, declared recently that he did not
recognize the consecrations as valid.
</P>
<P>
   The consecrations come at a time of great internal stress within
American Christianity over cultural issues that began to emerge in
the 1960s, like the leadership role of women and the rights of
gays.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Within the Roman Catholic Church in the United States, some
conservative groups appeal directly to the Vatican, seeking
crackdowns on priests and theologians they view as transgressing
church teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) have spent years
fighting over the question of whether to ordain gays and lesbians,
with opponents of that idea prevailing.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Church, too, has wrestled inconclusively with how
to relate to its gay members. One retired bishop in 1995 faced
heresy charges for having ordained a noncelibate gay man as a
deacon, although a church court cleared him of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Wednesday, Rodgers said the
consecrations should not be seen as a conservative response to one
issue, but to a larger sense of crisis, involving questions about
the authority of Scripture as the guide for life. He also said he
felt ``firm and clear'' about his own status as a bishop in the
Province of Southeast Asia. But what future role he and Murphy
would play, he said, ``really depends on how the primates work it
all out'' at the Portugal meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, 52, is the son, brother and brother-in-law of Episcopal
priests. Ordained in 1975, he has led All Saints since 1982. When
he arrived at the parish, he found fewer than 100 people in Sunday
worship, he said, but now has about 600, a sizable congregation in
an area far more rural than urban.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat in a rocking chair with a back cushion that read,
``Life is Short, Hell is Hot and the Stakes are High,'' Murphy said
he felt ``100 percent Anglican,'' and impelled ``to lead, not
leave'' the faith.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he drew inspiration from the work of the consumer
advocate Ralph Nader, who fought in the 1960s to make automobiles
safer. ``What Ralph Nader decided to do was to go over the heads of
the Big Three automakers and go directly to Congress,'' Murphy
said. ``After a long battle with no results, we went over the heads
of the American church and appealed to the international church.''
</P>
<P>
   The international church is weighted increasingly toward the
Southern Hemisphere, where the faith, in all its varieties, is
growing rapidly. A century ago, about nine in 10 of the world's 31
million Anglicans lived in Great Britain, the United States and
Canada. But now, according to statistics common in Anglican
circles, Africa and southern Asia account for slightly more than
half the globe's Anglicans.
</P>
<P>
   The shift was made apparent in 1998 at the Lambeth Conference,
the bishops' meeting that occurs once a decade, where African and
Asian prelates joined their socially conservative peers to pass a
resolution declaring homosexuality ``incompatible with
Christianity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
