<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CALIF-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS-     03-04 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO LIMIT POLITICAL CONTRIBUTIONS GETS SOME UNLIKELY HELP 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cowboys have long been a vanishing breed in
California, but when it comes to campaign finance, this is still
the wild, wild west. It is one of only six states, and the only big
one besides Illinois, with no restrictions on political
contributions or spending. Its Democratic governor, Gray Davis,
raised a record $13.2 million in his first year in office last
year.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say Californians have not tried to rein in
campaign spending. In 1996, voters easily passed a ballot measure
that limited individual contributions to $500 in statewide races,
but a federal judge struck it down as unrealistically low in a
state in which one week of television advertising costs more than
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now another proposal to limit giving and spending is on the
primary ballot here on Tuesday, Proposition 25. And though polls
show it failing to draw the majority support needed to pass, it got
assistance from an unusual source this week: a $1 million
contribution for television and radio advertising from the
millionaire Max Palevsky, a longtime donor to Democrats from George
McGovern to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around politics for a while, and whether I go to
Sacramento or Washington these days, there's just a climate that
everything is for sale,'' said Palevsky, who made his fortune in
computers. ``And what is shocking is that all the people take that
as a fact of nature, that it's just the way it is. Until we do
something about that, everything else doesn't really count that
much, because we'll never get any serious reform in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 25 is sponsored by Ron K. Unz, the Silicon Valley
software millionaire and former Republican gubernatorial candidate
whose ballot measure to end bilingual education passed
overwhelmingly two years ago. Unz was introduced to Palevsky by the
actor Warren Beatty, who toyed last year with running for president
on a platform of campaign finance overhaul and flirted with making
an advertisement for the measure this week.
</P>
<P>
   But in a twist, Proposition 25 is opposed not only by business
and taxpayer groups who do not like its provisions for public
financing of campaigns, but by a number of newspaper editorial
boards and civic groups that generally support campaign finance
changes. These include the California League of Women Voters, which
argues that the measure is not restrictive enough and would create
a range of new complications and potential abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the pragmatists vs. the purists,'' said Robert Stern, a
former counsel to the state's Fair Political Practices Commission
and president of the nonpartisan Center for Governmental Studies
here.
</P>
<P>
   Stern supports the measure, but a colleague, the center's
campaign finance director, Craig Holman, opposes it. ``That's just
the nature of reform groups,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would limit contributions to $5,000 for statewide
races, require immediate Internet disclosure of all contributions
of $1,000 or more, ban corporate contributions, and provide
vouchers for free television and radio time to statewide campaigns
that agree to limit spending. Unz contends the cost would be less
than $2 a year per voter.
</P>
<P>
   Critics counter that the measure would amount to a $55 million
annual tax increase, would not restrict so-called soft money
donations to political parties and would provide public subsidies
for the ballot initiative campaigns that have increasingly come to
dominate the state's politics.
</P>
<P>
   Unz, a policy wonk who does not hesitate to plunge into issues
that others have worked on for years, said that some groups had
looked askance at the measure simply because of his involvement.
``That's certainly an element,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Henderson, legislative director for the state chapter of
the League of Women Voters, acknowledged that it was unnerving to
have ``someone who hasn't been working on this to come along and
say, `Well, this is what I want and take it or leave it.''' But she
added: ``We think it isn't real reform. It basically takes pretty
much what they have at the national level, which I think everybody
knows by now is a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   But longtime advocates of campaign finance limits, like Fred
Wertheimer, the former leader of Common Cause and now president of
Democracy 21, a public policy organization in Washington, said
Proposition 25 was better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find the problems with it, but there are important
elements to it, and its passage would send yet another signal to
the politicians around the country that this issue is real,''
Wertheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest statewide Field Poll found nearly half of likely
voters opposed to the measure, with about 36 percent supporting it
and 18 percent undecided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
