<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-0305-COX     03-04 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONFIDENT OF NOMINATION, GORE ROAD TESTS ANTI-GOP CAMPAIGN
THEMES
 &HT;    For Sunday, March 5
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Vice President Al Gore, confident of a ``Super
Tuesday'' primary victory over Democratic challenger Bill Bradley,
road-tested campaign themes against Republican presidential rivals
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   His most potent weapon against the GOP nominee, judging from his
emphasis during a swing through Massachusetts and New York, is the
economy, the strongest in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue now is whether or not we're going to keep that
prosperity going or whether or not we're going to take the advice
of both Republican candidates and take a right wing U-turn back to
the old polices of the past,'' Gore said during a rally at Boston's
historic Faneuil (pronounced FAN-yuhl) Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also raised environmental issues in his criticism of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain, something he has
rarely done in the Democratic contest with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the environment, just remember two numbers _ zero and one,
since this is the digital age,'' Gore said of the GOP presidential
contenders:
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them in the Senate two years ago had a zero rating from
the League of Conservation Voters. The other one is the governor of
a state which he has just led to the position of number one in air
pollution, number one in water pollution, number one in land
pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   He also ripped Bush for his anti-abortion stand, noting that the
Texas governor had met privately in the past with televangelists
Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell. He said the ``code'' language
Robertson and Falwell used following the meeting indicated Bush
would appoint Supreme Court justices committed to overturning Roe
v. Wade, the court ruling that granted abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're saying is they had a solid promise to give the
right wing extremist wing of the Republican Party control of our
Supreme Court and the interpretation of our Constitution,'' Gore
said. ``Let's stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   He ridiculed Bush's recent concession that he would allow
voluntary trigger locks on firearms. ``That's not the issue,'' Gore
said. ``The issue is we want to make mandatory child safety
locks.''
</P>
<P>
   And later, during a speech in Buffalo, he criticized the two
Republican candidates for opposing health care reforms and hate
crime legislation backed by Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore barely mentioned Bradley in a morning speech to several
hundred people who gathered on a sunny, brisk day in the square in
front of Faneuil Hall, which was built in 1742 and has provided a
forum for a number of historic figures, including Samuel Adams,
Frederick Douglass, Susan B. Anthony and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's passing reference to Bradley was to remind voters that
both he and his challenger have said that Tuesday's primary voting
in 15 states, including Massachusetts, ``will be the decisive
moment'' in the campaign for the Democratic campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You here in Massachusetts ... have an opportunity to close the
book on the Democratic nomination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' two senators, Ted Kennedy and John Kerry, joined
Gore on the stage and in the attacks on the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry ridiculed Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' with a
joke about Bob Jones III, president of Bob Jones University in
South Carolina, and John Rocker, the Atlanta Brave pitcher who made
inflammatory remarks about minorities, gays and immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The definition of George Bush's compassionate conservative
(cq.) is Bob Jones III forgiving John Rocker,'' Kerry quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Bob Jones University prohibited inter-racial
dating, barred gays from its campus and regarded Catholicism as a
false religion.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a Catholic, also took note of Bush's appearance at Bob
Jones and McCain's criticism of the Christian right's influence on
the GOP's nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that the only thing these Republican candidates
can talk about is religion,'' Kennedy said. ``But neither one of
them has a prayer against Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy added to the general election atmosphere of Gore's final
weekend of campaigning before ``Super Tuesday'' by making jokes
about possible running mates for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had found a note in one pocket asking him to remind
Gore that New York has 33 electoral votes. He said it was signed,
``Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he found another note addressed ``Dear Dad,'' asking him
to remind Gore that Rhode Island has only 8 electoral votes. He
said the note, supposedly from his son, Rep. Patrick Kennedy of
Rhode Island, cautioned the senator against reminding Gore that the
younger Kennedy is only 32, too young under the U.S. Constitution
to be vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
