<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-GAMBLING-NYT     03-04 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GAMBLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE OPPOSITION THIS TIME TO AN EXPANSION OF TRIBAL CASINOS
</HEADLINE>
  (With CALIF-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS) 
(nk) 
 BY ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nevada's gambling halls might be about to face
some significant competition right on their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Californians, who account for about one-third of the visitors to
Nevada, will vote on Tuesday on a proposal to allow a broad
expansion of casino-style gambling on Indian reservations in their
own state. Some analysts say the measure would eventually make
California the nation's second largest gambling state, ahead of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggest that the measure will win approval. Tribes
and other supporters of the measure, known as Proposition 1A, have
raised about $20 million for advertising, while the opponents have
raised only about $44,000.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some tribes are planning to enlarge and embellish
casinos, even adding hotels and restaurants. New casinos are
planned, some of them near the major highways linking San Francisco
and Los Angeles to Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   California has 41 tribal casinos, with about 19,000 slot
machines. But the tribes never had an agreement for those machines
with the state, as required by federal law, so the casinos have
been in danger of being shut down.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 ballot measure to legalize the casinos won 63 percent of
the vote but was ruled in violation of the state constitution's ban
on Nevada-style casinos. The new measure would change the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming Proposition 1A is approved, the number of slot
machines in the state could more than double to nearly 45,000 under
an agreement between the state and nearly 60 tribes. Some opponents
say the agreement could be interpreted to allow more than 100,000
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Even the lower number is greater than the 36,000 machines in New
Jersey, though far behind the roughly 200,000 in Nevada. Card games
like blackjack and baccarat would also be allowed for the first
time, but not craps or roulette.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would push California fairly quickly into the second
largest jurisdiction in the country,'' said William Eadington,
director of the Institute for the Study of Gambling and Commercial
Gaming at the University of Nevada in Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 ballot battle was the most expensive in state history,
with the tribes spending more than $60 million and opponents, led
by Nevada casinos, more than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   This time, labor unions, which opposed the 1998 proposition, are
happier because the new agreement would allow casino workers to
unionize. And some Nevada casinos have decided that they cannot
beat the tribes and have joined them.
</P>
<P>
   Three Las Vegas-based gambling companies _ Harrah's
Entertainment, Station Casinos and Anchor Gaming _ have announced
agreements to finance and manage California tribal casinos. Stephen
A. Wynn of Mirage Resorts is talking to the Cabazon Band of Mission
Indians about building a resort near Palm Springs, a tribal
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of gambling have seized upon this. ``It will be a Las
Vegas Indian tribe industry in California,'' said Cheryl Schmit,
co-director of Stand Up for California, an opposition group.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of Proposition 1A downplay how much expansion might
come. The tribes are emphasizing in advertisements that approval of
the proposition is needed to prevent the shutdown of existing
casinos, which have allowed the tribes to escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Some proponents say that many reservations are too remote to
support a big casino. California will not become like Nevada or
Atlantic City, N.J., they say, because the casinos will be sparsely
scattered and each tribe can have no more than 2,000 slot machines,
about the number found in a mid-size casino in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-four thousand machines is not going to turn California
into anything huge,'' said Anthony Pico, chairman of the Viejas
Band of Kumeyaay Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Pico said his 300-member tribe had water and sewage, health
insurance and full employment because of its casino about a
30-minute drive east of San Diego. The tribe has acquired a bank
and is buying a television station and building a gambling cruise
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the tribal casinos could become more
attractive with the modern slot machines that would be permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. says that expanded gambling in California
would divert $626 million, or about 6.9 percent, of Nevada's
gambling revenues in 2004. Hardest hit would be Reno and Laughlin,
a city at the southern tip of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas is expected to be relatively unscathed because it
offers entertainment beyond gambling and is less dependent on
California tourists than other parts of Nevada. The $100 million
casinos being announced in California would pale beside the
billion-dollar theme resorts clustered along the Las Vegas Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Landau, chief financial officer of Boyd Gaming, which
operates several Las Vegas casinos, said, ``It's not like Las Vegas
is going to be reproduced in Palm Springs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1436EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS0305-COX     03-04 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astros expect Central struggle after payroll cut
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Visitors to new Enron Field in Houston this
spring will find the following: a 30-degree hill in deep center
field with a flag pole atop it, all of it in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose idea was that?'' asked new Astros center fielder Roger
Cedeno. ``I thought they were joking.''
</P>
<P>
   It was club president Tal Smith's idea, the layout inspired by
quirky old Crosley Field. But it's not Houston management's only
radical thinking this season. Visitors to Enron also will find
something else: a lesser team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good point,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``You'd like to
go into the new stadium with the strongest team you've had. But the
economics of baseball don't always work out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the franchise's most successful run _ three NL
Central titles in a row and a 283-203 record under manager Larry
Dierker _ the Astros voluntarily took a step back this winter.
Houston management doesn't worry as much about Ken Griffey's
arrival in Cincinnati as it does about St. Louis' upgraded
rotation. The Astros could tumble to third this year.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect to go every year without losing somebody
along the way,'' closer Billy Wagner said. ``But when you make
changes, you don't want to make a lot of big ones _ like we have
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cy Young runner-up Mike Hampton (22-4) was traded away, as was
center fielder Carl Everett (25 home runs, 108 RBIs). The rationale
was the same in both deals; each was approaching free agency, and
the club could not pay to keep them. Still stinging from the Randy
Johnson experience _ three prospects lost for 84 1/3 total innings
_ Houston sent them off.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros know the road well. Hampton is the third ace the team
has lost in three years, after Johnson and Darryl Kile in 1997. The
club lopped off position players Sean Berry and Brad Ausmus after
the 1998 season for similar payroll maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I expect every year,'' manager Larry Dierker
said. ``I think it's a big challenge for (general manager) Gerry
(Hunsicker), as much or more than for us, because he's got a
payroll limit. He has to find ways.''
</P>
<P>
   In what should be a celebrated time, Hunsicker has assembled a
lesser cast. Hampton, who made it clear he would not discuss a
contract extension, went to the New York Mets, along with
disgruntled outfielder Derek Bell, for Cedeno and right-handed
starter Octavio Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who enters his last season before free-agent
eligibility, went to Boston for shortstop prospect Adam Everett and
pitcher Greg Miller. Adam Everett is highly regarded but is still a
year away from consideration for the majors. Dotel joins the bottom
of the rotation, Cedeno takes over in center, and the Astros try to
say that will be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The club's anchor of Craig Biggio (34 years old) and Jeff
Bagwell (32 in May) remains, and the team expects a big year from
Moises Alou after a year's absence with a damaged knee. But minus
an ace and Everett's production, another division title might be
too much to ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly doesn't become easier,'' said Hunsicker, the 1998
NL executive of the year. ``You know you're trying to beat the odds
every year. It's just reality. Unfortunately, there's a direct
correlation between money and success in this business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spending money certainly doesn't guarantee anything, but not
spending, at least to a certain level, pretty much guarantees
you're not going to be able to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, though hardly cash-strapped, have midmarket
financial restrictions. While their projected payroll of $48
million is nowhere near the Braves' $83 million-plus, Houston has
determined to cut losses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite drawing 2.7 million fans a year ago and a guaranteed 3
million with the opening of Enron Field, owner Drayton McLane
ordered an $8 million reduction in 2000 payroll. McLane, who never
saw a major-league game until he purchased the club in 1993, claims
the Astros have lost $100 million since then.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Everett signed a four-year contract worth $30
million. In New York, Hampton already has said he will explore free
agency next fall instead of re-signing with the Mets, and he'll
fetch top dollar. If those developments aren't enough vindication
for Hunsicker's moves, he need only consider pitchers Freddy Garcia
and John Halama, who would have had big roles in Houston if they
hadn't been shipped to Seattle for Johnson and his two months of
the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things that have to start happening for (the
new players) to get us going,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the past three seasons, the Braves and Astros have met
in the postseason. The series might not have made the blood boil,
as the New York Mets and the 1999 NLCS did, but the two teams and
the two organizations developed a sense of respect. However, it
might be a while before the Astros are back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd told me with all the injuries we had last year, that
we're still going to win, I'd say you're crazy,'' Bagwell said.
``But you know what? We're going to have to try it again this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
