<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: W., IN THE PINK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONY BROOK, N.Y. _ Like trapeze artists, the Republican
governors catch George W. Bush as he flies into their states and
swing him through the air, trying to get him to the platform
safely.
</P>
<P>
   They supply the machines and muscle and brass-knuckle
strategists and line of attack for those blistering ads. They
remold W. into whatever will work for their states.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, former Gov. David Beasley banished
Compassionate Conservative Bush and gave a bear hug to Bob Jones
Bush. In Michigan, Gov. John Engler banished Bob Jones Bush and
wrapped his Catholic arms around Moderate Compassionate Reformer
With Results Bush. In Arizona, Gov. Jane Hull contrasted Stormy
McCain with Sunny Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes New York. It's George Pataki's turn to dangle W., his
old Yale classmate, from his wrists. He's determined not to drop
his charge, as Engler and Hull did, or leave him black-and-blue, as
Beasley did.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has come up with a truly novel incarnation: Breast Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The New York governor and the Texas governor sashayed onto the
stage at the State University of New York at Stony Brook sporting
little pink ribbons on their lapels. (To add authenticity to the
portrait of men dripping with female empathy, they had Elizabeth
Dole trotting alongside W., for the first time in weeks.)
</P>
<P>
   The pink ribbons were designed to trip up John McCain once and
for all. The Bush campaign aired a radio ad scorching the Arizona
senator as an opponent of breast cancer financing.
</P>
<P>
   In his anti-pork crusade, McCain has targeted some health
spending that was slipped into unrelated bills, including some for
breast cancer facilities in New York. But that hardly defines him
as a breast cancer research opponent. The ad, with its selective
reading of the McCain record, makes no mention, of course, of other
breast cancer research he supported.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki team chose Long Island for its panel discussion on
breast cancer and press conference because it has high rates of the
disease and is a locus of anti-cancer activism.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush crew had some queasiness when Salon reported, after the
ad began running, that McCain's sister suffers from breast cancer.
But the Pataki team told the Bushies to buck up, outlining Bush's
comeback that it was ``all the more reason to remind him what he
said about the research that goes on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's state, meanwhile, has the highest percentage of women
without health insurance, according to one private health group,
and four in 10 women over 50 haven't had a mammogram in two years.
</P>
<P>
   W., who was merely following the Pataki script, had no new
proposals to fight breast cancer. When asked what he had done in
Texas, he hemmed and hawed, mentioning his wife's efforts to
encourage early detection and admitting he wasn't sure if there was
money in his state budget for cancer research centers. ``I'll have
to check,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   It was sickening to see the laudable goal of fighting breast
cancer twisted into just another campaign blast.
</P>
<P>
   Equally sulfurous was another ad, this one sponsored by the
so-called Republicans for Clean Air, lauding Bush as a great
environmentalist despite the notorious Texas smog.
</P>
<P>
   While W. denied having anything to do with the ad, one of his
big contributors, Texas businessman Sam Wyly, a Bush Pioneer, owned
up on Friday to paying $2.5 million to broadcast the ad in New
York, California and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   So here was W., who has been laboring to rap McCain as a
Democrat, wrapping himself in such Democratic issues as the
environment and women's health.
</P>
<P>
   As the McCain bus rolled from Grand Central to a Wall Street
rally on Friday, the candidate and his two renegade supporters,
Rep. Peter King and the Staten Island borough president, Guy
Molinari, discussed the Bush ad, which they referred to in
shorthand as ``the breast.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked McCain why he always seemed so taken aback and aggrieved
at each new ploy, given the predictability of tough Bush campaign
tactics. ``I'm not surprised,'' he objected. Then after a second,
he admitted: ``Oh, maybe I am. I am surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   But the senator has a fatalist streak. He knows that if he
survives Super Tuesday, he'll be treated to the grand finale of the
gubernatorial trapeze act in Texas and Florida _ with two guys
named Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
