<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6731 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-RDP-1STLD-WR     03-04 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN AND BUSH FACE CRUCIAL TEST IN TUESDAY VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (subs 7th graf to remove references to 2 states) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After an extraordinary five-week roller coaster of
contests, the Republican presidential contenders head into Tuesday
_ the most consequential and climactic primary day of the 2000
campaign _ with Sen. John McCain determined, at long last, to crack
Gov. George W. Bush's hold on party loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the political swings have been as turbulent as the
stock market in recent days, no one can safely predict how voters
will size up their choices in the 13 Republican primaries or
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But a close examination of the contests in those states, based
on interviews with strategists and politicians, and on fresh
polling data, found that with the exceptions of New York and New
England, McCain has had difficulty moving past the base of
independents and Democrats who propelled him into the most
competitive primary struggle in decades _ and one of the most
vitriolic.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling contests amount to the closest this country has
ever come to a national primary, with races in every region and
nearly one-third of the national convention delegates at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The battle has centered mostly on the electoral powerhouses of
California and New York, the biggest delegate prizes, and, to a
lesser degree, Ohio. McCain has the best shot of pulling off a
victory in New York, polls show, and Bush is ahead in California
and Ohio. But the rivals are competing mightily for the popular
vote in California, which carries no delegates but could be an
important lift for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins two out of those three contests would be well on
his path to the nomination. Those three states have always been
critical for candidates in a general election. Now, for the first
time in decades, they are primary battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The predicament for McCain is that except in his home state of
Arizona, he did not capture more than 40 percent of the vote from
self-identified Republicans in any of the contests thus far. And
polls show that McCain is drawing 40 percent or more of the vote
only in one state voting Tuesday: New York.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Davenport, who ran the delegate operation for Bob Dole in
1996 and is neutral this year, said he had seen no evidence that
McCain was making headway with Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a little too late to move the fumbers,'' he said.
``The Bush campaign has done a good job at painting George Bush as
the Republican candidate who supports all of the Republican
platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who have not had a major contest since New Hampshire
on Feb. 1, are on ballots from coast to coast Tuesday. But with
Vice President Al Gore having won all of his party's contests thus
far _ and former Sen. Bill Bradley trailing in the polls in every
state voting Tuesday _ most leading Democrats have pronounced the
race all but over.
</P>
<P>
   Before McCain's impressive upsets in New Hampshire and Michigan,
most Republicans had predicted that Bush, with his stacks of money
and endorsements, would have wrapped up the nomination earlier.
Now, after McCain's losses last week in Virginia, Washington state
and North Dakota, the pressure is on him to prove that he can
attract Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   So far, McCain has benefited from victories in states where
independents and Democrats could rally behind him in Republican
primaries. There are far fewer ``open contests'' coming up.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of McCain's advisers acknowledged that they were
having trouble winning over loyal Republicans. The problem, they
said, is that the recent discourse has been dominated by charges
and counter-charges over advertising tactics _ and over McCain's
condemnation of two religious conservative leaders _ that have
prevented the senator from hammering at his message that he is a
conservative in the Reagan mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're talking about campaign reform and cutting spending
and saving the military, Republicans are very supportive,'' said
Dan Schnur, the McCain campaign's communications director. ``When
we get bogged down in push-polling and third-party attack ads and
Pat Robertson, we lose our way and the less time there is to sell
the reform message. And that's what's going to win it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   In states like Maryland, where independents can vote in the
Republican primary, McCain supporters said they had all but given
up trying to appeal to the Republican faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our effort is better spent trying to get out the independents,
instead of trying to convince Republicans to change their minds,''
said Donald E. Murphy, a state delegate and one of the few elected
Republicans in the state who supports McCain.
</P>
<P>
   By aggressively emphasizing McCain's tensions with religious
conservatives, the Bush campaign is trying to stir a backlash among
Republicans _ and to score enough victories Tuesday to put down the
McCain candidacy once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that this is all about delegates right now,'' said
Scott Reed, who ran the Dole campaign four years ago. ``This is
about momentum and direction and putting away the McCain
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, is confident to the point of
being almost dismissive of McCain. That is in part a reflection of
Bush's triple victory last week. And no matter what happens
Tuesday, Bush is well positioned a week later when the contest
turns south and he has enormous advantages in his home state of
Texas and in Florida, where his brother, Jeb Bush, is governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the flavor du jour _ or was,'' Rove said, speaking of
McCain. ``There's a little bit of traction with the guy but it's
not durable, it's not long lasting, and it hasn't been.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both camps concede that McCain is not likely to catch up to win
the Republican vote in California, which means Bush would get all
the delegates. But McCain hopes to beat Bush in the popular vote,
which includes Democrats and independents. Rove said he believed
Bush may well surpass McCain in what it called the ``beauty
contest.'' Yet if there is such a split verdict _ if Bush wins the
delegates and McCain wins the popular vote _ the senator could
challenge the results and could make the case that he is more
electable because he attracts Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain camp is counting on a triumph in New York and a sweep
of the New England states. McCain seems to be running best among
Republicans in those states because they have more moderate voters
who are most hospitable to his message of campaign reform and his
attacks on religious conservatives. McCain is also competing
aggressively in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush campaign officials said they were confident
that besides California, they would prevail in New York and Ohio.
Just as McCain is running relatively uncontested in New England,
the same is true for Bush in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, the McCain campaign has seemed on the
defensive, and has been somewhat off stride because of internal
sniping and tactical blunders. For example, McCain had at first
dropped out of a nationally televised debate in Los Angeles on
Thursday with Bush and Alan Keyes. After the decision drew scalding
publicity in the state, McCain relented and agreed to participate,
but by a satellite linkup.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest question that will be answered Tuesday is
whether McCain can persuade traditional Republican voters to
support him. Both campaigns are concentrating their television
advertisements in New York, California, Ohio, Missouri and Maryland
as they make appeals to Republican voters. Here in California,
McCain has appealed to those voters in television commercials in
which he portrays himself as heir to the Reagan legacy. His
campaign has focused its energies _ and McCain's appearances _ on
Orange and San Diego Counties in Southern California. He has also
held rallies in inland cities like Stockton, Fresno, Bakersfield
and Riverside, which are more conservative than cities closer to
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But in many states, McCain's supporters said they had all but
given up trying to woo hard-core Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, one of the most conservative states voting Tuesday,
the McCain campaign has essentially conceded the race to Bush. For
McCain, the state, with its increasingly urban population, was one
of his best hopes to break the governor's hold on the South. But
the candidate has not visited the state recently, and the
campaign's resources largely consist of volunteers and used, pasted
over campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   Kil Townsend, a veteran organizer who has volunteered to help
McCain's seat-of-the-pants effort in Georgia, groused at how the
candidate has neglected the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Up north in Minnesota, Bush also has a far more organized
campaign than McCain. That has left the senator's loyalists trying
to court independents who can vote in the caucuses on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials in the state said McCain had picked up
support in the area, but not among traditional Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional and core Republicans like we have here are going
to stick with the established candidate, Bush,'' said Chris
Jacobson, a local Republican official. ``As a rule, we're pretty
tried and true. One of our concerns is how many independents and
Democrats will be crossing the lines. But Bush seems to have a
stronghold on Republican voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides painting McCain as divisive and questioning his
Republican credentials, Bush has highlighted some of the more
moderate elements of his record in states where conservatives are
less of a factor in the primary electorate.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, for example, the Bush campaign produced a
statewide mailing, radio advertisements and telephone banks to
emphasize the candidate's position on such local issues as his
support of mass transit and of the Seawolf, a nuclear submarine
produced in Groton.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain organization appears far less organized. Richard
Foley, a former state Republican chairman who is a leading McCain
backer in the state, said after the New Hampshire primary, McCain
supporters collected weathered McCain placards to use back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw as many as we could in our cars after New
Hampshire,'' Foley said. ``We're not above it all. There's no room
for the guys in the expensive suits with the $20 cigars on our
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
