<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6737 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GIBBS0305-COX     03-04 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GIBBS0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gibbs: doctor of defense
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The first thing Gary Gibbs has had to do is get
used to living somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's new defensive coordinator hasn't lived anywhere other
than Norman, Okla., for 30 years. And during that time, Gibbs spent
almost every waking moment focused on either his family or Oklahoma
Sooners football.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs starred as an inside linebacker on two Oklahoma national
championship teams in the 1970s and was 32-1-1 as a starter. He
stayed on as a graduate assistant, was promoted to part-time, then
full-time assistant, then coordinator and, finally, head coach. A
native of Texas, Gibbs even remained in Oklahoma after being forced
out as head coach in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Norman is 1,000 miles away _ in both literal and figurative
terms _ and Gibbs is starting a new life in a new place. He left
his family and the Sooners behind to try to help his old friend
return the Bulldogs to glory.
</P>
<P>
   SETTLING IN
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen, Athens is a lot like Norman,'' said
Gibbs, hired by coach Jim Donnan on Valentine's Day. ``Things
revolve around the university. It's a great place to raise a
family; there's a lot of interest in the team. But I really haven't
had a chance to get out and look around very much. I've really just
gone from point A to point B most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Point A'' is his suite at the Holiday Inn Express hotel on
Broad Street, and ``point B'' is his office on the second floor of
Butts-Mehre Heritage Hall. Gibbs arrives at work at 5:30 each
morning and he doesn't leave until 8:30 or 9 at night.
</P>
<P>
   He has a lot of work to do. Anyone who watched Georgia play
defense last year can attest to that.
</P>
<P>
   Under former defensive coordinator Kevin Ramsey, the Bulldogs
(8-4) finished last in the SEC in total defense (382.6 ypg) and
11th in scoring defense (25.9 ppg). They gave up an average of 39
points a game in losses to Tennessee, Florida, Auburn and Georgia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs' task as Georgia's third defensive coordinator in three
years is to make sure that it doesn't happen again. His credentials
say it shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners posted impressive defensive numbers under Gibbs.
Their final national rankings were second in total defense and
first in rushing defense in 1984; first in total defense and second
in rushing and scoring defense in 1985; first in total, rushing,
passing and scoring defense in 1986; and first in total, passing
and scoring defense in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, Oklahoma finished sixth, first, third and
third in the final AP polls during those seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gary Gibbs, with all due respect to all of our
coaches, is Coach Donnan's best hire,'' athletics director Vince
Dooley said. ``He has an incredible record of success as a
defensive coordinator. Not only is he an excellent coach, but he's
highly regarded in college athletics as a man of high integrity....
I think he's just what the doctor ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oklahoma, competing then in the run-oriented Big Eight
Conference, wasn't facing offenses as sophisticated as college
teams are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has changed, certainly,'' Gibbs conceded. ``I don't
think I'm going to come in here and wave a magic wand and recreate
the defenses that we had at Oklahoma. That was a unique group that
really accomplished a lot....
</P>
<P>
   ``But Georgia is an outstanding program. We've got good athletes
here. What we want to do as a staff and as a unit is just to
understand our roles and what we have to do to achieve certain
goals. And have fun doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE SCHEMES FLEXIBLE
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey swore by pressure, attacking defense. Gibbs swears to no
single scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to doing what you have to do defensively to win,
and there's not one answer to that,'' he said. ``Coach (Barry)
Switzer used to say, `It's not the alignment that's important; it's
the alignees.' I believe that. It's what kind of players you have
and creating situations that are in your favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs has been on the job just three weeks and only 10 days
remain before spring practice begins, so he is hesitant to make an
assessment. But he will offer this: Few of Georgia's problems have
anything to do with talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got good speed and quickness and guys who can run,'' he
said. ``You see spurts of great team speed. You see Richard
(Seymour) and Marcus (Stroud) making plays and Boss (Bailey) making
plays. But, you know, there's a thin line between winning and
losing. There's usually seven or eight plays that make the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs said Georgia came up on the short end of most of those
plays last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes teams beat themselves,'' he said. ``You hear that
about offenses all the time, that they had too many turnovers or
they didn't convert third down or just didn't execute, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the same thing applies on defense. If we've got a
linebacker who misaligns or he's got coverage on the tight end but
he covers the back and the tight end's free, that wasn't physical,
that was mental.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Gibbs said, he isn't going to totally remake the Georgia
defense. A tweak here and there, a lot of work on fundamentals and
an attitude adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to bring in a new playbook,'' he said. ``We're
just going to put a new cover on the old one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
