<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPY-NERVE-GAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DANGLED POISON SECRETS BEFORE SOVIETS, BOOK REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An American double agent working for the FBI
provided the Soviet Union with nerve gas data in the 1960s that may
have spurred Moscow's own efforts to develop chemical weapons, says
a new book on the espionage case.
</P>
<P>
   The spy, an Army sergeant, was told by the U.S. government to
hand over the nerve gas information, the book says.
</P>
<P>
   The American officials had decided to give the Soviet Union the
secret nerve gas data because they hoped the information would lead
it down the wrong path in the development of its own chemical
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   The data concerned a formula that the United States had tried to
develop but had then abandoned because it was considered too
unstable for weapons use. By giving it to the Soviets, American
officials hoped, they would lead Moscow to waste time trying to
develop an unusable nerve agent.
</P>
<P>
   But questions remain about whether the American information
actually aided the Soviets, according to the book.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that the nerve gas formulas passed to the
Soviets led them to develop new chemical weapons. But intelligence
gathered about the U.S. weapons program may have prompted the
Soviets to conduct more intensive research and development on their
own program, the book says.
</P>
<P>
   The complex double-agent case in which the nerve gas information
played a central role has been revealed for the first time in a new
book, ``Cassidy's Run: The Secret Spy War Over Nerve Gas,'' by a
Washington-based author, David Wise, and is to be published this
month by Random House.
</P>
<P>
   The story centers on Joseph Cassidy, an Army sergeant whom the
book calls the FBI's longest-running double agent of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Selected by the FBI from a pool of noncommissioned officers in
1959 as a ``dangle'' to lure Soviet intelligence officers to
recruit him as a spy, Cassidy worked as an FBI double agent against
the Soviet Union for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   His case, code-named Operation Shocker, was designed to learn
more about Soviet intelligence operations in America and to keep
the Russians busy with an American agent under FBI control, rather
than with real spies.
</P>
<P>
   The book says that the Cassidy case ultimately allowed the FBI
to unearth deep-cover Soviet moles operating in the United States
who were assigned by the Soviets to work with Cassidy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is extremely accurate about my role as a double
agent,'' Cassidy, now 79 and living in retirement in Florida, said
in an interview. The FBI declined to comment on the book.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had to allow Cassidy to pass the Soviets some
genuine secrets in order to keep them interested, the book says. By
establishing his credibility with real secrets, Cassidy was then in
a position to give distorted information to the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, while Cassidy was assigned to the Army's Edgewood
Arsenal in Maryland, where the government was then developing
chemical and biological weapons, the FBI had him pass the Soviets
information about a nerve gas agent on which the United States had
done research.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had halted research on the nerve agent, called
GJ, and it had never been developed into a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   But Cassidy passed the Soviets documents that indicated that the
United States had successfully created the nerve agent, to try to
convince the Soviets that the United States was ahead in nerve gas
development.
</P>
<P>
   Real information about the U.S. research effort on the nerve gas
was mixed in with the fake documents.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve gas deception operation ran for 3{ years, as Cassidy
repeatedly passed documents _ some real, some fake _ to the Soviets
about the GJ nerve gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
