<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-RULE-CHANGE-2TAKES(1100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END TO SOCIAL SECURITY PENALTY WELCOMED BY COMPANIES AND THEIR
WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN with LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At McDonald's Corp. in Oak Brook, Ill., the oldest
workers, those 65 to 69, scrutinized their paychecks as the end of
each year approached. Last year, when their accumulated wages
neared a magic number, $15,500, many resigned. ``A senior would
sadly say, `I can't afford to work here anymore,''' said Walt
Riker, the company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   As McDonald's workers went, so went Emily Galvenz, 68, of Miami,
out walking in a park on Thursday. ``That was one of the reasons I
never took a full-time job after I retired,'' said Galvenz, who
works part-time managing a beauty salon. ``It just hurts to give
money like that away to the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that from now on, Galvenz and the McDonald's
employees will be able to work and earn as much as they like _ with
the enthusiastic blessings of their employers.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by election-year politics and complaints from employers
scrambling to find enough workers to help them keep the boom alive,
the House voted 422-0 on Wednesday to purge the Social Security
laws of a relic of the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the provision has reduced the benefits of workers
ages 65 through 69 for every dollar they earned over a certain
amount. At the time it was enacted, the law was designed to move
older workers aside in favor of younger ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and President Clinton are widely expected to go
along, and the bill they are considering would be retroactive, to
the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Across virtually every sector of the economy, the initiative is
receiving enthusiastic acclaim, reflecting the now-rare unanimity
among lawmakers of both parties on Capitol Hill. With the sole
possible exception of the leadership of organized labor, which has
yet to take a position, this is one of those exceptional government
initiatives that hardly anyone faults publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But while saying the overall effects should be positive for
workers, their employers and the economy, some experts in workplace
management say it creates new challenges for employers in managing
older work forces and, once the economy stalls, in dispensing of
those who have lost their edge. Increasingly, they say, retirement
is becoming a matter of negotiation, requiring new flexibility in
setting workers' schedules and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many corporations will look to phased retirement,''
said John Woyke, principal of Towers Perrin, a human resources
consulting firm in New York. ``In the typical job _ especially in
the service economy where people aren't constrained by their
muscles _ we do not see a decline in ability at age 65.'' And in
this tight job market, he said, ``we will see a definite number of
initiatives to encourage people to stay longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, older workers are docked $1 in Social
Security benefits for every $3 they earn above a limit the
government sets _ rising to $17,000 for this year from $15,500. The
repeal means little for those who earn less than $17,000. At
$20,000 in wages, the worker loses $1,000 in benefits. And at about
$68,000, the worker loses it all, up to $17,196 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unambiguously a good thing,'' said Gary Burtless,
labor economist at the Brookings Institution in Washington. At the
point at which workers start losing Social Security benefits, he
said his research has shown, they simply stop work because they see
themselves paying an additional tax on top of all their other
taxes. ``It's just a pure bad tax,'' Burtless said.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Morton, a lobbyist for the AARP, calls it ``good labor
policy, good social policy and good economic policy.'' Bruce
Josten, executive vice president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
said, ``Everyone's running out of workers. Anything that will
ameliorate that problem is useful.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's biggest retailer, Wal-Mart Stores, is also one of
its biggest employers, with 885,000 workers in the United States.
The company does not know how many are older than 65, but it says
134,000 are over 55.
</P>
<P>
   Most Wal-Mart employees earn low wages, less than $10 an hour.
But when they do cross the $17,000 annual threshold, or about $8.30
an hour for a full-time job, the penalty kicks in at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This House vote will mean a lot to them and it will make us
happy too,'' said Tom Williams, a Wal-Mart spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The repeal also pleases a company where workers earn vastly more
than at Wal-Mart _ Lockheed Martin Corp. in Bethesda, Md., the
giant defense contractor. There, older professional workers
routinely earn more than $68,784 a year, the point at which the
$1-for-$3 formula wipes out their entire Social Security benefit.
Restored, the benefit comes as a significant bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might cause people with deep experience to stay longer,''
said James Fetig, a Lockheed spokesman. After Lockheed experienced
a series of rocket launch failures, Fetig said, an analysis showed
that one reason was that too many ``mature, first generation''
rocket scientists had left the company in the mergers and
downsizings of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   At General Mills in Minneapolis, one of the nation's oldest big
companies, Michael Peel, the vice president for human resources,
says the company has ``lots and lots'' of employees who are in
their 60s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view it as irreplaceable talent,'' Peel said. ``And given
the demographic crunch in our country and the scarcity of
intellectual capital,'' the repeal of the earnings limitation
``will have a beneficial impact'' on the company's efforts to hold
onto those workers.
</P>
<P>
   Jana Weatherbee, spokeswoman at IBM, said, ``The basic point is
that we want the skills that will win in the marketplace, and these
skills come across in all ages.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, at least, concerns about whether workers'
performance declines with age appears not to be an issue, or at
least not one that employers openly discuss. With the job market so
tight, consultants say employers have an incentive to retrain
workers with expiring skills, or move them to jobs where they can
be more productive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they say, employers have another reason for holding
on to the workers they have even if the economy slows: the
baby-boom population is moving into its 50s, and far fewer younger
workers are coming up behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a corporation wants to get rid of its work force it has
no problem doing it,'' said William Goldberg, partner in charge of
personal financial planning in the Houston office of KPMG, the
consulting firm. ``It is just the opposite in this tight labor
market.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At universities, where complaints of doddering tenured
professors have become commonplace, administrators say they doubt
that the ending the earnings limitation will have much to do with
the professors' choices to stay or move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals, either at the faculty or at the staff level, at
that age level, at that age bracket, view working for the
university as a calling,'' said Sheldon Steinbach, general counsel
at the American Council on Education, which represents 1,800 public
and private colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as a profession,'' Steinbach said, ``rather than as a job.
And to the best of my understanding, no individual in the past,
present or future, viewed the cap as an impediment or a stricture
on their desire to continue to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But for workers in other fields, the repeal is likely to achieve
just what employers and lawmakers hope in expanding the labor
force.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Homer May of Sagamore Beach, who turned 65 in
June, said he would not let the repeal thwart his plans to retire
soon from his job as a mechanical piping designer. ``We want to go
places and do things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also plans to work, part-time, until he reached the
earnings limit of $17,000. ``My cap was like four days a month,''
he said, ``and this will give me the opportunity to be a little
more flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend and fellow piping designer, Robert Flaherty, of
Quincy, Mass., turned 65 on Wednesday, and he has no plans yet to
slow down or retire. ``But the concern about making the money and
losing the Social Security was down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew people,'' Flaherty said, ``who worked for me some years
ago when the limit was $7,000, and they would work until three in
the afternoon, and they would leave because they didn't want to
lose any Social Security money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
