<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-VIETNAM-WAR-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S CANDIDACY REOPENS VIETNAM-ERA WOUNDS FOR CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Next month's 25-year anniversary of the fall of Saigon
and the presidential campaign of Sen. John McCain are reopening a
long forgotten fissure between two groups of Canadian
50-somethings: the roughly 25,000 American draft dodgers still
living here, and the almost equal number of Canadians who
volunteered to fight in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where most people have access to American
television news, scenes of crowds flocking to hear McCain are
striking deep chords among the Vietnam War generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been surprised by the deep emotional responses _ anger
and resentment, empathy and compassion,'' said Michael J. Strada, a
West Virginia professor who did not flee to Canada but has been
researching those who did, connecting the ``dodger diaspora''
through an e-mail chat list.
</P>
<P>
   How draft dodgers feel about McCain's candidacy has a lot to do
with how they see themselves today, 30 years after they left the
United States. Those who have climbed into the establishment here _
as lawyers, business executives, teachers and doctors _ are more
even-handed about the political popularity of the Vietnam veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Others who are less well-off are sometimes still hostile about
what drove them to leave and are critical of the McCain candidacy.
And among Canadians who voluntarily signed up to fight with the
Americans, the senator's compelling story makes him a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Diamond, a social worker who came here from Connecticut
in the fall of 1968, sees the political rise of McCain as heralding
a simplistic revisionism of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is rehabilitating the war by bringing up the fact that he
went to Vietnam, that he did his duty, that he was a POW, defending
the U.S.,'' said Diamond, a University of Hartford graduate who
works here with homeless people. ``It would take an awfully big
person to say, `I was a POW for 5{ years, and I was wrong, and my
country was wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lebowitz, who left his home in New York to escape the
draft and is now president of a Vancouver software development
company, said: ``John McCain represents the aging of an American
generation. And he represents it with grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Malboeuf was a Vietnam volunteer who crossed the border
heading south, signing up for a two-year stint with the U.S. Army's
101st Airborne in Vietnam. Today, he sees McCain's rise as
vindication for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see him win it,'' said Malboeuf, a salesman
who is active in a Toronto chapter of a Canadian Vietnam veterans
group. ``He would bring back some credibility, some respect for the
veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate also focuses attention on a rare northbound migration
in modern North America. Americans often see population movement
along the Canadian border as uniformly southbound with Canadians
moving to the United States for lower taxes, milder weather and
better jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But upheavals in the United States have provided immigrants to
Canada: British loyalists after the Revolutionary War,
African-Americans escaping slavery before the Civil War, farmers
during Canada's Western land rush, and in the late 1960s, about
50,000 young men who came to Canada to escape the Vietnam draft.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's government accepted American draft evaders by
forbidding its authorities to ask American men about their draft
status. In 1969, after a heated debate, Prime Minister Pierre
Trudeau extended Canada's welcome to American military deserters.
Roughly 1,000 deserters are believed to have taken refuge in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the dodgers and deserters are believed to have
gone home after President Jimmy Carter declared an amnesty in
January 1977, his first official act as president.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Canadian volunteers returned home, they were
greeted like mercenaries, according to Tracey Arial, author of ``I
Volunteered: Canadian Vietnam Vets Remember'' (Watson &AMP; Dwyer,
1997). Referring to their historically low profile here, she said:
``The only time these guys get called by the media is on the
anniversary of My Lai. The draft dodgers get all the coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Vandals have occasionally hit the two Canadian memorials to the
110 countrymen who died fighting in Vietnam. In the late 1990s,
Canadian federal officials said that Vietnam was not Canada's war
and refused to allot public space in Ottawa for a war memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Now, emboldened by the political rise of McCain, the volunteers
are emerging from the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCain would make a good president _ if I was there,
he would have my vote,'' said Lee Hitchins, a U.S. Navy veteran,
who is president of the Canadian Vietnam Veterans in Ottawa.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Canadian veterans are nearly unanimous in saying they feel
vindicated by McCain's rise, the aging draft dodgers are split.
</P>
<P>
   Hostility to the presidential ambitions of an unapologetic
Vietnam veteran comes from some dodgers who remain outside of
Canada's power circles, men like Diamond, the social worker, or
Morgan Davis, a professional blues singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain fits like a glove as far as the United States goes,''
said Davis, a former California campus radical with the Students
for a Democratic Society. A resident here since 1968, Davis added:
``It's an imperialistic nation. They love to have war heroes _ John
F. Kennedy, Dwight Eisenhower.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, 31 Canadian organizations worked to help
American draft dodgers make the transition here. Today, all these
groups have vanished, largely because the Americans, mostly middle
class college graduates, have proved to be successful immigrants.
They include university professors, a Toronto business consultant,
a Montreal psychiatrist, a Vancouver airline pilot, and, in Ottawa,
a member of the National Parole Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an expatriate but I can't remember why,'' said Lebowitz,
the president of the software development company.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back 35 years to when he was an 18-year-old growing up
in New York, Lebowitz said that he and McCain made different
choices, partly in response to different upbringings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was third generation Annapolis,'' he continued. ``I grew up
in a left-wing American household in Flushing. I grew up hating the
McCarthyites that killed the Rosenbergs,'' referring to the
execution of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg in 1953 on espionage
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Similar views came from Dave Lutz, who left a teaching job in
Brooklyn in the summer of 1969 to escape the draft. He came to New
Brunswick, where this one-time ``long-hair,'' as he described
himself, rose to become president of the provincial law society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an accident of history that I am here, and did not go
to Vietnam,'' he said, talking on his cell phone as he drove to a
skiing weekend in Maine. Most of the draft dodgers who stayed in
Canada have dual citizenship, and regularly visit the land of their
birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as revisionist,'' he said of the response by
American voters to McCain's war record. ``The country is
desperately looking for a hero, and this happens to be the guy with
the credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   Strada, who teaches political science at West Virginia
University, said that many Canadian-American draft dodgers today
``view vets as co-victims of the Vietnam War.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deep philosophical difference between vets and
draft dodgers,'' said the professor, who has interviewed about 75
American dodgers in Canada for his research. ``But today I see
expressed by the draft dodgers a considerable amount of empathy for
the suffering that veterans went through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1457EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
