<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CALIF-RULES-ASSESS-NY     03-04 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-RULES-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MCCAIN, A FAINT ECHO OF EISENHOWER'S COUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas, Pa., Ohio, N.H., Mich., Mass., Conn., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A war hero challenged the choice of the
establishment, a member of an old political clan, for the
Republican presidential nomination. For reasons that were not
entirely clear, the war hero, who saw himself as a stout
conservative, was considered too liberal by the party's old guard.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign unfolded, the war hero's undoubted popularity
with the public prompted newspapers to suggest that only he could
defeat the Democratic nominee in the fall. But the state-by-state
rules governing the selection of delegates were stacked against
him, and his rival was the clear favorite when the convention
opened, with 530 delegates to the war hero's 427.
</P>
<P>
   So the hero challenged the rules with a cleverly named ``Fair
Play'' amendment, promoted with banners proclaiming ``Thou Shall
Not Steal!'' and persuaded the convention to overturn them. The
forces of orthodoxy were completely outflanked, and the hero won
the nomination. In November, to no one's surprise, he was elected
president by a decisive majority.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1952, the contenders Dwight D. Eisenhower, the
liberator of Europe, and Robert A. Taft, the son of former
President William Howard Taft. Nearly a half century later,
Republican politicians are looking back to that tumultuous
convention in Chicago's International Amphitheater and wondering
whether something vaguely similar might happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the obvious similarities, there are major
differences between the half-forgotten Republican contest of 1952
and the battle between this year's war hero, Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, and this year's establishment standard-bearer, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas. Unlike McCain, Eisenhower was a political
neophyte; unlike Bush, Sen. Taft was the most prominent member of
his party, twice before a contender for the presidency and
thoroughly tested in the politics of Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most delegates are chosen in primaries and caucuses
rather than by party leaders, as in 1952, and most of them arrive
at conventions already committed. That means there is less room for
insider maneuvering. In 1952, the delegations of Michigan,
California and Pennsylvania were at least nominally unpledged _ a
pool of votes that Eisenhower ultimately managed to tap. (A
byproduct of the need to woo California was the choice of its
junior senator, Richard M. Nixon, as the vice presidential
nominee).
</P>
<P>
   But the peculiarities of the California election law could
conceivably precipitate a credentials fight at Philadelphia this
summer, as did unusual procedures at the Texas state Republican
convention in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The primary in California is in two parts. In the first, all
registered voters will chose among presidential candidates of all
parties, listed on the same ``bedsheet'' ballot; that so-called
beauty contest will give a strong hint as to which candidates have
the best chances of capturing the coveted electoral votes of the
nation's biggest state in November.
</P>
<P>
   But because of Republican party rules, it will have no impact on
the choice of California's 162 convention delegates. They will be
allocated strictly on the basis of votes cast by registered
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush inherits no great California following from his father,
former President George Bush, who wrote off the state in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite possible that McCain, who has scored heavily in
states where Democrats and independents crossed over in large
numbers to vote for him, could defeat Bush in the beauty contest
yet lose the convention delegates to him. Indeed, one of the
shrewdest observers of California politics, Bill Carrick, a
Democratic campaign consultant, has suggested that as one logical
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   If it happens on Tuesday _ a large ``if'' _ and if McCain
manages to win a significant number of the other primaries the same
day, including Massachusetts, Connecticut, New York and perhaps
Ohio _ another big ``if'' _ the Arizonan would have a significant
bloc of delegates. Would he then challenge the credentials of a
California delegation pledged to a candidate whom he had beaten in
the state's all-comers contest?
</P>
<P>
   It would not necessarily be a lopsided fight if he chose to do
so; under the present party rules, contested delegates cannot vote
on their own challenged credentials.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has issued no threats, but speaking in Stockton,
Calif., this week, he said that a muddled verdict would present
Republicans with a seriously messy problem.
</P>
<P>
   Although careful to say he did not want ``some big delegate
fight,'' McCain added: ``If there's a split decision, that's going
to be a debate taking place within the Republican Party. Do they
want somebody who won the majority, or do they want somebody who
only won Republican votes?''
</P>
<P>
   Aides, less circumspect, said all options would be considered,
including a lawsuit challenging the delegate-selection process, an
appeal to the California party to share delegates and a credentials
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would argue forcefully, no doubt, that he had played by the
rules in other states and accepted his losses (in New Hampshire and
Michigan, for example) and that McCain should do the same thing in
California. But a new ``fair play'' gambit could put considerable
pressure on him, particularly if he barely eked out a victory in
the Republicans-only vote there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
