<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-DEATH-PENALTY-     03-04 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN GINGERLY QUESTIONS BUSH ON DEATH PENALTY   
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ Sen. John McCain is gingerly questioning Texas
Gov. George W. Bush's refusal to use DNA evidence to review the
guilt or innocence of convicted murderers awaiting execution on
Texas' death row.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, campaigning against Bush for the Republican presidential
nomination, told reporters that executions ought to be suspended
until authorities determine whether the convictions warrant a
second look using high technology identification technology that
relies on genetic material.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that if he were a governor he would ``review every
murder case, every person on death row and see if there's a DNA
application so we can either substantiate their conviction or maybe
give them another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain made his remarks aboard his campaign bus, ``Straight Talk
Express,'' as he traveled from New York City late Friday evening to
a campaign rally in Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has presided over more executions than any governor in
U.S. history, has publicly defended Texas' handling of death
penalty cases _ most recently during the nationally televised
candidates' debate last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has 453 inmates awaiting execution. A total of 121 inmates
have been executed in Texas since Bush became governor in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   McCain conceded that as a member of the U.S. House and Senate
for the past 18 years who has never served as governor of a state,
he had never faced ``an issue like that.'' McCain added: ``But it
just seems to me that I'd be glad to say to my people, `Look,
there's a new technology out there called DNA.'''
</P>
<P>
   McCain contrasted Bush's continuation of executions in Texas
with the decision by Illinois Gov. George Ryan to suspend lethal
injections for convicted murders pending a comprehensive review of
prosecutorial conduct, police investigations and DNA. Ryan ordered
the reassessment after a series of murder convictions were
overturned due to police or prosecutorial misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's action affects 161 inmates on Illinois' death row.
Thirteen convicts condemned to die have been exonerated, some as
the result of DNA tests. Of the 12 convicts executed since 1977,
serious questions have arisen about the innocence of one of those
executed.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan is Bush's campaign chairman in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about the cases in Texas or Illinois,''
McCain told reporters. ``But I know the governor of Illinois said,
`Time out. Let's look at all these cases to see if there's
applicability (for DNA).'''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added: ``If I were the governor of a state and there were
some cases on death row that were on appeal _ which they all are _
I would say, `Okay, why don't we just pause here a minute or a week
or a month or however long it takes you _ and find out those cases
where DNA technology might have some application, look at that and
with the rest of them, press on.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said whenever new technology emerges with possible value
to the criminal justice system, ``It just seems to me that... you
should see if it applies.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain insisted that he didn't intend to ``second guess''
Bush's actions.
</P>
<P>
   As president, McCain said, he would review the convictions of
any federal prisoners on death row, adding: ``I would just make
sure that every person on death row where DNA applied would be
checked out. I don't understand why not.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's comments came in response to a question about Bush's
remarks about the death penalty during Thursday night's televised
debate. Bush defended Texas' justice system, noting that a federal
court had ordered the release of a convicted murderer whose rights
to legal counsel had been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is out,'' Bush said. ``I'm sorry he's out, he's a
really violent person. I hope he gets retried soon. But the system
worked in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that he was ``absolutely confident that everybody who
has been put to death'' during his six years as governor had been
``guilty of the crime charged'' and had had ``full access to our
courts, both state and
</P>
<P>
   federal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush reiterated that he supported the death penalty, saying that
if the penalty is ``administered surely, swiftly and justly it will
save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
