<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BUSH (PORTLAND, Maine) _ Sen. John McCain, seizing upon a
controversial broadcast attack financed by allies of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, urged New Englanders Saturday to soundly reject an
effort ``to hijack an election.'' Bush, campaigning in western New
York en route to the Midwest defended the anti-McCain ad blitz that
he said had been launched without coordination with his
presidential campaign. By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-DEATH PENALTY (PORTLAND, Maine) _ Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., is gingerly questioning Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
refusal to use DNA evidence to review the guilt or innocence of 453
convicted prisoners awaiting execution on Texas' death row. McCain,
campaigning against Bush for the Republican presidential
nomination, told reporters that governors ought to suspend
executions until authorities determine whether the convictions
warrant a second look using high technology identification
technology. Bush, who has presided over more executions than any
governor in history, insists the rights of convicted murderers on
Texas death row are protected by the state and federal court
appeals process without the need for a separate DNA review. BY
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-HISPANIC-VOTE (Chula Vista, Calif.) _ California's primary
Tuesday is a crucial test for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, not only
in his battle against Sen. John McCain for the Republican
nomination, but also in his effort to show that he can attract the
Latino vote, which has traditionally gone Democratic. We look at
how Bush is wooing Hispanic communities. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed
Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JUDICIAL-NOMINATIONS (Washington) _ After a four-year wait, one
of California's most controversial judges is expected to be finally
voted on this coming week in the Senate. Many conservative
Republicans oppose Richard Paez's nomination to the U.S. 9th
Circuit Court of Appeals because they say he is too liberal. But
defenders of Paez, a U.S. District Court judge in Los Angeles, deny
that. By MARK HELM. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ In the current campaign, the men
who would be president have been called such things as liars,
cheats, cowards and phonies. But such vitriol is nothing new. It is
part of a tradition that began in 1796 with the first presidential
clash between Thomas Jefferson and John Adams. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
