<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOBJONES-NYT &LR;      03-04 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOBJONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BOB JONES UNIVERSITY, THE STUDENTS WONDER WHAT ALL THE FUSS IS
ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ The impression one is most likely to gain on
entering the campus of Bob Jones University, a place of yellow
brick buildings and well-kept lawns, is that it is a very long way
from the typical American college. Young men wear neckties. Young
women wear skirts with hemlines at the knee or ankle. No one is
smoking. And a visitor is nearly always addressed as ``Sir.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a place where life is shaped by fundamentalist Christian
beliefs, and by a great many rules as well. Home to 5,000 students,
Bob Jones has a dress code emphasizing modesty. Classes begin with
prayer. Rock music is forbidden, as are alcohol, tobacco and
holding hands during dates. A bell in the dormitories signals
lights-out at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me more disciplined,'' said Miriam Rybak, 20, a
junior from Damascus, Pa., talking with friends outside the student
snack bar.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Stevens, 18, a freshman, agreed. ``Anywhere in life there
are going to be rules, whether they're federal laws or moral
standards,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   And Lauren Dooley, 19, from Tyler Hill, Pa., added, ``It's a lot
less of the party life than other schools, but I think that's a
good thing.'' She also said that she believed she had made her
life's best friends at Bob Jones: ``We all know we love God.''
</P>
<P>
   But if that is part of the larger picture here, it has been
obscured of late by the political firestorm that blew up around Bob
Jones after Gov. George W. Bush of Texas visited the school on Feb.
2. Bush's opponents faulted him for not speaking out against Bob
Jones' ban on interracial dating and its leaders' harsh criticisms
of Roman Catholic beliefs _ positions that seemed at odds with the
pride the university takes in its academic and fine arts programs.
</P>
<P>
   And then, unexpectedly, the university dropped the ban on
Friday, a move announced by its president, Bob Jones III, on CNN's
``Larry King Live.'' It had become a distraction, Jones said. ``Our
concern for the cause of Christ, our concern for our graduates''
was more important, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, the university placed full-page advertisements in
USA Today and South Carolina newspapers saying that it was not
racist and that it did not hate Catholics. On the CNN program,
Jones made similar statements, but he emphasized the theological
differences between Catholics and fundamentalist Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking not just of Catholics but also of Mormons, Buddhists,
Hindus and others, Jones said, ``We wish these people knew the Lord
Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy seems to have taken many students by surprise.
Several said that the issues had not been the subject of discussion
before the political furor provoked by Bush's visit. Some said that
neither they nor others at Bob Jones had any antipathy toward
Catholics _ even if they rejected Catholic teachings about the
church and the sacraments _ and denied that the university was
racist.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Inafuku, 22, a senior from Waiane, Hawaii, who is student
body president, is the son of an East Asian father and a white
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bob Jones were racist, would I be student body president?''
Inafuku asked. ``Would I be allowed to be in this position? I don't
think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones began admitting blacks in 1970 and has a relatively
small number of African-American students. One of them, Angela Lee,
20, a junior from Ellicott City, Md., said she had been impressed
with what Jones said when he spoke at her Baptist church when she
was a high school student.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I prayed about the decision, when I visited the campus, I
didn't believe what other people told me'' that was negative about
the university, she said, ``because I experienced firsthand the
love of the Lord'' through faculty and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wasn't a popular decision,'' she added. ``I went to a
more liberal Christian school, and it was kind of a joke _ me, the
black girl, going to Bob Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   The university was founded in 1927 in Florida by Bob Jones Sr.,
an evangelist who had been licensed to preach at 15. He later moved
the school to Tennessee, then in 1947 to Greenville, a city located
near the Appalachian foothills in northwest South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Academically, it offers more than 110 majors, from accounting
and aircraft maintenance to English, foreign languages, nursing and
special education. It is also known for its serious interest in
fine arts, enhanced by its second president, Bob Jones Jr., who
built up a nationally known collection of Baroque religious
paintings (many of them done by Catholic artists). The university
stages operas and Shakespeare plays.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Brighton, 22, a senior, said, ``I came as a violin
performance major, and I was looking for a college with a very,
very good music program.'' As for the rules of campus life, she
said, ``They're really not that hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Jones' theological outlook _ which has led the
university to be sharply critical not just of Catholicism, but of
the National Council of Churches, the Southern Baptist Convention
and the Rev. Jerry Falwell _ is never far from view. The bookstore
features titles like ``Reclaiming Authentic Fundamentalism,'' as
well as small tracts about Christian fundamentalism that students
can use to proselytize others. Among the speakers scheduled for an
upcoming Bible conference are the Rev. Ian Paisley, the militant
Presbyterian from Northern Ireland, who is an old friend of the
school.
</P>
<P>
   James L. Guth, a professor of political science at nearby Furman
University, said Bob Jones represented a separatist fundamentalism
that is far less common in the United States than it once was. Some
very conservative Protestants _ Falwell perhaps most prominent
among them _ recognize the value of cooperating with other faiths
to advance common social causes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Bob Jones, the science department does teach about evolution.
``But it is taught as theory, in opposition to creation,'' said
Jonathan Pait, the university's spokesman. ``We do think students
should be aware of the theory _ and what we believe is an
unacceptable theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Pait declined to provide a copy of the student handbook, on the
grounds that its statements about rules for students could be taken
out of context. ``What makes us sigh is when that becomes the
focus,'' he said. ``We are distressed when the excellence of this
place is not stressed at the same level as the differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the university seems so strict, it has sometimes
been the subject of strange rumors.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Terry Haskins, a graduate of the school and now
president pro tem of the South Carolina state Legislature, chuckled
when he recalled that in the early 1970s, some in Greenville
believed the university had painted its sidewalks pink and blue,
one for women and the other for men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's first and foremost a Christian college, teaching the
nondenominational fundamentals of the Protestant faith,'' Haskins
said. ``In many ways, by society's standards, it's very
old-fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Rhonda Galloway, a professor of English, spoke to her
students about Ralph Waldo Emerson, whose spiritual pilgrimage led
him into territory that she made clear was vastly distant from the
fundamentalism of Bob Jones. Her prayer before the class, however,
focused on the issues at hand.
</P>
<P>
   As students bowed their heads, she said, ``We pray, Lord, that
out of this controversy that faces us right now that you will be
glorified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
