<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ADS-715(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIERCE AD WARS ON BALLOT ISSUES, NOT PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On television and radio the pitch is made
relentlessly. Every commercial break brings another political
come-on. But most of the time it isn't the governor of Texas or the
senator from Arizona, the vice president of the United States or
the former senator from New Jersey whom they are asking you to vote
for.
</P>
<P>
   It is Yes or No.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second spot clock never seems to stop, whether it is for
Indian gambling or against insurance reform, in favor of clean
water or in opposition to gay marriage. So many groups are elbowing
for television time to broadcast their positions on one of the 20
initiatives and referendums on the California ballot that they are
all but drowning out the political advertising by the presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The California campaign of the air is unlike any other in the
nation. The presidential candidates may have made big financial
investments in the state's sprawling network of media markets; Sen.
John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush have spent a total of about $5
million in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers are dwarfed by the expense and intensity of
the campaigns for the ballot measures _ a fierce, electronic war
lasting months, on which interest groups have spent over $120
million of an astonishing $150 million, a war chest over twice the
size of the one amassed by the national campaign of Bush. It is
among the most expensive barrages of political advertisement any
state has seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's madness,'' said Kim Alexander, president of the
California Voter Foundation, a nonprofit group that, among other
things, tracks campaign spending. ``The ads are designed to scare
voters, manipulate voters, do everything but inform voters. I think
people are going to wonder whether we have too much democracy in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   The veritable dust bowl of issues before the voters _ ``I have
29 decisions to make on my ballot, and I have over 80 candidates to
consider,'' Alexander said _ prompted her to compose a song and
post it on her foundation's Web site: ``If we pass Prop 17 church
raffles are OK/Eighteen changes the length of time we put murderers
away,'' it goes.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1900s, California has a quirky history with
voter initiatives, with the most famous being Proposition 13, the
1970s ballot measure that capped local property taxes and caused
deep cuts in education financing. But rarely have commercials for
the questions created such distracting static in a presidential
primary here.
</P>
<P>
   That is because traditionally the state held its election near
the end of the primary season. This year the contest was moved up
to prime time on the primary calendar, making the nation's most
populous state crucial in the selection of the nominees, and thus a
more frenetic media battleground.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the most expensive in the country for political
advertisers, with a dozen major media markets and highly
competitive local stations whose newscasts do not put a premium on
political coverage. (``Would your child know what to do if they
were kidnapped?'' asked a promotion for one dinnertime newscast
last week. ``Tools to get out alive!'')
</P>
<P>
   ``California, for many years, has not been a determining factor
in a presidential primary,'' said Allan Zaremberg, president of the
California Chamber of Commerce. ``We've never had a lot of
competing messages in a presidential primary before, so you haven't
had that presidential clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaremberg's group has taken sides in several of the ballot
fights. The chamber is allied with those opposed to Proposition 25
(which provides for public financing of political campaigns) and
those in favor of Proposition 26 (which changes voting procedures
for local school construction projects). It is also aligned with
groups spending $50 million in the most confusing and expensive
ballot question-fight, which concerns two propositions, 30 and 31,
dealing with lawsuits in insurance cases.
</P>
<P>
   There are also ballot measures involving gambling on tribal
American Indian land (Proposition 1A), safe drinking water (12),
watershed protection (13), restricting marriages to those between a
man and a woman (22), and repealing excise surtaxes on cigarettes
(28), which have active ``for'' and ``against'' advertising
campaigns on television.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The commercials run a gamut from appeals to the heart _ as in a
pro-1A spot suggesting that the right to gamble will help lead ``to
Indian self-reliance'' _ to nasty jabs at the opposition. In one
advertisement running constantly against Propositions 30 and 31, a
trio of sleazy-looking lowlifes, with greasy hair and lounge-lizard
shirts, sling beer bottles as they discuss a scheme to bilk
insurance companies in a scam called the ``swoop and squat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You find the car you like,'' one of them says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice car,'' adds another.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gotta have insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I pull in front of the car we like, Frank cuts in front of me,
I slam on the brakes _ boom! `The squat.'''
</P>
<P>
   A narrator interrupts: ``Propositions 30 and 31 make it easier
for cheats to get away with fraud, driving up your insurance
rates,'' the voice says, as the con men gloat in oily triumph.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a pair of referendums that supporters assert would
essentially force insurers to settle claims more quickly in some
accident cases. To make it all the more confusing, though, the
groups that spearheaded the campaign to get the measures on the
ballot are opposed to the propositions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mind-numbing, isn't it?'' asked Kelly Hayes-Raitt, a consumer
advocate active in the ``Yes-on-30'' campaign, which is being
outspent by the ``Nos'' by 10 to 1. ``I've been watching their ads
since November,'' she said of the opposition campaign. ``What it's
done is forced the yes campaign to respond to all of these
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus California viewers are treated to what one might call
double-negative spots. ``Slick and misleading, drivel, blatant
distortions, untruths,'' the Yes-on-30 commercial begins, in an
attack on the attack ads run by the No-on-30 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, in the endless cycle of grainy footage revealing
the deterioration of California schools in the Yes-on-26 ads, or
the rueful-sounding voice-overs of the No-on-22 spots, the grinning
visage of Bush or the silver-haired McCain pokes through for a
fleeting moment, as if to signal, from a remote point on the
horizon: Hey, remember us? And then it's immediately back to
``swoop and squat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't figure out 30 and 31,'' said Arnie Kleiner,
general manager of KABC, the ABC affiliate in Los Angeles. He calls
the spots for the propositions ``a blessing and a curse'': good
because they bring revenue _ unlike candidates for federal office,
the yes and no campaigns are charged full advertising rates _ and a
bit of a nuisance because they crowd out some of the stations'
regular advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said she believes the chaotic flow of proposition
spots has a corrosive effect on voters, that the disjointed parade
of video pleas for yeses and nos jades viewers and overstuffs their
brains. ``The more choices we ask voters to make, the more we
dilute voters' abilities to make informed choices,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the California ballot to come up with a potential
remedy for itself. Among the many propositions is number 23, which
asks that in future elections, voters be allowed to cast their
ballots for ``None of the above.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
