<SLUG> BC-POLITICAN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SENATE RACE; LOS ANGELES PROSECUTOR'S STRATEGY; ILLINOIS
GOVERNOR'S WOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA: SENATOR'S OUTLOOK IS SUNNY
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the hoopla surrounding the presidential primaries, it
has gone almost unnoticed that there will be a U.S. Senate race on
the ballot when California voters go to the polls on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state's senior senator, Dianne Feinstein, a liberal
Democrat, is seeking a second six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when she first ran for a full term (she initially went
to Washington in 1992 to fill out the final two years of an
unexpired term), Feinstein was barely able to fend off her
conservative Republican challenger, Rep. Michael Huffington of
Santa Barbara. He set a national record that year for a Senate
candidate, dumping almost $30 million of his personal fortune into
the contest, and he came within a couple of percentage points of
turning Feinstein out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Huffington has since gone on to other pursuits. And Election
2000 appears to be shaping up as a comfortable romp for Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   She has scared off all Democratic challengers of any
consequence. And on the Republican side, the likely primary winner,
Rep. Tom Campbell, a moderate from the Silicon Valley, has yet to
come up with either the name recognition or the money neede$ to
oust a sitting California senator _ especially one who has plenty
of money and is advertising heavily, who over the past six years
has boosted her job approval rating to around 60 percent, and who
is frequently mentioned as a possible choice for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls have Campbell losing by a solid 20 points in
the fall, with more than half of all voters saying they hardly know
who he is. Perhaps more telling, the polls indicate that come
Tuesday's primary, when cross-party voting will be permitted, about
1 in 5 Republicans and 3 in 5 independents plan to support
Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks are fat and happy in California right now and not
inclined to change horses,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffee, a
political analyst at Claremont Graduate University. ``This is
Dianne Feinstein's race to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA: LOS ANGELES PROSECUTOR BIDES HIS TIME
</P>
<P>
   No district attorney in the country is better known than Gil
Garcetti of Los Angeles _ and no wonder. The city has a mix of big
crime, big money and big celebrity that is straight out of, well,
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But high-profile prosecution has high risks, as Garcetti found
out after he failed to win a conviction in his biggest case, the
O.J. Simpson murder trial. Angry voters almost installed a new DA
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Garcetti managed to squeak back in at the last moment.
And he is up for re-election again on Tuesday, facing two other
candidates in a quest for a third four-year tour. Once more he
finds himself in a tough fight.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Garcetti has enjoyed a number of major prosecution
successes. His office has also been praised for undertaking
aggressive campaigns against welfare fraud and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   But all that has been tempered lately by a major scandal in the
police department _ a scandal that Garcetti's detractors charge was
not only not uncovered by his office but has been pursued only
halfheartedly.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti has been notably reticent about firing back at his
challengers, Steve Cooley, one of his deputies, and Barry Groveman,
a lawyer who had worked in both private practice and with some city
agencies. Why, since both men are campaigning hard and spending
heavily on advertising?
</P>
<P>
   According to his aides, Garcetti figures there is a strong
possibility he will end up in a runoff in the contest, which is
nonpartisan, and therefore has decided to save most of the $1
million he has raised for that. They say he has concluded that any
major statements he might make to win on Tuesday and thereby avert
a runoff would surely be drowned out by all the noise surrounding
the presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS: TAKING ADVANTAGE OF A GOVERNOR'S WOES
</P>
<P>
   Hardly any governor in the country is under more fire now than
George Ryan of Illinois. Ryan, a Republican, has been trying for
months to fend off charges that long before legal authorities began
a major investigation into corruption in the office of the Illinois
secretary of state, which he once occupied, he knew things were
amiss.
</P>
<P>
   One recent poll found that seven of every 10 Illinoisans do not
believe the governor's denials.
</P>
<P>
   That statistic caught the eye of State Rep. Bill Brady, who is
running for Congress in the 15th District in east-central Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Brady is a Republican himself. But he figured there were votes
to be had by playing off the governor's difficulties. He came up
with two television ads that politically dovetail.
</P>
<P>
   The first says: ``In 1999, George Ryan called for higher taxes.
State Rep. Bill Brady urged the governor not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The second ad accuses state Rep. Tim Johnson, one of Brady's
major opponents in a party primary set for March 21, of voting for
higher taxes. Ryan has endorsed Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1539EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
