<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE GIL HODGES CAMPAIGN CONTINUES, WITH LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lady is angry. And justifiably so.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want is an answer,'' Joan Hodges was saying. ``I don't
want to go out of the house and have somebody ask me, `What
happened?' I need an explanation. Maybe I could live with it if I
lived somewhere else, but I'm right here in Brooklyn, in the same
house for 40 years. Ever since Tuesday, I've had people come up and
kiss me like he just died.''
</P>
<P>
   And last Tuesday Gil Hodges' candidacy for the Baseball Hall of
Fame did die, at least for another year. Again. Some friends even
sent his widow flowers, as if in mourning. But the campaign won't
die.
</P>
<P>
   As if she were still sitting behind home plate at Ebbets Field
and rooting for him, Joan Hodges is keeping his memory alive. As if
he never died of a heart attack during spring training in 1972 when
he was managing the Mets after having hit all those home runs as
the Dodgers' huge and humble first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last thing Gil would want me to do, campaign for
him,'' she continued, sitting under a painting of her late husband.
``But I've got to keep fighting for my player, my man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this was the year. Everybody was behind him _ the
mayor, the governor, the borough president, the bishop. We had a
restaurant on Flatbush Avenue reserved for the celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite simply, Hodges did not get enough votes from the Hall of
Fame's Veterans Committee for induction into the Cooperstown, N.Y.,
shrine, but strangely, neither did any other former players since
1945 on the ballot, notably Bill Mazeroski, Tony Oliva, Joe Gordon
and Mel Harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had let Mazeroski in, that's all right, that's their
prerogative,'' Joan Hodges said, referring to the Pittsburgh
Pirates second baseman, whose home run won the 1960 World Series
against the Yankees. ``But when nobody else got in, how could they
ignore my husband?''
</P>
<P>
   In other categories, the committee did elect Sparky Anderson,
the third-winningest manager in history, who measured the Reds and
the Tigers for three trays of World Series rings; Bid McPhee, an
1890s second baseman, and Turkey Stearnes, a Negro League
outfielder from the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   In his 18 seasons with the Dodgers (both in Brooklyn and Los
Angeles) and the early Mets, Hodges hit 370 home runs and drove in
1,274 runs. He knocked in both runs in the 2-0 seventh-game victory
over the Yankees in 1955 for the Brooklyn Dodgers' only World
Series title.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he was never ejected from a game,'' Joan Hodges said. ``He
had the integrity and character that Cooperstown insists on in its
Hall of Famers.''
</P>
<P>
   It is baffling as to why the committee, which considers players
who never got enough Hall of Fame votes in the annual Baseball
Writers' Association of America ballot, keeps rejecting Hodges when
it has elected so many of his contemporaries who often got fewer
votes from the writers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Hodges received more writers' votes than any
player not eventually elected by the committee. In one year or
another Hodges also received more writers' votes than the nine
eventually elected by the writers _ his Dodger teammate Duke
Snider, Don Drysdale, Bob Lemon, Early Wynn, Eddie Mathews, Luis
Aparicio, Juan Marichal, Hoyt Wilhelm and Billy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges also received more writers' votes in one year or another
than the 11 later elected by the committee _ his Dodger teammate
Pee Wee Reese, Phil Rizzuto, Red Schoendienst, Bobby Doerr, George
Kell, Hal Newhouser, Enos Slaughter, Johnny Mize, Nellie Fox, Jim
Bunning and Richie Ashburn. Another committee choice, Rick Ferrell,
received a total of only two votes from the writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year Richie Ashburn got in, he called me in tears,'' Joan
Hodges said, referring to the 1995 election. ``He told me, `I can't
believe I got in before Gil did.' And for Gil not to get in this
year. He's not only overqualified, he had no competition.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Joe L. Brown, the former Pirates general manager
who is the committee chairman, there were ``so many outstanding
candidates, it split the ballot.'' Actually there were two ballots.
On the first, each member could vote for as many as 10 players. If
nobody received the required 75 percent, the top 10 vote-getters
were put on a second ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buck O'Neil was ill,'' Brown said, referring to the Negro
League representative on the 15-member committee. ``That meant 11
of the 14 votes were needed. But nobody got 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprising. In recent years, at least one relatively recent
former player has been elected by the committee of five former
players, notably Hank Aaron, Ted Williams and Stan Musial; five
former executives, notably Brown and Bill White; and five news
media members, notably Leonard Koppett and Jerome Holtzman. That
cast is expected to change slightly by next year.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hall of Fame bylaws, a committee member serves a term of
three years, but no more than two consecutive terms. Williams has
been there since 1966, Musial since 1973, O'Neil since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bylaw was put in, I forget exactly, but sometime in the
'90s,'' Ed Stack, the chairman of the Hall of Fame's board, said.
``Starting next year, some current members will be rotating off the
committee each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that will help (or hurt) Hodges' chances at next year's
meeting, but his widow will continue to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a radio interview I did the other day, I used the phrase,
`personal vendetta.' I'd like to retract that,'' she said. ``And
some people think our campaign hurt Gil this year; that maybe the
committee thought, `We'll show you.' But I'll continue to campaign.
Right now the whole country is listening to the presidential
campaigns. Don't I have that right, too?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1544EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
