</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PETTITTE'S FATHER SHOWS HIS RESOLVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The pitching line was two and one-third innings,
four hits, two runs. These numbers meant nothing, nor did the game,
and for those very reasons, Andy Pettitte's father took a seat
behind the Yankee dugout, in the warm Florida sun, to watch his boy
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Those other games, the ones that count in the standing and
beyond, have become too stressful, too much for a man who has
always prided himself on how much he could handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy Pettitte,'' he said Friday afternoon, introducing
himself while extending his right hand on the top step of the
Yankee dugout at Legends Field. Not Tom, or Thomas, because, after
all, he is only 50, a strapping man with a youthful face who
nonetheless gazes in the mirror and demands an explanation for what
his body in recent years has put him through.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, doctors removed two feet of his colon. The
following year, they cut him open to unclog the main artery to his
heart. There have also been operations on his lower back, his neck
and a whole mess of issues with his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' he said, at an exasperating loss, ``all that weight
lifting caught up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was never competitive, just recreational, the mark of a man
who wishes to stay busy, work hard, hold up his end. For 14 years,
Tommy Pettitte was a police sergeant in Baton Rouge, La. When Andy
was 8, the family moved to a town near Houston, where Tommy worked
in a chemical plant that produces additives for motor oil.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't use the word retirement, not yet, preferring to say
he is on leave, or ``LTD,'' and wanting very much to believe he
will eventually return, or as soon as the doctors determine what's
wrong with him this time. As soon as the experts can explain the
mysterious chest pains and the near-blackouts, which they believe
are not heart-related and may be caused by some undetected muscle
spasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked since I was 13,'' he said. ``This is a mental
thing for me, being 50, in this situation. I'm too young for all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   While we were on the subject of the hard-working, resolute
Pettitte men, Tommy knew that his son, at 27, was too young to be
considered past his prime, Yankee bait, when the trade rumors were
flying last summer, like some of the home-run balls Andy was
throwing.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy knew this in his heart, and thank goodness for Joe Torre,
for Mel Stottlemyre, for their patience and faith and the lobbying
that made George Steinbrenner back off and trust his baseball
people. Andy showed 'em down the stretch, and in the postseason,
just as Torre and Tommy expected he would. With a new $25 million,
three-year contract, Andy Pettitte pitches on for Torre, for a man
Tommy Pettitte called ``more of a father to him than I am, if you
know what I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   What he meant was that for the long baseball haul, from here to
October, it is Torre who watches over Andy, not him. Heck, the last
two years, Tommy hasn't even been able to watch Andy pitch in the
World Series. That fourth game of the 1998 Series, he was in the
hospital, with a catheter plugged inside him. And last season,
while his son was pitching Game 3 at Yankee Stadium, Tommy picked
up and went to the ``picture show,'' which is what they called the
movies when he was a kid in Louisiana, because he knew the pressure
of watching couldn't be good for his heart.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, he just doesn't want to be a burden, the way he
was in the playoffs a couple of years ago when, 15 minutes before
Andy took the mound, they were talking on the telephone and Tommy
made a mistake and stopped lying about the chest pains. Andy went
out and got bombed that night, and Tommy has since worried that his
health has contributed to his son's diminishing pitching returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell him all the time, `Daddy, when I'm out there pitching,
I'm not dwelling on you,''' Andy said before taking the mound
against Toronto Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy, Andy said, was never the pushy Little League father,
never planned for his son to be a ballplayer, even insisted he
spend a year in college after the Yankees drafted him in high
school. ``He coached me as kid,'' Andy said. ``He bought all the
books and videos and tried to learn as much about pitching as he
could. But once I was in high school, he never tried to be my
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not until recently when, much to his chagrin, Tommy
Pettitte has had more time on his hands than he knew what to do
with. Father and son filled some of it together, breaking out the
film of Andy's halcyon Yankee days from 1996-97, when he won 39
games. They discovered his motion was slower, more deceptive,
giving him greater command of his sinker and changeup, which he
threw for strikes Friday, which made both Pettittes smile.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, the pitching coach, has nothing to worry about.
Tommy Pettitte said his only ambition is a clean bill of health,
and to get back to work. He said: ``I told Andy, `I'd like to get
up to New York one of these years and see you all get your rings.''
</P>
<P>
   He settled Friday for seven spring training outs, and then Tommy
Pettitte and his wife, Joann, went home to Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
