<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIFFERENT TRINIDAD CONQUERS REID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ If Oscar De La Hoya took time out from his Hawaiian
vacation to watch Felix Trinidad beat David Reid here on Friday
night, then he might want to extend his time away from the ring.
And he might want to scratch Trinidad from his 2000 date book.
</P>
<P>
   The 153-pound Trinidad who steamrolled Reid over the last seven
rounds en route to a 12-round unanimous decision was not the same
stiff 147-pound Trinidad who was outboxed through eight rounds and
spent the last four rounds futilely chasing a retreating De La Hoya
last Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Looking more comfortable with the additional weight, Trinidad
(37-0) entered the ring loose and confident against Reid (14-1),
who lost his World Boxing Association superwelterweight title (154
pounds). Reid's speed seemed to get to Trinidad early as Reid
decked Trinidad with a right cross in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went down to the canvas for the first time, the first
thought that came to my mind was, `It's over for David Reid,'''
Trinidad said. ``I have been down before, but when I get up I'm
always dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid had no idea what awaited him. He said he wanted to finish
Trinidad off in the third round but couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt close to victory, but I couldn't hit him with the shots
to finish him,'' said Reid, who wore dark glasses to hide a badly
cut and swollen right eye. ``I wanted to box him more. I wanted to
stay inside and bang with him. But I learned he was too slick for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Mitchell, Reid's longtime trainer and manager, said that Reid
got away from the game plan, which was to throw the jab and stick
Trinidad with the right hand. It worked like a charm in the first
four rounds, but then, Mitchell said, Reid lost focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave got a little too comfortable,'' Mitchell said. ``Dave was
right on the money until the sixth round, and he got off the plan.
That's just inexperience. You have to remember that this was just
his 15th fight. By the time he gets to 20, he'll be a heck of a
fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad took over after the sixth round. He pressed Reid at
every turn and stayed on him, hitting him with hard shots. He
opened a cut over Reid's right eye in the seventh and floored Reid
with a left to the chin. That shot seemed to take everything out of
Reid. His legs became rubbery and he never seemed to recover. Reid
took an awful beating in the 11th round, going down three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came close to stopping it three times,'' Mitchell said.
``But Dave went down to one knee and I saw him wave me off.''
</P>
<P>
   After the third knockdown in the 11th round, Trinidad jumped up
on the second rope of the neutral corner and began yelling to the
crowd as if the fight were over. But Reid got up and came out in
the 12th round and showed tremendous courage by finishing the fight
on his feet and throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said that Reid would take a break from the ring and
determine where he will go from here.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad will most certainly give up the International Boxing
Federation and World Boxing Council welterweight titles now that he
has won the WBA superwelterweight title. He has 72 hours to give up
the IBF title and 15 days to decide whether he wants to defend or
vacate the WBC title.
</P>
<P>
   If he vacates the WBC title, then it goes to De La Hoya, who
defeated Derrell Coley last week in an elimination bout for the
147-pound title. Trinidad said he would like to meet De La Hoya
again, but closer to 154 pounds and never at 147 pounds. Don King,
Trinidad's promoter, said he would get in touch with De La Hoya's
promoter, Bob Arum, as soon as possible to try to work out a deal
for the rematch. But Arum has said that De La Hoya is all set to
meet Shane Mosley at 147 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   King tried to embarrass De La Hoya and HBO, which has an
exclusive contract to broadcast De La Hoya's bouts, into abandoning
the Mosley fight and doing the Trinidad rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is not a welterweight. He's a lightweight,'' King
said of Mosley. ``He's only fought twice as a welterweight, and one
of them was Willie Wise. HBO has too much integrity to put on such
a sham of a match.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Trinidad-De La Hoya rematch cannot be made, then Trinidad
said he wants to unify the 154-pound titles, which means fighting
the winner of the Fernando Vargas-Ike Quartey bout on April 15 or
Javier Castillejo of Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
