<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-A     03-04 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL DUQUE REWRITES THE BOOK ON PITCHING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Orlando Hernandez, the Yankees pitcher, does this
drill: He places his fingertips at his ears, extends his elbows
out, turns to his right and spins around 10 times. Without pausing
his motion, he then reverses himself, spinning around 10 times in
the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   He stops and plants his feet, staring forward, his body weaving
slightly. It's the sort of thing aspiring astronauts might do. It's
the sort of thing you shouldn't try right after lunch.
</P>
<P>
   He does this to improve his equilibrium. Other Yankees pitchers
admire his equilibrium; they probably wish they had his
equilibrium. But no other pitcher has adopted this training method.
``If I tried some of Duque's drills, I'd probably break my neck,''
pitcher Andy Pettitte said.
</P>
<P>
   They share the same fields with Hernandez for eight months out
of the year, and they don't understand much of what he does, how he
trains or the purpose of some of his exercises. He is the medicine
man of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain mystique about El Duque, even among his
teammates,'' pitcher David Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   All they truly comprehend about Hernandez is his success. They
have seen him win, in the most important games, watched him humble
the best hitters in the most crucial moments, and there is no need
to ask why or how. They don't know anything firsthand about Cuba,
where Hernandez is from. They aren't sure how old he is, whether he
is 30, as the Yankees' media guide says, or 34, as government
documents and other baseball records indicate.
</P>
<P>
   He does not possess the instruments of the typical mound
surgeon, the 95 mph fastball, a split-fingered fastball or the hard
sinker. Hernandez's stuff is quite ordinary, in its raw form _ a
fastball of 88 to 90 mph, a nice little curve, a wide-breaking
slider; if he were a doctor, it would be like treating a patient
with okra root, daisy petals and boiled bark. But the medicine man
wins.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez does this drill: He draws up his left leg, as if to
begin his pitching motion. His left kneecap is chest high. Then he
hops, from right to left, his 220 pounds propelled solely by his
right leg. He lands on his right foot, without lowering his left
leg, and continues to hop, again and again. El Duque could hop for
hundreds of yards, it seems, to strengthen and stretch the muscles
that power his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Other Yankees pitchers admire Hernandez's physical strength.
None of them are hopping off one leg before they pitch. ``I tried
it,'' said the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre, ``and I'd fall over
after two or three hops.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez sometimes works out with Rohan Baichu, the team's
massage therapist and a distance runner attempting to represent
Guyana in the 2000 Olympics. Baichu finds he cannot jog leisurely
when he runs alongside Hernandez; rather, Baichu must push himself.
Hernandez showed him a drill in which he leaps forward, off one leg
and then the other, over and over. ``He is like a track athlete,''
Baichu said. ``His legs are extremely strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Baichu believes that with training, Hernandez would run 400
meters in under 50 seconds, and he is sure Hernandez would be a
great boxer. He and El Duque have traded shadow punches, and he was
surprised by the quickness of El Duque's hands. Jeff Mangold, the
team's strength and conditioning coach, thinks Hernandez would be
great at basketball, as a point guard, because of his awareness of
all that is happening around him.
</P>
<P>
   Mangold recalled that game last summer when Hernandez stabbed at
a grounder and discovered the ball was tangled in the webbing of
his glove. There was a runner on third base at the time, but with
virtually no hesitation, Hernandez sprinted toward first and threw
his glove, while running, to first baseman Tino Martinez. To
Mangold, the play required many of those subtle parts of what makes
Hernandez special _ the instant diagnosis of the situation, the
confidence to even attempt a toss of his glove, and, in the end, a
perfect throw of that oddly shape package of ball and glove. ``And
to throw it for distance,'' Mangold said. ``He's a special guy.''
</P>
<P>
   If records held by scouts and the state of Florida are accurate,
then Hernandez was born in 1965, rather than 1969, the date listed
in the Yankees' media guide, and his performance in his first two
seasons, his 29 victories, is unique. Only one pitcher in the
history of baseball started his career after the age of 32 years 8
months _ Hernandez's age at the time of his debut _ and had more
success in his first two seasons, according to the Elias Sports
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Turner pitched his first game in the big leagues at 33 years
10 months and won 34 games for the Boston Braves in 1937 and 1938.
Turner, who went on to become the longtime pitching coach of the
Yankees during Casey Stengel's tenure as manager, didn't pitch in
the big leagues until an advanced age because he struggled to
interest any team, said Fred Russell, a longtime friend of Turner's
in Nashville. (Turner died in 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's opportunities were limited because he was not
allowed to leave his homeland. When Joe Torre, the Yankees'
manager, told Hernandez that he would pitch the first game in each
of the playoff series last year, he and Stottlemyre could see the
pride in Hernandez, a gleam in his eye. But there was more.
Hernandez appeared greatly honored that he had been given the
responsibility to represent his team in such important games. Maybe
it wasn't such an unusual response for someone who had pitched in
the name of his countrymen before defecting from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I not be honored,'' Hernandez asked rhetorically the
other day, with Jorge Posada interpreting, ``with David Cone, Roger
Clemens and Andy'' Pettitte on the team? ``The Lion, the Tiger and
the Monkey,'' Hernandez said laughing, referring to Cone, Clemens
and the long-armed Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There had been skepticism in the organization about Hernandez at
first, about the high leg kick and seemingly mediocre stuff. Joe
Girardi, the former Yankees catcher, conceded to Cone that he had
been very wrong about Hernandez's ability after watching El Duque's
debut, in which he allowed only one run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was sure, almost immediately after meeting El Duque, that
Hernandez possessed a special understanding of pitching. Cone
played catch with El Duque in spring training of 1998, and
Hernandez's fastball seemed to have an unusual movement. Cone asked
Hernandez to show him how he was holding the ball, to share a
secret among pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez held the ball out, and Cone was stunned: When pitchers
throw a four-seam fastball, they brace their fingertips against the
seams of the baseball, using the stitches as a lever as they pull
down and release the ball. But Hernandez placed his fingertips on
the smooth surface, somehow managing to generate enough traction to
make the ball turn like the standard four-seam fastball _ but with
that added unusual movement.
</P>
<P>
   A dry four-seamer, Cone called it, because most pitchers
gripping the ball on the smooth surface could do so only with the
aid of spit or another foreign substance, making it a wet
four-seamer. Anyone who could grip a baseball this way and make it
work, Cone decided right then, had an uncommon insight into his
craft.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has started six games in the post-season, and the
Yankees have won all six. In those games, Hernandez has permitted
just 24 hits and 5 earned runs in 44 innings, for a 1.02 earned run
average. ``You can see fear in a pitcher,'' shortstop Derek Jeter
said. ``You can  &UR; see  &LR; it,'' he repeated, as if his brain was
rifling through stored images of frightened pitchers, with faces
that betrayed confusion and panic.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter watches Hernandez, with his cap curled and pulled low
above his eyes, like a tunnel for his vision. Jeter sees no fear.
``I don't think he's afraid to fail,'' Jeter said. ``That has a lot
to do with being a big-game pitcher. He just looks focused. He
looks like he's going to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been times during the regular season, Stottlemyre
said, that Hernandez might become distracted, by an umpire or his
frustration. But in the post-season, Stottlemyre has noticed,
Hernandez ignores everything on the periphery; Posada agrees.
``He's just looking straight at me, thinking about what he's trying
to do,'' Posada said. ``It's just him and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez reaches the dugout between innings and grasps a copy
of the opponent's lineup card, studying the hitters to come. He has
a strong sense of how he wants to pitch, Stottlemyre said, a
distinct plan, like a pool player anticipating shots in advance.
None of his teammates who were asked can remember Hernandez
complimenting opposing hitters by name, referring to them only
according to their vulnerabilities. ``He's not afraid to give
credit,'' Stottlemyre said, ``but he doesn't ever want to be
intimidated, no matter how big a hitter it is. He believes if he
executes his plan, then his plan will be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   At every point of decision in his post-season starts, he has
prevailed. He struck out Cleveland's Jim Thome with the bases
loaded and a full count in 1998, throwing a changeup. He struck out
the Rangers' Juan Gonzalez with two inside fastballs and a slider
last year. He struck out eight of the first 11 Atlanta batters he
faced in last year's World Series. Veterans like Bret Boone, Gerald
Williams and Eddie Perez swung and missed by 2 feet or more _ a
tribute, Martinez thought, not only to his deception, but also to
the quality of his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has this drill: He stands on his head. He can do this
for a full minute, swinging his legs back and forth. He does this
to relax, a form of yoga, something he learned nearly 10 years ago
from Euclides Rojas, his pitching coach in Cuba. Hernandez will do
handstands. No other Yankees pitcher does this. No other Yankees
pitcher is like El Duque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
