<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUTTS TAKES NEW ZEALAND REINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ For Russell Coutts, the long sea journey
that has brought him fame, fortune, Olympic gold _ and now, for the
second time, the America's Cup _ began at the helm of a touchy
little P-class dinghy off the windswept coast of Dunedin on New
Zealand's rugged South Island.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of the prodigal nautical sons of this sailing-obsessed
country, Coutts' first command was one of the technical, difficult
7-foot woodies unique to this island nation. If you can master the
P-class, it's often said here, you can sail anything. But Coutts,
who won his first P-class regatta at the ripe old age of 9, has
sailed better and farther than all of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 38, Coutts may face his greatest challenge yet. For,
after skippering Team New Zealand to a 5-0 sweep of Italy's Prada
Challenge in its first defense of the America's Cup, Coutts is
expected to fill, at least partially, the power vacuum left by the
departure of Sir Peter Blake, the Kiwi legend who spearheaded the
syndicate's fund-raising and shoreside efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Blake is off to head up the Cousteau Society, and the reins have
been passed to Coutts; his lieutenant and tactician, Brad
Butterworth, 40, and the navigator and design-team supervisor, Tom
Schnackenberg, 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their turn,'' Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   A natural-born leader, Blake has navigated Team New Zealand
through the tricky, sometimes hazardous shoals of international
television-rights negotiations, sponsorship procurement and
internal squabbles. Some wonder if the new regime, whose sole
concern has been winning boat races, is up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear is that Coutts and Butterworth care more about
themselves than they do about the longevity and well-being of the
event,'' the American cup veteran, Paul Cayard, said in a recent
interview. ``But we have to hear their plans and, more importantly,
see what they actually do about them, not what they say they're
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Coutts and the others have kept their intentions to
themselves, insisting that they first had to tend to the business
at hand. It does appear that they will continue to operate under
the auspices of a single defense campaign. ``Certainly we'd have to
have good reason to change anything,'' Coutts said. ``It's
obviously worked pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Any doubts about Coutts' selflessness and leadership skills were
allayed when, in the decisive fifth race of the series, he replaced
himself at the helm with his understudy, Dean Barker, who was
steering the boat when the cup was defended.
</P>
<P>
   It was like Tiger Woods handing his putter to his caddy for the
tap-in on the 18th and final hole of the Masters. Many believe the
act of sportsmanship will earn Coutts a knighthood.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts says it was just teamwork. ``I think it showed our
strength,'' he said. ``It's not just about Dean or myself. There
are plenty of other young sailors coming through, too. They're part
of our long-term vision for this regatta.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the cup finals, Coutts said he'd like New
Zealand to hold the trophy for the next two decades or more. After
their Prada deconstruction, the notion may not be far-fetched. The
Kiwis' intricate local knowledge of the Hauraki Gulf proved to be a
devastating home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   And their design program, now riding the crest of consecutive
5-0 whitewashes in the last two cup regattas, seems exponentially
ahead of anything the challengers have created. ``The boat looked
even more impressive when I was off it for Race 5,'' Coutts said.
``When you're on board, you worry about little things, but when
you're off you can see the whole concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more worrisome for potential challengers, Coutts said the
Kiwis still had several things they could've done to improve their
boat, but they hadn't been pressed to reveal them. And perhaps just
as troubling for the competition, even with his greater role in the
program, Coutts isn't ready to relinquish his command permanently,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll still be involved in the sailing,'' he said. ``I'll still
be competing internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on the international match-racing circuit where the Kiwis
kept their edge sharply honed in the five years since liberating
the cup from San Diego. By admitting that his competitive fires
were still burning, Coutts was likely admitting that he'll be as
involved in the sailing program as he is in the shoreside
administration in the next cup defense scheduled for 2002-3.
</P>
<P>
   It has been his career, which has now spanned three decades,
claimed countless world championships in many disciplines, and an
Olympic gold medal in the Finn class in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Now Coutts is driving a ship much grander then the Finn or the
P-class dinghy of his youth, one that carries the hopes of his
entire country. Thus far, his course has been nothing but straight
and true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1614EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RENT-RULING-REAL-2TAK     03-04 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENT-RULING-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RENT-RULING SAGA ON 110TH STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anne Gilman, an artist and teacher whose works on
paper are quietly riveting, moved into her two-bedroom apartment on
West 110th Street 10 years ago with her husband at the time and
their daughter, who was then 7. It is in a well-maintained building
with polished marble floors and friendly doormen, in a neighborhood
more homey than chic.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, she became convinced that her landlord,
Marsid Realty, was overcharging for the rent-stabilized apartment,
so in 1990 she filed a rent appeal with the State Division of
Housing and Community Renewal, an agency that oversees rent
regulation. For four years, she heard nothing, but the silence
didn't really matter, because she and her husband, who had met as
teen-agers in Queens, could afford the $2,095-a-month rent.
</P>
<P>
   However, when they decided to break up after 20 years of
marriage, and she still hadn't received an answer, she filed a
request for a resolution of the case, called an Article 78. If the
rent was going to remain, neither she nor her husband could afford
it alone. She began looking for a smaller, cheaper place, and found
one across the street and down the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had no doorman, and the fire escape led right into the
apartment, which scared my daughter,'' she said. Still, it seemed
she had to move, and it had two bedrooms. But just as she was about
to sign the lease, she got a letter from the state agency telling
her that her rent had been too high and that it would be
essentially cut in half. So she decided to stay. The landlord was
also assessed treble damages of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has paid the amount established as her new legal
rent and specified in her lease, $1,011.12 at the time, and later,
adjusted upward by the legally allowable increases. So when she
received a letter two months ago saying that the rent decision had
been reversed on appeal six years after the first ruling, and that
she would now have to pay $2,223 a month, she was in shock.
</P>
<P>
   But that was hardly the worst of it. The state told her that she
also had to pay her landlord back rent, estimated at more than
$47,000. And it nullified the treble damages, which the landlord
had not been required to pay while the case was on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   And so, instead of planning the surprise party she had hoped to
give for her father's 80th birthday in April, maybe making the
salmon with cilantro and tomatoes she had prepared for her parents'
50th wedding anniversary, she is now wondering whether she will be
evicted before that, and if she is, where she can go.
</P>
<P>
   Her family now includes not only her daughter, Lisa
Gilman-Rosen, a junior at Stuyvesant High School, but also her
husband of 11 months, a writer and translator, and his two
daughters, one at Hunter College High School and one living away
from home at college. She declined to give her husband's name,
saying she did not want potential landlords to know they were
married.
</P>
<P>
   The case, she said, has tainted her, making her appear as a bad
tenant, when in fact she has lived as a careful person, never
taking the big risks or rash steps that put people in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could call the credit bureaus today,'' she said. ``I pay
off my credit cards. I always have a zero balance. I find this
humiliating.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her new husband spend a lot of time at home; they cook,
they play Scrabble on their bed _ which is in the dining room so
their daughters can have the bedrooms. They live carefully and
quietly, and yet, she said: ``I feel inept. I feel like I've done
something wrong to get us in this position, and I've never lived
that way. I've never lived on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agency's ruling, she was supposed to begin paying the
new rent of $2,223 in January, plus $1,900 a month toward her
back-rent debt. She said she could not pay that much and continued
to pay her old rent. The landlord has gone to court to evict her,
and to collect the back rent.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to get help, she has applied to an arts organization for
an emergency grant. ``They say they help with catastrophic
events,'' said Gilman, who teaches at Pratt Institute and at
Purchase College, State University of New York. She exhibits her
work four or five times a year, and she recently had a piece bought
by the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of being evicted, and of having to declare
personal bankruptcy, has left her distraught. Sitting at her dining
room table, she said she found the situation unbearable and
mystifying. ``I had no evidence at that time that the ruling was
something I should doubt,'' she said. ``I have leases. Nowhere does
it say this is a provisional rent.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the latest ruling, she filed appeals of the
state decision and the eviction action through her newly hired
lawyer, Robert Levy, who has handled many tenant-landlord cases.
``I've been doing this for 30 years, and I've never seen anything
like this,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Gilman filed her fair market rent appeal, she was
challenging the rent under provisions that guide landlords in
setting new rents when apartments move from rent control to rent
stabilization.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the rent-control laws apply to apartments
that have been occupied by the same tenant since July 1, 1971, and
are in buildings of three or more units built before Feb. 1, 1947.
When such tenants vacate an apartment, its rent is generally
regulated by the rent stabilization laws.
</P>
<P>
   The previous tenant in Gilman's apartment had paid $605 a month;
the landlord then raised the rent to $2,000. Under the law, the
landlord can show rents for comparable apartments to justify the
establishment of the initial rent under stabilization laws.
</P>
<P>
   In the four years before the first ruling, Levy said, the
landlord presented no comparables. The decision was reversed last
year, Levy said, because the agency decided that a legislative
change in 1997 allowed the landlord to submit comparables that
would buttress his case, even though new evidence is typically not
allowed in an appeal unless it was unavailable the first time
around.
</P>
<P>
   Because the landlord in his appeal submitted evidence that
pertained to rental leases signed around 1990, it should have been
previously available to him, Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feature that's so upsetting is that they changed the rules
in midstream,'' he said. ``They bent them beyond recognition.''
Gilman, he said, was right to assume that even if her landlord
prevailed in an appeal, any rent change would be minor.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reason, he said, for her to believe that the agency
could fully reverse itself. ``It's really a Kafkaesque situation,''
he said. ``You wake up one morning and you owe your landlord nearly
$50,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Harra, a vice president of ABC Realty and the managing
agent for the building on West 110th Street, said the landlord had
at one point voluntarily lowered Gilman's rent somewhat when she
and her first husband were having financial difficulties. The
landlord did not even get notice of the first challenge to the
rent, Harra said, until several years after it was filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DHCR apparently lost the papers for two years,'' he said.
Because of that, he said, the landlord did not have time to gather
the comparables that his case required. When the landlord was told
that the rent was being rolled back _ and that he was being
assessed the $50,000 in treble damages _ he appealed, and during
that process, the overcharge he owed Gilman was frozen.
</P>
<P>
   He has now taken her to court to get the back rent and to evict
her, Harra said, because she is still paying the old rent. ``She
chose not to pay the new legal rent,'' he said, ``and the landlord
said, `I got to take you to court.'''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Del Pino, a spokeswoman for the Division of Housing and
Community Renewal, said it would not comment on its procedures in
the case, or the time it took to issue rulings, because it cannot
talk about cases that are pending or on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gilman is wondering where she will go if her appeal
is unsuccessful, or even worse, if she is evicted before a ruling
on the appeal is issued. Most important to her is a safe place, in
part because she still remembers the terror of being assaulted at
knife point as a teen-ager in Queens. To her, a good neighborhood
is not fancy, but ``lively, well lit and well trafficked.''
</P>
<P>
   But she has talked to some real estate agents and says she is
gloomy about her prospects. ``There's no place to move to that is
comparable,'' she said. ``We're not lawyers. We're not doctors. How
do normal people pay the rent?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
