<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      03-04 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUSH AND McCAIN BATTLE IN NORTHEAST   
 &HT;     (EDS: Stands for Portland, Maine-dated item on budget)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEMAN   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John
McCain campaigned in northeastern states Saturday, with Bush
knocking McCain's record on education and McCain attacking radio
ads bought by Bush supporters in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates had their eye on Tuesday's Republican primaries
in 13 states including California, New York, Ohio and four New
England states. A total of 613 of the 1,034 delegates needed to
secure the GOP presidential nomination is at stake Tuesday _ the
largest delegate treasure yet in the hard fought battle for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, polls show the race tightening to a dead heat.
Among Republicans, a poll Friday by the Marist Institute of Public
Opinion showed Bush ahead of McCain by 45 percent to 42 percent.
Last Wednesday, the same poll showed McCain ahead of Bush 47
percent to 43 percent among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate selection in the New York and California primaries is
limited to registered Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls showed Bush widening his lead by small amounts in
California, Georgia, Maryland, Missouri and Ohio while McCain was
ahead of Bush in the New England states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning across upstate New York and into Connecticut,
participated in an early St. Patrick's Day parade in Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also launched a new radio commercial citing the Republican
debate in Los Angeles last week, where McCain referred to his
service on the House Education Committee 15 years ago as one of his
accomplishments in the education field during his 18 years in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The ad cites the news account of the debate as reporting that
McCain gave a `vague, unfocused answer'' to a question about
education. `If John McCain has never made education a priority as
Senator, why would he as president?'' the ad asked.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Rochester, Bush highlighted his own
record on education in Texas and contrasted it to McCain's.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush pushed for higher educational standards,
accountability for schools where children do not achieve and
against promoting children to the next grade regardless of the
achievement level.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his criticism of McCain was fair in light of
McCain's service as a federal legislator and Bush's own view that
Washington should stay out of local and state education policy,
Bush said: `The senator's running for president. The man ought to
have a vision for the future. He ought to be able to articulate
ideas he's not running for legislator, he's running to be chief
executive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stumped through New York with an entourage that included
Gov. George Pataki and former former American Red Cross President
Elizabeth Dole, herself a former presidential candidate and an icon
among Republican women.
</P>
<P>
   At a Rochester rally, Dole told the crowd of over 2,000 that the
`gender gap'' _ shorthand for the fact that women overwhelmingly
voted for President Clinton in the last election _ would come out
in Bush's favor this year.
</P>
<P>
   `That old gender gap in America is going to swing itself inside
out,'' Dole predicted.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, campaigning in Portland, Maine, and Boston, cited the
$2.5 million in broadcast ads that Bush allies purchased for
weekend airing and urged New Englanders to reject an effort ``to
hijack an election.'' The ad being broadcast in New York, Vermont,
Ohio and California was paid for by a newly formed advocacy
organization, Republicans for Clean Air.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Wyly, a Dallas entrepreneur and co-owner of two software
firms that recently sold for $7.9 billion, said he bought the
advertising blitz to draw distinctions between Bush and McCain on
environmental regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly's brother, Charles, also is a top fundraiser for Bush's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain decried the ``attack ad'' as one of the ``worst
examples'' of the need for the federal campaign finance reform and
ban on undisclosed, unlimited soft money campaign contributions
that he advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law limits the amount of money that an individual can
contribute to a political candidate. But there are no limits to the
amount of money that an individual or a corporation or a union can
spend to talk about issues. This so-called ``soft money'' is the
target of McCain and other political reformers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of sudden there's a proliferation of attack ads, of $2.5
million worth, in the last few days of this campaign, all over
America,'' McCain warned.
</P>
<P>
   Labeling the blitz ``a disgrace'' and ``shameful,'' McCain
added: ``I'm asking you to see through these cronies of George
Bush's that are perverting the political process with this $2.5
million in ads, see through it and reject that, reject that kind of
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in Boston's Copley Square, McCain raised the issue by
quoting Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know if I might borrow the words of Bob Dole and
(say): ``Where's the outrage? Where's the outrage?'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Playing off the crowd's reaction, McCain asked: ``Are we going
to allow two Texan cronies of George W. Bush to hijack an
election?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' roared the crowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them to keep their dirty money in the state of Texas, my
friends,'' McCain continued. ``Don't spread it all over New England
and America.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd took it from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``No new Texans; no new Texans,'' chanted the audience, much to
the delight of McCain and his wife Cindy, standing on a stage
surrounded by a sea of waving placards, small swaying American
flags and shouts, of ``Give 'em hell, John,'' and ``Don't give up
John.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted the Wyly ads were not connected to his campaign
and that he had no control over their content. Bush said he too had
been tarred by ads of the Sierra Club which he said `polluted my
record.''
</P>
<P>
   `In politics people have the right to freedom of speech, the
right to spend money the way they see fit,'' Bush said. `There's no
coordination'' with his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's wife Cindy left her husband's campaign to make
appearances on his behalf in Rhode Island and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
