<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEASONAL-RENTALS-REAL     03-04 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASONAL-RENTALS-REAL-1145(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SUMMER RENTALS HAVE ALREADY BEEN SNAPPED UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I wish you had called me two weeks ago, because the
rentals are just zapping up,'' Kelly Lee, an agent with B&AMP;K Real
Estate in Bay Head, N.J., said regretfully to a caller one day in
early February.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought we were too early to call,'' the astonished
woman responded. In fact, though the snow was still on the ground
and the breeze off the ocean was chilly, the woman was anything but
early in her quest to rent a house in the picturesque Jersey shore
village.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the right house in the right areas, we probably have six
or seven people waiting,'' Benia Grygent, an agent with B&AMP;K, said
as she drove around town showing houses. ``We start in the fall, so
that by now 80 percent of the available properties are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if the number of leases already signed and the swarms of
prospective tenants looking over houses, mansions, cottages or
condos everywhere from Nantucket to Connecticut to the Pocono
Mountains of northeastern Pennsylvania are indicative, it will be a
banner season for the rental market _ and a profitable one for
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Prices in these areas have risen from 5 percent to 25 percent in
the last year, brokers say; in the Hamptons they have escalated by
at least 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Fire Island Pines, a community with some of Fire Island's
more lavish homes and many swimming pools, ``99 percent of the
seasonal rentals for this summer were spoken for by Columbus Day,
and now we are getting inquiries about shorter rentals,'' said
Carole Weissman, an owner of Island Properties Real Estate and
Management Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the Poconos, Rob Baxter, a broker and owner of C.R. Baxter
Rentals Unlimited, said: ``People who know the community often
started looking last summer. It seems like the market is up over
last year, and we have run out of homes in certain categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Rentals for the properties that Baxter represents generally run
from $500 to $3,000 a week, depending on size, amenities and their
proximity to a lake. Most of his rental houses are in two lakeside
communities, Arrowhead Lakes and Lake Naomi, and he also has town
houses, two-story homes attached in groups of three or four,
bordering a lake in Pinecrest.
</P>
<P>
   In Nantucket, Mass., ``the market is out of control,'' said
Joyce Montalbano, a sales associate with Congdon and Coleman Real
Estate. Rentals listed by her agency range from $1,000 a week for a
one-bedroom cottage in town to $17,500 a week for a six-bedroom
house in Brant Point that is coveted for its easy access to both
beach and town.
</P>
<P>
   And in Martha's Vineyard, Ann Floyd, the owner and principal
broker of Sandcastle Realty, said: ``The demand is still
extraordinary despite the fact that some people say we have priced
ourselves out of consideration. We got inquiries starting last
summer and now we are wondering what are we going to do about the
inquiries for the year 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, rents go from $1,000 a week for a rustic workshop on
a farm to $15,000 for a house that is on a saltwater lagoon, sleeps
10 and has a private beach and dock.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere is panic over renting more palpable than in the
Hamptons. ``You show people a rental for $50,000 and they say,
``Bring my check to the landlord immediately so I am sure will have
a house,''' said Judi Desiderio, the vice president of Cook Pony
Farm Real Estate.
</P>
<P>
   The number of houses rented through her agency, which has seven
offices from Westhampton Beach to Amagansett, is up by 18 percent
over last year at the same time, she said, and the average rent has
increased by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``One couple walked into our Bridgehampton office last weekend
and were distraught because there were no brokers available to help
them,'' she said recently. ``They pleaded with the manager, `We
must get a rental right now.' They would have taken anything we
would have shown them.''
</P>
<P>
   Given their experience, such desperation was not totally
irrational: They had lost bidding wars to other renters with fatter
checks. ``They made an offer on one house and the offer got
topped,'' Desiderio said. ``On the second one, they signed a lease
and mailed it to the landlord, but by the time the landlord
received it, an aggressive broker from another office had
hand-delivered a check for more money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are frantic,'' she continued. ``We tell them: `Pick one
of the houses you saw. It won't be here next week.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though it is possible to find a small house in the Hamptons for
as little as $12,000 for the season, oceanfront mansions command at
least $250,000. The highest rental that Desiderio has heard so far
is $410,000 for the season, and that was snapped up in January.
``It is a complete estate,'' she said, ``with everything known to
man but a helicopter pad.''
</P>
<P>
   According to George C. Ballantyne, senior vice president and New
England regional manager of Sotheby's International Realty,
responses to what only a few years ago would have been considered
astronomic rents are largely dependent on where people come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers are more used to spending and are more prepared to
do so,'' he said. ``Residential prices are still substantially less
expensive in Boston and New England, even in Back Bay and Beacon
Hill, than they are in Manhattan. For example, in the past month I
sold a town house in Boston for a new record: $5.9 million. Many
town houses in New York sell for more than $10 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, does it make sense, no matter how unlimited the budget,
to plow hundreds of thousands of dollars into rent?
</P>
<P>
   For people who want grand mansions with breathtaking views,
tennis courts, swimming pools and other luxuries, that may be the
only choice, in the view of Timothy G. Davis, principal managing
director for Allan M. Schneider Associates, which has seven offices
in the Hamptons and Montauk. ``If you want to live in that kind of
a house, you can only rent it,'' he said. ``It is not available.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said: ``There is a house we rent in East Hampton
that has several guest houses and a pool on 30 acres and is
$400,000 for July 1 to Labor Day. If it were for sale it would be
$25 million, but it's not. There is no way to build it or buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   And though the economy has been soaring, there is no certainty
that it will continue its upward flight. That has bred a
live-for-the-moment attitude toward putting what would certainly be
the down payment on a house, and in some cases could buy a sizable
house, into rent.
</P>
<P>
   With all the bonuses on Wall Street, people find they have a
certain amount of disposable income,'' said Anne Orton, manager and
associate broker in the Southampton office of Cook Pony Farm. ``But
they don't know if they will have it next year, so they don't want
the responsibility of owning or maintaining the property, and they
don't want the continued overhead that kind of house would
command.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
