<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEASONAL-RENTALS-REAL     03-04 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASONAL-RENTALS-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: would command.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to stock-market profits and hefty bonuses, second-home
sales have been unusually brisk, depleting the supply of houses
available for rent and driving up rental prices, brokers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who want to be in the Pines will pay whatever is
necessary, and there is no balking, because they have the
discretionary funds,'' said Weissman, the Fire Island broker. An
oceanfront house there would go for $75,000 for the period between
May 1 and mid-September, she said; a simple three-bedroom inland
cottage for $18,500 for mid-May to mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   In Nantucket, ``we're probably getting up to 50 new inquiries a
day,'' said Douglas Foregger, chairman of Country Village Rentals
and Real Estate, which conducts business there as well as in Stowe,
Vt.; Aspen, Colo.; St. Bart's in the French West Indies; and Lyford
Cay and Harbour Island in the Bahamas. ``We have doubled the number
of houses rented over the same time last year, and the phones are
ringing nonstop.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he added: ``The market in Nantucket is now very strong
for October and November, because prices go way down then. You can
figure that a rental that would be $10,000 for a week in August can
be as low as $5,000 a week in late October and November.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lake Wallenpaupack in the Poconos, prices exceed those of
last year by about 10 percent, said Peter Helms, president of Davis
R. Chant Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   The rental season in Lake Wallenpaupack does not go into full
gear until the beginning of March, ``but we are getting probably
twice as many calls already as last year,'' Helms said. ``A rustic
cottage with three bedrooms and a loft starts at $800 a week and
can go to $1,100. A four- to five-bedroom house can bring as much
as $1,600 a week. The $800 house would have been $750 last year,
and there has been no resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some house hunters have found they have to spend much more than
they planned. Others have made compromises, and still others have
found themselves shut out, so far.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick D. Hoff of Hackensack, N.J., who retired as director
of national accounts for the former Celanese Corp. five years ago,
was fully prepared to pay $22,000 a month for a long season rental
in Bay Head or Mantoloking, N.J. But when he went to look last
month, he found what he considered all the nicely appointed places
taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead I saw a lot of yuck, smelly older places,'' said Hoff,
who was widowed and is now in the process of getting a divorce from
his second wife. ``Sure I could easily spend $100,000 and like what
I am in, but that is crazy. It is a down payment on something. I
want value for my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Millington of Manhattan, a 28-year-old financial
software account executive, has been renting group houses with
friends almost every summer in towns on the New Jersey shore like
Belmar, South Belmar, Sea Girt and Spring Lake since graduating
from college in 1993. She began looking in those locales in
November but didn't take anything then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was $20,000 to $24,000 for Memorial Day to Labor
Day, and we thought we would have a bigger group,'' she said. ``We
didn't have enough people who wanted to spend that kind of money or
make that kind of commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   In January she resumed her search and found a house for $9,000,
but it was only for five weeks between Memorial Day and the end of
July. Finances were a major consideration. ``The price worked out
better for the partial summer, and we figure we will be more likely
to come down every weekend this way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Susan Kirshenbaum of Manhattan, a partner at Greenberg
Kirshenbaum, a recruiting firm for advertising agencies, and two
friends paid $24,000 for the Memorial Day to Labor Day season for a
three-bedroom, two-bath house on a cul-de-sac in Amagansett, Long
Island, that she found barely adequate. ``It had a Murphy-bed
version of a kitchen where if you opened the refrigerator door, it
hit the wall,'' she said. ``The broker told the owner he could get
$40,000 for it this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead she and her friends will pay an amount she would only
describe as ``significantly more than $30,000'' for a small
three-bedroom house perched on a dune in Amagansett. ``Two years
ago we rented that same house for June and July because we thought
the rental for the whole summer was absurd, and now we are paying
it,'' she said. ``But how much is happiness worth?''
</P>
<P>
   That depends on the locale, on the size of the house, on the
amenities and the length of the rental _ but more than anything
else on its proximity to the water, preferably the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   In Osterville on the south shore of Cape Cod, for example, Paul
Grover, senior vice president of Kinlin Grover GMAC Real Estate,
which has 14 offices on the Cape, said: ``A nice oceanfront rental
on a sandy beach could be $30,000 to $50,000 a month for July and
August. Across the street, you would pay $15,000 to $20,000 per
month, and if you are in the village, walking distance to the
beach, you can get a nice house for $10,000 a month, but then you
wouldn't have a private beach. If you have to drive to the beach,
then the rental could be $5,000 a month.''
</P>
<P>
