u f BC-SEASONAL-RENTALS-REAL     03-04 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASONAL-RENTALS-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: a month.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Lake Naomi in the Poconos, prices range from $500 to $3,000 a
week. ``It's the lake that makes the difference in price,'' Baxter
said. ``Off the lake they don't bring in more than $1,100. Those on
the lake have their own private beach and maybe a boat docked, and
most of those are already booked.''
</P>
<P>
   Rents for houses in Litchfield County, where many artists,
writers and theatrical and political luminaries have homes, are
significantly less than on Long Island. ``If the Hamptons is upward
of $70,000 for the season,'' said Seymour Surnow, owner of the
Surnow Group at William Raveis Real Estate, ``then our top rent is
$50,000.''
</P>
<P>
   And there would be no roughing it at that price. ``That would
get you a four-bedroom, centrally air-conditioned house with a
heated pool on 10 acres with ponds and English gardens, if you're
lucky,'' he said. ``It is up 10 percent over last year, and several
years ago it went for $10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The range of rents in the area goes from $8,000 or $10,000 for
the season up to $50,000, he said. Surnow said last week that he
had just got a listing for a four-bedroom saltbox in Bridgewater
for $13,000. Another listing he described as modest is for a
three-bedroom house in Roxbury on 46 acres that is available for
$21,000 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the bargain _ relatively speaking _ prices, he said, the
area offers a more subdued lifestyle despite its high quotient of
celebrities. ``There is no scene here at all,'' he said. ``You
could see Mia Farrow, Stephen Sondheim, Dustin Hoffman and Arthur
Miller in the grocery store, and no one gives them a never-mind.''
(You won't see Whoopi Goldberg anymore; Surnow just sold her
farmhouse in Cornwall.)
</P>
<P>
   ``And you don't have to make restaurant reservations two weeks
ahead,'' he said. ``In fact there are not that many restaurants.
The big excitement on Saturday evening is having friends come
over.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as ambience is concerned, modernity seems to prevail over
charm, no matter what the locale. ``In the past a lot of people who
would go to Martha's Vineyard or Nantucket would want a great old
farmhouse with a lot of character,'' Foregger said. ``Now they want
new and shiny and not as much rustic.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Nantucket has exceptionally strict rules on
architecture, style, color and trim _ the rules dictate, for
example, that in most circumstances houses must be gray _ ``you can
still make an old house new inside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Martha's Vineyard, ``people may want a quaint New England
shingled cape with a rose-covered fence,'' Floyd said, ``but they
also want it to be well equipped. They ask for fax machines, a
second plug and phone for Internet access, Jacuzzis and nicely
equipped kitchens. We hardly ever get requests for swimming pools
or tennis courts.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the Hamptons, ``most people won't even look
unless something has a pool and is centrally air-conditioned,''
said Tina S. Fredericks, a broker who has been in business in the
Southampton to Montauk area for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think people came here for the beach and the air
quality,'' she said. ``If they could go swimming in the bay they
were very happy. Now everyone wants air conditioning, not air
quality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1626EST &QL; 
