<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-0305-COX     03-04 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRADLEY INVOKES HARRY TRUMAN IN PREDICTING COME-FROM-BEHIND
VICTORY
 &HT;    For Sunday, March 5
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the latest polls showing him trailing Vice
President Gore by 20 points here, Democrat Bill Bradley invoked the
name of Harry Truman Saturday to galvanize voters for a come from
behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little behind, but it's not over,'' Bradley told 250
supporters standing outside in New York's Washington Square Park.
``You know, I came from Missouri. You know Harry Truman. They said
he was finished in 1948, that he didn't have a chance, and you know
what happened there? He came from behind and won.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley campaigned in four New York neighborhoods Saturday _ two
of its richest and two of its poorest _ before boarding a plane to
his native Missouri to deliver a speech to Democrats in Hannibal,
the birthplace of writer Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley plans to campaign in Buffalo, Cleveland and Maryland on
Sunday before winding up his campaign in New York again Sunday
night. He is scheduled to remain in and around New York City
through ``Super Tuesday,'' when 15 states and American Samoa cast
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Although polls show him trailing Gore in all the Super Tuesday
states, Bradley insisted Saturday that he could ``surprise some
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of 250,000 people have voted in this country,'' Bradley
told a CBS interviewer on Manhattan's upper west side. ``I think
Tuesday will be a decisive time because eight and a half million
people will vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's New York city rallies in Washington Square Park and on
the upper west side drew small, but enthusiastic crowds. They
chanted the candidate's name and waved Bill Bradley posters.
</P>
<P>
   On the upper west side, Bradley was joined on stage by his wife,
Ernestine. Mrs. Bradley danced on stage to the rhythms of Latin
music provided by a live band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all going to dance our way into next Tuesday,'' she
told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate was joined at various stops by former New York
mayor Ed Koch, actor Harvey Keitel, Sen. Pat Moynihan , D-N.Y., and
a former New York Knicks teammate, Dave DeBusschere.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, several of Bradley's New York supporters said they
were relieved that the candidate was finally campaigning in New
York. Koch, who had publicly criticized the campaign's decision to
spend six days in Washington state before its March 29 primary, was
one supporter who said he was glad to have Bradley back in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question ... he's the underdog, but New Yorkers
love the underdog,'' Koch said after appearing with Bradley in
Washington Square Park. ``So I'm hopeful that we can turn it around
and make him a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   But Koch also underscored the importance of the Empire State to
Bradley's chances of winning the Democratic nomination. ``If you
can't win New York, you can't win the country,'' Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley encountered some skepticism as he campaigned in
Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood, a lower income
African-American community. Bradley shook hands with voters as he
walked along Fulton Street, which bustled with sidewalk vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you really, really do something for the community?'' Mary
L. Greene asked Bradley skeptically.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for me to do this if I am not going to do
something that is important to people,'' Bradley responded.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said nothing about Gore in any of his public speeches to
voters Saturday, but his campaign released a statement from Bradley
that again called on the vice president to explain more fully his
presence at a California fund-raiser in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley issued the statement in response to a story appearing in
the Philadelphia Inquirer. The newspaper account suggested that
Gore knew in advance that the event, held at a Buddhist temple, was
in fact a fund-raiser. The event has become significant because the
organizer of the event, Maria Hsia, was convicted last week of
campaign fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said only that he knew the event was ``finance
related.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ``has yet to explain what his mistakes were
and why he made them,'' Bradley said in the statement. ``Now is the
time for Al Gore to be straight with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for the vice president's campaign,
said the charges were ``the most recycled story in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole issue has been gone through with a fine tooth comb
by the Justice Department and congressional committees,'' Hattaway
said. ``And they have found no wrongdoing on the vice president's
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett can be reached by e-mail at: kenf(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
