<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CLINTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS CLINTONS MAKE RACE AN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Saturday that President
Clinton appeared to have joined his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
in making police brutality and race relations a major issue in the
New York Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds as if the Clintons are trying to drive this as a
political issue,'' the mayor said, speaking to reporters before a
St. Patrick's Day parade in Queens. Giuliani was responding to the
president's remark on Friday night that he found it ``hard to
imagine'' that if Amadou Diallo had been white, and in a white
neighborhood, he would have been killed. Diallo, an immigrant from
Guinea, was killed in a Feb. 4, 1999, police shooting in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was also responding to criticism made on Friday
by Hillary Rodham Clinton, who said that Giuliani's administration
had failed to maintain the trust of people in some New York
neighborhoods while acting aggressively to reduce crime.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the president's comment, Giuliani said, ``With
all deference to the president of the United States, I think he
should give more deference to the jury forelady, an
African-American lady.'' The forewoman, Arlene Taylor, had said
that race was not a factor in the acquittal of the four police
officers in the Diallo shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
