<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-ADS-NYT     03-04 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN TRIES TO STOKE ANGER OVER ENVIRONMENTAL ADS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ Borrowing a line from the Republicans' last
losing presidential nominee, Sen. John McCain of Arizona thundered
``where's the outrage?'' Saturday as he tried to spur a backlash
against political commercials paid for by a Texas businessman whose
family members are big backers of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The question _ once Bob Dole's futile end-of-campaign outcry
against President Clinton's 1996 campaign fund-raising practices _
allowed McCain to return to his centerpiece issue as he barnstormed
through New England and upstate New York in the last weekend before
Tuesday's critical primaries.
</P>
<P>
   All across the Northeast, McCain tried to stoke rebellion
against Bush by pointing to the revelation that Sam Wyly, a wealthy
Texas businessman, and his family had paid $2.5 million for
advertisements criticizing McCain on the environment, an issue that
resonates among the kinds of moderate voters McCain is trying to
draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two cronies,'' McCain called out to a crowd in Boston's Copley
Square, ``two cronies of Governor Bush got together 2 and one half
million dollars and spent it on attack ads that are being run all
over America attacking me on environmental issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyly and his brother Charles gave more than $200,000 to Bush's
two gubernatorial campaigns; Charles Wyly is a ``Pioneer,'' the
name given to Bush's top fund-raisers, those who have brought in at
least $100,000 for the Bush presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that at first the origins of the commercials were a
mystery. Then they were linked to the Bush supporters. ``It is a
disgrace,'' he said, ``and I want to know, if I may borrow the
words of Bob Dole, `Where's the outrage? Where's the outrage?'''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd shouted back ``It's here,'' McCain asked ``Are we
going to allow two cronies of George W. Bush to hijack the
election?''
</P>
<P>
   He wound up, ``Tell them to keep their dirty money in the state
of Texas.'' The crowd, waving McCain signs, whimsically shouted
back, ``No new Texans, No new Texans,'' a variation of the usual
Republican chant of ``No new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, at whose side McCain campaigned in 1996, began shouting
out ``Where's the outrage?'' at the end of his losing campaign for
president after revelations that a fund-raiser for the Democratic
National Committee had raised questionable and in some cases
illegal contributions from overseas sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats ultimately returned several million dollars and
Clinton's fund-raising eventually came under intense scrutiny from
Congress. Just this week Maria Hsia, a fund-raiser close to Vice
President Al Gore, was convicted of laundering illegal donations in
the last presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   By Maine, McCain had dropped his ``where's the outrage'' cry but
not his condemnations of the last-minute ads, which he said
violated the spirit of the contribution limits in the campaign
finance law.
</P>
<P>
   In Binghamton, N.Y., Bush told voters Saturday that he was the
one Republican candidate for president who had both an impressive
record on education and a detailed vision for federal education
policy and repeatedly belittled McCain for speaking in what Bush
said was a vague, uncertain voice on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally at the airport in Rochester, Bush noted the many
young children whose parents had brought them to the event and
said, ``Seeing the faces of the future reminds me of how important
it is to have a nominee for the Republican Party and a president of
the United States who understands how to make sure that every child
is educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running against a person that, when asked about education
reforms, said, `Onetime, I was a member of the education committee
of the United States Congress,''' Bush continued, referring to an
answer McCain gave in a debate on Thursday. ``That's not good
enough to lead our party to victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was trying to steer the focus away from the Wyly
advertisements that McCain and many political analysts have
criticized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
