u a BC-NY-RAPE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      03-04 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RAPE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED IN SEX ATTACKS BASED ON DNA MATCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A suspected serial rapist was charged in four sexual
attacks in and near Rosedale, Queens, late Friday after DNA from
blood on a knife linked him to two of the crimes, officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Rodolfo Beach, 31, of Rosedale was arraigned late
Friday on charges of rape, attempted rape, sodomy and robbery, said
Sherry Hunter, a spokeswoman for the Queens district attorney,
Richard A. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Beach was arrested Wednesday and charged after his DNA matched
DNA samples recovered in two rape cases and after a victim in a
third case identified him in a lineup, the police said. The fourth
case involved endangering the welfare of a child during a burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Beach had been a suspect in nine sexual attacks: eight in
southwestern Queens and one in Nassau County, police said. The DNA
tests cleared him of suspicion in one attack, but he now faces
charges in four and remains a suspect in four others, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   All the attacks occurred within five miles, and last year
officials said they believed the rapist was familiar with the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst kind of crime, one that leaves women afraid
in their own homes and looking over their shoulders in their own
neighborhoods,'' Brown said in an interview Saturday. ``Hopefully,
the filing of these charges will restore a sense of safety to the
Rosedale community.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from the New York Police Department's Queens Special
Victims Squad began investigating Beach in the series of attacks
that began two days before Christmas 1998 and continued until last
November. Beach became a suspect soon after he was found in the
bedroom of a 12-year-old girl in Rosedale, according to Hunter,
Brown's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had broken into this woman's house and a 12-year-old girl
woke up and he was standing beside her bed, unbuttoning his
pants,'' Hunter said. ``She and her mother began screaming and then
the uncle came in and stabbed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncle, whose name was not released by the police, began
chasing Beach on 240th Street, but eventually lost him, officials
said. Police officers spotted him and arrested him outside a
friend's house on 240th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught him not far away in a driveway where he was
bleeding from the stab wound, but because nothing happened in the
house they could only really arrest him for the burglary even
though he fit the pattern of other rapes that had occurred,''
Hunter explained.
</P>
<P>
   Beach was charged with burglary and endangering the welfare of a
child. Law enforcement officials said that Beach was unable to post
the $250,000 bail on the burglary charge and was sent to Rikers
Island.
</P>
<P>
   His arraignment came two weeks after Gov. George E. Pataki
proposed the most aggressive laws in the nation for solving crimes
using DNA analysis. The proposals would require every person
convicted of a crime to provide a biological sample for a state
database.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That aspect of the proposal has come under fire from some civil
libertarians who say it is an inappropriate government intrusion.
But Brown said Saturday that Beach's case is the strongest evidence
yet to support the governor's proposal, adding that the collection
is ``something we should be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that Beach did not immediately
become a suspect in the other attacks because the home invasion in
November did not fit the pattern, which involved a man following
women from cars, cabs and dollar vans and then attacking them in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   But the DNA, taken from blood on the uncle's knife blade, linked
him to two Rosedale attacks in September and October. In the first
of those attacks, a 20-year-old college student was raped and
robbed after Beach followed her home from school, officials said.
In the second incident, a 55-year-old woman was attacked behind her
home, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Beach was later identified during a lineup by the 30-year-old
woman who was attacked in December 1998. Beach was on parole for
burglary until March 2001, but because his previous offenses were
not on a certain list of felonies that require DNA samples, his DNA
was not placed in the state databank, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite cases like Beach's, civil libertarians have expressed
concern that the state might improperly use DNA samples collected
and that the sampling should be done only in the most serious
crimes, as opposed to cases like civil disobedience and turnstile
jumping.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, Brown said that Beach's case was an excellent
example of why ``it makes a great deal of sense to have the DNA of
everyone who commits a crime in the state's DNA databank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
