<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-POLICE-BIAS-910(2T     03-04 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-BIAS-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH CHOICES FOR NEW JERSEY POLICE LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ During his first four months as superintendent
of the New Jersey State Police, Col. Carson J. Dunbar Jr. has tried
to move the force beyond its racial-profiling scandal by
instituting several new procedures intended to deter future
discrimination by troopers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the coming months, Dunbar faces two far more incendiary
tasks that are likely to determine whether he can change the
culture of the force and restore public confidence in the agency.
</P>
<P>
   First, Dunbar must determine how harshly to punish officers
whose discrimination led to the profiling scandal. Then he must
decide how aggressively to investigate dozens of supervisors
accused of tolerating, and in some cases encouraging, racial
profiling and sexual harassment by troopers.
</P>
<P>
   This month Dunbar will begin hearing a backlog of nearly 100
disciplinary cases against troopers, many involving charges that
officers singled out or mistreated civilians based on the color of
their skin. The state attorney general's office is also reviewing
about 31 Equal Employment Opportunity Commission complaints that
some troopers and supervisors harassed minority and female
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to weighing the evidence against officers and
punishing those who are guilty, Dunbar must also decide the
delicate issue of whether to hold the troopers' commanders
accountable for failing to supervise them. More than a dozen
lawsuits have been filed by troopers who say they were ordered or
taught to single out drivers based on their skin color, or were
subjected to racial or sexual discrimination on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those accusations have yet to be heard in court, but in
at least two cases, state judges have ruled that there was
compelling evidence that some supervisors contributed to an
atmosphere in which discrimination flourished. So in shaping the
force he hopes to lead into the future, Dunbar will have to pass
judgment on midlevel commanders who have been accused of a litany
of racial and sexual discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   One sergeant accused of maligning black and female troopers
drove a pickup truck emblazoned with the words ``Coon Hunter'' for
more than a year, despite complaints from minority officers,
according to court papers. At least six supervisors are named in
lawsuits as encouraging troopers to single out black and Latino
drivers on the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Several supervisors who devised the training techniques that a
state judge blamed for encouraging racial profiling are still on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Most noteworthy is the case of Lt. Col. Robert Dunlop, now the
deputy superintendent, who has had significant input in Dunbar's
reorganization of the agency. Dunlop has been named as a defendant
in three discrimination suits, and one of the plaintiffs has said
he encouraged discrimination against blacks and routinely referred
to female troopers using a vulgar reference to female genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlop did not return repeated calls requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar has postponed more than 300 promotions that he had
scheduled for Friday _ partly, he said, because he needed more time
to review the accusations against supervisors and determine whether
their promotions should be denied.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar is left with some uncomfortable choices. He must bring
about enough change to win over the public, assure minority
officers that their rights will be respected and convince all
employees that they will be held accountable for their actions.
Meanwhile, he has to avoid inciting the politically powerful state
police union and alienating the 2,800 officers under his command.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dunbar has taken great pains to portray himself as a
reformer rather than a vindictive avenger.
</P>
<P>
   He has accelerated the state's campaign to install video cameras
in all patrol cars to monitor troopers' actions during traffic
stops. But he has also used the cameras to seek criminal charges
against civilians who falsely accuse troopers. Last month, Dunbar
announced that he would add equipment and staffing to Internal
Affairs, yet he has not transferred any of the 10 investigators
who, he said, performed shoddy investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar has also announced that he will impose stiffer penalties
on employees guilty of misconduct in the future. But last month,
when he was asked whether he would aggressively investigate the
supervisors accused of teaching profiling techniques, he seemed
uninterested in delving too deeply into the past. ``I have a hard
enough time looking forward now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar has since amended that statement, saying that he would
not initiate any intensive review of state police commanders, but
would investigate any new evidence suggesting that supervisors
encouraged or engaged in discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to look at the cases we have, almost 100 of them,
then follow the trail wherever it leads me, whether it involves
supervisors or anyone else,'' he said last week in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Those mixed messages make some civil rights advocates question
whether Dunbar has the will or political muscle to upset entrenched
members of the state police hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The State Troopers Fraternal Association has thus far been
supportive of his measured steps. But many police experts say
Dunbar could further alienate members of New Jersey's minority
community and undermine morale on the force if he leaves in place
commanders who committed or encouraged discrimination.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Patrick V. Murphy, who took over the New York Police Department
in 1970 after the Knapp Commission found a widespread pattern of
systemic payoffs and corruption, said that without accountability
of supervisors, any reform plan would quickly become mired in
officers' cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If among that top command there are bad apples and everybody
knows it, the new superintendent does himself a disservice to
permit that kind of person to remain in power,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only a handful of officers have faced departmental
punishment for racial profiling. The department would not say how
they had been disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   The two troopers who shot three unarmed minority men on the New
Jersey Turnpike in April 1998, making racial profiling the state's
dominant issue, now face criminal charges in the shooting and are
accused of misrepresenting the race of the drivers they stopped, in
order to conceal their racial profiling. Ten other troopers may
face prosecution for filing false documents about the race of
people they stopped, Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   To Dunbar, who spent over 20 years at the FBI, the highly
publicized troubles of the New Jersey State Police offer an
opportunity to establish a national reputation as a reformer.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent's performance also carries high stakes for
Gov. Christie Whitman. The governor belatedly acknowledged the
existence of racial profiling last year _ more than two years after
a Gloucester County judge found evidence of widespread
discrimination by troopers _ and now seems committed to changing
the culture of the force.
</P>
<P>
   If Dunbar makes only marginal progress, however, history could
well remember Whitman as the governor who acknowledged the problem
of racial profiling but failed to solve it.
</P>
<P>
   The governor forced the former superintendent, Carl A. Williams,
to resign last year for racial insensitivity, after he told a
newspaper reporter that minority groups were largely responsible
for the illegal drug problem. But some of the governor's more
recent statements suggest that she does not believe midlevel
commanders should bear the bulk of the responsibility for
institutionalized racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leaders, many of whom have praised Dunbar's
performance, say that the Whitman administration's reluctance to
focus on supervisors has made his job as superintendent more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Reginald T. Jackson, head of the Black Ministers
Council of New Jersey, pointed out that the attorney general's
office investigated the force for several months last year and
could have disciplined or fired the most troubled supervisors
before Dunbar became superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the attorney general's office put him in a tough
spot,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office has also been accused of
taking a lenient approach to harassment complaints. One trooper,
Jennifer Morse, filed a sexual harassment complaint and a civil
lawsuit claiming that she had been harassed and verbally abused for
years by a lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Morse's lawyer, Phil Moran, said the supervisor repeatedly
touched her hair and body, and humiliated her in front of
co-workers by making unwelcome sexual advances and forcing her to
listen to his sexually explicit fantasies about his stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Attorney General John Farmer found that most of her
charges were substantiated, although the lieutenant admitted to
touching her in a different way from what she alleged. Farmer
ordered the lieutenant to undergo counseling, but he remains on the
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret any inconvenience that you may have experienced as a
result of matters you expressed in your complaint,'' Farmer wrote
to Morse. ``It is my hope that you and the other employees involved
will be able to put these matters behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Shatzkin, a spokesman for the attorney general's office,
said the lieutenant could still be disciplined by the department.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar has taken steps to open up the historically secretive
state police discipline system, by releasing statistics on the
number of cases against officers, but he refuses to discuss
individual cases, so it is unclear whether the lieutenant will face
administrative charges. That reticence, a hallmark of the FBI
internal discipline system in which Dunbar worked for years,
worries some civil rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years the state police discipline system was veiled in
secrecy, the good ol' boys protected each other and it turned into
a civil rights disaster,'' said William Buckman, a lawyer who
represents several clients in racial profiling cases. ``If they're
allowed to continue that secrecy, there's no reason to believe that
anything will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar said that while he understood the public's desire for
more thorough disclosure of police disciplinary matters, they were
private personnel issues. No one _ in the state police or out _
should mistake his discretion for timidity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something is wrong, it's wrong,'' Dunbar said. ``And if I
see patterns of conduct that is improper, I'm not going to tolerate
it, even if it may make some people upset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
