<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-FRANCO-NYT     03-04 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-FRANCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HUNGER CONTINUES FOR FRANCO IN BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ There is no single low point. When John
Franco looks back on the last 10 years, so many of which were so
forgettable, he cannot pick out rock bottom. The worst part, he
said, was that empty feeling, most acute on the afternoon drives to
Shea Stadium, the neighborhood park that was jumping before he
started working there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lowest point?'' the Mets reliever said, repeating a
question. ``When you're out of contention in June, driving to the
ballpark knowing that you have don't have a chance to make the
playoffs and World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   There was 1992, Franco remembers, and that was bad. The Mets had
made several expensive additions, and looked ready to return to the
postseason for the first time in four years. Instead, they lost 90
games, then lost 103 the next season. There were injuries, Franco
said, but the mix of players was just not right.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bunch of guys, it's a little different now,'' Franco
said, standing at his corner locker at Thomas J. White Stadium. The
stall to his left belongs to Al Leiter, who won the World Series
with Florida, and the stall on his right belongs to Robin Ventura,
who won a division title with the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody seems a little more hungry,'' Franco said. ``Not to
say that we weren't hungry in '92, but maybe we're better prepared
now than we were then. Back then we still had a lot of guys from
the '86 team and the '88 team, when they won. But now we've got
guys from different organizations coming in, guys who haven't won
before, guys who have. Everybody's on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Franco's pages have been printed on Mets stationary since
Dec. 6, 1989, when the Mets acquired him from Cincinnati in the
deal that sent Randy Myers to the Reds. Franco had made three
All-Star teams in four years before the trade. The year he left,
Cincinnati won the World Series. Franco still laughs at the memory,
and shakes his head: that's life.
</P>
<P>
   Franco had a chance to move on again last winter. He had 19
saves when a finger injury in July sidelined him for two months.
When he returned, Armando Benitez was the closer. Franco played in
the postseason for the first time in his career, but he had
effectively lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year veteran who has played the last five years for the
same team, Franco controlled where the Mets could have traded him.
He wanted to know if contending teams had interest in him as a
closer. The Mets checked around: Boston, Cleveland, Philadelphia,
St. Louis and Seattle were looking for closers, and Franco was an
appealing name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wanted that, that could have happened,'' said Franco's
agent, Dan Horwits. ``That was the easy part.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard part was deciding if Franco really wanted it. The
advantages of staying were obvious: Franco is a Brooklyn native who
lives in Staten Island with his wife, Rose, and their two children,
and the Mets had just been two games short of a World Series berth.
But if the 39-year-old Franco and the 27-year-old Benitez both
stayed, Benitez was the obvious closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the toughest decision he's ever made in his
professional career, by far,'' Horwits said. ``Every night,
probably for several weeks, he and Rose and I would discuss the
pros and cons, the what-ifs. It was a very tough decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco's chance at the career saves record was a consideration,
Horwits said, though not a major one. Franco is second on the
career list with 416 saves, 62 behind Lee Smith, and with two good
seasons he could have the record _ and, perhaps, a shot at the Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I had to sit back and think about,'' Franco
said of his decision. ``You know, you're so used to doing something
for a long time. But it all comes back to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Steve Phillips and the co-owner Fred Wilpon
assured Franco that the Mets were committed to making a big push to
win in 2000. Winning had meant so much to Franco in '99 _ ``You
could tell by his emotions, what he said and what he did; it wasn't
subtle,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said _ and he didn't want to miss
out if the Mets went all the way this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot about him, not to ask for a trade when he's a
guy who has a really good chance to take over the saves record and
he doesn't know if he's going to be the closer or not,'' said the
Mets right-hander Bobby J. Jones. ``It just shows how he feels
about the organization and how much he wants to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco has not been told his role for this season, and Valentine
has been careful not to officially tag him a setup man. Valentine
said he has not seen Benitez throw in games yet, and points out
that Benitez is coming off knee surgery. But Benitez signed a
four-year, $22 million contract extension last month, and Mets
officials openly talked of him as their closer. Franco politely
insists he will do whatever is necessary to help the Mets win.
</P>
<P>
   The saves record may not be out of Franco's reach. He has no
plans to retire soon, and can be a free agent after the season. As
Horwits said: ``Obviously, teams are going to want him as a closer
next year. Probably the same teams that were interested over the
winter will be interested in having him back as a closer.''
</P>
<P>
   When Franco decided to stay, then, he was not saying he wanted
to be a Met forever. Or was he?
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is full of decisions,'' Franco said, ``and I'll just
worry about that when the time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Franco said, he is not looking back. ``I made the right
decision,'' he said. ``It feels good, the organization's been good.
I want to win. I got a taste of winning last year, and I think
we've got a real good shot of winning this year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
