<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FAMILY-FIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 HURT, 2 DIE AFTER FAMILY FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Bronx woman was in stable condition Saturday after
the man she lived with attacked her and her daughter with a knife
and hammer, then threw himself and their 9-year-old son off the
roof of the five-story apartment building where they lived.
</P>
<P>
   The man, David Pizarro, 38, died early Saturday at the scene,
and the couple's son, David Jacob Pizarro, was pronounced dead at
Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center, said a police spokesman,
Detective Walter Burnes.
</P>
<P>
   Pizarro and the woman he lived with, Anna DeValle, 35, fought
around midnight Friday in their apartment at 1819 Weeks Ave. in the
Bronx, Burnes said. They argued over $70 that she had taken from
him early in the day, the police said. Pizarro then attacked
DeValle, slashing her on the left arm with a knife, prompting the
woman's daughter, Annie Fernandez, 15, to intervene, the police
said. Pizarro then began to hit the girl in the head with a hammer,
the police said. The girl fled the third-floor apartment, and
Pizarro resumed attacking DeValle, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter ran downstairs, knocking on doors to try to find
help. She ran into the apartment where Sharees Nelson, 19, was
visiting his extended family.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was on her knees, her clothes were ripped, and she was
saying, `Help, help! He's going to kill my mother! I tried to call
the cops, but they asked too many questions,''' Nelson said
Saturday. Police said they had no record of a 911 call coming from
the Pizarro apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter told Nelson and his family that as she was calling
the police from her apartment, Pizarro hit her in the head.
</P>
<P>
   DeValle managed to flee the apartment, despite several knife
wounds in her torso.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in the apartment, Pizarro grabbed their son, David, the
police said, and took the boy to the roof of the five-story
building, where he jumped.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that a small number of witnesses tried to
persuade Pizarro to come down from the roof's ledge. Arriving at
the apartment building, the police found the 15-year-old girl, who
was treated for her injuries at a hospital, then released, Officer
George Jensen said.
</P>
<P>
   DeValle was treated for her wounds at a hospital, where she was
in stable condition Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that Pizarro had no history of domestic
abuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-PRIMARIES-VIEWER0305-     03-04 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-VIEWER0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presidential eggs in one early basket
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ So big, so soon, such an anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   That's the short take on politics this week, when voters in 16
states and American Samoa go to the polls in the biggest day of
presidential primaries and caucuses in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   For those tuning in late on the race for the Democratic and
Republican presidential nominations, it may all seem like one big
balloon drop. With about 60 percent of the delegates needed up for
grabs, Tuesday could pretty much decide the nomination in one or
both parties _ before many voters have fully caught up with the
fact that it's a presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   Even for loyal C-SPAN junkies, sorting through Tuesday's action
presents a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The big election day is not a planned event. It's the result of
an incremental process that began when several states, including
California and New York, took note of the success the South had in
attracting candidates in the 1980s with its big regional primary,
Super Tuesday, and moved their primary and caucus dates up even
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was already ahead of Super Tuesday, having moved its
primary date up at the behest of former Gov. Zell Miller to help
Bill Clinton in 1992. This year, the state has lots of company, not
concentrated in one region but spread all over the national map.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of differences among the states and between the
parties over how the delegates will be divvied up. Most states are
only concerned with presidential matters, but Ohio also has U.S.
Senate primaries. California, the most closely watched state, has a
confusing combination of an open primary with an election of
convention delegates confined to party members.
</P>
<P>
   It's so uncoordinated it doesn't really have a name. Some still
call it Super Tuesday, but that moniker has also been reserved for
the March 14 primary of six Southern and Southwestern states.
Titanic Tuesday has been used as a name, but it hasn't had time to
catch on.
</P>
<P>
   The same may be said for the primaries themselves. One thing to
watch for Tuesday is whether turnout falls below the record levels
set this year in New Hampshire, South Carolina and Michigan. There
was also a lot of political advertising in those states that most
voters in Tuesday's battleground states didn't see.
</P>
<P>
   If turnout is very low, there will be more calls to do something
about the front-loaded primary system. If it's higher than
expected, we'll probably hear more arguments for a national primary
or a rotating system of regional primaries.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few other things to watch for Tuesday, if the
nomination races don't provide enough suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Political insiders already know what the newscasters' body
language means when they go on the air before the polls close:
They've already seen early data from exit polls telling them the
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Advance word of the exit results usually sifts out into
political circles, but this year information has also been showing
up on the Internet for a much larger audience to see.
</P>
<P>
   This is touchy business for Bill Headline, executive director of
Voter News Service, which conducts the exit polling for a group of
news organizations. He declined to comment on what action VNS has
taken to discourage Web sites from publishing the information
before the polls close.
</P>
<P>
   One site where Web surfers won't get a sneak peak is Microsoft's
Web magazine, Slate, which last week declined to publish early
information on the Virginia and Washington state primaries, saying
that VNS had threatened legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``While my heart lusts for a battlefield pulped crimson with
bodies from the legal departments of Microsoft and VNS, we have
capitulated,'' Jack Shafer, a Slate editor, wrote. ``Although we
think VNS is stupid and wrong to want to keep this information
secret ... we stand censored.''
</P>
<P>
   For those concerned with letting the news out too early, the
continental ripple is another concern. Ever since Ronald Reagan's
victory over Jimmy Carter in 1980, there have been concerns about
voters on the West Coast staying at home because of early reports
from the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time the problem has surfaced at the primary
level. It may not matter so much in the Democratic race, where
former Sen. Bill Bradley's campaign was clearly sagging across the
board. But there could be questions if, for instance, Sen. John
McCain were to have a disappointing day in New York and news about
it suppresses turnout in California.
</P>
<P>
   The vice presidential name-drop game will be another feature to
watch for as the returns trickle in. Picking a running mate will be
the next big political question after the nominations are settled,
and the jostling won't take long to start Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   And while most returns are reported in percentages, take note of
which party gets the most voters out to the polls. The parties
certainly will be. So far this year the Republicans have had larger
turnouts, which can be attributed to a more spirited contest for
their nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But starting this week, both parties will be watching turnout,
with an eye toward who might have the advantage in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
