u a BC-NY-CHINATOWN-MAYOR-NY     03-04 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHINATOWN-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOISILY BUT FONDLY RECALLING CHINATOWN'S `MAYOR'
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the din of the festive banquet hall, it was
difficult to hear the elder statesmen praising Man Bun Lee, the man
who was popularly known as the mayor of Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed fitting that the crowd of more than 1,000 gathered
at a dinner last week to honor the memory of Lee, a man known for
urging the community to speak up for its rights, made so much
noise. It was fitting, also, that to reach the party at Jing Fong,
a restaurant on Elizabeth Street, most had to pass the Fifth
Precinct station house, which Lee had fought to keep open.
</P>
<P>
   Lee died of a heart attack at 75 last year, but in the
neighborhood, he remains a symbol of civic activism, the battle for
civil rights and the increased power of New York's Chinese
population.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent members of the Chinatown community, many of whom
considered Lee their civic compass, held the dinner on Tuesday _
Feb. 29, the day Percy E. Sutton, then Manhattan borough president,
proclaimed Man Bun Lee Day in 1976. The event was a fund-raiser to
support the building of a child care center in Chinatown bearing
Lee's name. The location of the center has yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Chang Wang, a former commissioner of the city's Department
of Employment, considers Lee her mentor. She said she remembered
his effectiveness, even in the face of disappointment. In 1982, the
neighborhood lost a battle with the city over a detention center
because it lacked the clout to fight to keep it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was extremely angry and hurt,'' said Wang, who was then
executive director of the Chinatown Manpower Project, the
employment and training group that sponsored the banquet. Lee was
its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Nora, you know what? It's a lesson for all of us in
the community. We lost for a good reason. We should form a voter
education alliance, to inform the community,''' she recalled. They
did, and 18 years later, the community has grown much stronger, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who emigrated from China in 1953 and earned a master's
degree in business and finance, helped lead two demonstrations of
20,000 people in the mid-1970s, in a march on City Hall against
police brutality, and in a fight to keep the precinct house.
</P>
<P>
   His concern for the young people of the neighborhood was well
known, and he was active in anti-gang efforts, even after he was
stabbed five times by a retaliating gang member, in the Kao Wah
Restaurant that he operated on Mott Street.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, Lee led many Chinatown institutions, including
the New York Lee Family Association, a fraternal and social
organization for members of the Lee family; the family
association's credit union, where he was comptroller; and the
Chinatown Consolidated Benevolent Association, the neighborhood's
largest civic organization. He also headed the board of Confucius
Plaza, a low-income housing complex in Chinatown, for which he
helped gain city approval.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the banquet, Sutton said he admired the way Lee
spoke out against injustices. ``Too often people who are recent
immigrants have a timidity, and do not speak up,'' Sutton said.
``He was concerned about children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
