<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMS-0305-COX     03-04 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONFIDENT GORE LOOKS PAST BRADLEY, WHO PREDICTS A
COME-FROM-BEHIND VICTORY
 &HT;    EDS: This is for papers wanting a single Democratic story. If
you desire serparate stories, please see BRADLEY-0305-COX and
GORE-0305-COX, which have moved.
 &HT;    OPTIONAL TRIM AT 800
 &HT;    For Sunday, March 5
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Vice President Al Gore is so confident of a ``Super
Tuesday'' primary victory over Democratic challenger Bill Bradley
that he began road-testing campaign themes against Republican
presidential rivals Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, campaigning in New York City, invoked the name of
Harry Truman as he predicted a come from behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little behind, but it's not over,'' Bradley told 250
supporters standing outside in New York's Washington Square Park.
``You know, I came from Missouri. You know Harry Truman. They said
he was finished in 1948, that he didn't have a chance, and you know
what happened there? He came from behind and won.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show him trailing Gore in all 15 ``Super Tuesday'' states.
The latest polls in New York put Gore ahead by 20 points there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the former New York Knicks basketball star insisted
Saturday that he could ``surprise some people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of 250,000 people have voted in this country,'' Bradley
told a CBS interviewer on Manhattan's upper west side. ``I think
Tuesday will be a decisive time because eight and a half million
people will vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore on Saturday looked past Bradley and began auditioning
anti-Republican attacks he is expected to use in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   His most potent weapon against the GOP nominee, judging from his
emphasis during Saturday's appearances in New York and
Massachusetts, is what is widely agreed to be the strong economy in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue now is whether or not we're going to keep that
prosperity going or whether or not we're going to take the advice
of both Republican candidates and take a right wing U-turn back to
the old polices of the past,'' Gore said during a rally at Boston's
historic Faneuil (pronounced FAN-yuhl) Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also raised environmental issues in his criticism of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain, something he has
rarely done in the Democratic contest with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the environment, just remember two numbers _ zero and one,
since this is the digital age,'' Gore said of the GOP presidential
contenders:
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them in the Senate two years ago had a zero rating from
the League of Conservation Voters. The other one is the governor of
a state which he has just led to the position of number one in air
pollution, number one in water pollution, number one in land
pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   He also ripped Bush for his anti-abortion stand, noting that the
Texas governor had met privately in the past with televangelists
Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell. He said the ``code'' language
Robertson and Falwell used following the meeting indicated Bush
would appoint Supreme Court justices committed to overturning Roe
v. Wade, the court ruling that granted abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're saying is they had a solid promise to give the
right wing extremist wing of the Republican Party control of our
Supreme Court and the interpretation of our Constitution,'' Gore
said. ``Let's stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore barely mentioned Bradley in a morning speech to several
hundred people who gathered on a sunny, brisk day in the square in
front of Faneuil Hall, which was built in 1742 and has provided a
forum for a number of historic figures, including Samuel Adams,
Frederick Douglass, Susan B. Anthony and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's passing reference to Bradley was to remind voters that
both he and his challenger have said that Tuesday's primary voting
in 15 states, including Massachusetts, ``will be the decisive
moment'' in the campaign for the Democratic campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You here in Massachusetts ... have an opportunity to close the
book on the Democratic nomination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' two senators, Ted Kennedy and John Kerry, joined
Gore on the stage and in the attacks on the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry ridiculed Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' with a
joke about Bob Jones III, president of Bob Jones University in
South Carolina, and John Rocker, the Atlanta Brave pitcher who made
inflammatory remarks about minorities, gays and immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The definition of George Bush's compassionate conservative
(cq.) is Bob Jones III forgiving John Rocker,'' Kerry quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Bob Jones University prohibited inter-racial
dating, barred gays from its campus and regarded Catholicism as a
false religion.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, several of Bradley's New York supporters said they
were relieved that the candidate was finally campaigning in New
York. Former New York Mayor Koch, who had publicly criticized the
campaign's decision to spend six days in Washington state before
its March 29 primary, was one supporter who said he was glad to
have Bradley back in the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question ... he's the underdog, but New Yorkers
love the underdog,'' Koch said after appearing with Bradley in
Washington Square Park. ``So I'm hopeful that we can turn it around
and make him a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Koch also underscored the importance of the Empire State to
Bradley's chances of winning the Democratic nomination. ``If you
can't win New York, you can't win the country,'' Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said nothing about Gore in any of his public speeches to
voters Saturday, but his campaign released a statement from Bradley
that again called on the vice president to explain more fully his
presence at a California fund-raiser in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley issued the statement in response to a story appearing in
the Philadelphia Inquirer. The newspaper account suggested that
Gore knew in advance that the event, held at a Buddhist temple, was
in fact a fund-raiser. The event has become significant because the
organizer of the event, Maria Hsia, was convicted last week of
campaign fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said only that he knew the event was ``finance
related.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ``has yet to explain what his mistakes were
and why he made them,'' Bradley said in the statement. ``Now is the
time for Al Gore to be straight with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for the vice president's campaign,
said the charges were ``the most recycled story in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole issue has been gone through with a fine tooth comb
by the Justice Department and congressional committees,'' Hattaway
said. ``And they have found no wrongdoing on the vice president's
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard, who is covering Gore, can be reached by e-mail
at: scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett, who is covering Bradley, can be reached by e-mail
at: kenf(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
