<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT &LR;      03-04 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' YORK HAS OUTSIDE SHOT AT TOP ROOKIE HONORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Gomez of the New Jersey Devils will probably win the
Calder Trophy as the National Hockey League's rookie of the year,
and there are good reasons for this. Gomez leads all rookies in
total points, he plays for a top team and he appeared in the
All-Star Game. As the NHL's first Hispanic star, the 20-year-old
Alaskan enjoys a considerable marketing push from league
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But another American playing in the New York metropolitan area
also will merit strong consideration for first-year honors, also
for good reason. He is Mike York of the Rangers, a center from
suburban Detroit, who leads all rookies in goals while centering
two veterans on the second line. York scored a goal and had an
assist in Friday night's 4-2 victory over Florida in Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The result helped the Rangers keep their precarious hold on a
low-rung playoff berth as they head for the West Coast to begin a
four-game trip on Monday night in San Jose. Going into Saturday
night, York's goal total of 21 was five more than that of Gomez.
But York's 41 total points were 16 behind Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   Other top rookies include Alex Tanguay of Colorado, Jan Hlavac
of the Rangers, Tim Connolly of the Islanders and Brian Rafalski of
the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   York's linemates are hardly rookies _ Adam Graves on the left
and Theo Fleury on the right. Including playoffs, these two have
combined for 1,952 NHL games and 747 goals over 25 seasons. Asked
after the Florida game what he likes about playing with York,
Fleury smiled and said: ``Oh, just about everything. He is going to
be a great player in this league. He competes. For a young guy, he
is good at all aspects of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves said York ``adds an element of speed. He sees the ice
well. He's good on defense and he's pretty good on the draws. He's
a smart player and a good kid, and he works hard.''
</P>
<P>
   York and Gomez met during a 10-day stint as roommates during
training camp for the U.S. junior team two years ago. ``We got to
know each other a little bit,'' York said. ``We don't talk on the
phone or anything like that. But when we see each other at the
rink, we'll say `hi' and talk a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Their routes to opposite banks of the Hudson River were
different. Gomez was a first-round draft choice who played as a
junior in the Western Canadian league. York was a sixth-round draft
choice who played four years in college at Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   York surprised everyone by winning a full-time job last autumn
with the Rangers. John Muckler, the coach, said he saw York play a
little last spring in the playoffs with the farm team in Hartford
and was not impressed then. But Muckler kept an open mind. His
evaluation improved in training camp and has stayed positive since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember when he's had two bad games in a row,''
Muckler said of York. ``He has that ability, if he does have a
stinker, to come right back. Earlier in the year I was concerned
about that, how a rookie gets into a rut and kind of drops off. But
he never did that.'' Muckler said York ``takes responsibility and
has leadership qualities'' and ``never wants to make a mistake and
he always wants to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has good quickness, good hands,'' Muckler said. ``Early on
in training camp we noticed the determination. He's just continued
to grow all year long.'' Muckler said that York ``has a good chance
of being in the final three'' for rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   York, 22, is from Waterford, Mich., the same town that produced
Pat LaFontaine. The area has a rich hockey culture. Near Canada, it
accommodates a top college league, a major junior team, two minor
professional leagues and, of course, the Red Wings, who have won
the Stanley Cup twice in the last three years for ``Hockeytown.''
Like LaFontaine, York is small for pro sports. At 5 feet 10 inches
and 185 pounds, York is slightly bigger than Fleury, somewhat
smaller than Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Like Fleury, York wears a goatee on his chin. Unlike Fleury or
Graves, he is not very verbal with the news media. When asked about
himself, York would rather praise his linemates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help me out a lot,'' York said. ``They tell me what to
expect from certain guys. They are excellent, both on and off the
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   He said LaFontaine was always his favorite player, that his
parents and an older brother knew LaFontaine, and that he met him
``a few times'' when he was growing up. York said he tried to play
LaFontaine's style. Regarding his personal success this season,
York said: ``I'm definitely surprised. I never thought I'd get this
many goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he is pleased or surprised by his Calder
candidacy, York said: ``Both. It would be a great honor. But the
biggest thing right now is to just get in the playoffs. The better
the team does, the better chance I'd have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
