<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIAGARA-MARIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART PROPELS NIAGARA OVER MARIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Niagara's Demond Stewart, the nation's
ninth-leading scorer in the regular season, picked up where he left
off in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference tournament on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart poured in 31 points _ eight above his average _ and
Niagara took off from a three-point halftime lead for a comfortable
83-65 victory over Marist in the quarterfinals at Pepsi Arena.
Stewart, a 6-foot-3-inch guard, has scored 30 points or more in
eight games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-seeded Niagara (17-11) advanced to the MAAC semifinals for
the second year in a row, while extending its winning streak to
three. Fourth-seeded Marist (14-14) had its four-game winning
streak snapped. Joe McCurdy had a team-high 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara expanded its 31-28 halftime lead to 46-36 with 11
minutes 21 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in scoring 15 points in the first half, Stewart darted
around the perimeter looking for the ball, and as soon as he got
it, he either shot it or burst to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   He swished a short turnaround jumper and then a three-point bomb
from the baseline to build a 51-36 lead midway through the second
half. After a basket by Marist's Tom Kenney, Stewart popped into
the lane for an easy layup to keep the lead at 15.
</P>
<P>
   The cushion grew to 19 with less than eight minutes left, but
Marist climbed back within eight points before Terry Edwards lofted
in a three-pointer to restore Niagara's double-digit lead with less
than five minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Marist, which advanced to the conference semifinals last season,
has not been to the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament since 1987. The winner of the MAAC tournament receives
an automatic bid to the national tournament. Niagara has not won
the conference tournament in its 11 years as a member, and has not
qualified for the NCAA tournament since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara rode a 7-0 spurt to take a 16-6 lead early in the first
half. The Purple Eagles made a 6-1 run minutes later to pull ahead,
22-10.
</P>
<P>
   But Niagara, the MAAC's worst-shooting team at 41 percent, is
also not the most selective when it comes to shots. The Purple
Eagles began missing from afar, allowing Joe McCurdy to pull Marist
back into the game. With his team trailing by 11, McCurdy hit a
short jumper and two 3-pointers on consecutive possessions, and
Drew Samuels glided in for a layup to cut Niagara's lead to 27-26.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart ended the half's scoring by bursting through the lane to
draw the foul and then making the free throws. Stewart made four of
10 field-goal attempts in the first half and six of eight free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara looked complacent at times on offense when it relied too
much on Stewart, but he compensated with improvisation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
