<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-HARBOR-REAL-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: NEW DOWNTOWN AREA TAKES ROOT IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With a 2.3-million-square-foot convention center as its
vanguard, a new commercial neighborhood with luxury housing is
emerging on Boston Harbor, which for almost four centuries has been
the heart of this compact city perennially in search of expansion
space. Nine projects valued at $3 billion are being developed in a
district once dominated by wharves, ship terminals, fish processors
and warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   On April 2, after almost a year of site preparation,
construction will start on the $700 million South Boston Convention
and Exhibition Center, the linchpin of this new downtown district.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big gorilla that's about to sit down on the
waterfront,'' said Dean F. Stratouly, a Cambridge developer who is
directing the convention center project for the Massachusetts
Convention Center Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Once completed in 2003, ``It will legitimize the whole area.''
Stratouly said, creating ``a demand for 4,800 hotel rooms and
support services that will drive up real estate values.''
</P>
<P>
   The modernistic 120-foot-long, six-story convention center will
be large enough to attract the major meetings that have been
bypassing Boston. The eight other projects being developed nearby
include luxury hotels, offices and 1,200 residential units to be
built within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   They will complement the convention center as well as the 1990s
projects _ a new federal courthouse and hotel _ that sprouted on
this section of the waterfront, which is a 10-minute walk from
Boston's financial district and a six-minute drive to Logan
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gold rush already,'' said Stratouly, president of
Congress Group Ventures, referring to the new projects being
planned and the rising real estate values. The increased real
estate costs are raising housing prices in the surrounding
residential areas of South Boston. ``The waterfront,'' Stratouly
said, ``is going from lunchboxes to briefcases.''
</P>
<P>
   But some wonder whether this boon for developers and businesses
will hamper the operations of New England's premier commercial
port, which in 1999, according to port officials, transported $10
billion in goods through its newly dredged waterways.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have incompatible uses, something has to give,'' said
Vivian Li, president of the Boston Harbor Association, a private
maritime advocacy group. ``The conventioneers and firms moving in
from the financial district will displace the small businesses that
work the commercial port.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 92 mostly maritime-related businesses were relocated to
assemble the 62-acre convention center site. But the Port of
Boston, which since 1996 increased the value of the cargo it
handles by 30 percent, hopes to acquire more waterfront space for
support operations like warehouses. ``We're bursting at the
seams,'' said Georgeanne Tacelli, a spokeswoman for the port.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling the competition under way for space at the harbor,
Gillette Co., one of New England's largest manufacturers, with a
sprawling plant on the South Boston waterfront, also intends to
continue growing in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the factor that has made all this development
possible and will determine which players can efficiently use the
waterfront is access to a modern intermodal transportation system,
a network that integrates travel by land, sea and air. ``What makes
this area work for any particular user is transportation,'' said
Li, the maritime advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1990s, about $20 billion in federal, state and
municipal funds has been earmarked to rebuild the land transport
network that runs through downtown Boston, linking the waterfront
and with the airport via a new tunnel under the harbor. During the
road construction, new sewer, water, electric and
telecommunications lines are being installed underground.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the funds has also been invested to upgrade facilities
at Logan Airport, as well as to clean and dredge the harbor waters.
</P>
<P>
   The convention-center site is at a crossroads where all forms of
the upgraded transportation network will intersect. It is within a
few blocks of what will be a rebuilt downtown highway, Interstate
93; a new extension of the Massachusetts Turnpike; a truck haul
road; a rapid transit line; and the Ted Williams Tunnel to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   However, while about $320 million in federal and state funds has
been allocated at the 500-acre commercial port for new terminals,
cranes and computerized truck-cargo processing, its transport
system is still missing a vital link.
</P>
<P>
   Modern ports need double-stack freight rail facilities so cargo
containers can be lifted off ships and loaded two high on freight
trains. In 1995 the state Legislature allocated $86 million to
modernize tracks and raise a few bridges to enable the double-stack
trains to pass underneath, but the funds have never been
appropriated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no more movement on double-stack rail,'' said David
Panagore, who is directing the convention center project for the
city planning agency. But a recent planning agency agreement with
CSX railroad will enable steel for the convention center to be
shipped to the site by rail, to lower construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Given these developments, shippers and truckers worry that they
may lose access to the area in a few years if roads are closed to
commercial traffic to make way for pedestrians, Li added.
Nevertheless, each year the port is generating $10 billion in
revenues and $3 billion in related economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the convention center, financed by $700 million in
state and municipal bonds and taxes, is likely to lose $15 million
annually in its early years while generating $500 million a year in
direct economic activity, according to Alan D. Reid, chief
financial officer of the convention center authority. ``The
convention center is a loss leader to fill the hotels and
restaurants,'' he explained.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The convention center has gone from concept to construction
quickly for a project of its size and complexity. In only three
years, a group of business leaders and politicians shepherded
enabling legislation through the Statehouse and agreed on a site
and a design; the city took the 62 acres by eminent domain; and the
South Boston community settled on a benefits package of about $10
million in housing, training and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The glass, steel and precast concrete convention center,
designed by Rafael Vinoly Architects of New York and HNTB
Architecture of Boston, will have a 600,000-square-foot exhibition
hall, 200,000 square feet of meeting rooms and parking for 1,000
cars in its first phase of 1.9 million square feet. Attached will
be a $265 million, 1,120-room Sheraton Hotel to be developed by
Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide Inc. of White Plains, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   While many hotel projects here and across the country have been
stymied by a dearth of financing, Starwood expects that banks will
extend loans and that pension funds will invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a hot hotel market, we're attached to a
state-of-the-art convention center, our site is a mile from the
airport and so much new development is planned for the area,'' said
Andrew E. Zobler, a vice president at Starwood.
</P>
<P>
   Development prospects are bright, Stratouly stressed. After he
completes his unpaid tour of duty for the convention center
authority, even he may invest there. ``At some point, this is going
to be prime property,'' he said. ``I can't develop anything now,
but I hope to in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
