<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-JAZZ-700(2TAKES)-     03-04 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ: EFFECTIVE, ENDURING _ AND ANCIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In February 1994, Jeff Hornacek boarded a flight for Salt Lake
City to play for his third team in three seasons. Traded from the
foundering Philadelphia 76ers to the veteran and, it seemed,
utopian Utah Jazz, the shooting guard was invigorated about having
a shot to win a National Basketball Association championship.
</P>
<P>
   The hope for Scott Layden, the Jazz general manager at the time,
was that Hornacek would blend in with Karl Malone and John Stockton
_ two original Dream Team members already over 30 _ before Utah's
shelf life as a contender expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the story going around about the trade,'' Hornacek
said last week. ``I got to town and it was: `They're getting
Hornacek to make their last run. This is it!' There was a sense of
desperation, like we had a season or two left, tops.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that, six years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   Trudging in with gimpy knees and games from another century,
America's last old-school team plays Madison Square Garden on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz meets the Knicks for an NBC matinee at 12:30 p.m.,
after which most of them will immerse their ankles in ice and
attach electronic stimulators to aching joints and muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a MASH unit,'' said Armen Gilliam, the 35-year-old
journeyman forward. ``We even have a wellness guy that travels with
us. Reflexology. Chiropractic care. You name it, we got it in our
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   They're as ailing and ancient as they are effective and
enduring.
</P>
<P>
   Utah is running a tight race with the San Antonio Spurs in the
Midwest Division, leading the defending NBA champions by half a
game. The Jazz (37-20) has the fourth-best record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of Stockton, Malone and friends dispatching Portland,
the Lakers and the Spurs to advance to the finals for the third
time in four years is almost unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   But then, this aging Jazz team has a phenomenal 9-2 record in
the second game of games played on back-to-back nights, and Utah is
all about defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looks at how many years you play,'' Malone said.
``They forget about what you do to slow down Father Time. You can't
beat him. But you can sure slow him down.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, still a most valuable player candidate, is pushing 37.
Stockton, too stubborn and savvy to be fooled by a crossover
dribble, turns 38 later this month. Along with Hornacek, who will
be 37 in May, they are not only three of the five oldest starters
in the league but among a handful of NBA players born before John
F. Kennedy was assassinated. The average age of the Jazz starting
lineup is 34.4, the oldest in the league. Six Jazz regulars played
college basketball in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a young pup,'' said Olden Polynice, the
35-year-old starting center.
</P>
<P>
   ``My players don't like it when I use the word old, but it's
pretty plain to see we're not a young team anymore,'' said Jerry
Sloan, who has coached the Jazz to two Western Conference titles in
the past three seasons. ``Are we slipping? Some nights I think some
of us believe we can turn it off and turn it on, win games down the
stretch like we used to. That bothers me a little. And our bench
has been up and down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Sloan added, ``there's something to be said about the
fact they still come to work every day and give everything. I like
the idea of our guys thinking they can still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah came close two seasons ago, pushing the Chicago Bulls to
six games before being stopped by the most indefatigable player of
all _ Michael Jordan. The Jazz took a step back last season,
falling to the Trail Blazers in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   As the league motored into the 2000s, Utah seemed left behind,
caught in some hoop time warp. Unselfish, comprised of players who
often pass before they shoot, the Jazz barely fits the mold of the
nouveau NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk to fans, they're not interested in back screens,
down screens and pick-and-roll,'' Sloan said. ``They're looking for
guys to get out and start running. Tough, sound, solid basketball
is a hard thing to sell. I understand that. But if you're not
winning with the other stuff, who's going to buy that? It's not
that our guys are boring. They just like to play a certain way: You
pass to me and I'll pass to you.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If its half-court style did not attract ratings, neither did the
perception that the Jazz clutched and grabbed too much, that its
players _ especially the future Hall of Famers _ were dirty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they have a few little tricks on the court that help them
gain a competitive edge?'' Gilliam asked rhetorically. ``Everybody
in the league does. The difference is, they do it better. I heard a
guy say one time, `If you're not cheating, you're not trying.' That
about sums it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice said: ``It's funny how people hate this team. Now that
I'm playing for them, I find myself asking people: `Why do you hate
them? Because they're good? Because they play hard?' I'm on the
inside, now, and I see what goes into making this team so good.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in Charlotte, the Jazz, in the middle of an Eastern
Conference road swing, was given an optional day to practice.
Following the lead of Stockton and Malone, every player either
weight trained or showed up at the arena to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   In his 14-plus seasons, Malone has missed three games because of
injury. Neither he nor Stockton has missed a game this season. The
bench has given Sloan more angst than his veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says we're doing it the old-fashioned way,'' said
Polynice, who has no problem drawing a distinction between the Jazz
and many of the game's younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has a simple rule that draw strings and shirts be tucked
in for the game,'' he added. ``What's wrong with that? I see all
these guys with headbands now and corn rows. I'm like, `Come on, do
you really know why you're doing that, what that means?' It's not
just black history, it's about guys on other teams having no idea
who Bill Sharman or Oscar Robertson was, how great Bill Russell was
as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping it real. Everybody else is faking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone and Stockton, both workout fanatics, have much to do with
the Jazz remaining contemporary. ``Instead of hanging out and
partying, I like to workout and go home,'' Malone said. ``I really
believe that has prolonged my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Layden, who was hired as general manager of the Knicks this past
summer, is one of the few people not astounded by the Jazz
longevity. Speaking by telephone from France on Thursday, he said
he planned to return home Sunday morning to watch the team he put
together come East for one of its final Garden appearances. He
still refers to the Hornacek acquisition as the best trade he ever
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people on the periphery were always more concerned about
their age than the group internally,'' he said. ``We'd go into
cities, and the media would have already written our obituaries. I
look at John and Karl today, and you can never count those guys
out. They're too mentally tough. They find ways to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   It bothers Sloan that the Jazz did not knock off the Bulls when
they had opportunities in 1997 and 1998. ``But I'm not obsessed
with it,'' he said. ``Sometimes these guys with a ring on their
fingers go out and pound their chests and then they don't go back
and play each year. These guys play every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd like to have a championship, but the bottom line is
that they walked off the court knowing they've given everything
they had. They know who they are and how hard they play this game.
To me, that's what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek has already announced his plans to retire at the end of
this season. Stockton said he planned to play one more season.
Asked if this is indeed Utah's final run, Hornacek said: ``People
are going to say it is until it's finally over. Then those same
people will say, `Look, I told you so.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he added, ``they won't admit they were wrong the
last seven years.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
