<HEADER>
A6864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT     03-04 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARKS DESERVING OF FREE AGENCY 
THE VINCE CARTER SHOW 
VAN HORN'S PASSION 
SEIKALY'S SKILL AT ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 BY MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From South Florida to New York last week, pro basketball zealots
were again talking about John Starks. Miami Heat fans were
salivating over the possibility of the team acquiring him for the
playoffs, if for no other reason than to stick it in the Knicks'
faces. Hard-core Knickies were telephoning WFAN Radio, begging to
know if it was true. Was Starks close to wearing orange and blue
again? Conjecture and gossip, always good for the game, abounded.
</P>
<P>
   Forget, for a moment, that Starks' best days are behind him, or
that the Knicks may have been saying they were interested because
it was the politically correct thing to say about a former player
who brought the franchise so many stirring memories. Shelve the
nostalgia and look at Starks for what he is today: 34 years old,
streaky and a step slow.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you take away the public emotion surrounding Starks,
there is still no good reason why Commissioner David Stern cannot
enforce his executive power and declare Starks a free agent, free
to sign with any playoff team he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Starks lost an arbitration hearing on Friday in an attempt to
preserve that right. The Chicago Bulls tried to do the former Knick
shooting guard a favor nearly 10 days ago. Knowing he wanted to
compete for a title and understanding Starks was not going to be
part of their rebuilding plans, the Bulls agreed to void the
remainder of Starks' contract that is worth $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Bulls attempted the move nearly a week before March
1 _ the date a player must be on a team's roster in order to
compete in the playoffs _ the hope for Starks was that he could
latch onto a contender. Starks and the Bulls seemed to be parting
amicably.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the hard-and-fast NBA. Shooting down the deal, the league
forced the matter to be heard by the arbitrator Kenneth Dam. The
players' union argued the league was circumventing an article in
the collective bargaining agreement that allows such a transaction
for a player in the last year of his deal. The league impressed
upon Dam that such a move could be made but only before Jan. 10 _
the last day to release a player before his contract is guaranteed
for the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   On a technicality, the NBA won.
</P>
<P>
   For all 29 teams, ground rules are ground rules. If players and
teams are allowed mutually to terminate contracts with less than
two months left in the regular season, what is to prevent Isaiah
Rider from doing all he can to make the Atlanta Hawks release him
from his deal and be rewarded by getting picked up by a playoff
team?
</P>
<P>
   Any disgruntled player could try to get out of a contract if he
knew his services were required elsewhere. For mercenary-style
reasons, the league did not want to set a dangerous precedent.
Mostly, it did not want to appear as a co-conspirator in funneling
a former Knick to a playoff team of his choice. What would Heat
Coach Pat Riley have said if the Knicks acquired Starks? Dave
Checketts' blood pressure would have shot up if Starks ended up
with Indiana or Miami, two teams with $1.1 million in reserve to
sign Starks for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the NBA could ever get past image and damage-control
concerns, it would see that Starks was neither malicious nor
conniving in his attempt to play for a playoff team. Shipped from
bad team to bad team the past two seasons, he quietly went about
performing his job for the Golden State Warriors and the Bulls
until he realized he would not be moved at the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Reinsdorf's frugal ways had a hand in Starks' fate. Starks
could have been a free agent had the Bulls chairman picked up the
tab for his contract instead of trying to negate it. Less than two
years after the Bulls won their sixth title of the 1990s, they have
another unhappy player on a last-place team.
</P>
<P>
   Starks is considering an appeal to a grievance arbitrator, but
that may take a week.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Stern could make an exception. He could look beyond
the legalese, beyond the unclear language in the collective
bargaining agreement and give Starks what he deserves after 10
years of exemplary service, what anyone who went from a grocery
checkout line to an NBA layup line deserves: one final chance to
play in front of a crowd that genuinely cares.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Stern's wisdom and sentimentality will prevail. Maybe the
omnipotent commissioner will see that few players have ever
exhibited the same heart and soul of John Starks, and maybe Stern
will exhibit some of his own in declaring Starks a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long shot. But then, so was the chance of Starks playing
in Stern's league.
</P>
<P>
   The Vince Carter Show
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off Vince Carter's 51-point detonation against Phoenix
last Sunday, NBC is tearing up the schedule. The network has added
two regional games featuring the Toronto Raptors and their
acrobatic forward. NBC will televise a March 12 game between
Seattle and Toronto and also the Raptors' game against Indiana on
April 2. In network promo language, that's Vince vs. Gary Payton
and Vince vs. Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn's Passion
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but the left-for-dead Nets are four games out of
the Eastern Conference's final playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   After victories at Denver and Dallas last week, New Jersey crept
up on Milwaukee. Stephon Marbury's determination and resilience are
the biggest reasons for their climb, but not enough can be said
about Keith Van Horn when he plays with passion. He hit the
game-winner over Dennis Rodman against Dallas on Thursday, pumping
his fist and rejoicing with his teammates. When he's not passive,
Van Horn is a completely different player from the slumping one
questioning his place in the league. He still may not be a bona
fide power forward, but he has the tools to be one of the NBA's
most complete players.
</P>
<P>
   Seikaly's Skill at Issue
</P>
<P>
   The Rony Seikaly arbitration case gets under way Tuesday. In
order to avoid paying Seikaly, the Nets are going to have to show
the reason they terminated Seikaly last year was essentially
because of his lack of skill. Considering the Nets' desperate
straits at the center position, an arbitrator may find that hard to
believe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
