<SLUG> BC-NY-ENDORSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIMES ENDORSES MCCAIN AND GORE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The editorial page of The New York Times on Sunday endorsed Sen.
John McCain and Vice President Al Gore in Tuesday's Republican and
Democratic presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their very different ways,'' the editorial said, ``each of
these two men communicates a greater capacity for overarching
presidential leadership than his opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times, noting that it does not always offer primary
endorsements and last did so in 1992, had praise for Gov. George W.
Bush and former Sen. Bill Bradley, but said their opponents were
preferable.
</P>
<P>
   Newsday yesterday also endorsed McCain and Gore. The newspaper,
which circulates on Long Island and in Queens, called McCain a
``genuine American hero'' who has ``exhibited a trait that has been
sorely missed in our politics: character.'' It cited Gore's
experience and said Democrats had found him ``willing, even eager,
to stretch himself to win the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News last week endorsed Gore, calling him ``the
candidate who has a firm command of all the issues and is best
prepared to take on the Republican challenger.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post last week endorsed McCain, saying he
``represents the nation's best hope for the future.'' It added,
``Not since Ronald Reagan has a leader so resonated with the
American public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
