<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FISHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLY-FISHING AFICIONADO DISCOVERS OTHER PLEASURES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the dead of winter, snow belt anglers are prone to review
what they learned when leaves were still aloft and their quarry was
both present and cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   My own ruminations on the 1999 season reminded me that I had
gotten into a fly-fishing rut. Last October, I clambered out of
that rut and rediscovered the pleasures of one-handed bait casting
rods and revolving spool reels, a confession that will disturb
fly-fishing aficionados. Let them wince. It's possible _ given the
weird impulses of advancing years _ that I may revert to boyhood
and once again go after trout with earthworms.
</P>
<P>
   The striped bass of Tisbury Great Pond on Martha's Vineyard
Island were responsible for my leaving my fly rod in the woodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, northward-migrating stripers moved into the pond
from the ocean via a man-made opening that is created two or three
times a year. In months or weeks, onshore storms or winds close
that cut and the pond is reopened, one of the purposes of this
being to keep the salinity high enough for its oysters to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Striped bass in Tisbury Great Pond are nothing unusual. Year
after year, they come in from the ocean in April or May and some
stick around all winter. What was different in 1999 was the numbers
of them: thousands of fish that could often be seen feeding on the
surface in swaths 100 yards wide and half a mile long.
</P>
<P>
   Early in summer of 1999, the bellies of the few legal-sized fish
_ 28 inches _ that I took from the pond were crammed with blue claw
crabs, plus an occasional sand eel or silverside minnow. By
October, young menhaden, having also entered the pond via the
opening, were their main forage.
</P>
<P>
   The pond remained closed during most of summer. I thought most
of the bass would depart offshore and south when a new cut was
made. I was wrong. The pond was opened in early fall but closed
again in about two weeks, and, as far as I could judge, most of the
bass remained in the shallow, brackish water gorging on menhaden.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, I went after those stripers with a fly rod. I had
first fished for the species with a fly rod right after World War
II, and more than two decades ago began to use that approach almost
exclusively. I am not sure why that happened. I don't feel that
fly-fishing is a superior way to angle; I simply favor that
approach. Perhaps it's the minimal amount of gear one has to carry
in addition to rod and reel: a book of flies and some leader
material. I also enjoy the rhythm of fly casting, particularly when
I am wading, when the wind is coming from the right direction, when
the fly is small and when there is plenty of room for a backcast.
</P>
<P>
   On my first visits to the pond in the summer of 1999, I had good
luck fishing from shore along the inside edge of the barrier beach.
After that, the bass usually were far out in the pond and I had to
pursue them from one of my canoes.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, I kept a big, old 20-foot aluminum Grumman canoe
at my home on the Vineyard and had no qualms about stand-up
fly-fishing from it. It now rests in the eternal shadows of spruces
at my family's wilderness lodge in Maine. Both of the canoes I have
at home are smaller and less stable.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to do a good job of fly-fishing for Tisbury Great Pond's
stripers from one of those smaller canoes left me seething with
frustration. The seacoast is rarely without wind, the fly
fisherman's nemesis. You can make adjustments for the wind if you
are wading, but doing the same from a sitting position in a small
canoe is often impossible.
</P>
<P>
   After several such excursions I decided to try something that
would work in half a gale. Defying my addiction to fly-fishing, I
plucked a long-idle one-handed bait casting outfit from the
rafters, found a few surface-swimming plugs _ the bait casting
equivalent of the dry fly _ for it, and sallied forth.
</P>
<P>
   So armed, I caught more bass and more big bass. I soon found out
that an old Smithwick Devil's Horse, a classic surface swimmer with
propellers mounted fore and aft, was effective, but it, designed
for fresh water fishing, couldn't take the punishment. Its hooks
were either torn off or straightened out after a few good-sized
fish. I switched to a fresh water Heddon Zara Spook, and it
suffered the same fate.
</P>
<P>
   A trip to Cooper Gilkes' tackle shop in nearby Edgartown turned
up a few Rebel Jumpin' Minnows _ salt water plugs with a surface
action much like that of the Zara Spook. They, with their heavier
hooks and superior hook linkage to the plug, proved to be what I
needed when the bass were chasing menhaden.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon in late October was one of my best days of the 1999
season on the pond. Pushed by a stiff southwest wind, the surf
moaned on the outer beach a half mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of gulls were wheeling over the center of the pond.
Drifting down among the gulls, I raised a bass on my first cast. It
wasn't hooked, but it knocked my plug four feet into the air. I was
fast to a 30-inch fish on the next cast, and that was the way it
went until sundown when I quit.
</P>
<P>
   Bass _ some that I failed to hook were in the 30-pound class _
slashed at the plug right up to the canoe and often what appeared
to be the same fish would make four or five passes on a single
cast. Intoxicated by the frenzied activity about me, I frantically
hooked and released stripers for the better part of two hours until
the sun's descent behind a dark, ragged cloud brought me to my
senses. I'd caught enough fish.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped casting and _ drifting across the darkening salt pond
through schools of breaking bass and fleeing menhaden _ reflected
that there clearly were times when a fly rod should be left at
home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
