<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6867 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SELMA-MARCH-0305-COX     03-04 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELMA-MARCH-0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO JOIN OTHERS SUNDAY IN RE-ENACTING SELMA MARCH
 &HT;    550 &AMP; ADD
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (a) national
categories
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ In 1965, a young black man named John Lewis
was severely beaten by white state troopers who attacked more than
600 nonviolent civil rights marchers trying to cross Selma's Edmund
Pettus Bridge on their way to the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, 35 years later, U.S. Rep. John Lewis will be joined
by President Clinton, former U.N. Ambassador Andrew Young and a
bipartisan group of 30 members of Congress and other luminaries who
will cross the bridge again in the Third Annual Congressional Civil
Rights Pilgrimage .
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Alabama state troopers will act as
supportive escorts. And a racially mixed crowd of onlookers is
expected to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have the president of the United States and some of my
colleagues from Congress walking across that bridge with me is the
impossible dream, the unthinkable,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, an Atlanta Democrat serving his seventh term in Congress,
has often returned to commemorate the ``Bloody Sunday'' attack. The
troopers used tear gas, bull whips and billy clubs to turn back the
unarmed marchers who were protesting poll taxes, literacy tests and
other tactics aimed at intimidating black voters.
</P>
<P>
   The vicious beatings, shown on national television, appalled and
galvanized much of America. Within months, Congress had passed the
1965 Voting Rights Act outlawing the poll tax and requiring that
Americans, regardless of race, be permitted to freely cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, only 2 percent of voting-age blacks were registered to
vote in Dallas County, where Selma is located. Today, nearly 60
percent are registered.
</P>
<P>
   This year's re-enactment, with the worldwide media attention
generated by Clinton's participation, is a special pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   It started Friday evening with a tour of the Civil Rights
Institute here in Birmingham. Saturday's events began with a tour
of the Kelly Ingram Park, which is dedicated to those who died in
the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   The participants then visited the 16th Street Baptist Church,
the city's first black church, where four young girls were killed
in the fall of 1963 when it was bombed by white segregationists.
</P>
<P>
   The group also made a 90-minute trip to Montgomery and toured
the Dexter Avenue Baptist Church, once headed by Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr. His widow, Coretta Scott King, briefly reflected on the
life of the slain civil rights leader. His, Martin Luther King III,
was in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress found the experience moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``My presence here is to honor all those who we've heard of and
those whose names I don't know,'' said Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee,
D-Texas, an African American. ``Because of them I am educated, I am
an elected official and I am a better person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the pilgrimage will serve as an important tool for
each participating member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old lawmaker said it can educate and sensitize
people his colleagues to the problems of race and ``just maybe all
of us can go back to our districts, our own states and get people
discussing race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a great deal to recognize those who made it possible,
but it can't continue if we don't pass it on to the youth,'' agreed
Rep. Tom Sawyer, D-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lewis remembers his ``Bloody Sunday'' march across the Edmund
Pettus Bridge ``like it was yesterday.'' There was a cool breeze
blowing that Sunday afternoon, on March 7. Lewis wore a beige coat.
In his back pack he carried two books, an apple, an orange and a
toothbrush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to be arrested and be sent to jail,''
said Lewis, who already had been arrested 40 times while pushing
for civil rights. ``So I wanted to have something to eat, something
to read. And since I was going to be in close quarters with my
friends and neighbors and colleagues, I wanted to be able to brush
my teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators first saw the sea of state troopers when the
marchers got to the crest of the bridge Although Lewis expected to
be arrested, ``something didn't seem right this time,'' he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell because if they were going to arrest us, they had
no way to take us to jail, no wagons, transporters, nothing,''
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no turning back. After all, the civil rights
activists had already trekked 54 miles from Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The state troopers ordered them to disperse. But the marchers
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 100 armed troopers began to push the marchers, who
resisted. The troopers reacted with force.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and others were sprayed with tear gas, trampled by police
horses and beaten with billy clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Some ran back. But others, including Lewis, were severely
injured. He suffered a fractured skull. Lewis doesn't remember how
he got to a hospital, but feels very fortunate to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to die. I think on that day I saw
death,'' he said. ``So when I go back (Sunday), I will feel very
blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   The state troopers' actions angered many people, who watched the
assault on television. Even Alabama's segregationist Gov. George
Wallace reprimanded the troopers for their actions. President
Johnson also condemn the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bloodshed and struggles of the civil rights
movement, people today don't exercise their voting rights, Lewis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me very sad, it troubles me a great deal when so many
people do not understand the significance of what Selma was all
about,'' he said. ``It makes me sad when we don't go out and vote
when people died for that right. And that's why I think during an
election year all Americans, not just blacks, should get out and
register and vote like they never voted before. It's a precious
right. People sacrificed, people died, people gave a little
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ismail Turay Jr. can be reached by e-mail a:
ismailt(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
