<P>
   ``I thought we were going to be arrested and be sent to jail,''
said Lewis, who already had been arrested 40 times while pushing
for civil rights. ``So I wanted to have something to eat, something
to read. And since I was going to be in close quarters with my
friends and neighbors and colleagues, I wanted to be able to brush
my teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators first saw the sea of state troopers when the
marchers got to the crest of the bridge Although Lewis expected to
be arrested, ``something didn't seem right this time,'' he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell because if they were going to arrest us, they had
no way to take us to jail, no wagons, transporters, nothing,''
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no turning back. After all, the civil rights
activists had already trekked 54 miles from Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   The state troopers ordered them to disperse. But the marchers
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 100 armed troopers began to push the marchers, who
resisted. The troopers reacted with force.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and others were sprayed with tear gas, trampled by police
horses and beaten with billy clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Some ran back. But others, including Lewis, were severely
injured. He suffered a fractured skull. Lewis doesn't remember how
he got to a hospital, but feels very fortunate to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to die. I think on that day I saw
death,'' he said. ``So when I go back (Sunday), I will feel very
blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   The state troopers' actions angered many people, who watched the
assault on television. Even Alabama's segregationist Gov. George
Wallace reprimanded the troopers for their actions. President
Johnson also condemn the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bloodshed and struggles of the civil rights
movement, people today don't exercise their voting rights, Lewis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me very sad, it troubles me a great deal when so many
people do not understand the significance of what Selma was all
about,'' he said. ``It makes me sad when we don't go out and vote
when people died for that right. And that's why I think during an
election year all Americans, not just blacks, should get out and
register and vote like they never voted before. It's a precious
right. People sacrificed, people died, people gave a little
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ismail Turay Jr. can be reached by e-mail a:
ismailt(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
