<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 03/04/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- CAMPAIGN-RDP-2 --
Massachusetts is among 13 states holding primaries on Tuesday, and
Vice President Al Gore feels confident about his prospects against
former Sen. Bill Bradley. Bradley campaigned in the Bronx at the
Bay Plaza mall Saturday; his wife, Ernestine, gave him a kiss as he
finished his handshaking duties. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- BKN-EWING -- Patrick Ewing
might be the most important player in franchise history. Almost
single-handedly, he has kept the team competitive from one year to
the next, as the players - and coaches - around him have changed.
Ewing reacted after missing a shot during a game against the
Charlotte Hornets in December. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 4, 2000 -- BBA-ARATON-COLUMN --
Though Yankees pitcher Andy Pettitte's father, Tommy, is only 50,
he nonetheless gazes in the mirror and demands an explanation for
what his body in recent years has put him through: Three years ago,
doctors removed two feet of his colon; the following year, they
unclogged the main artery to his heart. Pettitte watched his son at
spring training Friday afternoon in Tampa. (Barton Silverman/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN -- Last
Tuesday Gil Hodges' candidacy for the Baseball Hall of Fame died,
at least for another year. Again. Some friends even sent his widow,
Joan Hodges, flowers, as if in mourning. But the campaign won't
die. ``I need an explanation,'' said Mrs. Hodges, standing by a
portrait of her husband, Gil, in the same house in which she has
lived since his playing days with the Brooklyn Dodgers. ``Ever
since Tuesday, I've had people come up and kiss me like he just
died.'' (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 4, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-2 --
Orlando Hernandez's stuff is quite ordinary, in its raw form - a
fastball of 88 to 90 miles an hour, a nice little curve, a
wide-breaking slider. But the Yankees pitcher knows how to throw
and how to win. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 4, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-1 --
The drills that Orlando Hernandez, the Yankees pitcher, does are a
mystery to the other Yankees. In one routine, he stands on his
head, swinging his legs back and forth, as a form of yoga,
something he learned 10 years ago in Cuba. (Gary I. Rothstein/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- SPEED-DATING -- It's called
SpeedDating, and it's the latest wrinkle in the Jewish singles
scene. The bell rings and couples pair off to chat for eight
minutes - not a second more - at a recent SpeedDating session at
Levana, a kosher French Mediterranean restaurant on the Upper West
Side of Manhattan. (Susan Farley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- DIALLO-VOICES-3 -- In the
year since Amadou Diallo died in his doorway in a hail of police
bullets, New Yorkers' attitudes about the police have begun a
subtle shift. Anita L. Halton, on the Upper West Side of Manhattan,
said she was almost oblivious to the police: ``I actually feel very
ignored by the police. It's almost an invisible force to me.''
(Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- DIALLO-VOICES-2 -- In the
year since Amadou Diallo died in his doorway in a hail of police
bullets, New Yorkers' attitudes about the police have begun a
subtle shift. At Pennsylvania Station, Sherry Gellis, a Long
Islander from Lynbrook, said: ``I do not think police do things
carelessly. I think they can become unnerved, like most human
beings.'' (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- DIALLO-VOICES-1 -- In the
year since Amadou Diallo died in his doorway in a hail of bullets,
New Yorkers' attitudes about the police have begun a subtle shift.
Jude Mignon, an owner of a barber shop in Crown Heights, Brooklyn,
said a police presence has been good for business. But at night, he
said, he has been pushed against a wall and frisked by plainclothes
officers who seem more like a rude gang. ``I don't hate all cops.
But some have too much power.'' (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PAWLEYS ISLAND, S.C. -- March 4, 2000 --
EPISCOPALIAN-RIFT -- The Rev. Charles H. Murphy III, of All Saints
Episcopal Church, was consecrated a bishop by the head of the
Anglican Province of Rwanda. The ceremony vividly showed an unusual
alliance that has developed between conservative Episcopalians in
the United States and the like-minded heads of some Anglican
churches overseas, who share a perception that the Episcopal Church
has come to rely less on Scripture than on ideas from secular
American culture, especially on issues of human sexuality. (Wade
Spees/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SCRANTON, Pa. -- March 4, 2000 -- BIG-FAMILY-2 -- Torn
apart after an eviction, the 19-member Smith family has been put
back together in a 10-bedroom home of their own in Scranton, with
the help of hundreds of volunteers and Habitat for Humanity.
``These days the government can't handle it when you have 17
kids,'' said Robert E. Quinn, the director of Habitat for Humanity
for Lackawanna County. Charlie Smith was on the porch of the new
house with several members of his brood. (Keith Meyers/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SCRANTON, Pa. -- March 4, 2000 -- BIG-FAMILY-1 -- Torn
apart after an eviction, the 19-member Smith family has been put
back together in a 10-bedroom home of their own in Scranton, with
the help of hundreds of volunteers and Habitat for Humanity.
Charlie Smith had his children's names tattooed on his left arm,
but his brood's penchant for nicknames has foiled his handy
checklist. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 4, 2000 -- NATIONAL-GUARD-2 --
The Army has decided to limit overseas deployments of these units
in peacekeeping and other military operations to a maximum of six
months, Pentagon officials said. The Army's chief of staff, Gen.
Erik K. Shinseki, is expected to announce the decision on Tuesday
at a ceremony handing over command of the American sector of NATO's
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia to the 49th Armored Division of
the Texas National Guard. A member of the 49th waited to board a
bus for Fort Hood, where a military airlift would transport the
division to Bosnia. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 4, 2000 -- NATIONAL-GUARD-1 --
The Army has decided to limit overseas deployments of these units
in peacekeeping and other military operations to a maximum of six
months, Pentagon officials said. The Army's chief of staff, Gen.
Erik K. Shinseki, is expected to announce the decision on Tuesday
at a ceremony handing over command of the American sector of NATO's
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia to the 49th Armored Division of
the Texas National Guard. Members of the 49th conducted exercises
in preparation for their upcoming mission. (Fred R. Conrad/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KABUL, Afghanistan -- March 4, 2000 --
AFGHANISTAN-HEIST-2 -- On Jan. 13, thieves made off with more than
$200,000 in cash from Kabul's main money bazaar. They met no
opposition from the Taliban soldiers who stood watch over the
deserted bazaar at night, indicating an inside job. Despite the
severity of Taliban punishment, the bazaar has been looted twice in
a small crime wave. Currency traders filled its courtyard recently.
(Barry Bearak/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KABUL, Afghanistan -- March 4, 2000 --
AFGHANISTAN-HEIST-1 -- On Jan. 13, thieves made off with more than
$200,000 in cash from Kabul's main money bazaar. They met no
opposition from the Taliban soldiers who stood watch over the
deserted bazaar at night, indicating an inside job. In Kabul a man
carried a stack of notes worth 10,000 Afghanis each, or about 20
cents, the largest denomination. The thieves would have had to
carry 24 tons of currency had they chosen to take their loot in
notes worth 5,000 Afghanis. (Barry Bearak/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- March 4, 2000 -- REPUBS-FOREIGNPOLICY-2 --
Sen. John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush are different in both
style and substance when they talk about foreign policy, coming to
their conclusions much as they run their campaigns: one by
instinct, the other by committee. McCain is rarely uncertain of his
positions whereas Bush, in contrast, is far less comfortable with
the subject matter. McCain attended a rally Friday in Boston's
Copley Square. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ROCHESTER, N.Y. -- March 4, 2000 -- REPUBS-FOREIGNPOLICY
-- Sen. John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush are different in both
style and substance when they talk about foreign policy, coming to
their conclusions much as they run their campaigns: one by
instinct, the other by committee. McCain is rarely uncertain of his
positions whereas Bush, in contrast, is far less comfortable with
the subject matter. Bush and his wife, Laura, greeted a supporter
Saturday at the airport in Rochester, before heading to campaign
stops in New York and Connecticut. (Stephen Crowley/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- NY-MRSCLINTON-DIALLO -- In
remarks leading up to what her aides say will be a major policy
statement on police conduct and the Diallo case Sunday, Hillary
Rodham Clinton said Friday that New York City ``obviously has a
problem when an innocent, unarmed man is gunned down.'' Mrs.
Clinton met Friday with the founders of Pax, a gun control advocacy
group that she said she enthusiastically supported. (Chang W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- March 4, 2000 -- CAMPAIGN-RDP -- Massachusetts
is among 13 states holding primaries on Tuesday, and Vice President
Al Gore feels confident about his prospects against former Sen.
Bill Bradley. Gore campaigned Saturday with Mayor Thomas M. Menino
of Boston, wearing glasses, at a South End diner. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- NITEOUT-WOODLAWN -- Holly
Woodlawn -born Harold Danhakl in 1946 - became the scene-stealing
transvestite in Paul Morrissey's ``Trash.'' Now, the movie, and
Holly, are being rolled out for a 30th-anniversary appearance.
(''Trash'' opens March 17 in New York and Los Angeles.) Woodlawn
during a recent visit to Lips. (Miles Ladin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- GALLERY-ART-QUEEN -- Mary
Boone, center, and Will Cotton, left, at the opening of Cotton's
show at her Fifth Avenue gallery. On the wall is ``Love Me,'' a
painting by Mr. Cotton, part of the wave of young artists Boone
represents. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) YEKATERINBURG, Russia -- March 4, 2000 --
RUSSIA-VIGILANTE -- In Yekaterinburg, where the supply lines of
opium and heroin out of Central and South Asia run into big
population centers, a group of tough guys have organized a
foundation called City Without Drugs in an attempt to take the
streets back from the dealers and the corrupt policemen who are
widely believed to be protecting them. Andrei V. Kabanov, of City
Without Drugs, with Dima, a heroin addict handcuffed to a bed
during withdrawal. (Patrick E. Tyler/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- March 4, 2000 -- OBIT-STREET-B&AMP;W -- Capt.
George L. Street III, who won the Medal of Honor in World War II
for directing a daring submarine attack that destroyed three
Japanese ships off the coast of Korea, died Feb. 26 at a nursing
home in Andover, Mass. He was 86. (United States Navy/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- March 4, 2000 -- OBIT-BRUCE -- Dominic Bruce,
a British bomber pilot who made no fewer than 17 attempts in four
years to escape from his German captors at the famous Colditz
prison, died Feb. 12 in England. He was 84. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- March 4, 2000 -- GORE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY --
President Clinton denied in January 1998 that he had had sex with
Monica S. Lewinsky. Not for seven months did he tell Al Gore the
truth. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
