Jude Mignon, an owner of a barber shop in Crown Heights, Brooklyn,
said a police presence has been good for business. But at night, he
said, he has been pushed against a wall and frisked by plainclothes
officers who seem more like a rude gang. ``I don't hate all cops.
But some have too much power.'' (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PAWLEYS ISLAND, S.C. -- March 4, 2000 --
EPISCOPALIAN-RIFT -- The Rev. Charles H. Murphy III, of All Saints
Episcopal Church, was consecrated a bishop by the head of the
Anglican Province of Rwanda. The ceremony vividly showed an unusual
alliance that has developed between conservative Episcopalians in
the United States and the like-minded heads of some Anglican
churches overseas, who share a perception that the Episcopal Church
has come to rely less on Scripture than on ideas from secular
American culture, especially on issues of human sexuality. (Wade
Spees/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SCRANTON, Pa. -- March 4, 2000 -- BIG-FAMILY-2 -- Torn
apart after an eviction, the 19-member Smith family has been put
back together in a 10-bedroom home of their own in Scranton, with
the help of hundreds of volunteers and Habitat for Humanity.
``These days the government can't handle it when you have 17
kids,'' said Robert E. Quinn, the director of Habitat for Humanity
for Lackawanna County. Charlie Smith was on the porch of the new
house with several members of his brood. (Keith Meyers/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SCRANTON, Pa. -- March 4, 2000 -- BIG-FAMILY-1 -- Torn
apart after an eviction, the 19-member Smith family has been put
back together in a 10-bedroom home of their own in Scranton, with
the help of hundreds of volunteers and Habitat for Humanity.
Charlie Smith had his children's names tattooed on his left arm,
but his brood's penchant for nicknames has foiled his handy
checklist. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 4, 2000 -- NATIONAL-GUARD-2 --
The Army has decided to limit overseas deployments of these units
in peacekeeping and other military operations to a maximum of six
months, Pentagon officials said. The Army's chief of staff, Gen.
Erik K. Shinseki, is expected to announce the decision on Tuesday
at a ceremony handing over command of the American sector of NATO's
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia to the 49th Armored Division of
the Texas National Guard. A member of the 49th waited to board a
bus for Fort Hood, where a military airlift would transport the
division to Bosnia. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 4, 2000 -- NATIONAL-GUARD-1 --
The Army has decided to limit overseas deployments of these units
in peacekeeping and other military operations to a maximum of six
months, Pentagon officials said. The Army's chief of staff, Gen.
Erik K. Shinseki, is expected to announce the decision on Tuesday
at a ceremony handing over command of the American sector of NATO's
peacekeeping operation in Bosnia to the 49th Armored Division of
the Texas National Guard. Members of the 49th conducted exercises
in preparation for their upcoming mission. (Fred R. Conrad/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KABUL, Afghanistan -- March 4, 2000 --
AFGHANISTAN-HEIST-2 -- On Jan. 13, thieves made off with more than
$200,000 in cash from Kabul's main money bazaar. They met no
opposition from the Taliban soldiers who stood watch over the
deserted bazaar at night, indicating an inside job. Despite the
severity of Taliban punishment, the bazaar has been looted twice in
a small crime wave. Currency traders filled its courtyard recently.
(Barry Bearak/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KABUL, Afghanistan -- March 4, 2000 --
AFGHANISTAN-HEIST-1 -- On Jan. 13, thieves made off with more than
$200,000 in cash from Kabul's main money bazaar. They met no
opposition from the Taliban soldiers who stood watch over the
deserted bazaar at night, indicating an inside job. In Kabul a man
carried a stack of notes worth 10,000 Afghanis each, or about 20
cents, the largest denomination. The thieves would have had to
carry 24 tons of currency had they chosen to take their loot in
notes worth 5,000 Afghanis. (Barry Bearak/The New York Times)
