<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 4, 2000 -- DIALLO-VOICES-1 -- In the
year since Amadou Diallo died in his doorway in a hail of bullets,
New Yorkers' attitudes about the police have begun a subtle shift.
Jude Mignon, an owner of a barber shop in Crown Heights, Brooklyn,
said a police presence has been good for business. But at night, he
said, he has been pushed against a wall and frisked by plainclothes
officers who seem more like a rude gang. ``I don't hate all cops.
But some have too much power.'' (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PAWLEYS ISLAND, S.C. -- March 4, 2000 --
EPISCOPALIAN-RIFT -- The Rev. Charles H. Murphy III, of All Saints
Episcopal Church, was consecrated a bishop by the head of the
Anglican Province of Rwanda. The ceremony vividly showed an unusual
alliance that has developed between conservative Episcopalians in
the United States and the like-minded heads of some Anglican
churches overseas, who share a perception that the Episcopal Church
has come to rely less on Scripture than on ideas from secular
American culture, especially on issues of human sexuality. (Wade
Spees/The New York Times)
</P>
