<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLFEA0305-COX     03-04 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLFEA0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This week's top newsmaker
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a seamless transition from coach to spinmeister
last week, Bob Hartley assured everybody not to be alarmed at the
Colorado Avalanche's atypical fall in the Northwest Division
standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with a championship race this time of
year,'' the Avalanche coach said. ``The only problem is that we in
Colorado are not used to that this time of year. We had the
division trophy won by January. But this is not a bad thing. We
wanted some excitement in our locker room, and now we have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Excitement didn't quite capture the moment. Expecting a soft
touch in its schedule, Colorado was stunned 4-3 by the Thrashers, a
team that hadn't won in 16 games. The Avs, arguably the most
talented team in the Western Conference, continued its tumble,
going winless in five games to fall within one game of .500, before
Thursday's win over New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Excitement? If boos are a measuring stick, Colorado fans clearly
are not thrilled with going from a Stanley Cup contender to a team
that might finish second to Edmonton and is not necessarily a
certainty for the playoffs. Going into the weekend, the Avs were
one of five teams within seven points of each other for the final
two playoff spots. If you think the chances of Colorado missing the
postseason are remote, what were the chances that a team with
Patrick Roy, Peter Forsberg, Joe Sakic, Milan Hedjuk, Chris Drury,
Adam Deadmarsh and Sandis Ozolinsh would even be in this position?
</P>
<P>
   The Avs have been dented by injuries all season, particularly to
Forsberg and Sakic. But they always have had the depth to overcome
injuries in the past. One reason they might not this year is a
shortage of veteran leadership. General manager Pierre Lacroix did
not re-sign several of the team's free agents in the offseason,
most notably Valeri Kamensky, Sylvain Lefebvre and Theo Fleury.
That is the biggest reason the team has pursued Kelly Buchberger
from the Thrashers in trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix thought it was time for the youth on his team to take
over. But the youth is not certain it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Peter and Joe out, the younger players have been getting
more ice time than they're used to,'' rookie Alex Tanguay said.
``When you're a rookie, you make a few more mistakes. We're working
hard, but we're not getting the wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado/Quebec franchise has won five divisional
championships in a row and finished between 13 and 17 games over
500. But Lacroix remains confident about a turnaround,
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the criticism,'' he said. ``To be honest, we
have not performed as well as we have in previous years. But we're
not going to hide behind a curtain. People expect a lot of this
franchise, and that's normal. But we still believe we can turn it
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
