<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLITEMS0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bang for the buck
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Eleven NHL goalies make at least $3 million per season. They are
ranked by how big a bargain they are for their team, with victories
through Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   Goalie/Team/Salary/Wins/Per win:
</P>
<P>
   Olaf Kolzig _ Washington _ $3,000,000 _ 30 _ $100,000
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur _ New Jersey _ $4,130,687 _ 36 _ $114,741
</P>
<P>
   Ed Belfour _ Dallas _ $3,500,000 _ 27 _ $129,629
</P>
<P>
   John Vanbiesbrouck _ Philadelphia _ $4,289,756 _ 21 _ $204,274
</P>
<P>
   Guy Hebert _ Anaheim _ $4,500,000 _ 21 _ $214,286
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Joseph _ Toronto _ $6,150,000 _ 28 _ $219,643
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter N.Y. Rangers $5,000,000 20 $250,000
</P>
<P>
   Mike Vernon _ Florida _ $4,378,007 _ 17 _ $257,529
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Roy _ Colorado _ $7,500,000 _ 21 _ $357,143
</P>
<P>
   Grant Fuhr _ Calgary _ $3,000,000 _ 5 _ $600,000
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek _ Buffalo _ $7,000,000 _ 6 _ $1,166,667
</P>
<P>
   Includes wins with San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   THE TOP FIVE
</P>
<P>
   The best teams in the NHL with five weeks left in the season:
</P>
<P>
   1. St. Louis. The Blues have won 14 of 16 without Pierre
Turgeon. It should quiet questions about their depth for a while.
</P>
<P>
   2. Toronto. The Maple Leafs followed a six-game winless streak
by winning four in a row. Chances are, they won't have another
slump.
</P>
<P>
   3. New Jersey. Mark Messier? George Steinbrenner would make the
trade in a second. But he doesn't own the team yet _ and might not
before the March 14 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   4. Dallas. So, if the Stars have been so decimated by injuries,
how come they have so many wins? And what happens if and when they
get healthy in the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   5. Florida. Pavel Bure will win the Maurice Richard Trophy for
being the league's leading goal-scorer. But Anna Kournikova _ is
that a power-play move or what?
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM FIVE
</P>
<P>
   The worst teams in the NHL with five weeks left in the season:
</P>
<P>
   28. Atlanta. So you think this is bad? The Thrashers still have
games left against New Jersey (two), Philadelphia (two) and
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   27. Tampa Bay. The good news is that goalie Dan Cloutier is back
from a groin strain. The bad news is that goalie Dan Cloutier is
back from a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   26. Boston. Now goalie Byron Dafoe is out. Somehow, general
manager Harry Sinden will find a way to blame it on coach Pat
Burns, the Scapegoat of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   25. N.Y. Islanders. After showing brief signs of life with a
season-high three-game winning streak, topping the Thashers' record
two-gamer, the Islanders won only one of their next eight, 1-5-2.
</P>
<P>
   24. Chicago. Try to explain this: The Blackhawks lose at home to
Nashville, then go on the road and beat Dallas and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   Detroit at Dallas, 8 p.m. today, ESPN: With college basketball
tournaments dominating, there is only one NHL game on ESPN or ESPN2
this week, but it is a good one. Dallas scored four third-period
goals to win 5-2 on Feb. 23 and take a 2-1 lead in the season
series between the Western Conference powers. Brett Hull of the
Stars and Steve Yzerman of the Red Wings each had two goals.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey at Atlanta, 7:30 p.m. Friday, WUPA: The expansion
Thrashers are 0-9-1 at home since Jan. 14 and things don't get any
easier. The Devils have the best record in the Eastern Conference
and are a definite Stanley Cup contender. New Jersey is 2-0 against
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Colorado at Edmonton, Friday: The Oilers went into Denver on
Tuesday and won 3-1 to stretch their lead in the Northwest
Division. If the Avalanche is going to snap out of it, this is the
time. One key is Joe Sakic, who is on pace to score just 15 goals,
which would be the lowest total of his career.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE/UNQUOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHL goalies are like Formula One cars. They have to be
perfectly tuned up so you can put your foot on the gas and go. If
you have two wheels on the side of the road, you are not faster
than a Volkswagen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Anaheim goaltender coach Francois Allaire, who is trying to
help Guy Hebert shake a slump in which he allowed 19 goals in a
four-game span.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Calgary's Jarome Iginla stretched his point streak to 14 games
and had a hand in half (21 of 42) of the Flames' goals in February.
But Iginla never has been a favorite of coach Brian Sutter, who
offered this backhanded compliment: ``If he had played the first
two months the way he played the last one, we wouldn't be in this
position (fighting for playoff slot).'' Gee, thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Vincent Lecavalier is on pace to finish with 24
goals and 65 points _ and he's still 19.
</P>
<P>
   FREE FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' Donald Audette scored 10 goals in his first 25
games but has only two in the last 22. The Kings are including him
in trade offers. He's an unrestricted free agent after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Daigle , the former No. 1 pick playing with his fourth
team, now has fallen out of favor with the Rangers' John Muckler.
``I've met with some of these other (skilled players) when they've
become 35 or 36 years old. I've had certain conversations with
them, and they're sorry now that they didn't take full advantage of
their talent. You get through to them when they're 35 or 36, but
it's too late by then.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTABLES
</P>
<P>
   Dallas defenseman Richard Matvichuk is out a week with a
sprained knee _ or should that be a ``dead'' one? Matvichuk had his
left ACL replaced by one from a cadaver in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So you just have to know what Sergei Fedorov thinks of his
ex-girlfriend, Anna Kournikova, getting engaged to Pavel Bure?
Tough. Said Fedorov: ``What's private is private. I have nothing to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina may not be the picture of stability right now but the
Hurricanes easily have the most attractive schedule of Eastern
Conference teams fighting for a playoff spot. Seven of their
remaining games are against the Thrashers (three), Blackhawks,
Islanders, Predators and Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton GM Glen Sather recently extended the deal of goalie
Tommy Salo to a relative bargain price of $1.8 million next year.
He has a better goals-against and saves percentage than the
departed Curtis Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   It's looking more likely Philadelphia coach Roger Neilson will
not be back from a bone marrow transplant in time for the start of
the second round of the playoffs, as had been projected.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes coach Paul Maurice on the new Staples Center in Los
Angeles: ``The ice here is (terrible) but, hey, it's a beautiful
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (15.6) is on track to have its worst power play
percentage since the expansion season (13.6).
</P>
<P>
   Alexei Yashin was on the move last week. Not to Ottawa. He quit
practicing with a Swiss club in favor of one in Italy, where
girlfriend/model Carol Alt is performing.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Tiger Williams on former Vancouver teammate Ivan Hlinka,
Pittsburgh's coach in waiting: ``We had no idea back then how big a
star he was in (Czechoslovakia). I guess it would be like dropping
Wayne Gretzky into Sudan, or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Your Canadian economics update: Vancouver lost $20.7 million in
the last six months of 1999. Canucks attendance dropped 1,900 per
game, amounting to lost ticket revenues of $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   _ Phoenix wants Carolina's Gary Roberts suspended after the
defenseman gave a two-handed chop to Jeremy Roenick after Roenick
scored an empty net goal. General manager Bobby Smith sent a tape
of the play to the league.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Mellanby scored the first goal in Florida Panthers
history and it was his ``assault'' of a rat in the locker room in
1995 that sparked fans to start throwing rats. So when Mellanby
played his 1,000th game last week, it's not surprising he was
showered with gifts: Rolex watch from teammates, Tiffany's clock
from the players union, a silver stick from the NHL and $10,000
donation to his charitable foundation from the club. Mellanby
played the game with the flu _ and he scored a goal.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   _ Ray Bourque has told Boston general manager Harry Sinden he
would approve a trade to two teams, Detroit and Philadelphia. Both
make sense, particularly the Red Wings, who last year acquired
Chris Chelios before the deadline and have made previous pitches
for Bourque and Al MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buffalo is shopping Brian Holzinger and Michal Grosek, who is
feuding with coach Lindy Ruff. Now that Dominik Hasek is back, the
Sabres may be aggressive in patching holes for the playoff stretch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edmonton is considering making a pitch for Montreal's Shayne
Corson, whose $4 million option next season would simply be passed
on by the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Panthers would be taking risk if they swing a rumored
trade for the Islanders' Kenny Jonsson and center Claude Lapointe
for Oleg Kvasha and another player. Jonsson would help the team on
the blue line, but he's a restricted free agent after the season
and will seek over $2 million. Lapointe is an unrestricted free
agent. Kvasha is slumping now but he's a 21-year-old with skill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
