<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0305-COX     03-04 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Happy ex-Hawk blazing new trail
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Watching the Hawks sink does not make Steve Smith feel
good. But the renowned nice guy is not feeling sorry for them,
either.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith and his Portland Trail Blazers continue to compete for
the best record in the NBA, the Hawks sink into an abyss that Smith
might have been able to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8 guard, part of a trade last year that brought
malcontent Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson, realizes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't foresee this for that team,'' Smith said last week.
``I thought they'd be better. But they took the heart and soul away
from that team.... And now they're paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   With salary-cap room, the Hawks dealt Smith to Portland for
Rider and Jackson. Jackson has been solid, but Rider has been more
disturbing than advertised, to the point that the team has
considered releasing him.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks moved Mookie Blaylock for the No. 10 pick in the
draft, which was used to select Jason Terry. Terry got his first
start Friday in a win against the Knicks. Also, the Hawks could not
come to terms with Grant Long, a backup forward who provided a
physical presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not just me and Mookie,'' Smith said. ``It was Grant Long and
Tyrone Corbin, too.... I thought we were doing well; we just had a
lot of injuries. I try to catch (the Hawks) whenever we aren't
playing. I feel for half the guys on that team. It's unfortunate
that they broke up our team. We were playing well as a team. But
injuries hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks were swept in the second round of the playoffs by the
New York Knicks, which sparked the changes. ``The sweep wouldn't
have happened if we were healthy,'' Smith insisted. ``We didn't
have Alan Henderson (out with eye injury) or LaPhonso Ellis, and
that was big. I'm not saying we would have beaten the Knicks, but
we had shown we could beat them in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we had played Indiana well, too, beat them in their place.
So, I thought we were close.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted a chance with the Hawks with a healthy complement of
players and a few key additions. ``But the Hawks thought getting
younger meant getting better,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   A lesser guy would gloat over how things turned out. Not Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``After nine years in the league, it's just a blessing to get to
Portland, with an organization that's committed to winning,'' Smith
said. ``We have a mixture of veteran guys and young guys, and
leadership with me and Scottie (Pippen). We're all willing to
forfeit shots to get that (championship) ring at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
