<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOFSTRA-B.U.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAXTON LEADS HOFSTRA TO TOURNEY SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRANDON LILLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, Del. _ The Hofstra Flying Dutchmen, behind the
conference player of the year, Speedy Claxton, built an early
double-digit lead and did not look back Saturday, defeating Boston
University, 80-62, in the quarterfinal round of the America East
tournament at the University of Delaware. The victory moved Hofstra
(22-6) into the semifinals against Drexel on Sunday. Behind Stephen
Starks' 25 points, fifth-seeded Drexel (13-16) beat Vermont, 71-59.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, Claxton finished with 14 points, well below his
average of 23.2 points a game, but made up for it with six assists
and only two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates really stepped up today,'' Claxton said. ``I had
a tough time scoring, so I was looking to get them shots and they
were knocking them down or they were making other plays to get
someone else a great shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra put the game away early in the second half. Boston
University rallied after the halftime break, chipping into
Hofstra's lead with a more fluid offense effort than it had
displayed. But each time Boston University seemed to be on the
verge of a run, Hofstra responded with a 3-point field goal or a
3-point play, demoralizing the Terriers, who got no closer than 11
points.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra guard Jason Hernandez scored nine of his 15 points
during that second-half surge.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra tried to apply the knockout punch early. The junior
forward Norman Richardson hit two 3-pointers as the Dutchmen scored
10 of the game's first 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra coach Jay Wright employed a man-to-man press to force
Boston University to start farther from the basket. The strategy
seemed to work as Boston University (7-22) never seemed to get in
sync on the offensive end, leading to easy transition baskets for
Hofstra.
</P>
<P>
   Poor outside shooting by Hofstra allowed BU to stay within
striking distance. The Terriers pulled to 19-15 on a 3-pointer by
Mike Costello with eight minutes remaining in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't played in a week and we were a little tentative and
a little sloppy at first,'' Wright said. ``I think as the game wore
on, they got a little tired and we were a little fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   That was when Claxton took over.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was used more as a decoy in the Dutchmen's set
offense in the first half, the senior point guard was particularly
effective in transition. Claxton's driving, 3-point play late in
the first half keyed a 12-2 Hofstra run that gave the Dutchmen a
14-point lead with four minutes left in the half. Hofstra went into
the locker room with a 42-29 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchmen took control in the lane early in the second half.
Hofstra began to dominate the glass. Forwards Roberto Gittens and
Lars Grubler combined for 15 rebounds, 12 of those coming after the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson finished with a game-high 21 points. Boston
University was led by forward Paul Seymour, who finished with 19.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Flying Dutchmen could play host to the
championship next Saturday if they get that far. The Flying
Dutchmen have never advanced past the semifinal round in their six
years in the America East Conference. But this is the first time
they have been top-seeded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
