<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WATER-WAR0305-COX     03-04 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-WAR0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tri-state water war not nearing truce
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Georgia, Florida and Alabama kicked off
negotiations two years ago to settle their acrimonious water war,
the states believed they would have an amicable settlement within a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having blown two deadlines and facing a third, negotiators
say that immense complexities unforeseen at the start of the
negotiations could doom efforts to devise formulas for sharing the
waters of two major river basins whose headwaters are in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the negotiations) fail because of the complexities, I
won't be surprised,'' says former Georgia Congressman Lindsay
Thomas, who represents more than 10 federal agencies at the
bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Without a settlement, the fracas likely will end up in the U.S.
Supreme Court, which could have serious repercussions for
Georgians. Litigation could cost Georgia $4 million to $6 million a
year, and the legal process could continue for years. The court
also likely would appoint a special master to oversee water use in
each state until a decision is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The special master could put on hold requests from
municipalities and industries for more water withdrawals, which
could shut down growth in metro Atlanta and North Georgia. ``The
(adverse) economic impact could run into the billions of dollars,''
warns U.S. Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   THE STAKES ARE HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Even if the states reach a settlement themselves, the stakes are
huge for Georgians. In exchange for guarantees of enough water for
metro Atlanta's growth in the next 30 to 50 years, Georgians may
have to pay higher electricity rates as hydropower production is
reduced. Southwest Georgia farmers face caps on irrigation, and
navigation at Georgia's inland ports at Bainbridge and Columbus may
be curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   Industries and municipalities _ and the people they serve _ may
have to pay more to treat waste discharged into rivers because of
less water to treat the effluent. In metro Atlanta, permanent
restrictions on outdoor watering and other stern conservation
measures may be put into place.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict, which began as a water fight between states, has
grown to include complex issues of science, agriculture,
environment, economics and, inevitably, politics.
</P>
<P>
   One potentially deal-breaking complication is the heavy use of
groundwater for crop irrigation in southwest Georgia _ reflected by
a controversial bill pending in the state Legislature that would
pay farmers in the area up to $30 million not to water their crops
during droughts.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have learned that the intensive irrigation can
substantially affect water flow in the Flint River, which, in turn,
may adversely affect the Chattahoochee and Apalachicola rivers.
Together, the rivers form the so-called ACF basin.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Alabama and Florida are haggling over water rights in
the ACF. On a second front, Georgia and Alabama are feuding over
the Alabama, Coosa and Tallapoosa basin, or the ACT.
</P>
<P>
   A DECADE OF BICKERING
</P>
<P>
   When Alabama triggered the water war 10 years ago by suing the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers over metro Atlanta's water use, the
irrigation issue and other now high-profile problems seemed of
little consequence.
</P>
<P>
   What was of burning importance to Alabama at the time _ and
still is _ was fear that a mushrooming metro Atlanta would hoard
most of the water in the ACF and ACT and leave little for Alabama's
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's fear seemed confirmed in 1989 when the Corps announced
a plan to reallocate 20 percent of the water normally reserved for
power generation in Lake Lanier to drinking water. The plan was
designed to ensure Atlanta an adequate water supply through at
least 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The decision triggered an uproar in Alabama. Then-Gov. Guy Hunt
demanded that the reallocation plan be suspended until the Corps
conducted a detailed analysis to determine the impacts on
downstream users, including Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, however, went ahead with another controversial plan: In
June 1990, Georgia asked the Corps for a permit to build a
4,200-acre reservoir on the Tallapoosa River only five miles
upstream from the Georgia-Alabama line. The lake would be the first
of a dozen or so state-built regional reservoirs that would
encircle metro Atlanta and ``drought proof'' North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the Corps received Georgia's request, Alabama
sued the Corps in federal court. Georgia's plan, Alabama said,
would vest Georgia with expanded water rights at the expense of
downstream users. Georgia countered that Alabama was trying to
interfere with its right to use water within its borders as it saw
fit. Florida sided with Alabama, contending that metro Atlanta's
unquenchable thirst would jeopardize growth in northwest Florida,
as well as Apalachicola Bay's world-famous oysters that depend on
nutrient-laden freshwater coming down the Apalachicola.
</P>
<P>
   DEADLINES FOR AGREEMENTS COME AND GO
</P>
<P>
   The water war quickly became bitter. At one point, Georgia
threatened to withhold permits for some Alabama companies to
withdraw water from the Chattahoochee, which Georgia contends lies
wholly within its borders through a right it claims as one of the
original 13 states.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the governors of the three states called a truce,
effectively putting Alabama's lawsuit on hold. Each state pledged
to help devise a plan to share the waters of the ACF and ACT.
Georgia pledged to put on hold its plans for regional reservoirs.
The states also agreed to use the results of a comprehensive study
of the river basins, which has cost more than $22 million so far,
to devise water-sharing formulas.
</P>
<P>
   With the study nearing completion in 1997, the three states
agreed that the best way to work out a settlement was to set up two
commissions _ made up of the governor of each state or his
representative, and a federal representative appointed by President
Clinton _ under two interstate water compacts to work out
allocation formulas that would be in effect for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations began in February 1998 with an aim to reach an
agreement by Dec. 31, 1998. When that time limit slipped _
negotiators couldn't agree on water sharing formulas _ they set a
new deadline of Dec. 31, 1999. Now, still far apart, the
arbitrators are working toward a May 1 deadline for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In two sessions last week in Atlanta, the negotiators failed to
make headway. In the ACT talks, Alabama wants more water at the
state line than Georgia is willing to provide during droughts.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA WILLING TO 'SHARE THE PAIN'
</P>
<P>
   The two states have agreed to hold one more meeting this month.
Alabama's chief negotiator, Jim Campbell, said it could be the
final session for the ACT talks.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman has said that Alabama will ``see them
in court'' if Georgia is not willing to ease up on its stance.
</P>
<P>
   In the ACF talks, negotiators also are facing the prospect of a
stalemate. Florida is demanding more water at the state line at
certain times in the year than Georgia is willing to provide.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators said they might consider an interim
water-sharing formula that would be renegotiated within seven to 10
years after some of the complex issues hampering the talks are
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Environmental Protection Division has started
a massive project to locate farm wells in 10 southwest Georgia
counties _ the most agriculturally productive region of the state _
in order to determine how much water farmers may suck out of the
ground and from the Flint River during dry years.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators say they need to understand exactly how the
Flint's surface flow is reduced by heavy irrigation before they can
work out a satisfactory water-sharing formula for the ACF.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the federal representative at the negotiating table,
says the irrigation dilemma is part of an even larger issue that
has emerged since the talks began _ unyielding demands for more
water from a variety of interests, including hydropower,
navigation, agriculture, recreation and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``These groups will not go quietly into the night,'' warns
Thomas, who has the power to veto any agreement reached by the
states if he deems it incompatible with federal environmental laws
and other regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kerr, Georgia's chief negotiator, says Georgia is willing
``to share the pain'' of any water agreement, but the state must be
cautious not to sign on to 50-year contracts that it can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're upstream, and you're the one signing the contract,
you have to be very careful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
