<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET RETURNS TO A CHANGED CHILE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ While General Augusto Pinochet was stuck in
London for 503 days, his beloved homeland did some things he never
would have allowed, such as:
</P>
<P>
   --Began a search with military officers and human rights
advocates to find the remains of thousands of people who
disappeared during Pinochet's 17-year dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   --Processed 60 lawsuits, filed by relatives of missing or
tortured Pinochet-era victims, that threaten to pull Pinochet into
a legal drama even more humiliating than the one he just endured in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   --And late last year, Chile elected its first socialist
president since Salvador Allende, the man Pinochet overthrew in a
CIA-backed coup in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Having Pinochet thousands of miles away has been both both
painful and liberating for this South American country of 12
million people.
</P>
<P>
   And now that their former leader is back, many Chileans wonder
whether Pinochet will return to the political stage he reluctantly
exited when he was placed under house arrest in Britain in October
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the country's new attitude was displayed this weekend,
when government officials roundly criticized the army's decision to
hold a homecoming ceremony, complete with a military band playing
patriotic songs, when Pinochet's plane touched down on Chilean
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Juan Gabriel Valdes called the welcome
celebration ``a disgrace,'' and President-elect Ricardo Lagos said
the retired general's televised arrival had damaged the country's
image. Thousands more Chileans protested on the streets of Santiago
for a second day Saturday, demanding his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinochet's supporters, bolstered by having their hero back
home, said they hoped he would stay active in the political
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a senator for life,'' said Matthew Aylwin, a 55-year-old
salesman who waved a Chilean flag outside the military hospital
where Pinochet visited for medical exams. ``He has to help fix the
things that have gone wrong while he was away, to keep the
communists out.''
</P>
<P>
   There is growing curiosity on whether the 84-year-old general
will attend Saturday's presidential inauguration for Lagos, whether
he'll return to the Senate, or whether he'll rekindle ties with his
longtime associates in Chile's army.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainty, most observers agree Pinochet's forced
absence brought two key changes: It opened the way for a socialist
president; and for the first time it elevated the issue of human
rights violations under Pinochet into a policy debate for
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Pinochet been here instead of Britain, chances are we
would not be talking today about lawsuits against him, a socialist
president or about whether he should retire from public life,''
said Armen Kouyoumdjian, who publishes a newsletter on Chilean
political and military affairs. ``He is someone who always has an
opinion and many people here are influenced by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger over Pinochet's return spilled over into a downtown march
Saturday by 3,000 protesters, who demanded that he be tried for the
same torture charges he avoided facing in Europe because British
doctors considered him too feeble.
</P>
<P>
   The British ``made the mistake of thinking he's too sick to
stand trial, but that doesn't mean he's innocent,'' said Diana
Lekis, 22, who joined in a rally held under a blazing late summer
sun outside the National Palace. ``Now it's up to us to resolve
this problem ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   News media from Chile to England, meanwhile, continued to
question British Home Secretary Jack Straw's decision to release
Pinochet from house arrest for medical reasons, especially after
the retired general appeared both steady and alert as he walked
away from his wheelchair and greeted family and friends after
returning to Santiago on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet left the military hospital Saturday &UR;  &LR; night under heavy
security and went to his suburban estate in the foothills of the
Andes. He must now wait word from an appeals court in Santiago,
which will decide whether to strip him of his parliamentary
immunity and make him stand trial for human rights torture in the
deaths and disappearances of some 3,000 people during his rule.
Polls show that most Chileans want Pinochet tried here.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Chilean citizen is above the law,'' President Eduardo Frei
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts such as Kouyoumdjian wondered whether Chile's army,
which suffers from low morale because of low pay and poor housing
conditions, might find inspiration from Pinochet's return. Another
military coup, they added, would be unthinkable because of the
effect it would have on Chile's world trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a new, more polished generation in the military, but
they're mostly the sons of old officers,'' said Kouyoumdjian.
``Their biggest concern is money. And the real power is not the
military anymore but the business and industrial community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
