<HEADLINE>
VILLAGERS FLEE FIGHTING BETWEEN SERBIAN POLICE AND ALBANIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALISHEVO, Yugoslavia _ A fierce firefight broke out early
Saturday morning between the Serbian police and Albanian guerrilla
fighters in an Albanian village in southern Serbia, causing an
exodus of villagers who fled by car into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the village, Dobrosin, was empty of inhabitants,
said its mayor, Rabit Saqipi, who had briefly returned there.
``Only soldiers are left,'' he said sadly.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting had flared up and frightened the last remaining
civilians, causing a new flight of Albanians from their homes in
southern Serbia, just beyond the Kosovo boundary.
</P>
<P>
   American troops of the peacekeeping force watching the border
with Serbia reported hearing periods of gunfire in the space of two
hours and then counted more than 70 villagers fleeing in cars in
the small hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-led peacekeepers and U.N. officials have recently expressed
concern about the volatile situation on Kosovo's eastern boundary
with Serbia, and the events around Dobrosin showed how unstable the
area is. In a sequence of events that Kosovo has seen played out
many times, Dobrosin is just the latest to suffer from skirmishes
between the Serbian police and self-appointed defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Armed men _ declaring themselves to be fighters of the
Liberation Army of Presevo, Bujanovac and Medvedja, Albanian towns
in southern Serbia _ went public last week saying they would fight
to defend the Albanian village of Dobrosin. The group, apparently
an offspring of the now disbanded Kosovo Liberation Army that
fought Yugoslav forces in Kosovo, vowed to defend the village from
Serbian aggression.
</P>
<P>
   But Saqipi, Dobrosin's mayor, sat in a cafe in Malishevo,
several miles into Kosovo from his village, and acknowledged that
the fighters had only drawn the ire of the Serbian police. He
looked crushed by the fate of his village. ``No one will return
now,'' he said. ``There is no way to persuade the villagers to go
back now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the shooting erupted just after midnight when the
Albanian fighters saw unknown figures on a ridge outside the
village and opened fire. For the next two hours they exchanged
gunfire with the Serbs from a distance. The Albanians suffered no
casualties, Saqipi said. The Serbian authorities have so far not
reported any casualties either.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of the mayor, Naip Rexhepi, a politician in Malishevo,
said a wolf or a wild boar could have frightened the men and caused
them to open fire.
</P>
<P>
   The fear and haste with which the villagers fled showed just how
they have been living on tenterhooks, expecting a catastrophe at
any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have constantly suffered maltreatment at the hands of the
Serb police,'' Saqipi said, adding that market day, when villagers
travel to the nearby town, has always caused problems. ``But things
got worse, so much so that we cannot think of going there
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   What started with harassment and bribery has escalated to death
threats and killings. Three villagers have been killed in the last
two months, and villagers are now frightened for their lives. ``It
is just how it happened in Kosovo,'' Saqipi said.
</P>
<P>
   One villager, who moved his family to Kosovo two weeks ago, said
his children had started asking if the Serbs were going to come and
kill them. ``They had seen a lot on television about massacres in
Kosovo and they asked me, `Are the Serbs going to come and kill
us?''' he said, his face sweaty with anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever caused the violence early Saturday, the results were
catastrophic for the village. Families bundled belongings into
their cars and set off in the middle of the night, as the guns
rattled around them, to escape into Kosovo, where American troops
have mounted a visible protection force on the boundary.
</P>
<P>
   Some 76 refugees had crossed by early morning, according to the
office of the U.N. high commissioner for refugees in the nearby
town of Gniljane. They have been quickly housed by local people,
and the refugee agency has some 90 families on standby to take in
people in such emergencies. It also has space ready for some 1,500
refugees in community centers, if the influx of refugees increases.
</P>
<P>
   Aid officials have been bracing themselves for this sort of
crisis as tensions have been rising in the area east of Kosovo.
``It is a strange time, when we are winding down the emergency
relief operation in Kosovo,'' said Andrea Recchia, an area field
officer for the refugee agency. ``But here tension has definitely
increased.''
</P>
<P>
   The villagers are pinning their hopes on the peacekeeping force
in Kosovo, known as KFOR, hoping that it will move into the buffer
zone that reaches five kilometers _ a little more than three miles
_ into Serbia, and so provide them with security. They say KFOR
officers have told them that they cannot operate beyond Kosovo's
border, but they persist in hoping. ``The best solution would be
for KFOR to move into the five-kilometer zone,'' said Saqipi.
``Many times we have asked for security.'' And for lack of any
other protection, he said they had to rely on irregular Albanian
fighters. ``If our soldiers leave, then we will be left to the
mercy of the Serbs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the whole village has fled, he looked defeated. The
only chance to return to their homes lay with the international
community, he said. ``All our hopes are on them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
