<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BACK IN CHILE, PINOCHET IS A REAL NOWHERE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert sentence in 4th graf about protesters in Chile.)  
 (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ When Gen. Augusto Pinochet traveled to London
16 months ago on a diplomatic passport, he was still a powerful
force on the Chilean political scene. He was a leader of
conservatives in Congress as a senator for life who could pick up
the telephone to weigh in on crucial military matters.
</P>
<P>
   No one seriously suggested that the former dictator would ever
be prosecuted for his past.
</P>
<P>
   But when he returned home Friday _ benefiting from a British
decision that he was too infirm to stand trial in Spain on charges
of gross human rights violations during his 17 years in power _ the
84-year-old was a shadow of his former self.
</P>
<P>
   His political future is being negotiated by military and
civilian officials who do not even consult him. Several of his
closest former aides are under arrest, and he himself faces months
if not years of legal proceedings to escape prosecution here.
Saturday, thousands of protesters marched in Santiago, demanding
that he be jailed.
</P>
<P>
   His own seat in the senate, which he was granted under a
constitution written during his 17-year military rule, now appears
to be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   For Pinochet, it is a bleak panorama.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Lavin, the star of the Chilean right, who nearly won the
presidential election in January, did not attend the small airport
ceremony honoring Pinochet's return. The few conservative
politicians who did come were quick to tell reporters that they
were there as private citizens, not as representatives of their
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Ricardo Lagos, the first Socialist president of Chile
since Pinochet overthrew Salvador Allende in 1973, have let it be
known that Pinochet is not invited to his inauguration March 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a great majority of the population,'' an editorial in the
daily La Tercera argued on Friday, ``Pinochet is now part of the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was at the height of his powers, Pinochet bragged that
``not a leaf shakes in Chile without my knowledge.'' And people
believed him, even after he gave up the presidency in 1990. The man
who ruled Chile for 17 years only stepped down after losing a
plebiscite, but he was able to negotiate a sweet deal from his
civilian opponents: He remained commander of the army until 1998,
then became a senator for life, thus gaining legal immunity and
lasting influence.
</P>
<P>
   But during his months under house arrest in Britain, he became,
in Chile, something akin to the emperor with no clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something incredible has happened,'' said Armando de Ramon, a
noted historian. ``They humiliated him and did what they wanted to
him. And that is the reason this country has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the taboo subjects of disappearances and torture
became the daily grist of the news media as journalists covered the
charges made against Pinochet by prosecutors in Spain, Belgium,
France and other quarters. Local rights groups resuscitated
themselves, and torture victims began to organize. And younger
military officers _ concerned that Pinochet's legal woes would
damage the armed forces _ began to distance themselves from his
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's absence opened a vacuum, and the man who filled it
was a previously obscure appeals court judge in Santiago, Juan
Guzman. Early last year, Guzman came up with an inventive legal
interpretation that has jolted the military's impunity, opened the
way for the arrests of 40 former military and police officers and
forced the military to begin a dialogue with rights lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman's ruling, which has been upheld by the supreme court,
found that an amnesty declared by the Pinochet regime to protect
officers involved in political crimes between 1973 and 1978 could
not be applied to cases involving people who are still missing,
since the victims may still be alive as victims of ongoing
kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly finding the missing people alive is unlikely. But this
interpretation has put pressure on the military to offer
information to family members who would like to bury their dead.
Otherwise, the officers face years of embarrassing prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman is now pushing ahead with the unthinkable: prosecuting
Pinochet himself. He has been assigned to investigate 60 criminal
complaints against the general, and he appears to be concentrating
on a possible connection between the former dictator and a
helicopter-borne death squad known as the Caravan of Death, which
removed 75 political prisoners from military and police prisons in
the month after the 1973 coup for summary executions and
clandestine burial.
</P>
<P>
   Since more than a dozen of the victims are still missing _ and
at least theoretically could be alive _ an investigation into the
death squad has already led to the prosecution of a retired general
who was a close aide to Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Before Guzman can indict Pinochet in the case, he will have to
seek the revocation of his senatorial immunity. That will not be
easy, especially because legislators are pushing a constitutional
amendment to allow the former dictator to step down from the Senate
but retain his immunity.
</P>
<P>
   But an indictment is not entirely out of the question, and Lavin
and other conservatives have said they will not stand in the way.
The conservatives still say they respect the former dictator's
economic accomplishments, but they read the opinion polls. And the
polls show that well over half of Chileans believe Pinochet should
face justice in Chile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
