<HEADER>
A6962 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     03-04 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO'S THE ONE TO BLAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless you're Rick Pitino's kid, these are not your father's
Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino and these Celtics do represent the resurrection of
truth in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   To the collective pique of many former franchise heroes, these
Celtics are the ironic predicament of last season's marketing
campaign. Looming above the streets of Boston were billboard
come-ons to fans from a team trumpeted as ``Rick Pitino's Boston
Celtics.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming them now requires guts.
</P>
<P>
   But to accuse the Celtics of being created in Pitino's image
would suggest the Boston coach is coyote ugly. They don't qualify
as hideous, but they are within walking distance.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of their trip into the news this week is traced to
the tantrum Pitino unloaded after Wednesday's home loss to Vince
Carter's Toronto Raptors. Pitino's rant pointed the middle finger
at Boston fans and reporters, who in his estimation are negative in
the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because the Celtics used to be great in the
extreme. Such history created a level of expectation that would
terrify anyone who isn't receiving a pile of money to conquer it.
Rick banks about $7 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Celtics' president has attempted to
accelerate Pitino's success by hiring inappropriate players and
paying them grotesquely high piles of money.
</P>
<P>
   The president's name, of course, is Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, as the personnel boss, Rick stinks. The abridged version
of his blunders:
</P>
<P>
   -Drafting Chauncey Billups with the third pick in 1997 when
Tracy McGrady didn't go until the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   -Paying Antoine Walker even more money than the Celtics are
paying their president/coach.
</P>
<P>
   -Trading Andrew DeClerq and a first-round pick to Cleveland for
Vitaly Potakpenko. The Cavs used the pick to draft Andre Miller.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough for us.
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino's disaster had nothing to do with judging talent and
everything to do with Ping-Pong.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons why the Celtics were able to lure Pitino
away from Kentucky where he was one of the nation's top sharpies
was the winning percentage he would inherit. That percentage
figured to qualify the Celtics for the first pick in the 1997 NBA
Draft, a pick that would yield some kid named Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtics were Ping-Ponged to pick No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the ego hasn't landed, but its wheels are
down.
</P>
<P>
   Motor City export
</P>
<P>
   According to most unsanctioned prophets, free-agent nominee
Grant Hill is expected to remain with the Detroit Pistons next
season.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one member of his buddy roster says Hill's desire
to win an NBA championship makes him a longshot to stay in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   His Duke education provided Hill with enough wisdom to calibrate
the distance between Detroit and another title.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hike.
</P>
<P>
   The lack-of-cap-room epidemic has infected the Pistons, whose
attempt to clear the salary of deserter Bison Dele off their books
may not provide enough relief to hire a big man who can make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons also are just good enough to eliminate the option of
being rescued by a high draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Another league source says Hill is keen on the idea of playing
for Michael Jordan's Wizards, whose renaissance is held hostage by
salary cap evils.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Sprite will obey Hill's thirst and sweeten their
endorsement deal to help mitigate the pain of signing for less than
the maximum market value. Nah.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Kenyon Martin continues earning support as the
early favorite to be the first college hotshot plucked in the 2000
NBA Draft. If you saw Thursday's game with DePaul, no explanation
is required. But you're probably howling over our tardy declaration
of this year's top Euro-prospect. Howl no longer. The name is
Iakovos Tsakalidis, and he's a 21-year-old, 7-foot-1 finesse
(skinny) center who plays for a Greek League team known as AEK.
Tsakalidis has yet to declare for draft inclusion, but could be
plucked in the middle of the first round when he does. ... Reports
of Miami offering Voshon Lenard and San Antonio dangling Avery
Johnson for Clipper Derek Anderson are swell fiction that's been
cannibalized by lazy reporters. ... Courtney Alexander, a
shoot-first, defend-never ``two'' guard at Fresno State, is making
scouts even more nervous than usual. Alexander, who's something of
a J.R. Rider rerun (on the court and off), challenged a few draft
inhibitions by dropping 40 points including the game-winning
35-foot bank in Wednesday's victory over San Jose State. But the
guy he was, ahem, guarding Spartan Cory Powell was 11 of 13 from
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ... Vince Carter may be capable of dunking over a Macy's Parade
balloon, but refuses to slam during Raptors' practices. Must be a
commitment to conservation. ... According to high school watchdogs,
Cincinnati recruit Jerome ``Buddy'' Harper has been considering a
skip to the NBA for a while. The 6-5 shooting guard from South
Carolina may have little left to ponder. After Harper was charged
with assault last week, Cincinnati rescinded its scholarship offer.
Many informed witnesses rate Harper ahead of Fresno's DeShawn
Stevenson as the nation's best prep at the two-guard spot. One
scout said Harper's name could be called in the draft's first
round. ... It's no secret that second-year Clipper Brian Skinner is
attempting to replicate the hair style (and game) of Portland's
Brian Grant. But you may not know the 6-9, 260-pound Skinner began
his coiffure adjustment after receiving frequent autograph requests
by L.A.-area pedestrians who thought he was Laker Kobe Bryant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
