Super Tuesday. Will turnout forecast the final result? Does an
early defeat for McCain in New England spell doom for the rest of
the night? Where to go on the Web for early exit polls. Which
pundits are worth your time. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   WASTE _ WASHINGTON _The reform movement, which has been
languishing in recent years, may be making a comeback in this
year's presidential elections. The war on waste and pork barrel
spending is seen as a powerful image in John McCain's insurgency
against politics as usual. Exit polls indicate that reform has a
strong appeal, especially for his backers. The message is one more
jarring one for the capital, where even Republicans have allowed
the crusade against waste and pork to languish in recent years.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-EXAMPLES _ WASHINGTON _ Some people scowl or shrug at what
they see as profligate spending of taxpayer dollars for marginal or
ineffective programs. Martin L. Gross does something else. The
retired college professor has made a second career out of combing
through thousands of pages of federal budget documents to discover
exactly where those dollars go. (Malone, Cox News Service). 13.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-WATCHDOG _ WASHINGTON _ Finding waste in the government
may seem about as easy as finding sand at the beach. The problem
for David M. Walker is that nowadays, the folks he works for aren't
very interested in all that sand. As comptroller of the United
States, Walker has the sometimes thankless task of heading the
agency that is the investigating arm of Congress. His General
Accounting Office is the chief watchdog for exposing waste and
mismanagement throughout the federal government. (Malone, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: All moved Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SELMA-MARCH _ SELMA, Ala. _ Exactly 35 years after he was beaten
by police in a civil rights march here, Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., is
leading a bipartisan delegation of Congress members to relive the
historic days and promote racial understanding. The visit
culminates with a Sunday march joined by President Clinton. (Turay,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-RALLY _ ATLANTA _ Hundreds of current and former black Coke
employees expected at St. Philip A.M.E. Church in Decatur to
discuss the layoffs and lawsuit. On the agenda: how to get the
company to change its position on a key issue, the release form
Coke requires of laid-off employees to get enhanced severance
benefits. A press conference is scheduled after the closed meeting.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Events is skedded to begin at 5 p.m. EST Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   WATER-WAR _ When Georgia, Florida and Alabama kicked off
negotiations two years ago to settle their acrimonious water war,
they believed they would have an amicable settlement within a year.
Now, facing their third deadline to reach an agreement, negotiators
are saying that immense complexities unforeseen at the start of the
negotiations may negate efforts to devise formulas for sharing the
waters of two major river basins. For instance, heavy use of
groundwater for crop irrigation in southwest Georgia has emerged as
a pivotal issue in the negotiations. The deliberators acknowledge
that so little is known about the impact of irrigation on river
flows in the region that several more years of intense study is
needed before they can some to a substantive agreement. When
Alabama triggered the water war 10 years ago by suing the Corps of
Engineers over metro Atlatna's water use, the irrigation issue was
not even regarded as a problem. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH MAP AND PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-AMNESIA _ BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Many don't even call it the
Lebanese Civil War. To them, it is the ``War of the Others.'' There
is no national monument to the tens of thousands who died, because
the country cannot face the carnage that tore Lebanon apart for 15
years, ending in 1990. But two events in the last
</P>
<P>
   month of cracked the ``national amnesia'' that Lebanese have
about the war. A deputy to one of the war's most notorious warlords
took out an ad in newspapers
</P>
<P>
   asking for forgiveness, and the government established a
commission to bring closure for the families of the 17,000 still
missing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). With Photo ofShaftari and
mothers of the missing.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVEDThurs., March 2.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ADVISORS _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ All the President's
Men: The St. Petersburg team. This story takes a look at the
players behind the candidate, who's running his campaign and the PR
team responsible for his image. Interesting characteristic is that
Putin, much like Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush,
is very open about his leaving policy stances and economic plans to
his team of strategists. Most of them have come from St.
Petersburg, Russia's cultural capital and second city, and they
could shake up the Moscow establishment. (Coker, Cox News Service).
With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., March 2, in (i) International (k) Commentary
categories.
</P>
