<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-ADVANCE0305-COX     03-04 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ADVANCE0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain the rebel could be facing last stand
 &HT;    By Jena Heath and By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is the GOP primary equivalent of the Main Event:
Titanic Tuesday is coming, raising the question of whether it will
spell the end of the heavyweight bout between Gov. George W. Bush
and Arizona Sen. John McCain. Or will the competitors go another
round to March 14 or beyond?
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high: 613 delegates are up for grabs, more than
60 percent of the 1,034 needed to seize the nomination. Bush wants
to land a knockout punch in California, where he holds a wide lead
among Republicans. McCain's survival hinges on sweeping New England
and New York and perhaps winning a major state such as Ohio,
Tuesday's third-biggest prize with 69 GOP delegates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's rebel candidacy, his proven appeal to Democrats and
independents, has made this Republican primary season anything but
run-of-the-mill. So unpredictable is it that even the most seasoned
party-watchers hedge about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds still very much favor Governor Bush as they have all
along, but many people, myself included, have underestimated
Senator McCain's appeal all the way through, and so I think it's a
bit premature to write off his candidacy,'' said Atlanta pollster
Whit Ayers, a Republican who doesn't work for either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   California is the Holy Grail for Republicans. During the 1970s
and '80s, winning the state was a virtual lock on the White House.
Richard Nixon won in 1972 and Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
President Clinton changed that in the 1990s, taking California in
1992 and in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the state's top Republicans, including members of the
congressional delegation, are behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Republican in the nation who has done more to
reach out to women, Hispanics, Asians, African-Americans and
independents and Democrats than George W. Bush,'' U.S. Rep David
Dreir said in a TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone can cast ballots Tuesday, but only Republican votes
count toward choosing California's 162 GOP delegates. With Bush's
overall lead far slimmer than his lead among Republicans, McCain
could wipe the glow off a Bush delegate win by seizing the popular
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp recognizes the possibility, but is more occupied
with counting delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lay of the land is that Governor Bush enjoys
strong support from the people who will be deciding the Republican
primary,'' said Bush adviser Mark McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas political scientist, said
that as much as Bush needs to win the ``beauty contest'' popular
vote in California, McCain needs it more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McCain wins the popular vote while Bush wins all the
delegates, and then McCain also has a Northeast slate of victories,
that just sets up a situation where party leaders will have to ask,
`What sense does it make to nominate somebody who has less of a
chance to win in November than McCain does?''' Buchanan said. ``All
those scenarios do is add more electoral weight to that very
pregnant question, which is the last hope of John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   That argument is resonating with some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Mayor Susan Golding, one of the few high-profile
California Republicans backing McCain, said her man would be a
better November contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans have to remember that if California wants
to beat Al Gore, that the right candidate to do that with is John
McCain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's other super prize, New York, the outcome is
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   It's a state where McCain had difficulty getting on the ballot,
given the state's complex election requirements. But the New York
GOP establishment, after the New Hampshire primary and with Bush's
belated blessing, finally agreed to let McCain on the ballot in all
counties.
</P>
<P>
   That was just in time for Bush to raise the ire of Catholics, a
huge part of New York's Republican Party, when he visited Bob Jones
University in his desperate bid to win South Carolina. McCain has
seized on that visit to appeal to Catholics, especially in New
York, forcing Bush to send an apology to New York's Cardinal John
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has since said he regrets not taking advantage of his visit
to Bob Jones to condemn that school's anti-Catholic views, and
Tuesday's vote may illustrate how Catholics have responded to
Bush's statements of regret.
</P>
<P>
   McCain either leads slightly or is in a dead heat in three New
York polls. The state's primary, open only to GOP voters, would be
an embarrassing one for Bush to lose, because he has been running
strong among Republican primary voters. A loss in New York could be
fatal, however, for McCain, who desperately needs a big state win
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers gives the McCain campaign points for doing ``a remarkable
job with the resources they've had,'' but he isn't putting money on
a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the laws of political gravity are about to assert
themselves,'' Ayers said. ``You can't win a Republican nomination
if you can't get Republican votes. The establishment does matter.
Money matters, especially in wars of attrition. None of those
political laws have been repealed.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
