<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     03-04 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO THE STAR IN BOSTON FOLLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Boston coach Rick Pitino had a motto, it might be, ``I
confess, he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino has been unwilling to take responsibility for virtually
anything during his misguided reign as Celtics coach, and finally,
things are beginning to fall apart in Beantown.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino, who has been under assault from the Boston media since
trying to trade Danny Fortson to Toronto for Alvin Williams last
month, is starting to wilt under the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Pitino said he would not have left Kentucky and come
to Boston if he had known the Celtics would not finish high enough
in the draft lottery to select Tim Duncan or Keith Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   He must have forgotten to add a clause in his
multimillion-dollar deal with the Celtics that the ping-pong balls
had to be rigged in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're sitting on top of a national championship at
Kentucky and someone tells you you're not going to get Duncan - and
you have a championship-caliber team coming back - I think you'd be
pretty astute and say, well, maybe you'd be a little crazy and
maybe you should get examined at Mass. General if you're going to
walk into that situation,'' Pitino said. ``I think that's stating
the obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, who exactly was holding the gun to Pitino's head to
leave Kentucky? No one really knows.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino's heartfelt comments came a day after he lost his cool
while talking to the Boston media.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this negativity in this town sucks. ... It makes the
greatest town, the greatest city in the world, lousy,'' Pitino
said. ``The only thing that will turn this around is being upbeat
and positive, like we are in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bird, McHale and Parish, Cousy and Russell are not walking
through those doors. What is walking through those doors are young
players who are going to be prone to mistakes at times until they
get experience, who are going to play hard and try to play exciting
basketball - and not always succeed at doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   It all seems to make sense, until you examine what Pitino has
done in Boston since being deprived of Duncan or Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   He wasted the third pick in the '97 draft on Chauncey Billups,
then traded him to Toronto. He drafted Ron Mercer with the sixth
pick, and traded him to Denver for Fortson.
</P>
<P>
   He acquired Vitaly Potapenko. He signed Travis Knight to a $22
million deal before shipping him back to the Lakers. He sent Eric
Williams to Denver in '97, then brought him back in '99. He did the
same thing to Fortson last month.
</P>
<P>
   It's the horrible wheeling-and-dealing, not the draft lottery,
that is responsible for Pitino's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Grizzly situation: The back-stabbing has begun in Vancouver,
just as the Grizzlies are showing promise as a franchise.
``Consultant'' Dick Versace is secretly sending his own handpicked
scouts to games that official Grizzlies scouts are already
attending.
</P>
<P>
   GM Stu Jackson is expected to be fired soon, a move that will
result in dissension. Star forward Shareef Abdur-Rahim has said
that if Jackson's contract is not extended, he wants to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Not giving up: The Wizards, or more importantly, Michael Jordan,
are expected to make another run at Toronto guard Doug Christie
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Washington nearly completed a deal sending Ike Austin and Tracy
Murray to Toronto in exchange for Christie and guard Dee Brown, but
it fell apart just before the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Wizards coach Darrell Walker, who coached Christie in Toronto,
would like to be reunited with the shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   Add Wizards: Magic Johnson always has an opinion on Jordan's
dealings, and had this to say when asked about Jordan's grand plan
for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what he's going to do? He's going to unload
everything and wait for Vince Carter! Ha ha!'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Canada: In what other country could curling outdraw Vince
Carter in the TV ratings?
</P>
<P>
   It's true, but don't blame Canadians as failing to appreciate
the Raptors' superstar forward. NBA rules limit the Raptors'
broadcast market to 120 kilometers from Toronto. That has
restricted the growth of the Raptors - and Carter - throughout
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences for Raptors games are limited to 55,000-80,000 viewers
because of the access problem.
</P>
<P>
   New owner? Frankie Muniz, the 14-year-old star of the new Fox
series ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' is also a basketball fan, or at
least a fan of bad basketball.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared on CBS' ``The Early Show'' this week and was asked
by Jane Clayson if he has a ``backup plan'' should he leave acting
one day.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz: ``I'd like to be a geographer, own the L.A. Clippers, be
on the PGA Tour or be in the Blue Man Group.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryant Gumbel: ``Frankie, why the Clippers? Why not a real
NBA team?''
</P>
<P>
   Muniz: ``The Clippers rule. I love 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel: ``The Clippers. Man. The kid's got his work cut out for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Start sweating the news: New Jersey coach Don Casey might be
worried over his future, after Nets owner George Steinbrenner
ordered team president Michael Rowe to make a road trip to
determine why the Nets are just 7-22 away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found what I've been looking for,'' Rowe said. ``This
team has a chemistry problem. ... We'll get it fixed. Some of the
things that need to be done will be done in short order.''
</P>
</TEXT>
