<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6969 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-KAN &LR;      03-04 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE GRIT IN LEGACY OF FAMILY'S CALAMITOUS SCORE OF DEATHS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Mo. _ When 82-year-old Rosetta Frakes Parks died of
diabetes in a nursing home in nearby Waverly three years ago, her
obituary noted that she had been preceded in death by several
brothers, sisters, half brothers and half sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Several? How about 20 _ lost one by one over the years to
tetanus, dropsy, tuberculosis, snakebite, meningitis, bad
mushrooms, auto accidents, suicide, appendicitis, murder,
influenza, brain tumors and cholera.
</P>
<P>
   And of all of them, only two brothers, Lincoln Frakes, who died
at 72 in 1968, and Grant Frakes, who died at 92 in 1994, and one
sister, Lulu Frakes Lockwood, who died at 88 in 1986, lived
anywhere close to a long life.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty out of 25 siblings in what one relative calls a ``family
tragedy.'' The family in this case began with a man who in the
course of his life had married two women, having 13 children with
one and 12 with the second.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a tragedy that _ through a stack of death certificates
and newspaper clippings _ opens a window to another side of the
20th century American experience.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, what happened to the Frakes occurred a mere 70 miles
from the bright lights of Kansas City, a place for most of this
century considered a refuge from the hardscrabble ways of rural
Missouri. In Kansas City were medical treatments, a modicum of
safety and 9-to-5 jobs that took people away from the dangers of
living off the land.
</P>
<P>
   Those 70 miles might as well have been a thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Frakes still are living. Charles ``Hap'' Frakes, 82,
lives in Grand Pass, Mo. Illness in his middle years robbed him of
most of his memories about the past.
</P>
<P>
   But Daisy Frakes Campbell, 68, who lives east of here near
Orearville, remembers all too well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen,'' she said. ``You can't be bitter. You can't
blame anybody for all the troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Tyler of Kansas City, a daughter of Hap's, said she
stumbled onto what she calls the Frakes' ``calamities'' while
researching the family genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about Job,'' she said. ``This family had sufferings most
of us can't imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Tyler said, she's been inspired by what she can only
describe as their grit and tenacity, qualities the Frakes somehow
coupled with an incredible dignity. She recalls that Rosetta _ two
years before her death and just after her husband died in a highway
accident in which she also was injured _ proclaimed: ``All us
Frakes are tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The patriarch was Aaron Albert Frakes, farmer, Missouri River
fisherman and occasional moonshiner. A photograph taken of Aaron
with his first wife, Mary Elizabeth Parsons Frakes, shows him with
three revolvers in his belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was rough and tough,'' Daisy said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron died at home in 1950 of stomach and intestinal cancer at
age 78. The death certificate noted he had no Social Security
number.
</P>
<P>
   Mary died in 1922 at age 44 while giving birth to her 13th
child, Jimmy, who weighed, according to family memory, 23 pounds
and was stillborn.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Mary's children died young. Viola, 2, died of a
snakebite in 1895; Cindia, 10 months, cholera, 1909; Ella, 8 days
old, tetanus, 1911; and Elmer, 3, mushroom poisoning, 1915.
</P>
<P>
   After Mary died, Aaron, widowed and with youngsters at home
sometime in late 1922 or 1923, headed south to Hickory County.
There he ``bought'' Hazel Girtha Adams, then 15 or 16, for $25. And
married her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember talking to her mother and my grandmother,'' Daisy
said, ``and she said that money was all that was between them and
starvation. Things like that happened in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazel would have 12 children by Aaron before she died in 1947 of
a throat infection at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   By then, though, other misfortunes had befallen the family. Soon
after Aaron arrived back home with his new bride, his 19-year-old
son from his first marriage, Willie, became smitten with his
stepmother. In September 1923, Willie committed suicide by putting
a shotgun to his heart and pulling the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Bessie Frakes Foote, injured by a fall from a horse in the late
1920s or early 1930s, was committed to a state hospital in
Missouri, diagnosed with an unspecified mental illness. She
remained institutionalized until her death from tuberculosis in
1954.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Frakes Sanderson, 31, died at home in 1936 in Miami
Station, Mo., of a stomach infection, nine months after undergoing
an appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth Frakes, 11, died of a brain tumor in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy recollected Mary Elizabeth's burial. At the cemetery,
Daisy recalled, the casket was lowered into a grave partly filled
with seep water that gurgled and bubbled as it covered the coffin.
Amid that came the weeping and protestations of the child's mother,
Hazel, who said, ``God, please don't put her in that awful water.''
</P>
<P>
   Girtha Frakes, 14, died in 1939 in Kansas City of what was
called dropsy.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Dale Frakes, who was named for his stillborn half brother,
was stillborn in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Inez Marie Frakes simply disappeared. Daisy thinks she may have
been killed in a car accident in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   After Hazel's death, the misfortunes continued.
</P>
<P>
   Della Frakes, 15, was fatally injured in 1948 when she was
struck by a bullet as she walked into the line of fire of her
brother, Aaron Louis Frakes, while he was target shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Lee Frakes, 30, working as a gas station attendant in
Kansas City, was shot to death in 1954 in a botched armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Cindia Ellen Frakes Morrow, 30, was killed in 1958 when the
rifle she was carrying while berry hunting discharged, the bullet
striking her in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Donnell Frakes, 25, died in a car crash in Independence in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Louis Frakes, 34, injured in an industrial accident and
suffering what he termed ``constant pain,'' killed himself with a
handgun in North Charleston, S.C., in 1969. Family members said he
never recovered from the shooting accident that took the life of
his sister, Della, 21 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Frakes, 37, was shot to death at Malta Bend, Mo., after
what apparently was an argument over hunting dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Frakes McComber died in Marshall in 1984, the victim of a
stroke at age 54.
</P>
<P>
   A snapshot, which years ago people called a ``Kodak,'' shows
five of the Frakes youngsters among schoolmates sometime in the
1930s. Four are Frakes girls, wearing feed sack dresses. Their
faces are clean, their hair combed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look here,'' said Daisy, pointing at the photograph. ``See
Cindia Ellen. See she has a dark sock on one foot and a light sock
on the other? That's how poor we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in letters before her death, Rosetta would describe a happy
childhood, one with plenty of food, abundant game down in the
Missouri River timber, and how every spring meant not only a run of
fish for the men and bounty in the big garden, but flowers blooming
for the women. Spring along the river, Rosetta wrote, was like
Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy says the Frakes were never victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss my family,'' she said. ``There's an empty place in my
heart. I go to the cemetery and I wish I could hold my mother in my
arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't blame nobody. Things just happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
