<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER: TOO EARLY TO GET SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. - Even though Orel Hershiser is competing
for a spot in the Dodgers' starting rotation, he has a message:
Don't even start evaluating for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the first spring start of Hershiser's Reunion Tour, the
right-hander allowed two wind-aided solo homers in one inning -
including one to ultra-light hitting Rey Ordonez - and had to pitch
out of a bases-loaded,none-out jam in his other inning of work
against the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser said none of that matters because he threw mostly
fastballs with a few sinkers mixed in. He'll incorporate a few
breaking balls and change-ups into his next outing, possibly throw
all breaking balls the next time out before easing into his
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing glorified BP (batting practice),'' Hershiser
said Saturday. ``This will be fun for three more weeks and then
it'll get serious. The last couple of outings it will come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   As a 17-year veteran with a vast knowledge of pitching and
coming off a 13-win season with the Mets, Hershiser's provided the
type of slack that doesn't exist for Carlos Perez, the closest
competitor for a starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of the rotation is set with Kevin Brown, Chan Ho
Park and Darren Dreifort. It leaves Hershiser, Perez and rookie
Eric Gagne to fill the last two spots. While Gagne is a near-lock
to start, Hershiser could begin the season in the bullpen, which he
knew when he signed as a free agent during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orel was just getting his work,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``He knows what day it is. The first time out, the
second time out, it's just getting your work in. Hopefully, the
guys are throwing strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Center of attention: Knowing who wins the center field job -
Todd Hollandsworth or Devon White - is a long way away, but if
Johnson's prognostication is accurate, the veteran White will have
to play well to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my pick to click this spring,'' Johnson said of
Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers suggest there is another possibility. Though neither
Johnson nor general manager Kevin Malone care to address the issue
at this point, a platoon seems possible. The left-handed-hitting
Hollandsworth has a .272 career average with a .325 on-base
percentage. The switch-hitting White was much better from the right
side last season. He hit .288 and had a .367 on-base percentage
against left-handers compared to .260 and .323, respectively,
against right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Garth: Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw considers himself a huge
Garth Brooks fan, but not big enough to groove a fastball so the
country music star can get a hit. Instead, Shaw struck out Brooks
on a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie (Shaw's wife) and I were talking about it just this
morning and then I heard the crowd and I'm like, `Oh, my God,' `'
Shaw said. ``He didn't even smile. He just came in there and got
ready. I struck him out twice, but (the umpire) didn't call it a
strike the first time. Then I threw the same pitch and he had to
ring (Brooks) up. Guess he didn't wantto do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Right-hander Chan Ho Park allowed one run in two
innings and struggled with his control. ``He was flying open
occasionally and air-mailing the ball up, but when he didn't I
thought he looked pretty crisp,'' Johnson said.... After stressing
fundamentals for two weeks, the Dodgers committed two more
blunders. A day after having two baserunners thrown out, Shawn
Green was picked off first and Mark Grudzielanek was late covering
second on a stolen base.... Righty Robinson Checo, who filed
insufficient documentation for a visa, has been cleared to leave
the Dominican Republic and should be in camp Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   DODGERS vs. METS
</P>
<P>
   When/Where: 11 a.m.; at Holman Stadium, Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Channel 5; XTRA 1150 AM
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: Staff ace Kevin Brown makes his first spring start
and will be followed by righty Eric Gagne, the leading candidate
for the fourth spot in the rotation. Lefty Al Leiter starts for the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's result: For the second straight day the Dodgers
surrendered four homers and lost to the Mets 7-3 on the road. Chan
Ho Park gave up a solo homer and Orel Hershiser allowed two homers.
Angel Pena homered for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   - Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
