<HEADLINE>
AT THE 11TH HOUR, BRADLEY CRANKS UP THE ENERGY  
 GORE LINKS GOP TO FAR RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just before 10 a.m. Saturday, on a chilly morning in
Washington Square Park, former Sen. Bill Bradley returned to the
neighborhood where he had come the day after his narrow loss in New
Hampshire. Back in early February, Bradley was greeted by hundreds
of supporters, cheering him on as he turned his fight from New
Hampshire to the New York primary. But on Saturday, with the
primary three days away, Bradley gazed over a sparse crowd of
students scattered over expanses of empty concrete.
</P>
<P>
   If Bradley was dispirited by the turnout, he did not reveal it.
Instead, he plunged into the speech that got him where he is today,
reprising some of the same jokes he had used in his last
appearance. And from there, he embarked on an exhausting day that
took him to Brooklyn, the Upper West Side, the Bronx and, finally,
to Missouri for a political dinner. Bradley's schedule called for
him to return to Buffalo, N.Y., to be ready for two early-morning
Sunday talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   There is little optimism in Bradley's camp this weekend, as his
aides gird for the series of primaries on Tuesday that most
Democrats believe will dispatch Bradley from the race, leaving Vice
President Al Gore the Democrats' presumptive nominee for president.
But that does not seem to have discouraged Bradley, who is
campaigning this weekend with the kind of blind energy usually
exhibited by a candidate locked in the tightest of races.
</P>
<P>
   The creases on Bradley's baggy face suggest the fatigue of a
candidate who has been at this for close to a year, yet on Saturday
he raced from stop to stop, handshake to handshake and storefront
to storefront, lingering to answer questions from anyone who wanted
to talk to him about education, Medicare, the IRS or, inevitably,
the New York Knicks. He gave a speech on foreign policy on Friday
and is planning to be in three states on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He is, in short, acting as if a display of sheer energy in these
potentially final hours will, if not win him any elections, at
least leave a graceful impression on the public, assuming it is
even paying much attention to this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help me out on Tuesday!'' Bradley bellowed in Brooklyn, in the
Bronx and in front of Zabar's, a famous food emporium on the Upper
West Side of Manhattan. ``What's your name?'' he inquired again and
again, as he hustled to keep pace with his energetic wife,
Ernestine.
</P>
<P>
   He posed happily with Edward Koch, the former mayor and one of
his chief New York supporters, at the Washington Square Park rally,
which was about two blocks from Koch's apartment. (Koch said he
would have gone to the end of the world to campaign for Bradley on
Saturday morning _ well, at least, he quickly added, ``to the end
of the borough.'') Bradley listened as his other top New York
supporter, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., compared the
reception Bradley found on the Upper West Side to what Moynihan
said he had witnessed when Franklin Delano Roosevelt visited the
same neighborhood when running for president 60 years before.
</P>
<P>
   And he went into Zabar's, sweeping into the store with a wave of
reporters and Secret Service agents. Once inside, he shed his
jacket, donned a Zabar's cap and apron, and headed for the deli
counter to pose for the kind of photograph that tends to play well
to Jewish voters who are so prominent in the neighborhood and in
the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   All seemed to be going fine until a few of Bradley's more
politically experienced New York supporters _ starting with Ronnie
Eldridge, a member of the City Council _ suddenly noticed that a
reporter had noticed that Bradley was happily slicing away at a big
ham, as the cameras clicked away. ``It's turkey! It's turkey!''
Eldridge whispered urgently, if perhaps disingenuously.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bradley's aides quietly took the candidate by the arm.
``Senator, we're going to go cut some lox.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE LINKS GOP RIVALS TO FAR RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Vice President Al Gore said Saturday that both major
Republican presidential candidates were in league with the party's
``right-wing extremist wing.''
</P>
<P>
   He painted a sinister picture of both candidates conspiring with
the Rev. Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out and Falwell and Robertson slap `em on the back
and say, `We heard everything we wanted to hear,''' Gore told 2,000
people packed into the narrow cobblestone streets around Boston's
Faneuil Hall. ``Let me break that code for you. What they're saying
is, they heard a solemn promise to give the right-wing extremist
wing of the Republican Party control of our Supreme Court and the
interpretation of our Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in New York, Gore attended a fund-raiser on the Upper
East Side of Manhattan where he raised $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few days from now, New York will have the decisive vote
in picking the Democratic nominee,'' he said. ``Both Senator
Bradley and I agree that it's the vote on Tuesday that will
determine the nomination. And so, New York's voice is louder than
ever before and that's saying something,'' Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
