<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-DORAL-NYT &LR;      03-04 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGHAM CLOSER TO FIRST VICTORY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Franklin Langham has never won on the PGA Tour. Yet,
after Saturday's steady third round, Langham will begin Sunday with
his best chance for victory.
</P>
<P>
   Langham shot a four-under-par 68 to take a three-shot lead into
the final round of the Doral-Ryder Open. He is at 19 under par
(197). Jim Furyk, who also shot 68, was in second place at 16 under
par, while Stephen Ames was in third place at 15 under.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Langham handles the pressure
of being the man to catch at the Doral Golf Resort and Spa, because
until you have won on tour, doubt can easily creep in. However,
Langham responded Saturday when he was challenged, shaking off an
early double-bogey on No. 3 and playing solid golf thereafter. Will
anyone be able to catch Langham? Those in pursuit were not waiting
for him to fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll be able catch him just making a bunch of
pars,'' said Furyk, who is pursuing his fifth career victory. ``He
has been playing great golf, and I've always felt more comfortable
with a lead heading into the final round, rather than having to
make up ground. He's in good position, so somebody will have to
make a run at him. Hopefully, it will be me, but one of us probably
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Shigeki Maruyama (14 under par) and Nick Price (13 under par)
were also within striking distance. Langham, who started the day
with a 3-stroke lead, has played three rounds in the 60's _
66-63-68 _ and in his 101st start on tour, he may finally be able
to break through.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't win, I'm sure I'll be disappointed,'' said Langham,
31, a native of Augusta, Ga. ``I'm sure I'll be nervous, excited,
all of those things. I expect it. I expected it today. That's one
of the reasons why I played well. Whether I was three ahead or
three behind, I have put myself in position to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Langham showed his resiliency after the par-4 No. 3, when he
pulled his tee shot, then hit his second shot into the water, which
led to his double-bogey. Many players who have never won would have
folded at that point. But not Langham. After Price went to 15 under
par and briefly took a one-stroke lead, Langham responded with
birdies on Nos. 6, 7 and 8 to reach 17 under par, and he maintained
his composure from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never panicked,'' said Langham, who has shown a steady
putting stroke on his ride to the top of the leader board. ``One
reason why I stayed calm is that I'm playing so well. It's
different when you're struggling and something bad happens to you.
But when you're playing well, you feel confident.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child living in the Augusta area, Langham worked several
Masters tournaments as a scoreboard operator, and he has dreamed of
playing in that fabled tournament. But unfortunately for Langham,
he will not qualify for next month's Masters even if he wins on
Sunday. Tour winners used to automatically qualify for the Masters,
but the qualifications have been changed, and the world ranking is
now used as one of the qualifications for the Masters. Langham is
171st in the world ranking, nowhere near the top 50 who will
automatically qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure would be nice to get in the Masters, but maybe if a
local boy wins, they'll think about changing it back to how it used
to be,'' Langham said. ``But the way I look at it, if I do well
here, it will move me closer to making the Masters next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ames was in close pursuit of Langham for most of the day, but a
double-bogey on No. 16 cost Ames dearly. It was the toughest day of
the tournament at the Blue Monster, as the long-awaited wind
finally arrived and made the course far more challenging. A 65 by
Robert Damron was the day's best score, but the barrage of birdies
died down, and players had a far more difficult time with club
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Price was eight under through 15 holes, but he bogeyed Nos. 14
and 17 to give away key strokes. Though he hit the ball
beautifully, putting remained a problem for Price, as he missed
several putts within striking distance on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   But while Price left the course wondering what might have been,
Langham left the course wondering what would happen Sunday. Often,
the first victory is the hardest to get, and Langham hoped his
first victory would come Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they'll be firing at me, because I'm a marked man
now,'' Langham said. ``I have to expect that. But if I play well,
I'll have a great chance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
