<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--MISSOURI-PRIMARY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS FOR BRADLEY, MCCAIN IN MISSOURI VOTE LOOK BLEAK  
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON and STEVE KRASKE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Her index finger tracing a horizontal line
across a printout of Independence voters, Bowen Hinton matches name
to number and punches another seven digits into the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello,'' she begins, the smile on her face seeping into her
voice.
</P>
<P>
   She's a local volunteer for the Bill Bradley campaign, Hinton
tells one caller after the next. ``May I,'' she asks, ``talk to you
about the senator?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, she says hurriedly, would be the first president from
Missouri since Harry Truman and is of ``the highest
integrity....Can the senator count on your vote?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the calls end up on answering machine tape. Nearly as
many are cut short. The person is Republican, or anti-abortion, or
simply not in the mood for politics.
</P>
<P>
   A few times she actually finds Democrats who plan to vote in the
Tuesday primary. Sometimes they like Bradley. Sometimes...
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh...and you're in support of the vice president.''
Disappointment fights against enthusiasm in her voice. ``Well,
thank you so much for your time.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurgency campaigns of Bradley and Sen. John McCain, his
Republican counterpart, limp toward the Missouri primary with
political insiders betting ever heavier on their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Polls in this Midwestern bellwether suggest that especially
among people most likely to vote Tuesday _ the core of activists in
the respective parties _ Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush reflect the sheen of probable victors.
</P>
<P>
   To overcome the political regulars, analysts say, both Bradley
and McCain must draw people to the primaries who do not walk a
party line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who is campaigning as an outsider, primarily without
the support of leaders in his own party, must appeal to people who
don't normally get involved,'' said Robert Salisbury, a professor
of American politics at Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost by definition, those are the hardest voters to
energize,'' he said. ``They're not involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's effort is undercut because even though only a handful
of delegates to the nominating convention have been chosen, he has
yet to notch a single victory. It has been hard to get traction as
the other maverick has drawn away many of the independents and even
some Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has won a few primaries, but he's lost more. And his
standing in the polls and with the press suffered recently when the
``Straight Talk Express'' at first denied and then owned up to
being behind a hard-hitting phone bank assault that hinted that
Bush was anti-Catholic. Then came his attack on Christian
activists, who have been pounding him.
</P>
<P>
   At their core, however, the intra-Republican and -Democrat
splits in Missouri and the country are between party establishments
and renegades. The resources that organize voters and attract
publicity are nearly all with Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a midtown Kansas City news conference held by Bradley
supporters at noon Friday. The campaign played two Bradley
television commercials, though it was uncertain whether the spots
ever would run in Kansas City. And it called on two college
students, a professor, a member of the Missouri Democratic
Committee, a woman who grew up in Bradley's hometown of Crystal
City and a former union official.
</P>
<P>
   Although they all argued that Bradley was energizing the
disaffected, they came up short on evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown an hour later, Gore backers filled the Jackson County
legislative chambers with union painters, firefighters, electrical
workers and Teamsters. The room held at least a dozen elected
officials, including a member of the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   And former Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver recounted a series
of major local projects _ the Bruce R. Watkins Drive, repair of the
Chouteau Bridge, development of the 18th &AMP; Vine District _ and gave
Gore credit for sending federal money for each of them.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver didn't bother to compare Gore with Bradley, choosing
instead to look to the general election in November. He noted that
McCain had opposed some of those grants in the Senate and argued
that Bush was an untested executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need,'' Cleaver said, ``somebody who is polished.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who stumped in St. Louis and Springfield on Wednesday, was
bringing out a host of big guns to bolster his efforts in Missouri.
Former GOP Chairman Haley Barbour was in St. Charles County on
Friday. Former presidential contender Elizabeth Dole was booked for
Cape Girardeau in southeast Missouri and Callaway County in
mid-Missouri on Saturday. And Sen. Kit Bond of Missouri was to
barnstorm across the state for Bush throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have quite a lot of stuff going on,'' said Catherine
Hanaway, Bush's executive director in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has campaign organizations in more than 80 of the state's
114 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my chances here in Missouri,'' Bush said when he
visited Kansas City last week. Upshot of speech
</P>
<P>
   Meantime the McCain cause staggered in southern Missouri's
``Bible Belt'' following his harsh criticism of Christian
conservative leaders Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell as ``forces of
evil.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Mark Wright, a Springfield Republican, said McCain's
comments were a hot topic in his die-hard conservative district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minimal support that he had, he lost because of those
comments,'' Wright said. ``I think there's zero support for him in
this area now.''
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
