<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--MISSOURI-PRIMARY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS FOR BRADLEY, MCCAIN IN MISSOURI VOTE LOOK BLEAK  
</HEADLINE>
 2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON and STEVE KRASKE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Some southwest Missouri Republicans were
particularly incensed at the comments directed at Falwell, a
graduate of Baptist Bible College in Springfield, a school that
Wright also attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in this area,'' Wright said, ``are very, very
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Once impressed with McCain's life story, Mike Cierpiot of
Independence also is switching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way over the line,'' Cierpiot said of the denunciation of
Robertson and Falwell. ``There was no reason to do that stuff. He
was doing well until that point.''
</P>
<P>
   The signals for McCain were mixed. Polls continued to show the
senator from Arizona behind. Yet two Zogby surveys indicated McCain
had cut a 34-point gap to only nine by Thursday. Similarly, a poll
commissioned by The Kansas City Star taken last weekend had the
race at 48 percent to 36 percent for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Missouri chairman, Rolla lawyer David Steelman, spoke
of a groundswell for the senator that keeps his phone ringing and
makes it hard for him to get any work done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a nuclear bomb going off,'' said Steelman, a
longtime GOP activist. ``It's fun. I've never seen anything like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steelman said the divide between elected politicians, who are
almost all backing Bush, and those rank-and-file voters who back
McCain, has never been more pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Only one member of the General Assembly, Steelman's wife, Sen.
Sarah Steelman, has endorsed McCain. Bush boasts of endorsements
from eight state senators and 43 House members.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain has no paid staff members working the state,
Bush will have nine by Tuesday. Late campaigning
</P>
<P>
   Bradley backers in Missouri said enthusiasm for the former
senator remained high, although more than a few expressed doubts
that he ultimately could upend Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be a last-minute surge, but it's unlikely,'' said
Rebecca Cook, the Missouri secretary of state who is one of the
former senator's best-known supporters.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Bill Skaggs, a Kansas City Democrat, pointed to The
Star poll last week that had Bradley trailing Gore 53 percent to 33
percent in Missouri, Bradley's native state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's true, then I think Bradley is in trouble across the
country,'' Skaggs said. ``It sure looks like Bradley and McCain
have both fallen on hard times the last couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was to make a stop Saturday evening in Hannibal, where
Democrats were holding one of their annual Democrat Days
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also made some last-minute plans to campaign in Missouri,
with an election eve stop Monday night in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the vice president's campaign planned to fan out
throughout Kansas City on Saturday to pass out literature. Weekend
telephone banks were expected to be operating full-tilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley will make a final push here, so we need to stay
on our toes,'' said Gavin Lodge, who was leading Gore's Kansas City
office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, evidence that Bradley or McCain were on the verge of
scoring upsets in Missouri has yet to surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk of them fighting over independent
voters, but those voters are hard to get in primaries to begin
with,'' said Stephen Caliendo, an expert on public opinion
research, at the University of Missouri-St. Louis. ``It's
especially hard to get those people when people don't think you
have much chance of winning to begin with.''
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
