r f BC-HALLMARK2TAKES-KAN &LR;      03-04 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLMARK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REORGANIZATION BRINGS WRENCHING CHANGES TO CREATIVE WORKERS AT
HALLMARK CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hallmark Cards Inc., keeper of one of the
world's best-known brands, is shedding many of its old ways in a
drive to triple sales to $12 billion by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Some changes, such as consolidating various marketing
departments and shifting some production jobs to more modern
facilities, already have been made. Other changes are designed to
make the enormous, 90-year-old Kansas City company more nimble and
responsive to modern-day customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our new structure allows Hallmark to focus clearly on the
consumer, bringing relevant products to the marketplace more
quickly,'' Chief Executive Officer Irvine O. Hockaday said last
month when Hallmark announced record 1999 sales of $4.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus on the consumer, combined with new products, new
business ventures and synergies among Hallmark's family of
companies, will help us achieve our growth targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Hallmark management is reorganizing the company's
1,100-person creative department _ the lifeblood of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Although that department makes up only 10 percent of the
company's North American work force, those artists _ illustrators,
sculptors, calligraphers, writers, photographers and others _ give
the company its soul. Their ideas are translated into Hallmark
greeting cards, gift wrap, party favors, picture frames, photo
albums, collectibles and more.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization of the creative department includes a new
``team'' approach to its creative process. The department has been
evaluated, collectively and individually. Top management says the
reorganization will require a different mix of creative skills.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Barker, Hallmark's senior vice president of creative
product development, said some employees would no longer have a
place in the new department. That prospect has fueled fear in the
ranks of the privately owned company, which has a longstanding
reputation for job security and an unusually comfortable corporate
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star interviewed a dozen of Hallmark's creative
employees with the agreement that their names would not be
published. All said they feared reprisals ranging from write-ups in
their personnel files to being fired if they spoke on the record.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark spokesman Steve Doyal, while saying that no one would
have been so punished, said he understood the desire for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed work at varying job levels in an array of
artistic disciplines _ photography, illustration, product planning
and others.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed, although a small sampling of the creative
department, used strikingly similar terms to characterize the
emotions sweeping the department: fear, anxiety, paranoia, even
depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is, `Apply so much pressure, and see who breaks.'
If you don't break, you get to stay another year.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ``it's not the change _ it's whether or not you're going to
have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Barker said he understood that some employees were anxious. He
also acknowledged some shortcomings in management's handling of the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask people to be patient,'' Barker said.  &LR; brk:External
pressures
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark first committed itself to a wide-ranging reorganization
in 1995. Shortly thereafter, it formed what it calls its North
American Management Team.
</P>
<P>
   In the next several years _ when the company saw sales gains
slip from 11.8 percent in 1995 to 5.5 percent in 1996 and 2.7
percent in 1997 _ it set out to think beyond traditional
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Hallmark announced that it intended to triple sales
by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   To reach that goal, Hallmark identified six business areas that
earned a total of $120 billion in annual U.S. sales. The aim is to
gain 10 percent of that total to reach Hallmark's $12 billion goal.
</P>
<P>
   The six areas: greetings; caring gifts; memories (including
albums, scrapbooks and a recently acquired chain of portrait
studios); life celebrations (party wares, gift wrap, ornaments and
more); personal development (products that help develop
creativity); and family entertainment (television and cable
production). The creative staff will support the first four areas
primarily, the two others to a lesser degree.
</P>
<P>
   Scanning the horizon, Hallmark saw a rapidly changing world.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark remains the dominant player in the sentiment industry,
claiming 55 percent of the revenue in the greeting card market.
</P>
<P>
   But new competition is everywhere, from the Internet to smaller
companies grabbing chunks of market share to free-lance
illustrators who are getting products in the marketplace at
lightning speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage (the creative staff) to take a hard look at
what's happening on the outside,'' said Barker, displaying a
newspaper article about Vicky Howard, an Overland Park artist whose
decorative products business does about $35 million in annual
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening everywhere,'' Barker said. ``I want to have
a work process where we can unleash the creative capabilities that
I know are there ...and I know that our work flow today doesn't
allow that to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   For a long time Hallmark's product development has been linear.
For instance, after an idea for a Mother's Day card is conceived, a
designer might give the idea to an illustrator.
</P>
<P>
   After the illustrator does the main artwork, the card might be
handed off to a writer to do the card's text. Further design work
and committee review would follow.
</P>
<P>
   Such a process sometimes took two years to get a product to
market. In today's fast-moving marketplace, such a lag could spell
corporate doom.
</P>
<P>
   To reorganize its creative staff, Hallmark is changing from the
linear process to a team approach. A core group of creative people
will bring in others as needed and then see a product through from
concept to completion.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for increasing use of new technology,
including millions of images that Hallmark has digitally archived
for almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   A recent pilot project using the new model moved one product to
market in 17 days.
</P>
<P>
   Using that model for the 1,100-person creative staff, Hallmark
officials say they will need fewer workers for some positions, such
as illustrators, and more for others, such as designers.
</P>
<P>
   Before starting the reorganization, Hallmark conducted a talent
assessment of the department to show how strong _ or weak _ the
creative staff was.
</P>
<P>
   Employees were asked to put together two display panels of their
best work. Employees were told the panels would be used only to
assess the depth and breadth of the talent pool, not to compare
each employee's talent against their peers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, such comparisons were made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6986 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HALLMARK2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      03-04 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLMARK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REORGANIZATION BRINGS WRENCHING CHANGES TO CREATIVE WORKERS AT
HALLMARK CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
 2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Barker said management didn't think the
process through, which he regretted, but the process was new to him
and the rest of management. Although individual employees are
evaluated regularly, Hallmark had never done a departmental
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   After the work samples were pulled together, managers judged
each creative employee's work on a scale of 1 to 4, with 1 being
the strongest. Employees were then told how they ranked relative to
their peers.
</P>
<P>
   That last element was not part of the original plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that we did not think through the communication at
the time,'' Barker said. ``I owned up to that and I apologized.''
</P>
<P>
   But a tone was set. Other changes soon exacerbated some workers'
worries.
</P>
<P>
   To figure out where employees should be placed in the new
organization, everyone was asked to fill out a job preference form.
The form includes the language: ``Please Note: All staffing
decisions will be driven by the principle to do what is right for
Hallmark business needs to support the...work process and
reorganization. Business needs will be the primary consideration in
the placement of candidates; employee preference is second.''
</P>
<P>
   Barker said he expected to have the same number of people in the
creative division when the reorganization is completed by the end
of next year. But he added that it would be a different mix of
people.
</P>
<P>
   Annual turnover in Hallmark's creative department is 2 percent
to 3 percent _ remarkably low compared with turnover of about 15
percent for all employers _ but Barker expects it to reach 5
percent, perhaps higher, as the company reconfigures the creative
department.
</P>
<P>
   It has been Hallmark's practice to ``surplus'' employees whose
jobs were eliminated. In essence, employees are put in a pool of
workers and may fill in for others or try out a variety of
positions until they find a new one within the company.
</P>
<P>
   And if that doesn't work out in the coming reorganization?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will handle those like we have other situations,'' Barker
said. ``In many cases that will be, `It doesn't look like there is
a role here at Hallmark for you _ let us build a bridge for you to
the outside.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Wrenching change
</P>
<P>
   Don Blohowiak, a New Jersey-based consultant who has helped
manage change for corporate giants ranging from AT&AMP;T to Exxon,
empathizes with Hallmark and its employees.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not worked with Hallmark, he said it wasn't hard
to imagine how many creative employees might feel. The various
changes might seem like ``judgment day,'' with livelihoods and
self-worth at stake.
</P>
<P>
   On the corporate side, Blohowiak said, it's essential that
companies change, and the model that Hallmark is moving toward has
proved effective, efficient and profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Blohowiak said, based on his experience, such a process often
means paring 5 percent to 10 percent of the work force and
replacing them with others who are a better fit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these cultural changes are shocking, Blohowiak said,
``particularly if Hallmark has had...a culture of entitlement,
security, a nicey-nicey country club environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Blohowiak said, Hallmark is likely to emerge a
stronger, more nimble, more formidable competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years from now, you will find that people have adjusted
and that they've attracted a different kind of person to the
payroll who wants to work this way,'' Blohowiak said. ``But
managing that transition is going to be hell on everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
