<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAITEMS0305-COX     03-04 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAITEMS0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The power struggle
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. Indiana Pacers: A three-game Western trip was hard on them,
but they remain the best the conference has to offer. They have
been the most consistent.
</P>
<P>
   2. Miami Heat: Without injured Alonzo Mourning, the Heat beat
the Knicks and Seattle _ impressive. Miami's found enough offense _
except for a 69-point debacle at San Antonio _ while maintaining
its tough defense.
</P>
<P>
   3. New York Knicks: The Miami loss was telling, but the Knicks
will get stronger with the returns of Marcus Camby and Charlie Ward
from injuries. Meanwhile, Patrick Ewing continues to find his game.
</P>
<P>
   4. Philadelphia 76ers: Toni Kukoc is getting more acclimated to
his new teammates, which means the team is getting better. When
Allen Iverson plays off Kukoc consistently, the Sixers can be
formidable.
</P>
<P>
   5. Toronto Raptors: They pass Charlotte on the strength of the
ascending Vince Carter. In a week, he scored 51 against Phoenix and
beat Boston at the buzzer with a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. Los Angeles Lakers: The win at Portland solidified their
position atop the league. Both Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant are
getting better, which is scary. Significantly, the bench,
especially guard Brian Shaw, is adding a punch.
</P>
<P>
   2. Portland Trail Blazers: They were fortunate to have three
days off after the disappointing Lakers loss. They were able to get
it out of their system and resume their strong play.
</P>
<P>
   3. Utah Jazz: If there's anyone in the league who appears
ageless, it's Karl Malone. He just continues to get it done, with
ample help from seasoned pros John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek and
Bryon Russell.
</P>
<P>
   4. Phoenix Suns: Jason Kidd is the ignition, but the pistons are
many. Penny Hardaway is quietly going about his business doing a
little of everything, while Rodney Rogers contines to be a force
off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   5. San Antonio Spurs: Except for a strong effort over Miami, the
Spurs have struggled on both ends of the floor without Tim Duncan
(abdominal strain).
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Toronto forward Vince Carter: Since establishing himself with
the dunk championship, Carter has led the league in scoring since
the break with 29 a game. His 51 against Phoenix and game-winning
3-pointer at the buzzer in Boston illustrate his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles center Shaquille O'Neal: He led the Lakers over
Portland by doing the unthinkable _ going 9 for 13 from the foul
line. If that becomes the norm, look out.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's Michael Dickerson: The second-year player gets
overlooked with Shareef Abdul-Rahim there, but he has been
outstanding. He was the reason the Grizzlies had a 6-7 record in
February, the best month in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   FREE FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee's Glenn Robinson, Ray Allen and Sam Cassell: The
self-proclaimed most-potent trio in the league has been terrible.
The Bucks never could defend, but now they can't score, either.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's John Starks: After winning over the fans with the
Bulls, Starks has tried to force his release. Speculation is that
he missed games last week to advance the cause to cut him and not
because of bad knees.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING HEADLINES
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter catapulted himself atop the NBA as its primary
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE OUTS
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks fired vice president for personnel Ed Tapscott,
supposedly because Tapscott bought his own ticket to the NBA
All-Star Game and was seen sitting with Milwaukee general manager
Ernie Grunfeld, who was fired by the Knicks last year. Both
Grunfeld and Tapscott were fired by team CEO Dave Checketts.
</P>
<P>
   BIG, BAD MASON
</P>
<P>
   Hornets forward Anthony Mason was charged with third-degree
assault outside a New York nightclub after being involved in an
early-morning fight. Witnesses said a hassle began inside and
carried into the street. Mason, who has had several run-ins with
the law, says he was breaking it up. He was late for the Hornets'
game with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   NBA-champion San Antonio Spurs make their only visit to Atlanta
on Thursday when they face the low-flying Hawks. By then, All-Star
Tim Duncan probably will be healthy enough to return to action from
a strained stomach muscle.
</P>
<P>
   BLAZERS HIT THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   The Portland Trail Blazers go on a four-game Eastern road trip _
to New Jersey, Indiana, Detroit and Washington _ that could
solidify their place among the best in the NBA or help widen the
Lakers' gap in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   OLAJUWON GETS TREATMENT
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Hakeem Olajuwon should return to action after learning
he has an asthmatic condition. Olajuwon grew concerned when he
would get winded after just a few minutes. Three days of tests
discovered a reactive airway problem that restricts the flow of air
through his bronchial passages during heavy exercise. It is treated
easily with an inhaler.
</P>
<P>
   ROOKIE RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, the Clippers' Lamar Odom emerged as the
most impressive rookie. Then, it was Houston's Steve Francis as the
front-runner for rookie of the year. Lately, Chicago's Elton Brand
has come forward. A statistical look at a very close race:
</P>
<P>
   Player/Team/Scoring/Rebounds/Assists
</P>
<P>
   Elton Brand _ Chicago _ 19.0 _ 9.8 _ 1.9
</P>
<P>
   Steve Francis _ Houston _ 17.1 _5.1 _6.8
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Odom _ Clippers _ 16.3 _7.8 _3.1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
