<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Eds: this has been reinstated
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADLEY LIKENS HIMSELF TO TRUMAN
</P>
<P>
   An upbeat Bill Bradley brushed aside long odds facing his
Democratic campaign Saturday and reminded his volunteers in
Greenwich Village, N.Y., that another Missouri native, Harry
Truman, defied the polls to win an election more than 50 years ago.
``You know Harry Truman. They said he was finished in 1948, he
didn't have a chance,'' Bradley said accompanied by supporter
former New York City Mayor Ed Koch. ``And you know what happened
there. He came from behind and won.'' Polls show him trailing
opponent Vice President Al Gore in all 15 ``Super Tuesday'' states.
The latest polls in New York put Gore ahead by 20 points there.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY GOVERNOR BACKS BUSH
</P>
<P>
   In Hartford, Conn., on Saturday, New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman added her name to the long list of Republican governors
backing Gov. George W. Bush. Whitman, unlike most Republican
leaders, supports abortion rights, an issue on which she differs
with Bush. ``As a Republican, I endorse him because we share a
conservative Republican philosophy that transcends litmus tests and
invites everyone to join us to make America the greatest and
strongest nation on Earth,'' Whitman told a packed hotel ballroom.
Bush called Whitman ``a good friend.''``I am proud to have her on
my team,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   GORE TRIES OUT ANTI-GOP ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Vice President Al Gore on Saturday looked past
Bradley and began auditioning anti-Republican attacks that he is
expected to use in the general election, while campaigning in New
York and Massachusetts. His most potent weapon against the GOP
nominee: the strong U.S. economy. ``The issue now is whether or not
we're going to keep that prosperity going or whether or not we're
going to take the advice of both Republican candidates and take a
right wing U-turn back to the old polices of the past,'' Gore said
at a Boston rally. Gore also criticized Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Senator John McCain on environmental issues, something he has
rarely done in the Democratic contest with opponent Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY PRESSES GORE ON FUNDRAISER
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley called on Vice President Al Gore to fully explain
his role in the 1996 campaign fundraising scandal surrounding an
event at a Buddhist temple. Bradley cited new information in a
Knight Ridder Newspapers report that appears to contradict Gore's
earlier claims about his ignorance of a 1996 fund-raising event at
a Buddhist temple. ``Now is the time for Al Gore to be straight
with the American people,'' Bradley said. Last week, longtime Gore
friend Maria Hsia was indicted on campaign law violations relating
to the temple investigation. Gore has denied that he knew that the
temple luncheon was staged to raise money for the Democratic Party,
but a previously unreleased Secret Service memo prepared around the
time that Gore flew to Los Angeles for the event describes it as a
political fund-raiser, Knight Ridder reported.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK TIMES ENDORSES MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   The editorial page of The New York Times on Sunday endorsed Sen.
John McCain and Vice President Al Gore in Tuesday's Republican and
Democratic presidential primaries. ``Each of these two men
communicates a greater capacity for overarching presidential
leadership than his opponent,'' the editorial said, noting that it
does not always offer primary endorsements and last did so in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
