<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED RESULTS FOR ANGELS PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- Ken Hill started for the Angels and was followed
by Ramon Ortiz in the Angels' 12-4 loss to the Oakland A's Saturday
afternoon at Tempe Diablo Stadium, and the results were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz was perfect in his two innings, and Hill wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz retired all six batters he faced in the third and fourth
innings, including strikeouts of Jason Giambi, Olmedo Saenz and Ben
Grieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good fastball, good location, good changeup, good
slider and control of my pitches,'' Ortiz said. ``My plan is to
throw first-pitch strikes and hit my spots and I did that today. My
arm's good and my body's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who has declined to speak with reporters all spring,
wasn't quite as sharp as Ortiz while pitching the first and second
innings. He gave up two runs and four hits in two innings,
including an RBI single by Jeremy Giambi and an RBI trible by Ramon
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia, however, said Hill is making progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed much better command than he has,'' Scioscia said.
``He looked sharp and he'll get sharper.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's broke the game open with an eight-run ninth inning
against Angels relievers Lou Pote and Steve Mintz. David McCarty
hit two home runs in the inning for the A's.
</P>
<P>
   Bengie Molina, battling for the starting catcher's job, hit a
three-run homer and singled in three at-bats. Molina, however,
knows that winning the job will be based on how he handles the
pitchers and not his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about hitting at all,'' Molina said. ``Maybe
moving runners over, but not hitting. Just pitching. But once the
bat is in your hands, obviously you want to get a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia keeps an eye on the number of the runs the opposition
scores when each particular catcher is playing, much like a
pitcher's ERA. Saturday, Molina caught six innings during which the
A's scored two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina has always been known as a glove man
because of his defense. Now, DiSarcina will wear batting gloves for
the first time in his career. Until now, DiSarcina, who has a .257
lifetime average, didn't wear batting gloves even on the coldest
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to save my hands,'' DiSarcina said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jason Dickson threw two scoreless innings, allowing two
singles while striking out two in a ``B'' game against the A's
Saturday morning. Dickson, coming off shoulder surgery and trying
to win a spot in the starting rotation, said he felt no pain and
was encouraged by the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first time out there in a year-and-a-half, so it was
nice to get over the competition jitters,'' Dickson said. ``I
spotted my fastball and my breaking ball will be there when it's
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson has been throwing live batting practice and threw in an
intrasquad game earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of times out my stuff was as good or better
than I had in '97 (when he was an All-Star),'' Dickson said.
``Primarily my fastball. My main thing is trying to sink the ball,
and I didn't have it at all in '98. Now it's back to what it used
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson's fastball was clocked between 86-90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game: The Oakland A's snapped a 4-4 tie with eight
runs in the ninth inning on their way to a 12-4 win. Oakland's
David McCarty hit two homers in the big inning, and the Angels'
Bengie Molina hit a three-run homer for the Angels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: The Angels travel to Phoenix to take on the A's
again. Kent Mercker starts for Anaheim against Oakland's Kevin
Appier.
</P>
<P>
   Radio: KLAC-570, XPRS-1090 -- 1:05 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
