<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MULTIPLE-SLAYINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SOUGHT FOR QUESTIONING IN 5 BRONX SLAYINGS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Detectives investigating the slayings of four members
of a Bronx family and the fiance of one of the victims want to
question a Miami man who they say knew the victims and had been
seen at the three buildings where the bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   The man was seen with some of the victims on Thursday, officials
said. The bodies were found later that night and early Friday. As
detectives searched the Bronx neighborhood where the killings
occurred, officials announced a $1,000 addition to the $10,000
reward for information in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for assistance from the public, from anyone who
might have information in this case,'' said Capt. Geryl McCarthy,
the commander of the Bronx major crimes unit. She said the Miami
man goes by the name Lou and is missing his left index finger. He
is about 35 to 40 years old, 220 pounds and 5 feet 9 inches to 5
feet 10 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   By 7:30 a.m. Friday, detectives in Bronxdale had found the
bodies of four members of the Santos family and the fiance of one
of the victims in three residential buildings near the New York
Botanical Gardens and the Bronx Zoo. All five had been slain, and
some had been stabbed and shot in a manner that was consistent with
torture, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of 14-year-old Ishmael Santos, who was shot in the
head, his uncle Eduardo Santos, 34, and Ervin Aguilar, 33, were
found at 2975 White Plains Road.
</P>
<P>
   Another victim, the boy's aunt Denise Santos, 30, was found
lying face up in the kitchen of her home at 2934 Radcliff Avenue. A
large carving knife was lodged in her neck, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister Evelyn Santos, 39, who was the fiancee of Aguilar,
was found shot and stabbed in the elevator of her apartment
building at 2825 Olinville Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Saturday afternoon, McCarthy would not say
when the man had been seen at the locations and added that any
suggestion of a motive was ``pure speculation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
