r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     03-04 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOULS DOOM CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In yet another season of dubious conquest, the
Clippers established one more standard of ugly.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was personal fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had foul trouble we couldn't overcome,'' said interim
coach Jim Todd, whose whistle-whipped team helped turn Staples
Center into a construction site at high noon. ``That's the nicest
way I can put it without getting myself into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   There was trouble enough from the Cleveland Cavaliers, who -
with the assistance of an unforgiving officiating crew -- turned 38
Clipper personal fouls into 54 free-throw attempts. The Cavs made
42 within the margins of Saturday's 109-99 victory before 12,522.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips, who may have become the first team in NBA history to
attract more whistles than its dance team, led by a dozen points
(32-20) when a 3-pointer from Charles Jones opened the second
quarter. But the familiar stew of poor defense and Vogue-posing on
offense was bitter enough for their 47th defeat in 59 games.
</P>
<P>
   The post-game spin cycle kept returning to the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed to be called more closely than usual,'' Todd
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor (13 points and 8 rebounds in only 27 minutes),
was officially accused of committing his third foul before the game
was four minutes old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like I was getting' rung up for heavy breathing,''
said Taylor, who was attempting to play king-of-the-hill with a
donut-enhanced version of Shawn Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers (24-34) weren't exactly exempt from scrutiny,
collecting 34 fouls the Clips turned into a 27-of-34 effort from
the line. Cleveland crusaders Kemp (22 points) and ex-Clipper
Lamond Murray (18 points, 9 rebounds) were ably assisted by rookie
point guard Andre Miller (15 points, 7 assists), the former Verbum
Dei High star who looked swell in his homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   Clipper Lamar Odom scored a team-high 17 points in only 19
minutes, before receiving a bonus technical with his sixth personal
foul. Center Michael Olowokandi (13 points, 12 rebounds)
participated for 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't beat anybody with those guys getting those minutes,''
Todd observed.
</P>
<P>
   One Clipper who spent his time well was point guard Jeff
McInnis, who was rescued from the CBA eight days ago. With Troy
Hudson (stomach virus) in civilian uniform, the former North
Carolina floor leader had the starting role and produced 9 points
and 3 assists in 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some great players here,'' McInnis said after a
glimpse of the Clipper psyche, ``but we just gotta know that we can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   McInnis, who's expected to be retained after his first 10-day
contract expires Monday, made it his business to, ``Come out and
bring some energy. Since I got here for the Atlanta game, everybody
seemed dead out there.''
</P>
<P>
   With 72 fouls called Saturday, both teams only seemed beaten up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty's in the eye of the beholder,'' said Todd, attempting
to define the vision of this particular officiating crew.
</P>
<P>
   The beholders, who know beauty when they see it, may want to
keep their eyes closed. The next Clipper date is with the Lakers on
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
