<HEADLINE>
JAGR HELPED BY NEELY'S HURTFUL HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fearing that a charley horse in Jaromir Jagr's left thigh could
turn into a debilitating, perhaps career-threatening mess, doctors
in Pittsburgh last weekend cut into the superstar's leg and drained
a pool of thickening blood. The team's medical personnel felt it
could turn into myositis ossificans.
</P>
<P>
   Does that sound hauntingly familiar, Bruins fans? It should. Cam
Neely's career was launched into the abyss when a charley horse in
his left thigh turned into a bonelike mass during the summer of
'91. Some four years since his last game, the 34-year-old Neely
read with interest the accounts of Jagr's injury and hospital stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the bits and pieces that I've seen on the Internet,''
said Neely. ``Other than that, I don't know much about it _ but it
sort of sounds like the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The key difference, Neely noted, is the timing of the injury and
the context of the times. Jagr was hurt in the thick of the season
and began receiving professional medical help immediately. Neely
was injured in Boston's last game of the season _ via a hit on Ulf
Samuelsson in Game 6 of the '91 Stanley Cup semifinals _ and
figured all he needed was an ice pack to take care of the pain.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Jagr benefitted from Neely's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't that much knowledge back then about what could
happen with that kind of injury,'' said Neely, who missed all but
nine games of the next season but worked himself back into shape
and played four more seasons, including his 50-goal campaign in
1993-94. ``At least there wasn't for me, and I don't think anyone
else. You just kind of figured, `Ah, it's OK, I'll ice it.' I
wasn't going to be back playing until September anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   By training camp, the charley horse in Neely's left thigh had
hardened into an ugly mass that was 9 inches long, 3 inches wide
and 1 1/2 inches thick _ approximately the size of a brick. He
hasn't had an X-ray lately but he knows the mass has shrunk only
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of strange,'' said Neely. ``I can still feel it. If
you take your hand and push into your (quadriceps), normally you'll
feel muscle there. If I do that to my left quad, all I get is
bone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins aren't saying how long Jagr, one of the game's most
exciting talents, will be sidelined. He also is hindered by a
pulled hamstring. Jagr was initially injured when Buffalo's Michael
Peca slammed a knee into his thigh Feb. 16. He played another five
periods over the next five days before the charley horse began to
bother him. If Jagr is out for much of the final quarter of the
season, there's a good chance Pittsburgh won't make the playoffs.
One top star is that vital. Consider: Neely last played in the
postseason in '95; the Bruins have won only one playoff round since
'94.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what happened to me,'' said Neely, ``it probably woke
some people up. I'm happy to see that with Jagr they're taking some
precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Equipment check
</P>
<P>
   A hot topic at last week's general managers meetings in La
Quinta, Calif., was injuries caused, rather than prevented, by
equipment. Pads for elbows, shoulders, and legs often can be used
more for assault than protection. The Lords of the Boards have
formed a committee of players, GMs, and union reps to assess
possible changes. Don't look for any big change right away, because
the investigaton will have to be thorough and, ultimately,
equipment manufacturers might have to be asked to make changes on
the production line . . . Look for gritty Islander checker Claude
Lapointe to be grinding elsewhere no later than the March 14 trade
deadline. One rumor last week had him headed to Florida, along with
defenseman Kenny Jonsson, for forward Oleg Kvasha. An ex-Nordique,
Lapointe will turn 32 at the start of next season and is exactly
the scrappy kind of center, excellent on the draw, the Bruins
desperately needed on their checking line this season. It would be
a nice break for the dependable Lapointe to land on a real playoff
squad. In nine seasons, he has played in only 13 postseason games.
Another possible Islander deportee: skilled center Olli Jokinen, an
underachiever since arriving on the Island in the Ziggy Palffy swap
. . . Some in the Colorado media, amid the Avalanche's second-half
slump, refer to Bob Hartley as the club's ``future former head
coach.'' Tough crowd. But it's hard to figure a club with
Colorado's abundance of talent struggling to make the playoffs. A
Hartley successor may be needed . . . Mark Tinordi, Atlanta
property via last June's expansion draft, is expected to land with
another club prior to the trade deadline (with the Thrashers owed a
draft pick). Tinordi, 34 in May, made more than $3 million last
year with the Capitals. He might not see half that now, but
interest should be keen, given a dearth of hard-hitting defensemen
and the mounting injuries as the postseason approaches . . . The
International Ice Hockey Federation will meet this week in
Barcelona to try to sort out all issues _ on its side _ pertaining
to NHL participation in the 2002 Olympics at Salt Lake City. Among
the sticking points: the IIHF's attempt to get the NHL to improve
transfer fees for young Europeans who make their way to the NHL _
even if they play junior or college hockey. The chance of making
huge money in North America, soon to sport 30 NHL teams, continues
to drain the European leagues . . . Vancouver GM Brian Burke
insists he has not initiated talks aimed at dealing Mark Messier.
However, he's left the door open for Messier to request a deal.
According to Burke, Messier hasn't asked out yet. One reason: The
Canucks have gone an impressive 7-3-2 (through Friday) since the
All-Star break, renewing playoff hopes. The Canucks have six games
in the 10 days leading up to the trade deadline. If they don't
collect, say, 8 or 9 of those 12 available points, it would be no
surprise to see the 39-year-old Messier ask for a last shot
somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Below-average idea
</P>
<P>
   The Lords of the Boards remain intrigued about expanding the
number of clubs eligible for the playoffs, possibly bumping it from
16 to 20. Not a good idea, at least not from the look of the recent
standings. Both the Rangers and Penguins are holding postseason
berths with below-.500 records . . . NHL look-alikes of the week:
Ex-Bruin Craig Billington, still backing up for the Capitals, and
Woody, the lovable cowboy from ``Toy Story'' in the Disney on Ice
tour . . . Anyone else feel that the curtain closed on the Bruins'
season with Tuesday night's 5-3 loss to the Senators? . . .
Hurricane Gary Roberts is one of the more interesting players
headed for unrestricted free agency July 1. Among the game's
nastiest forwards, Roberts, even at 34 years old, likely will draw
significant interest. Given how the market was discounted late last
summer, however, it's doubtful Roberts will get the $2.5 million he
is making this season. Carolina's Sean Hill and Paul Coffey also
will be unrestricted as of July 1. Hill, only 30, has the right to
walk because he's now in his 10th season and is making $750,000,
well below the $1.4 million average . . . Lost in this car wreck of
a Bruins season has been the exemplary play of Don Sweeney. Nearly
as lost: The fact that Sweeney, making $1.2 million, can walk as an
unrestricted free agent July 1 . . . Agent Jay Fee said he has been
given permission by Oilers boss Glen Sather to look for a suitor
for right wing Alex Selivanov, the streaky scorer who was red-hot
in October. Selivanov is also the son-in-law of ex-Bruin Phil
Esposito, once his boss in Tampa Bay . . . Boston University's Mike
Eruzione was invited to the Penguins-Rangers game in Manhattan Feb.
22, 20 years after the Yanks defeated Mother Russia in the '80
Olympics at Lake Placid. By and large, MSG gave Eruzione and some
of his pals from the squad, including ex-Terrier Dave Silk, a
hero's welcome. But Ken Morrow, who won four Cups with the
Islanders, was heckled with the standard chorus of boos reserved
for all Islanders. ``Kenny knew that was going to happen,'' said
Eruzione. ``At one point he said to me, `I'm just glad I'm not
(Denis) Potvin.' '' . . . Nice building in Los Angeles, the Staples
Center, but players generally consider it to have the worst ice
surface in the NHL. For all the millions spent on these
state-of-the-art buildings (read: cash cows), you'd think they
could master the art of freezing water. They seem to do a fine job
of filling those $3.50 soft drinks with decent ice . . . Look for
the Coyotes to be sold this week to a California-based construction
company, Ellman. Word is that Wayne Gretzky was offered the chance
to buy up to 35 percent in the venture but the Great One passed on
the shot . . . They take traffic laws seriously in Canada. To wit:
Darius Kasparaitis recently was written up for jaywalking in
Calgary (he was hailing a cab), and initially refused the ticket.
His tone changed when the cop tossed him in the cruiser and asked
to see his work visa or passport. On a personal note: Your faithful
puck chronicler, hurrying to get to a news conference during the
'88 Olympics at Calgary, was pulled over by one of Calgary's
finest. ``You're not from Canada, are you?'' he said, as I rolled
down the window of my rental. ``In Canada, we wear seat belts.''
Buckled up, I drove along _ safe, sound, and late for the briefing
. . . For the record: Yes, Donald Brashear, who switched
effortlessly from English to French during his news briefing
Monday, was able to speak French before Marty McSorley cracked him
in the head . . . Good guy Roger Neilson, coach of the Flyers, is
expected to undergo a stem cell transplant, perhaps as early as
Monday, for treatment of multiple myeloma (bone marrow cancer). In
the meantime, ex-Bruin Wayne Cashman and Mike Stothers will serve
as assistants under interim coach Craig Ramsay. Earliest possible
return for Neilson: mid April . . . Lou Nanne, the ex-North Stars
general manager who shoveled Brad Palmer and Dave Donnelly to the
Bruins in 1982 _ compensation for the Bruins selecting Gord Kluzak
first in the draft instead of Brian Bellows _ needs surgery for
prostate cancer. Nanne, 59, is being treated by the same Mayo
Clinic doctor who helped golfing legend Arnold Palmer . . . Look
for the Sabres to move potential power forward Michal Grosek in the
next few days. Grosek, 6 feet 2 inches and about 210 pounds, has
the skill to be a 60- or 70-point scorer, but this is his seventh
season and he has lacked the day-to-day determination to get the
job done. Transplant Peca's transmission into Grosek and you've got
something . . . Hmm, life after Ray Bourque. It had to happen
sometime. And there's nothing wrong with Bourque moving on. Just
wondering, if he wins the Cup elsewhere, will he pull off his new
sweater _ a la Phil Esposito night _ and reveal another with the
spoked B on the chest?
</P>
</TEXT>
