<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTE-PITINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO PICTURE NOT TOTALLY INACCURATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a grain of truth to what Rick Pitino said last
Wednesday night. We're quick to find the negative here in just
about anything.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where politics, sports, and revenge rule the day, we
can dissect anything to find the most depressing element. Maybe it
wasn't the best idea to put a football stadium on the South Boston
waterfront. But it was dead on arrival the moment it came out of
Bob Kraft's mouth, as much as anything because of the way Kraft
haplessly handled the situation. Maybe there isn't taxpayer support
for using public money to build a new Fenway Park. But we haven't
even heard what the Red Sox will want and people already are saying
no.
</P>
<P>
   It almost seems everyone here has to have a say. Proposals don't
move quickly, as they do elsewhere, but at a glacial pace. How long
did it take to build the FleetCenter? The new convention center?
</P>
<P>
   In sports, our Calvinist leanings have conditioned us to expect
the negative, especially with the Red Sox. The only team that
didn't meet our lower expectations over all those years was the
Celtics. They won. Maybe that's why their current plight is so
upsetting.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the weather. We're in a lovely springlike weekend,
but how many of us wonder when the next snowstorm will arrive?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Top cat
</P>
<P>
   The race for No. 1 is over. Unless, of course, the Bulls
(crafty) or the Clippers (clueless) get the top pick in the 2000
draft. Anything goes in those cases. But Cincinnati's Kenyon Martin
put on a virtuoso performance Thursday night against DePaul,
cementing his stand as the top player in the land. In front of 18
NBA scouts, including Celtics general manager Chris Wallace, Martin
was a monster. He had 33 points, 21 in the second half, and 10 in
the final 3 1/2 minutes. The 6-foot-8-inch forward, best described
as a Bo Outlaw-type with offense, also had 9 rebounds, 2 blocks, 2
steals, and the first 3-pointer of his career. ``He was the
favorite going in unless someone else was going to draft strictly
for need,'' Wallace said. ``Even though it's still early, with the
NCAAs and the camps still ahead, I think the league would
unanimously agree that this kid is the best prospect.'' Now, if the
Bulls get the No. 1 pick, they may go elsewhere because Martin is
projected to be a power forward and Chicago seems safe with Elton
Brand. The Clippers? Who knows? It was a veritable cornucopia for
GMs at the game. Not only did they get to see Martin, they also saw
Cincinnati freshman DeMarr Johnson, who many feel is a lock to come
out because he has had the NBA on his screen since the age of 10.
Another possibility for the draft is DePaul sophomore Quentin
Richardson, who toyed with the idea of coming out last year . . .
After delivering his usual quota of one-liners regarding Pitino's
rant, Kevin McHale offered the following: ``The hardest thing to
have in this league is patience. It's a Nintendo league. We'll play
four or five pretty good games and I'll think, `All right.' Then
we'll play a couple of games and I'll be there saying, `What was
that?' Then I step back and look at the whole thing and say, `I
guess we're getting better.' '' . . . John Starks wants a shot at
another ring and he's willing to pay for it. Starks offered to
forfeit the remainder of his $4 million salary so he could go to
Miami or New York. The rub is this: Any player waived after March 1
who signs elsewhere is ineligible for the playoffs. So, not only
does Starks want the Bulls to release him (which, under normal
circumstances, would make the Bulls liable for the money) but also
to have it done retroactive to March 1. Not surprisingly, the union
supports Starks, while the league says there's nothing in the
collective bargaining agreement to support it. The matter went to
arbitration and Starks lost . . . You're going to start hearing a
lot of talk about Pitino going elsewhere. He denies it and says he
intends to stick around. But the relationship with chairman of the
board Paul Gaston is strained and no one would be surprised if the
two came to an agreement on a parting . . . And this from Antoine
Walker: ``I think we've got to stay with the nucleus we have and
add a piece or two. We can't keep adding five or six new players
and have players jumping ship at the end of the year, because that
will just kill us.'' . . . Lakers coach Phil Jackson said last
Tuesday's game in Portland represented the biggest regular-season
game he's been involved in since he left college 33 years ago. The
Lakers won and are the team to beat. ``We're still getting
better,'' said Robert Horry in a sobering assessment. ``Now that we
have the trade deadline behind us, guys can relax and play loose.
We just need to stay positive and strong.'' And healthy. The Lakers
still have a giant hole in the middle that could be critical in a
long series against Portland or San Antonio. But they also have
Shaquille O'Neal, who, as McHale noted, ``is playing the way
Orlando and Los Angeles hoped he could and the way we all feared he
could.'' Travis Knight was with O'Neal as a rookie and he's back
with him again. He says the arrival of Jackson is a factor in
Shaq's play, but the bigger reason is much simpler. ``He's
healthy,'' Knight said. ``That's the main thing.'' . . . Garry St.
Jean says he intends to stick around and coach the Warriors next
season. The only other applicant was Orson Bean.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Orlando magic
</P>
<P>
   Here's a lead you didn't expect to see in the Orlando Sentinel
in March: ``It's time to officially start the playoff chase.'' Yup,
the Magic are right on the heels of Detroit and Milwaukee _ and
ahead of the Celtics _ as they make their first appearance in
Boston Sunday afternoon. Orlando starts a stretch of seven straight
games against teams with losing records. Sunday's game marks Ron
Mercer's FleetCenter debut in a Magic uniform. Mercer told Orlando
reporters ``the hype is already gone'' about playing against his
old team. He's right. The only time we hear Mercer's name is when
Pitino says he couldn't afford to re-sign him . . . McHale on
Pitino's plea for veterans: ``They're critical. When we got (Terry)
Porter and (Sam) Mitchell in here, I sat down with them and I told
them the whole story. I laid it out for them. You empower guys like
that and you know what? That's one less thing for the coach to
worry about.'' That's typical of McHale's easy-come-easy-go
management style. ``He hires people to do jobs and gives them the
freedom to do it,'' GM/coach Flip Saunders said. ``He has a great
mind. He understands what he wants to do and boils things down to
simplicity. No one feels that they can't talk or say anything.
Kevin's never going to look down at anyone. Everyone understands
he's going to play his golf, do his fishing, and we've got people
in place when he does that to cover for him. He knows what he does
well. The things he doesn't do well, he gets people to do those
things.'' . . . Toronto coach Butch Carter keeps hoping
(fruitlessly?) that more legend-enhancing performances like last
Wednesday from Vince Carter will convince Tracy McGrady to stick
around. The skinny seems to indicate McGrady would prefer Orlando,
but the Raptors can pay him more than anyone and also have Carter
as an undeniable lure. ``We need to create an atmosphere where we
win, where Tracy will say, `I like it here, I like the guys. I want
to stay,' '' Coach Carter said. ``Tracy's not a bad guy. We've
grown together, we've been here since Day One. The only time it
gets tough is when we don't talk. I've told him I don't want to
read about his problems in the paper or hear them from other
players. Right now, the challenge is to keep him out there at the
end of close games because he's still not a very good free throw
shooter. It's a challenge for me to give him a chance to fail at
the end of a game.'' . . . Speaking of free throws, longtime
bricklayer Eric Montross went to the line last Wednesday for the
first time this season and tried jump shots. He still missed both.
Montross went into the weekend having played 188 minutes for
Detroit, spread out over 28 games. That's about seven minutes a
game . . . Retired Numbers Dept.: The Mavericks retired Rolando
Blackman's No. 22. He joins Brad Davis as the only Maverick to have
his number retired. (What, no Bill Garnett?) Meanwhile, the Harlem
Globetrotters will retire a uniform for the first time in their
74-year history when Wilt Chamberlain's No. 13 is put on permanent
display at Chamberlain's high school, Overbrook in Philadelphia.
Chamberlain began his pro career with the Globetrotters in 1958,
playing one season. In one of the last interviews before his death
last Oct. 12, Chamberlain called that year one of the most
enjoyable of his career . . . On a recent stop in Charlotte, Tim
Duncan was asked if he thought there was any way a team from the
Eastern Conference could win the NBA title. ``I don't see it
happening,'' Duncan said. ``The West is incredibly strong, one
through eight. I'm sure there are some good teams in the East, but
I just don't see it happening. This may come back to haunt me, but
I don't see how.'' Neither does anyone else . . . The Knicks'
victory over Milwaukee Thursday night marked the first time in six
years they swept the Bucks in a season series. Not only that, the
Knicks trailed by 10 points or more in all four games . . . How bad
was Indiana's 31-point drubbing in Phoenix Thursday? Larry Bird
said it was the worst game he'd seen in three years on the Indy
bench. (There also was a 31-point loss to Detroit in his first
season.) To give you an idea of how the game went, the Indiana
coaching staff had the Pacers down, 29-0, in fast-break points. The
Pacers are on a brief, three-game Western swing that concludes
Sunday night in Golden State. The Pacers are 26-2 at home but have
a losing record on the road. In fact, no Eastern Conference team
has a winning record on the road. Miami is 5-15 heading into
Sunday's biggie with the Lakers. In the West, the Lakers and
Blazers are 14 games over .500 on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
