<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-GAMACHE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALES TIPPED AGAINST GAMACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The aftermath of Joey Gamache's last fight lingered on this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Seven days after he was knocked unconscious in two rounds by an
opponent who outweighed him by 19 pounds, his head continued to
pound and he was scheduled to revisit a New York neurologist.
</P>
<P>
   But medical concerns are not the only thing bothering the junior
welterweight from Maine. He has retained an attorney and may sue
the New York State Athletic Commission, claiming it failed to
ensure that his opponent, Arturo Gatti, ever weighed the 141 pounds
that was announced at the weigh-in the night before their fight at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scales never balanced,'' Johnny Bos, Gamache's manager,
insisted Friday. ``Gatti stepped on and the arrow went up and never
came down and he jumped off and started drinking water and they
called out 141. What was I supposed to do then?''
</P>
<P>
   What Bos could have done was insist that Gatti get back on the
scale until the arrow balanced. Bos says he did but a commission
official told him to forget about it because Gatti had made the
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran trainer Teddy Atlas theorized last week that Gatti
perhaps did not gain 19 pounds in 36 hours but may have already
been several pounds heavier than 141 when he got on those scales.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do in that case is say, `He gets back on the scale or
there's no fight,' '' Atlas said.
</P>
<P>
   Bos was faced with that question Friday and responded in the way
those on the outside edges of the sport often do. He said he and
Gamache had little choice but to accept the commission's handling
of the situation, although now Gamache is threatening to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time the arrow on the scale moved from the top was
when Gatti threw up his hands,'' Bos now claims. ``Then it bounced.
I complained, but we had three options: Demand he weigh in again
and give him two hours to make weight if he couldn't do it then,
prove he was overweight and negotiate for more money, or refuse to
fight. Joey had already said this fight wasn't about the money, so
he wouldn't do that. The commission refused to reweigh him, so
what's left?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pull out, they pull Joey's license and he can never
fight again and I'm not in much of a better position, either. So
what can you do? I didn't know Gatti was 160 until we were walking
toward the ring and a guy from HBO told us. What do I do then? Turn
around and go back to the dressing room?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, what you do is sue after the fact. Gamache may have
a case of negligence by the commission or he may not. Certainly
proving it will be as difficult as trying to make a conspiracy
argument based on the refusal of Gatti's people originally to agree
to a weight of 145 or 146, which would have made it easier for him
to make but only if he in fact ever intended to make 141 in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Charging conspiracy or negligence is one thing. Proving it is
quite another. If in fact Bos and Gamache were concerned about how
the weigh-in was conducted, the time to raise the issue was then.
If the commission refuses to put Gatti back on the scale, then you
walk out and take your chances.
</P>
<P>
   Bos and Gamache say they didn't do that because they didn't want
to threaten their futures. Fact is, nothing threatened Gamache's
future more than walking into that ring a week ago to face a
power-punching opponent carrying 19 more pounds of ammo than he
had.
</P>
<P>
   Bos and Gamache were worried that walking out on that fight
might result in a loss of license and an end to his career. As
things turned out, walking in is what did it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No odd couple reunion
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Felix Trinidad was set to face World Boxing
Association junior middleweight champion David Reid Friday night,
he lost an even bigger fight with Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks the two have sparred more over the terms of a rematch
contract than they did during the 12 rounds of their first fight.
Both sides had agreed long ago to evenly split $40 million in purse
money, and the push was on this week to tie the entire deal into a
two-fight contract _ one fight in June and another in September.
But one issue hung them up: weight.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya finally pulled out Monday and ordered his promoter,
Bob Arum, to make a deal with undefeated former lightweight
champion Shane Mosley for a June 10 or June 17 fight. The deal, all
sides say, is done, with Mosley collecting $5 million and De La
Hoya the same $20 million he would have gotten for Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage, though, is all with De La Hoya. Despite Mosley's
great speed and skill, he will be the little man in the ring.
Although both may weigh 147, Mosley is a lightweight masquerading
as a welterweight, and once he gets hit, he will learn what that
means. If he can survive that shock and continue to use his skills,
it could be an interesting night, but De La Hoya has sparred with
him many times and believes he knows what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sparred a lot in LA,'' someone close to De La Hoya said.
``Oscar admits Shane is quicker than he is. But every time they
sparred, once he landed a few punches Shane started running. That's
what he still believes will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's right, De La Hoya made the best business move of his
career by telling Trinidad that if he wants to fight at 154, go
find someone his own size to do it with.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   World Boxing Organization heavyweight champion Vitali Klitschko
faces once-dangerous Razor Ruddock April 1 in Berlin in an effort
to force his name into the big-time heavyweight picture. The
6-foot-8-inch Klitschko will be making his third title defense
while Ruddock will try to show he has something left of what made
him a household name in two losses to Mike Tyson. This will be
Ruddock's first title shot in 18 years of boxing. After being off
three years, Ruddock has won eight straight fights under the
careful matchmaking of Mike Acri and is now 36-5-1 with 28 KOs.
What Ruddock will bring to Berlin is a big name. Whether he still
has a big punch is suspect . . . Beginning next month, the New York
Athletic Commission will no longer allow standing-8 counts. The
theory is that if a boxer has sustained enough punishment to
receive a standing 8, he's received enough to be asked to sit down
. . . America Presents CEO Mat Tinley has bought the long-term
commercial rights to Golden Gloves boxing and hopes to return the
tournament to past glories. He hired Jon Franklin, a former
executive with IMG, to market the event, and Fox will televise the
finals on May 14, delayed a week from the May 7 event in Detroit at
Joe Louis Arena . . . In case you were wondering why Julio Cesar
Chavez didn't appear as scheduled on the Reid-Trinidad card, the
reason was an old one. They paid him some money in advance. Chavez
was supposed to fight a meaningless opponent in hopes of
positioning himself for one last title fight vs. World Boxing
Council junior welterweight champion Kostya Tszyu. But, as he has
often done in the past, Chavez demanded his pay be increased the
week of the fight and Don King refused, so Chavez stayed in Mexico,
claiming he had a bad ankle . . . Riddick Bowe's claim that brain
damage caused him to kidnap his estranged wife and children got him
a big win and a big loss. Bowe avoided a lengthy jail sentence in
North Carolina, receiving only 30 days and an order that he seek
treatment for his brain injuries. But that claim also cut off any
chance Bowe had of getting back into the ring. The 32-year-old Bowe
had started to train again in hopes of regaining the heavyweight
title he once held, but Marc Ratner of the Nevada commission said,
``A claim of brain damage like that would have to be taken
seriously into account if he applied for a license in Nevada. I
would doubt Riddick would be allowed to fight again.'' . . . IBF
junior middleweight champion Fernando Vargas has hired Washington
Redskins conditioning coach John Philbem to prepare him for his
April 15 showdown with Ike Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local bleatings
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea heavyweight John Ruiz was in Las Vegas for a photo shoot
with Evander Holyfield last week to publicize their May 20 showdown
. . . Ruiz's representatives will also attend a WBA meeting seeking
to have Lennox Lewis stripped of that title for fighting Michael
Grant instead of Ruiz. If they are successful, Ruiz-Holyfield will
be for the WBA title. Don't count on it . . . Lowell's Micky Ward
travels to London next weekend to take on World Boxing Union junior
welterweight champion Shea Neary (22-0, 17 KOs) underneath Prince
Naseem Hamed-Vuyani Bungyu on HBO. If Ward can pull off the upset,
he could get into the big-money picture.
</P>
</TEXT>
