<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS RIVALRY REVIVAL FINE WITH CAMPO
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be the ultimate insult, but first, there has to be
validity attached to a story that goes this way:
</P>
<P>
   Little Danny Snyder, boy owner of the Redskins, successfully
scammed Jerry Jones when the Cowboys traded for and signed receiver
Joey Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Although Washington had minimal, if any, interest in Galloway,
the Redskins drove up the price by deceiving Jones into believing
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Redskins coach Norv Turner said on Friday.
``We wanted Joey Galloway, except not at the price the Cowboys
paid, with the two No. 1s and all that money. Jerry wasn't going to
let us get Galloway. He needed Galloway at that position more than
we did, and Jerry got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Aw, shoot. The other version makes for a better story, and also
adds credence to the theory that Snyder wants to reopen those old
wounds which once made Cowboys-Redskins a storied rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, now that part of it, you might be on to something,''
Turner added, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   A national publication recently listed Jones vs. Snyder as a
budding NFL owners' feud worth watching for potential fireworks. At
the moment, however, it's more about Snyder seemingly being
obsessed with advancing the Redskins to the prominence the Cowboys
have always known, even with the latest slippage on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, of course, has to be honored that anyone still takes his
Cowboys seriously enough to want to start a feud. And particularly
the owner of the Redskins, a team that can be listed as the early
favorite to win the next Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, of course, knows both participants very well. If his
current boss and his former boss are headed for feudville, Norv is
going to be involved in the football part and nothing else. That's
just the Turner personality.
</P>
<P>
   But Dave Campo, the new Cowboys coach, was almost overcome with
glee on Friday when discussing the possibility of Cowboys-Redskins
and Jones-Snyder turning a bit nasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to be a little excitable anyway, and that wasn't going
to change,'' Campo said. `But something like this is just what we
need, the Redskins need, the NFC East needs. I do ``want'' a big
rivalry with the Redskins again. Let's get that stirred up.''
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to a Chan Gailey, Campo brings a feisty personality
to the head-coaching post, and he promises to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two areas where I hope to have an impact,'' he said.
``I come from the defensive side, but I want my input as far as
offensive philosophy. The head coach has to be able to game manage
on both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, I will put a big emphasis into the motivational
areas. I'm not one of those guys who thinks since the players are
pros they don't need motivating. Some don't; those are the
self-starters. Then there are those you couldn't motivate with a
stick of dynamite. But somewhere in the middle, I feel there's
always a group you can reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, Campo added: ``The way it once was, nobody ever worried
about motivation when the Cowboys played the Redskins. Those are
the best kind of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Campo was an honored guest at a banquet in his
native Connecticut. But most of the ceremony that evening was to
recognize the New York Yankees as the team of the century. ``I'm
sitting there watching this film of the old Yankees right up to
their current team, and suddenly it hit me,'' Campo said. ``I got a
knot in my chest. The film was on the Yankees, but I'm thinking
about the Cowboys. The Cowboys are the only other team in the world
as well-known as the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would a Dan Snyder be coming after us? Because we're the
Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, however, appears to now be holding the superior football
hand. He was heavily irritated at losing both games to the Cowboys
last season, but the Redskins had a better overall record and
should prosper greatly in the April draft. Through trades,
Washington has the second and third picks in the first round, and
will probably add an impact linebacker and offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   If the Redskins don't take a receiver with either pick, and
Turner says they won't, then that might confirm their not having
had a large interest in trading for Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Campo has off-season defensive worries after the big
splash in adding Galloway. ``We have to get some things done on
defense, but come draft day I'm still going to be very happy with
our No. 1 pick,'' he said, meaning, of course, Joey.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the bonus for Campo would come next fall if the
Cowboys-Redskins rivalry has been stirred by an eager Snyder.
``Wouldn't that be fun,'' he added, sounding like a coach willing
to help Danny boy in getting the process started. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 2136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000304.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTE-GRIER-BOS     03-04 2626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTE-GRIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY STILL OUT ON GRIER AND HIS PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gil Brandt, the architect of five world championships with the
Dallas Cowboys, rated the Patriots' 1999 draft the fifth-best in
the NFL, based on the percentage of players who made rosters and
how many games they started.
</P>
<P>
   Many folks around here might disagree with Brandt. Some might
think Bobby Grier's draft was closer to fifth-worst than
fifth-best. But the reality is, people like Brandt respect Grier's
work.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Patriots rookies had a total of 30 starts, most of
them accounted for by Damien Woody and Andy Katzenmoyer. Only the
Browns (83), Eagles (48), and Redskins (32) had more. Brandt rates
the drafts of the Browns, Eagles, Colts, and Bears ahead of New
England's.
</P>
<P>
   If Grier's drafts in '97 and '98 were considered poor, he came
back strong last year _ at least according to Brandt, who by the
way is a friend of Bill Belichick _ though not strong enough for
Grier to keep his power. He no longer has the final call on
selections, but according to Belichick, Grier will be very much
involved in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Will he set up the draft board?
</P>
<P>
   Likely, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Will he make the selections?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a meeting I have scheduled coming up in the near
future,'' said Belichick. ``We haven't gone over some of the
specifics. We've talked about some of the things we want to do in
the draft generally, but we haven't talked specifically. Bobby has
addressed it but we haven't talked about that yet. He may have the
answer to that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has certainly gone out of his way to indicate that
Grier is still a big part of the front office. How long that lasts
remains to be seen. Can the guy who used to be in charge coexist
with the person who is now in charge? Usually, those situations
don't work out. It may come down to how long Grier can tolerate his
new role. After all, the Patriots also have in-house former Jets
pro personnel man Scott Pioli, who was handpicked by Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've been the general, it's hard to be a soldier again.
This was the crux of Bill Parcells's beef with Bob Kraft when the
owner put Grier in charge of personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby and I have worked together for a year (1996) and we had
a good relationship,'' said Belichick. ``I think it'll go fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were whispers at the scouting combine last week in
Indianapolis that Grier would stay on through the draft (April
15-16) and then be ``on the bubble.'' Those same whispers indicated
that Pioli, despite having a title of assistant director of player
personnel, may already have more power than Grier.
</P>
<P>
   While many have condemned Grier's draft choices the past three
years, Belichick said those players are going to have a chance to
play significant roles.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Floyd could be the starting fullback; Rod Rutledge will at
least split time with Eric Bjornson at tight end; Tebucky Jones
will get a chance to start at cornerback; Tony George and/or Chris
Carter will play free safety; Tony Simmons will get ample time at
receiver; Sean Morey will be in the mix more; Michael Bishop will
be introduced into the offense; Derrick Fletcher will get a crash
course on left guard with the idea that he'll start; Brandon
Mitchell will be a starting defensive lineman, inside or out;
Katzenmoyer will start at outside linebacker, Woody will stay at
center, and Ed Ellis may be forced into a tackle spot.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean all of these players will perform at a high
level, but we will get a better indication of Grier's eye for
talent when his players are actually playing. Grier stated at the
end of last season that the young players didn't play enough, which
was interpreted as a dig at Pete Carroll. Time will determine
whether Grier was right, and with the Patriots having so little
room to work with under the salary cap, Belichick will have to use
those players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll get great opportunities,'' said Belichick. ``Sometimes
it's hard to evaluate a player in a different system. They'll get a
good opportunity to see what they can do. I don't know if starting
is a big thing but they can create a substantial role for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier will always be known for selecting Chris Canty and Jones
with first-round picks. But he also selected Woody, Katzenmoyer,
Robert Edwards, and Terry Glenn with first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   Grier has declined interviews, but he defended his picks late
last season when he said, ``The picks haven't made an impact?
That's not true. When we've needed a guy to step in and start,
we've produced those players. Robert Edwards stepped in and played.
We needed and played Damien Woody at the toughest position. Andy
Katzenmoyer moved inside and played and (Kevin) Faulk has played.
People ask about Chris Canty and whether he's a bust. Personally, I
don't think he was. What got Chris Canty in trouble here was his
personal life and off-the-field stuff. He was the 29th pick, which
is basically the top of second round. He was supposed to be a
nickel and dime guy for us after we had signed Steve Israel to be
our starter. Chris is in Seattle playing very well as a nickel and
dime guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished they would have played more because you build your
team through the draft and you supplement your team with free
agents. Because of the salary cap and free agency, you have to play
the picks to see if they are what you think. You play them because
you have to find out whether they can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier's wish may come true. Carroll may have been afraid to play
young players because he felt his job was on the line, but
Belichick shouldn't be. He'll play them often in preseason, seeing
who is and who isn't a player. He'll also bring in another two or
three veterans to push the young guys.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Grier has been drafting players based
on Carroll's coaching style and philosophy. Now he's going to
recommend players based on Belichick's style.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go in any direction,'' said Belichick. ``We need help
at every position.''
</P>
<P>
   As for moving up into the first round, perhaps by trading a
package of picks, the coach said, ``I think it's possible, but that
would probably only happen on draft day. If we saw a player we
wanted that we could reach by making a trade, we'd try to do it,
but that's so hard to predict. I could see us trading up to that
spot. How likely? Probably below 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had to give up their No. 1 pick to the Jets for
Belichick, but because of free agents they lost, they do have four
supplemental picks to work with.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're all invited
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has written to all players about showing up for the
March 15 kickoff meeting for the strength and conditioning program
but has not heard back from any players who have other plans. ``I
would expect all the players to be here,'' he said. ``I've written
to all of them. I haven't heard back from anyone, but it doesn't
mean I won't between now and two weeks from now. If someone has a
conflict or a problem, we can talk about it.'' Asked about Ty Law,
who usually takes part in Bob Kersee's program, Belichick said,
``I'm sure Ty will be here.'' Glenn also will be there on the 15th
. . . Belichick will have a camp April 29-30 for rookies and other
invitees; his first official minicamp will be at the end of May.
He'll also have two ``get-togethers'' with players in May to ``do
some things in groups'' rather than having a full-squad mini-camp,
to which he's entitled as a first-year coach . . . Mike Shanahan's
proposal for a ``soft cap,'' under which teams would count only 50
percent of salaries for players with 10-plus years, has not
received much support from owners or commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
Perhaps owners should reconsider. Successful coaches like Shanahan,
Parcells, Joe Gibbs, and Bill Walsh understand the importance of
having older players on a team. Shanahan won two Super Bowls with
older players because they, in Parcells's words, ``get it.'' But in
this era when about 10 players per team get the big money and the
rest are just fill-ins, the older players are getting chopped off
rosters. Asked prior to the Super Bowl about a ``soft cap,''
Tagliabue said, ``Well, you know, I asked a number of people about
their reaction to it, and not to be too flip because Mike's got a
lot of good ideas, but I think the overwhelming reaction was that
it was for the birds and that we're not going to get into
exceptions to our salary cap.'' The Patriots have been hurt by this
trend of older players leaving. It used to be that a Bruce
Armstrong could keep younger players in line, that a Ben Coates
could offer great insight to the tight ends and receivers. Said a
former Patriot, ``I remember when Sam Gash walked into that locker
room and he heard garbage pouring out of younger guys' mouths he'd
say, `Shut the (expletive) up,' and not one guy would utter a word.
As soon as Sam and Curtis (Martin) left, it wasn't the same. These
guys kept other guys in line.'' . . . At the combine, the Patriots
spent a lot of time with Miami of Ohio's Travis Prentice, a big,
powerful running back. His stock is rising but the Patriots may be
able to get him by Round 3 . . . The Cowboys may make a run at
Coates, which would be ironic since it was Ernie Zampese's system
that was blamed for Coates's lack of production last year. Zampese
is now a consultant in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going for Gogan
</P>
<P>
   When guard Kevin Gogan was cut by the Dolphins, Troy Aikman
called Cowboys owner Jerry Jones to see if they'd consider signing
Gogan, who is a close friend of the quarterback's. Gogan played
left guard with the Dolphins, but at 35 the only position he can
play is his natural right guard spot . . . The Berlin Thunder of
NFL Europe named Westwood native and former Holy Cross head coach
Peter Vaas, 47, their head coach. Vaas spent two years under Jack
Bicknell in Barcelona. ``I'm very excited about being a head coach
again,'' said Vaas. ``Berlin offers an exciting opportunity because
it's only been in existence for a year. We have a chance to
establish football in Berlin.'' Vaas, a 1974 Holy Cross graduate,
spent four years as the Crusaders' head coach and had stints at the
University of New Hampshire and Allegheny College . . . Jack Mula
is getting more involved in contract negotiations for the Patriots.
Like Green Bay's Andrew Brandt and Oakland's Bruce Allen, he is an
ex-agent who brings a unique perspective to the job. Brandt and
Mula, both formerly of Woolf Associates in Boston, have taken on
other football operations and administrative duties. Having dealt
with players on the other side of the fence appears to make a big
difference . . . An NFL offensive line coach calls Alabama's Chris
Samuels the only ``sure thing'' in the draft among offensive
linemen. The coach said others are a tad risky and teams must do
their homework to see which players would be best-suited for their
specific schemes and system . . . The combine is an exercise in
numbers, most of which don't mean a whole lot once the players make
it to the NFL. But here are this year's winners. Strongest:
Texas-El Paso defensive lineman Leif Larsen, who set a combine
record by bench-pressing 250 pounds 45 times. Fastest receivers:
Southern Cal's R. Jay Soward and Texas A&AMP;M's Chris Cole, who ran
the 40 in 4.35. Fastest running back: Arizona's Trung Canidate, who
ran a 4.39. Fastest defensive lineman: Virginia Tech's John
Engelberger, with a 4.65. Fastest linebacker: New Mexico's Brian
Urlacher, who ran a 4.6. Fastest defensive backs: Wake Forest's
Reggie Austin and Oklahoma's William Bartee, who ran a 4.4. Fastest
quarterback: Hofstra's Giovanni Carmazzi, at 4.7. Biggest player:
Oklahoma offensive tackle Stockar McDougle, at 6 feet 5 1/2 inches,
361 pounds . . . There's no question the trend is toward bigger
tight ends. As coordinators spread out offenses and utilize four
wide receivers, you see the tight end being used more to block than
to receive. Miami's Bubba Franks, at 6-6, 265 pounds, will likely
be the first tight end taken in the draft, and there's a great
chance he'll go to the Jets. The Jets may look to package their two
first-rounders and move higher rather than pay first-round money to
two players.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doing their share
</P>
<P>
   Interesting mechanism in place in the NFL, as the league and its
31 teams all share in the payment of $2.4 million to the state of
Connecticut for costs incurred in the ill-fated attempt to lure the
Patriots, who bowed out of a $380 million stadium deal. Methinks
the Patriots likely paid out more than the Cincinnati Bengals . . .
There must be something more to Bishop not playing in NFL Europe
than the confusion of a different system. Most quarterbacks who
play in NFL Europe have to play in different systems. Bishop didn't
want to go to Europe from the beginning, and it appears he got his
way . . . The next step in a new contract for Drew Bledsoe might be
a Leigh Steinberg-Robert Kraft meeting. Steinberg is looking for a
new deal that would include a signing bonus in the $15 million-$20
million range. It's either that or take the $8.66 million hit on
the salary cap this year . . . Press the button when you're excited
by the following list of free agents the Patriots have brought
through Foxborough: DE Tim Morabito, DE Bobby Hamilton, DT Shane
Burton, LB Jim Schwantz, LB Marcus Buckley, CB Robert Bailey, WR
Leslie Shepherd . . . There's a good chance Armstrong will end up
playing in his hometown of Miami. He's been there for a physical,
and it certainly doesn't hurt that former Patriots offensive line
coach Paul Boudreau is there. There seems little chance of the
Dolphins paying incumbent Richmond Webb the $4.1 million he is due
as a franchise player. The Dolphins will likely seek a deal for
Webb. Armstrong once said of Boudreau, ``I learned more from him
than any coach I've ever played for.'' . . . Carroll may be
involved in an Internet pregame show, breaking down the top five
games of the week in terms of coaching strategy, decisions, etc.
His attorney, Harry Manion, is putting the deal together. ``Pete
wants to do more than just be an analyst,'' said Manion. ``He loves
computers and wants to get involved in that end of things.'' . . .
He wasn't a high-profile player, but Marty Moore, who is now a
Cleveland Brown, was one of those guys who understood the game and
played it with every ounce of blood and guts he had . . . Good
draft talk on Patriots.com Wednesdays from 12-1 p.m. with CBS
Sportsline draft guru Frank Coyle and Patriots Football Weekly
editor Bryan Morry and writer Paul Perillo . . . Former Patriot
offensive lineman Scott Rehberg, a 13-game starter with the Browns
last year who was ripped for not playing in a Nov. 28 game because
of the flu, went to NFL hell for that sin, signing a two-year deal
with the Bengals . . . The Houston Texans, the Houston Apollos, the
Houston Stallions, the Houston Wildcatters, the Houston Bobcats _
they're all finalists for the new Houston franchise's nickname. Any
of them roll off the tongue like, say, the Houston Oilers? . . .
The Saints actually cut some ticket prices for end zone and
``terrace'' seats, but elevated the price of the better seats. The
Saints were last in the league in ticket sales, selling only 73
percent of the Superdome . . . Bicknell's Barcelona defense in NFL
Europe will be fun to watch with Patriots linebacker Marc Megna and
former South Carolina State defensive end Chartric Darby, a 6-foot,
275-pound terror. Though he is considered undersized, Darby may
wind up on an NFL roster when teams get a chance to watch him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
