</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-CLARKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARKE A CHAMP OF LIGHTHEARTERD APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long after his impressive victory over David Duval in the
semifinals of the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship last
Saturday, Darren Clarke was simply trying to savor the moment when
a thought occurred to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What time tomorrow?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The final match against Tiger Woods, he was told, would start at
7:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why so early?'' asked Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because, Darren,'' said his manager, Andrew ``Chubby''
Chandler, ``the final is 36 holes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just one of a handful of exchanges that brought levity to
a sport that sometimes forgets to factor in human elements. More
and more players are becoming so deadly serious _ what with purses
so outrageous _ that they can't play a good round without wondering
how to make it better, or play a bad round without wondering
whether they'll ever play well again, or play at all without
wondering whether their pants are perfectly creased.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Clarke, who readily conceded that Woods was the best
player in the world, though it wouldn't stop him from showing up.
Though he had played beautifully to dispatch five opponents _
including Ryder Cuppers Duval, Mark O'Meara, and Hal Sutton _
Clarke spent his press conference following the semifinals talking
about his physical appearance. It is, he conceded, not in the mold
of Woods or Duval, arguably leaders of the new breed that believes
the key to great golf is a fine-tuned body.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys keep trying to get me to the gym,'' kidded Clarke,
when asked if he would have the stamina for the 36-hole finale. His
weight has been reported at between 245 and 260 pounds, and
Chandler, himself a former pro, said there is concern, but not
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not fit, but he's strong,'' said Chandler. ``He could
stand to lose 20 pounds, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect that to come from pumping iron, a la Duval, who
lifts before or after his round, depending on tee time. There's a
simple reason why Clarke avoids weights. They are heavy, he said.
And besides, he lifted during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``My right arm is stronger than my left,'' he said, indicating
he had raised many a Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Which should make Clarke a hero to the majority of the golfing
population. Particularly since he proved in the final that the
promise many held out for him was justified. The big guy can play _
and have fun at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   At the 13th hole of his match with Woods, Clarke had a 6-footer
for birdie, a putt he figured to hole. He missed it, and Woods,
standing well to the back of the green, was slow to offer the
concession par.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Clarke knocked in the putt, then turned and said
something to Woods, who laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Are we playing medal?' '' Clarke later revealed.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked what he would do with the $1 million prize, there
wasn't even a hint of hesitation. ``Spend it,'' said Clarke, who
has a widely publicized passion for fast cars and expensive cigars,
which he smokes while playing.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the result that put Clarke in a good frame of mind; he
was lighthearted from the start. On the driving range at 7 a.m.,
Clarke didn't get much attention from his swing coach, Butch
Harmon, who was occupied with his main student, Woods. ``That's OK,
Butch,'' Clarke yelled down to Harmon, ``I'm fine. I don't need
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Harmon had to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Clarke's approach is the only way to tackle competition
against Woods. Keep it light. Keep it simple. Keep it in
perspective. Clarke said he had to play his best and hope Woods
didn't play his best, which is the truth. It's also what happened.
</P>
<P>
   The result did nothing to convince anyone that Woods isn't the
best player in the world. It did everything to remind us that the
game's foundation is still intact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tiger factor
</P>
<P>
   PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem, during an informal gathering
with reporters at the Match Play, touched upon a variety of
subjects, among them TV ratings that have been quite impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a ratings-driven sport,'' said Finchem, ``but good
ratings are awful sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Finchem isn't naive; he knows the key ingredient is Woods. It
was Woods's stretch duel with Ernie Els at the Mercedes that
established a cable TV ratings record for golf, and it was Woods's
chase for a seventh straight win that enabled the Buick
Invitational to score higher in the ratings than the NBA All-Star
Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lift he is generating is by getting more and more eyeballs
on the TV,'' said Finchem.
</P>
<P>
   How big a lift, said the commissioner, is ``hard to quantify,
but what is pleasing is that when he hasn't played, the tournaments
have held up well.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour is reaping benefits of a huge TV pact negotiated
not long after Woods's historic victory at the Masters in 1997, and
talks will open next summer on a new contract, said Finchem.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the World Golf Championships events, they remain a
somewhat contrived bunch, though certainly a presence:
</P>
<P>
   --Andersen Consulting Match Play. Finchem conceded that next
year's event in Australia may not get all Top 64 players. It's a
long way to go for such a format, and the timing (first week of
January) is not attractive. ``Either they go or they don't go,''
said Finchem. ``We won't entice them.''
</P>
<P>
   --NEC Invitational. A mess, thanks to a stubborn Ken Schofield,
Finchem's counterpart with the European Tour. The eligibility, as
drawn up two years ago, was simple: the most recent Ryder Cup and
Presidents Cup players made it. Schofield, in an effort to keep his
stars on European soil, is threatening to change the eligibility to
the Top 12 players on the Order of Merit. Since 1999 Ryder Cuppers
such as Jesper Parnevik, Sergio Garcia, Paul Lawrie, and Jean Van
de Velde will play a lot in the United States, chances are they
won't qualify. Schofield could be headed for a showdown he may
regret.
</P>
<P>
   --American Express Championship. It's set for Valderrama, Spain,
again this year, though the date moves up a month to September,
which will please US players who wanted their Tour Championship to
remain the season's finale. Next year, the event comes to the
United States (site to be determined), but will not conflict with
the Ryder Cup at The Belfry. It will probably head to Ireland for
2002.
</P>
<P>
   --EMC World Cup. It will be played in December in Buenos Aires.
There will be two-man teams playing foursomes and four-ball, and
the top-ranked player in each country will qualify and get to
choose his partner (the early guess is that Duval accepts Woods's
offer).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arnie's guest list
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Baddeley, the Australian teenager who surprised by winning
his country's Open championship last November, will have a pretty
good event at which to tune up for his Masters debut: the Bay Hill
Invitational. Baddeley, 18, accepted a sponsor's exemption into
Arnold Palmer's little gathering in two weeks. Sponsor's exemptions
also went to, among others, Gary Nicklaus, Irishman Padraig
Harrington, Billy Andrade, Peter Jacobsen, Curtis Strange, and
Casey Martin. Martin was an interesting selection since Palmer was
among those who testified for the PGA Tour in its court fight
against Martin's request for a cart. Martin put up his best
performance last week in Tucson, finishing T-17, and is 115th on
the money list with $51,015 . . . John Daly has signed a
sponsorship agreement with SoBe Beverages, a South Beach (Miami)
company that produces herbally enhanced refreshments. Its slogan?
``Grip it and sip it.'' But these ``wellness beverages'' aren't
exactly the kind Daly has been known to embrace, though for
goodness sakes perhaps he should try them. The deal was announced
Thursday, after which Daly shot 79 at Doral on a day that 44
players broke 70. He has entered five tournaments in 2000 and the
linescore reads as if there are still some problems: one WD, three
MCs, T-72 . . . The Massachusetts Golf Association's spring
conference will be Thursday at the Westin Copley Place. For
information, call 781-449-3000 . . . A roast to pay tribute to Jack
Burke Jr. was held the other night in Houston, and the legendary
player/instructor/golf course owner went toe-to-toe with an
impressive list of dignitaries _ Steve Elkington, Phil Mickelson,
and Sutton among them _ who were more than happy to challenge him
to barbs. About one of the roasters, Ben Crenshaw, Burke said:
``Ben cried on the 18th green when he won the Masters and he's been
a water hazard ever since.'' Widely considered one of the great
putting instructors around, Burke has tutored Mickelson for the
past year, and the lefthander related a story told to him by Billy
Ray Brown: ``Billy said he missed his first putt, and Jackie came
over and whapped him on the side of the head. And Jackie said,
`Son, I want you to feel pain when you miss a putt.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
