<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7010 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BO     03-04 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT SURE LOOKS LIKE BOURQUE IS GONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Bourque is about to go, his skates not packed, his ticket
not punched, but his days in the Hub at an end nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   How do we know this? Only by appearance. Bourque refused to
speak to the media following the Bruins' 3-0 loss to the Flyers
Saturday at the Vault, the second straight day he has remained mum
on the subject of moving. Some 45 minutes after the game ended, he
walked hurriedly through the dressing room, shaking his head, and
offering only a terse, ``Sorry, guys,'' as he headed for the door.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, flanked by a couple of Fleet security guards,
Bourque was ushered past the third-floor press room, afforded safe
passage to his car. It had that ``Baby Doc departs Haiti in
Mercedes'' feel to it.
</P>
<P>
   These are strange times on Causeway Street, even stranger than
usual. Bourque is leaving, but he continues to play on for a club
that most nights and afternoons is grossly overmatched by the
opposition. While Boston president/general manager Harry Sinden
collects offers from Cup challengers far and wide, the 39-year-old
captain continues to take his spot on the backline and shoot and
skate as if it's just another day on the job, albeit 21 years
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as professional as can be,'' said winger Ken Belanger,
who was one of the four other Boston skaters on the ice with
Bourque for the closing seconds of Saturday's loss. ``Before the
game, after the game, he didn't say anything about what's going on
with him. I think, more than anything, he didn't want any
distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Any hour now, the hockey world expects Bourque to be swapped to
a club like the Flyers or Red Wings. How strange that will be from
a Boston perspective. It would be like waking up one day and
finding out that the Swan Boats had been sold to a Florida theme
park. What if Arthur Fiedler hadn't put down the baton while with
the Pops, and surfaced in Boise leading a barbershop quartet?
</P>
<P>
   Bourque in Detroit, a winged wheel masking his spoked B? What
next, someone covering the Golden Dome with Day-Glo orange?
</P>
<P>
   There were no fewer than 19 NHL scouts, representing 13 teams,
at the Vault for what might have been Bourque's last game in Black
'n' Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to Columbus,'' kidded Doug MacLean, general
manager of the expansion Blue Jackets, who open for business in the
fall. ``I can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   If the crowd was thinking this could be Bourque's Causeway
serenade, they certainly didn't shake down the thunder for the
aging icon. Only two seats beyond where Bourque sits on the Boston
bench, a fan occasionally held up a small sign that read, ``Good
Luck, Ray, Wherever You Play.'' In the closing seconds, another
fan, standing just behind the glass near head coach Pat Burns, held
up another cardboard testimony, ``NO RAY. NO PAT. NO FAN.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, the crowd called little attention to what could
have been a landmark game. When the final horn blew at 4:04 p.m.,
few noticed Bourque skate over to an on-ice official and ask for
the puck. Absent flair or even so much as a nostalgic final glance
over his shoulder, he hopped off the ice near the Boston bench and
made the penguin-like waddle down the hall with the rest of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to discuss it,'' said veteran blue liner Don
Sweeney, reluctant to speculate over where Bourque's trails may
lead him now. ``It brings up feelings that obviously haven't been
addressed. It brings up words like if and when and if ever . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something, if it happens, I'd prefer to address then.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston dressing room, remarkably, was hauntingly quiet. The
TV was off. There wasn't a CD pumping through the speakers. While a
crowd of some 40 reporters and photographers waited patiently for
Bourque to appear from his shower and shave, three ceiling fans
whirred, a hum almost audible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about it,'' said netminder Rob Tallas.
``Obviously, we've read a little and, hey, if it happens, it
happens. I can tell you it would be a sad day for a lot of
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Sunday's noon workout in Wilmington, the Bruins return
to Causeway Street Monday night to face the Senators. If he hasn't
been dealt by then, Bourque will be expected back on the blue line
for another night (Adieu, Part Deux) that could be his last with
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds strange, doesn't it, keeping the future former
Bruin in uniform? Given the awkwardness of the situation, and given
how the Bruins are now out of the playoffs _ spiritually, at least
_ it could make sense for Bourque to ask out of the lineup while
Mssrs. Sinden and O'Connell work the phones. If come March 14 they
still haven't found a suitable trade partner (highly unlikely),
they then could let Bourque play out the string here.
</P>
<P>
   In those final seconds Saturday, Tallas stood in net and Bourque
was paired on defense with Darren Van Impe. Up front, Shawn Bates
centered Steve Heinze and Belanger. The stands were half-empty when
the horn blew. There was the usual smattering of applause and the
standard obligatory booing, the latter all too familiar in recent
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   No. 77, puck tucked away for posterity, silently made his way to
the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sad,'' said Belanger, standing just outside an area that
is off-limits to the media, only feet from where Bourque reportedly
was signing pucks for teammates. ``But at the same time, I'm happy
for whatever decision he makes. The Stanley Cup is hard to win. And
if anyone deserves it, it's Ray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 2141EST &QL; 
