<HEADLINE>
WHEELS OF FORTUNE SPIN AT LAS VEGAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Las Vegas oddsmakers have installed NASCAR Winston Cup Series
champion Dale Jarrett as a 9-2 shot to win Sunday's CarsDirect.com
400 at Las Vegas Motor Speedway. Bobby Labonte, the winner of last
week's race at Rockingham, N.C., is 6-1, Jeff Gordon 5-1, Rusty
Wallace 12-1, and Dale Earnhardt 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   You want a long shot? Try Darrell Waltrip at 300-1.
</P>
<P>
   The smart money would be on Roush Racing's Mark Martin (7-2) and
Jeff Burton (9-2). They are the only two drivers _ both behind the
wheel of a Ford Taurus _ who have won a Winston Cup race at the 1
1/2-mile Las Vegas track. Martin won the inaugural event two years
ago, beating Burton, who won last year's Las Vegas 400 ahead of
older brother Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think it's one of the best racetracks we go to,''
said Jeff Burton, who finished second to Jarrett in the Daytona 500
but had a subpar effort at Rockingham, dropping him to 14th in the
standings. ``It is a racetrack where you saw last year with Ward
and me racing that will provide an opportunity for some great
side-by-side racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a racetrack like that, there's really no excuse
in having cautions. We ought to be able to race each other really
clean. There's enough room to do it. There's enough different
grooves to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ward had the better car for the majority of the race last
year, Jeff wound up pulling it out in the final 20 laps. Jeff took
the lead with 10 to go and withstood a furious charge from Ward. It
was the first of six victories for Jeff Burton, three at the
expense of Ward, who finished runner-up at Las Vegas, the Pepsi
Southern 500 in Darlington, S.C., and the Pop Secret 400 in
Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can certainly enjoy it, but it does have a negative sense
to it in a way,'' Jeff Burton said. ``I don't think I enjoy winning
races as much when I beat Ward as I do when we're beating somebody
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the emotion of that was it was an early win for us, it was
the earliest we had ever won a race since I'd been at Roush Racing,
and it felt good to get that win behind us. We had gone to
Rockingham the week before and run well (starting second and
finishing fourth) and then we came (to Las Vegas) and won. It was
just a really good start to the year for us after a terrible
Daytona start (35th place).
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, having to beat Ward, you felt great that you won the
race, but you felt bad that you beat your brother. That's the only
way I know how to describe it. I take a lot of pride in being able
to say that, even though it is Ward, I still tried as hard as I
could try and didn't try any harder because it was Ward or didn't
try any less because it was Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, it was just another car, but it is difficult
when you have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next test awaits
</P>
<P>
   While there was much hubbub over NASCAR's new shock/spring rule
at Daytona and how it favored the redesigned Ford Taurus over the
new Chevrolet Monte Carlo and the unchanged Pontiac Grand Prix,
Labonte's victory in the Dura-Lube/Kmart 400 last week at
Rockingham showed that GM may not be lagging that far behind the
Fords, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's victory in his Joe Gibbs Racing Pontiac, which vaulted
him to second in the standings behind Jarrett, led a GM sweep of
the first four spots, which was quite a departure from Daytona,
where Fords took the top five spots. To their credit, NASCAR
officials resisted the repeated complaints of GM drivers and owners
to implement aerodynamic changes, saying they needed to collect
more data on the track and in the wind tunnel before taking any
drastic measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that Chevrolet has not been up to our standard is not
true,'' Jeff Burton said. ``They struggled down at Daytona, but
that's because they built too much drag in their car. That's the
same thing we did down there three years ago. We're coming here (to
Las Vegas) to race and to win and so I don't worry about the whole
Ford-Pontiac-Chevrolet issue a whole lot, other than I think a lot
of people should look at the facts and not make presumptions on
just one or two races.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chevys really complained at Daytona, and rightfully so,
but at the same time we knew that going to Rockingham they'd be
awfully tough, and they were.''
</P>
<P>
   While Daytona and Rockingham are vastly different tracks that
yielded inconclusive evidence, NASCAR officials will be watching
the performance of the GM cars vs. Ford at Las Vegas, which is
similar to many of the 21 other venues on the circuit with its 1
1/2-mile span and 12-degree banking in the corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what NASCAR is going to be looking at real
hard,'' said Martin. ``They've taken some cars to the wind tunnel
already, and they've heard everybody complaining and arguing about
who has what and telling them what to do about it. But it looked to
me like Rockingham was a pretty good race. NASCAR might change some
rules before too long, but right now all we can do is race what
we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crash course
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart has certainly experienced his share of ups and
downs at Las Vegas. In his first Indy Racing League event four
years ago, Stewart suffered severe hip injuries from a crash. He
returned in 1997 and wound up clinching the IRL championship. Last
year, in his Winston Cup rookie season, Stewart crashed again, but
wound up 36th. ``Obviously the high was winning the IRL
championship at the last race of the year in '97,'' Stewart said.
``The low definitely would've been in '96 in the first IRL race we
ever had out there. I had the worst crash I've had in 21 years of
racing. It was something that I didn't have any control over and
couldn't have predicted that it would happen. There was no warning.
The tire just went. I hit the wall backward at about 215 miles per
hour. That was a painful experience. Vegas has just been one of
those places that's either been really good or really bad. I either
wreck there or win a championship. It's a place where we haven't
found a happy medium yet.'' . . . After he finished third at
Daytona, where he lost the lead on the last lap to eventual winner
Mike Wallace, Andy Houston captured his first victory of the season
in last weekend's NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series race at
Homestead-Miami Speedway . . . Barry Bodine, the 22-year-old son of
NASCAR veteran Geoffrey Bodine, climbed behind the wheel of the No.
15 Ford F-150 truck that his father demolished in a fiery 13-truck
crash at Daytona, and finished 13th. Said Barry, ``Dad's still not
feeling good; he's pretty sore. But he's feeling a lot better than
he did.'' The elder Bodine suffered a concussion and fractures to
his wrist, ankle, and a vertebra.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ready to roar
</P>
<P>
   Formula One teams wrapped up testing this week in Spain in
preparation for the season-opening Australian Grand Prix March 12
in Melbourne. The F1 circuit will make its first US stop in more
than a decade at the US Grand Prix Sept. 24 at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. In the final test session at Spain's Jerez circuit,
Jaguar-Cosworth R1 drivers Eddie Irvine and Johnny Herbert were
fastest, with Irvine turning a quick lap of 1 minute 23.2 seconds
and Herbert a tick off the pace at 1:23.3. Reigning F1 champion
Mika Hakkinen drove only on the first day, in the West
McLaren-Mercedes MP4-15, before turning over the test to teammate
David Coulthard and test/reserve driver Olivier Panis, who drove
all three days of testing and was seventh at 1:23.9, a hair quicker
than Coulthard (1:24.0) . . . When he won CART's inaugural US 500
in 1996, which went head-to-head with the Indy 500 after CART and
the IRL split, Jimmy Vasser was defiant in victory, quaffing
champaigne while saying, ``Who needs milk?,'' a reference to the
Victory Lane tradition at the fabled Brickyard. It seems Vasser has
changed his tune now that car owner Chip Ganassi has announced
plans to field entries for Vasser and Juan Montoya, the reigning
CART champion, at Indy this May. ``I'm looking forward to the
competition, for sure,'' said Vasser, who has competed in four Indy
500s (1992-95) and recorded his best effort in 1994, finishing
fourth. ``I really enjoyed all the races I had here before. It's
still the Indianapolis 500, and it's something I want to add to my
credentials as a race win.'' In his last race at Indy, Vasser was
dueling Scott Pruett for the lead when he made contact with the
wall on Lap 170, forcing him to retire in 22d place. ``I remember
clearly the last lap I ran here at Indianapolis, I led,'' he said.
``And then I ended up in the fence. It was great racing. That
moment was the springboard for what was to come for me in 1996 and
the coming years. To think that was five years ago seems unreal.''
Team Target-Ganassi will test at Indy March 29. Though Montoya will
be listed as a rookie, he will not have to undergo the rookie
orientation program because of his previous experience on
high-speed ovals in CART. ``It doesn't matter to me if they make me
race in a school bus,'' said Montoya. ``I'm excited to finally see
the famous track that I've been watching on television since I was
5 years old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
