<HEADLINE>
FANS SQUARELY IN DEFENSEMAN'S CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask Bruins fans if Ray Bourque should be traded to a Stanley Cup
contender and they answer with a resounding no.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Philadelphia Flyers fans _ and there were plenty of them on
hand at the FleetCenter Saturday _ and it's a whole different
story.
</P>
<P>
   Of 25 fans polled between the second and third periods of the
Flyers' 3-0 win over the Bruins, 20 of them, or 80 percent, said a
trade shouldn't happen. Yet, if a trade was Bourque's request, they
felt it should be honored. The other 20 percent said yes. And all
but one was a Philly fan.
</P>
<P>
   Unscientific to be sure, but a pretty good sampling of just how
highly Bruins fandom thinks of Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Westphal of Winthrop, who roamed the corridors bedecked in
a Bourque jersey, was the only Bruins fan who thought Bourque
should be traded, but if it happened, he said, it would bring him
to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they should trade him,'' said Westphal. ``I love the
guy. He's put in hard years with us here, but I believe he deserves
a shot at the Cup. He definitely deserves it. If he leaves, though,
I'll be heartbroken. He's given so much of himself to the town, to
the team, and to the game. But he deserves the chance to win it
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling what other fans had to say.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Conches, 42, of Philadelphia: ``Absolutely not. It would be
like the Flyers trading Bobby Clarke or Eric Lindros. He is a
Boston Bruin and he should stay a Boston Bruin. I'd love to see him
with the Flyers, and if it happens, I'd be delighted, but I don't
think it would be right for the Bruins to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Pearson, 34, of Keene, N.H.: ``They should keep him. He's
been here a long time and he should end his career here. If it was
going to happen, it probably should have been done last year. I'd
hate to see him go, but if he does, I wish him the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken DiGuilio, 43, of Methuen: ``I'd hate to see him go, and I
hope it doesn't happen, but if it's a chance for him to get a ring,
well, maybe it's best for him. He deserves one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Jean, 35, of Pelham, N.H.: ``No, they shouldn't trade him.
If he requests it, maybe, but other than that, no way. He's a
legend here. This is his town and he belongs here. I'd be
disappointed if it happened, but I love Ray, and if it's a chance
for him to win a Cup, maybe it's best.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Schulman, 36, of Philadelphia: ``As a Flyers fan, they
should trade him. But only to Philadelphia. We'd only be renting
him for two months. After that, he'd be a free agent and could
return to Boston if he wanted. But at least he'd get a chance to
win a Stanley Cup. That's not going to happen with the Bruins.
Right now, we need puck-carrying defensemen and he'd fill that
role.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed DiMeo, 35, of Philadelphia: ``He's been in Boston so long
without winning and (Harry) Sinden owes it to him to give him a
shot at the Cup. I'd love to see him in a Philly uniform. We need
defensemen and he'd take a load off (Eric) Desjardins.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Plante, 30, of Attleboro: ``He came in a Bruin and I think he
wants to go out a Bruin. Detroit, though, not Philadelphia, has the
best shot. Either way, I hope it doesn't happen. I think he should
stay here in Boston, unless, of course, he asks to be traded.''
</P>
<P>
   Patty Canillas, of Everett: ``Should they trade him? No. But if
he wants to be traded to a contender, more power to him. I'd wish
him nothing but the best. I don't want to see him wear any other
uniform than what he's been wearing for more than 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Eva Aubin, of Biddeford, Maine: ``No way. No how. He's one of
the best players on the team and has been for so long. He shouldn't
leave this team. Sure, the Bruins need more offense, but he's a
fixture here. I think he's loyal and would never request a trade. I
think his roots here are more important to him than winning a
Stanley Cup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
