<HEADLINE>
EVERETT SHOWS HE'S EAGER TO PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The question of how Jimy Williams will deploy
Carl Everett in the Red Sox lineup won't be answered with any
certainty until sore-kneed Nomar Garciaparra is cleared to play in
exhibition games in another week or so.
</P>
<P>
   But Everett offered a pretty good reason why opponents can
expect to see him hitting third, with Garciaparra batting cleanup:
Nomar likes it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Nomar what he prefers and he basically said he likes
the 4 hole,'' Everett said. ``If he likes it there, that's fine
with me. It doesn't matter to me as long as the No. 1 and 2 guys
get on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett hit his first home run of the spring in Saturday's 7-1
win over the Minnesota Twins, a third-inning drive over the
right-center field fence with Trot Nixon aboard on a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing about 15 miles an hour,'' Everett said.
``I knew it was going out.''
</P>
<P>
   No one should have been surprised that Everett's home run came
on the first pitch he saw from Jason Ryan, a 24-year-old
righthander who came to the Twins from the Cubs in the Rick
Aguilera deal. Everett is a first-pitch hacker in the Garciaparra
mold.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Everett hit .466 (34 for 73) when swinging on the
first pitch, and 40 percent of his home runs (10 of 25) came on
first pitches. Lifetime, he's hitting .368 when first-pitch
swinging, with 18 home runs. Garciaparra batted .421 with 6 home
runs last year on first pitches (114 at-bats) and is .398/20 HR
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on the pitcher,'' he said. ``A lot of times I
take the first pitch. But if there are guys on base, I don't want
to fall behind in the count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to keep the pressure on the pitcher. If there's
somebody on base and they throw me a first-pitch strike, I'm going
to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett said he's feeling better than usual at this stage of
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing the ball, and I'm landing on time,'' he said. ``I
have a leg kick when I hit lefthanded, and right now I'm right on
time. I feel if the season started tomorrow, I'd be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who has been in big league camp with four teams, was
asked what he thought of the way the Sox run things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's similar to Houston,'' he said. ``It's nothing like it was
with the Mets and Marlins. The Mets and Marlins run boot camps.
You're tired in April and part of May. That's the downfall in those
camps. You did a lot of stuff. You're burned out in April. I
believe that's why those teams don't have success in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This camp allows you to be where you are. The responsibility
is on the player if you're out of shape. They're asking you to be
professional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
