<SLUG> BC-BKN-BRUINS-WEIRDGAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME SEEMED LIKE DISNEY ON ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday's Bruins game at the FleetCenter took on a surreal
quality. Everyone in the building was waiting for future Hall of
Famer Ray Bourque to switch jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   No, he didn't whip off an old Bruins sweater before the game to
reveal a new one underneath, as he did during Phil Esposito's
number-raising ceremony years ago. In those days of wine and roses
for the Bruins, Bourque, in deference to Espo, switched from No. 7
to No. 77. Sunday, there are just days of whine in Bruin country.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unnoticed was the fact that the Bruins were put to sleep
by Philadelphia, 3-0, for their third straight loss. These days the
Bruins should put a warning on all ticket stubs: ``Caution. This
game may impair the ability to drive or operate heavy machinery.
May cause drowsiness or dizziness.''
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing aspect of the first period was that the
scoreboard clock broke down. For a second, it even flashed
``Raptors 96, Celtics 94.'' The public address announcer had to
give updates on time remaining in the period. The period did not
even end with a buzzer, but with an announcement: ``Time has
expired.'' Seemingly so has the Bruins' season.
</P>
<P>
   It is a philosophical debate whether L'Affaire Bourque is
distracting the Bruins or whether the team is simply caught up in a
yearlong slide that cannot be stopped. Nevertheless, one thing is
certain: These are strange days on Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was on the ice during the final seconds and took a last,
desperate shot to avert the shutout.
</P>
<P>
   An official picked up the puck, and Bourque went over and took
it as a souvenir, possibly of his last game ever. A fan behind the
Bruins' net lifted a sign: ``No Ray, No Pat, No Fan.''
</P>
<P>
   It was right on the money. If you closed your eyes, you would
have sworn you were inside the First Union Center in Philadelphia.
The loudest chants were ``Let's Go Flyers.'' The grandest cheers
were after all three Philly goals. In the stands, there were more
Flyers jerseys than Bruins shirts.
</P>
<P>
   If all this had transpired in the old Garden, the building would
have collapsed in despair.
</P>
<P>
   So the soap opera continues for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year long something like this has been happening,'' said
defenseman Hal Gill.
</P>
<P>
   ``These trade rumors aren't the reason we lost. We're immune to
all that stuff by now. We had to take each day as it comes and play
each game, one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The players did not want to talk about the impending Bourque
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to speculate. I don't want to comment on the
situation,'' said Bourque's longtime teammate and fellow defenseman
Don Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support Ray in whatever he wants to do,'' said goalie Rob
Tallas. ``We're not out of the playoffs yet. We have to play hard
and focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque had very little to say. He kept the media waiting for
nearly an hour before making an appearance. Earlier, former
teammate and Flyers goalie coach Reggie Lemelin reportedly had
escorted Bourque's family out of the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   When Bourque appeared, he walked by the gaggle of minicams and
notebooks and with an embarrassed smile said, ``Sorry, guys.''
There would be no comment on this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player,'' said Gill. ``I hope that whatever
happens is the best for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he asks out, it's a personal decision. He has our respect
and I hope he does what's right for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
