<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BIGLEAGUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A TASTE OF THE BIGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ They wear the same uniform as Stan-o and Tek,
have a locker just like Sabes and Val, sign autographs just like
Pedro and Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not as many as Pedro and Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so they sign for Mom and Dad and any little kid just happy
to have anyone who looks like a Red Sox player sign their programs
and scrap paper.
</P>
<P>
   They are the players who are in their first big league camp,
here with the Red Sox, tasting the big league life for the first
time and hoping it won't be their last.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you not be nervous?'' said Paxton Crawford, a
righthanded pitcher from Plummerville, Ark., (pop. 500) who last
season pitched for Double A Trenton. ``There are 40-50 big leaguers
here and we're the new kids on the block.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Rick Riccobono was pitching in Lowell, his first
season of professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Riccobono, who is 20, is standing next to Crawford
when Pedro Martinez breezes into the clubhouse and extends his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `What's up, how you doin'?'' Crawford said. ``That
was real cool, that he came over and introduced himself to us.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Crawford, who goes by Pac-Man, P.C., or
Pac-Dog, pitched against Boston College. The next time he is
scheduled to pitch, the Yankees are in town. ``Man, I hate them
Yankees, I hate them with a passion,'' said Crawford, who has a
tattoo of a wildcat on his right biceps and another exotic design
above his left ankle. (``That one hurt a little bit.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the schedule, and lo and behold, it's the Yankees,''
he said. ``I'd love to face (Derek) Jeter and (Paul) O'Neill.''
</P>
<P>
   Any time a team places a player on its 40-man roster, he is
automatically eligible to be in big league camp. That's what
happened with Crawford. For Riccobono, a sixth-round draft pick out
of Commack (N.Y.) High School in 1998, it was in his contract that
he'd be invited.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rose thought Riccobono would be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I know I was,'' said Rose. ``I was with the guys that I'd
grown up watching on TV. I told him, `Get right in those drills,
take away the nervousness.' He said, `I'm not nervous.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember feeling like you just don't want to screw up a
drill while everybody's watching,'' Rose said. ``It's like your
biggest fear is to blunder the first time you're in front of
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Riccobono grew up about an hour's drive from Yankee Stadium.
Yes, he said, he was a Yankees fan. ``But I've seen the error of my
ways,'' he said. ``My blood is red.''
</P>
<P>
   Riccobono also pitched against Boston College on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous when I went out there because I've been
pitching BP against these guys for a week,'' he said. ``I'm here to
enjoy myself. I'm not going to make the team, so I'm not putting
pressure on myself. This is a great experience. I'm having fun with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first spring with the Seattle Mariners, Derek Lowe
pitched only one inning the entire exhibition schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I thought it would never end,'' he said. ``I pitched
against the Cubs, and I was trying so hard, I gave up five runs. I
thought I was terrible. I walked guys, hit guys. I walked a couple
of guys on four straight pitches. I felt like running up the white
flag. `Come get me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The new kids, they're usually here to be seen and not heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play golf,'' Lowe said, ``but nobody ever asked
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanley's first camp was with the Texas Rangers, who at the
time trained in Pompano Beach, Fla. Stanley grew up in nearby Fort
Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I got to stay at home,'' he said. ``Things happened
real fast. I didn't stay long. I hit a home run off John Cerutti,
who was with Toronto. I remind him every time I see him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys didn't say boo to you. You were a rookie. Veterans didn't
talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck says he was lucky. When he attended his first camp with
the Giants, after going 18-5 the year before, veterans Jeff
Brantley and Dave Righetti schooled him in the big league life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took me under their wing,'' Beck said. ``You're trying to
make the club, it's nails from Day 1. They knew I was closing in on
their job, and they still helped me. That's why I think it's my
responsibility to help someone else out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Sox batting coach Jim Rice said, talent dictates
whether a player is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the rookie, how good he is,'' Rice said. ``I
came up, Freddy (Lynn) came up. There was nothing slack about us.''
</P>
<P>
   From the time he was a walk-on at Florida, David Eckstein has
almost always been on a team inclined to ignore him at first. He's
short, for one thing, with electric blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like Bart Simpson,'' said one Sox official. ``I
thought he was one of the clubhouse kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But on each level he has played in the minors, Eckstein has hit
.300: .301 at Lowell, .306 in Sarasota, .313 in Trenton. This
season, he figures to start in Pawtucket, where he should remind
fans of another Sox second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've heard them call me Jeff Frye's little brother,''
Eckstein said. ``Bart? Hadn't heard that one before. That's
sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Eckstein agreed, you come into your first big league camp
hoping to make an impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be perfect on every play no matter where I'm
playing,'' he said. ``But there's just a great atmosphere here,
very professional. Everybody goes about their business. You can
tell everybody is intense and focused on one goal: winning the
World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   For the new guys, making the team comes before being fitted for
a ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I see guys like Juan Pena and say, `Wow, he's my
competition?' '' said Crawford. ``These guys are tough. But I think
I can hang with them. I hope I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
