<HEADLINE>
PITINO OPTIMISTIC DESPITE CIRCUMSTANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Sunday's game with Orlando at the FleetCenter
appeared to be a good opportunity for a Celtics victory. The Magic,
after all, already had told their fans to wait until next season.
</P>
<P>
   But the tables appear to be turned. Team Green is in the midst
of a four-game slide and its season is quickly disintegrating. At
27-31, Orlando is happy to be in fourth place because nobody
expected it to be there. The Magic are playing as if they have
little to lose. And, as a subplot to the game, they are led by Ron
Mercer, the former Celtic who was Rick Pitino's No. 1 draft pick
nearly three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino, though unhappy about the Celtics' 23-35 record,
continues to defend his young team, albeit not in the same language
he used after last Wednesday's 104-102 loss to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I do look at life through rose-colored glasses,'' said
Pitino, after Saturday's practice. ``I'm not down at all. I'm
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team is a little short on overall talent. And
we've got to enhance the talent by getting a good draft pick this
year and make a smart move. We have to bring in a wise veteran. And
we have to mature because we're very young.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lifestyle is to be upbeat and positive. Encourage people
rather than discourage them. I believe that's how you get the most
our of your basketball abilities. If they are encouraged. Those
1-point losses turn to 1-point victories. You can't let people get
down. You have to want players to want to come here. I'm just a
believer in the positive.''
</P>
<P>
   While he hopes Celtics fans will cut the team some slack, he
can't expect much sympathy from Mercer, who was the odd man out
last summer when the Celtics chose between the salary demands of
Mercer and Paul Pierce. Mercer, a free agent after this season,
wanted a commitment. Instead he was traded to Denver in a deal that
brought Eric Williams and Danny Fortson here.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer is averaging 14.5 points and 3.9 rebounds in 11 starts
for the Magic and is 34th in the league in overall minutes played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make a decision that Paul was better than Ron or
that Ron was better than Paul,'' said Pitino. ``It's just that at
the time we did not have the kind of money available that Ron
wanted. We had to make the best deal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitino was not surprised by his ejection Friday night by veteran
referee Joe Crawford, who also banished Antoine Walker in Boston' s
114-104 loss at Toronto. ``Antoine's was a lot quicker than mine
but I told (Walker) I deserved it a lot more than he did. There are
certain guys in the league _ referee-wise _ to whom you're not
going to say much. Young players, like the kind we have, are going
to have learn that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
