<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-REID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REID LEARNED HARD LESSON FROM TRINIDAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ After 15 fights, many boxers are still six-round
fighters. Friday night, so was David Reid.
</P>
<P>
   For that distance, the World Boxing Association super
welterweight champion was dominating undefeated welterweight
champion Felix Trinidad with his superior hand and foot speed. He
had knocked him down once with a perfect right hand to the chin and
twice more rattled his cage with similar punches. His jab was
landing and he was keeping his challenger at the distance he wanted
most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   And then he made a classic amateur's mistake, the kind you learn
around this time in your career one way or another. Against a great
champion, you learn it the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's tutorial began in the seventh round when he was knocked
flat by a crushing left hook that Trinidad had made available to
himself by spending much of the first six rounds cracking Reid in
the ribs with the same punch to bring his opponent's hands down.
Reid staggered back, his hands falling to his sides, and his body
going limp. A full second or more passed before he actually
collapsed, a delayed knockdown that did not bode well for his
senses.
</P>
<P>
   When he got up, Reid's right eyelid was sliced open and swelling
and his tongue hung out of his mouth, signs that he was in a
confusing place he had not been before. He was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, the fight belonged entirely to Trinidad, who
hammered out a unanimous decision after knocking Reid down three
more times in the 11th round and battering him to the head and body
as Reid tried frantically to land one more wild right that might
flatten out his learning curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was right on the money up to the sixth round,'' said Al
Mitchell, who has trained Reid since he was an amateur. ``He lost a
little focus after that. That's experience. Young athletes got a
tendency to get away from the program. This was his 15th fight. By
the time he gets to 20, he'll be a hell of a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, young Reid was a hell of a fighter Friday night
against Trinidad, who had more than twice as many knockouts (31) as
Reid had fights (15). It was in the boxing department that he came
up short for the first time since long before he won the 1996
Olympic gold medal in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to fight,'' said promoter Don King. ``He knocked Tito
down and nearly won the fight. When he got knocked down, he got
back up and fought. He ain't got no heart trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Reid did not, but his record fell to 15-1 _ while
Trinidad's swelled to 37-0 _ because he could not maintain his
mental control when his more experienced opponent refused to buckle
from early troubles and kept moving forward, crowding the young
champion and making him feel uncomfortable until he broke him down.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the rest was easy for Trinidad, who looked far
stronger and more powerful at 154 pounds than he had in defeating
Oscar De La Hoya to win two-thirds of the welterweight titles last
September at 147.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt close to victory (in the third round) but I couldn't
hit him with the shots to finish him,'' Reid said from behind
sunglasses that hid badly swollen eyes. ``I should have boxed more
but I decided to stay on the inside and bang with him. I learned he
was a little too slick for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started slow and I then let him dictate the pace when he
picked it up. I was in control for a while but then his experience
got me.''
</P>
<P>
   His experience and his fists, both of which tattooed Reid and
took away first his legs, then his reflexes, and finally his
senses. It was a process that began in the seventh round as
Trinidad moved closer and closer to his opponent, whacking him with
digging lefts to the body that took the legs from Reid over time
and then delivering powerful rights to the head, three of which
knocked him flat in a terrible 11th round so lopsided that one
judge gave it to Trinidad, 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think David got a little too comfortable, especially after
he knocked Trinidad down,'' Mitchell said. ``Up to the sixth round
he was perfect. He stopped throwing the jab. He stopped throwing
his right hand but Felix kept throwing his left.''
</P>
<P>
   That left tore Reid apart and tore loose the 154-pound title,
which will now allow Trinidad to vacate the welterweight
championships, one of which will go automatically to De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   The two had been negotiating for months about a June rematch but
arguments over what weight they would fight at persisted, and after
seeing how strong Trinidad was at 154, De La Hoya's concerns about
that clearly are justified. That is why he will fight
ex-lightweight champion Shane Mosley instead on June 10 or 17 while
Trinidad pursues another piece of the 154-pound title or moves up
again to 160.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the new super welterweight champion of the world,''
Trinidad said. ``I will be waiting for De La Hoya here.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be waiting for him just as he was for Reid after he got
knocked flat in that third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was down on the canvas, I felt when I got up it would
be over for David Reid,'' Trinidad said. ``If you don't get me
early, the fight is over. When I get up, I'm dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous to an inexperienced champion ahead of his time, and
just as dangerous to one with as much experience as himself: Oscar
De La Hoya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
