<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSIONALLY SPEAKING, IT WAS QUITE AN AT-BAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The at-bat of the 1999 Boston Red Sox season
belonged to a 27-year-old rookie named Brian Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this time, it was ``Brian Who?'' But by the night
of Aug. 16, Brian Daubach had established himself as a serious
major league hitter, the kind of guy you'd like to see up there in
a pressure circumstance. And with his team trailing the Oakland A's
_ its chief wild-card competition _ 5-3, the bases loaded and two
away in the ninth, this was a certified capital C, Clutch
situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland pitcher was hard-throwing Tim Worrell. Daubach had
faced him once before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was earlier in the season in a blowout situation,'' Daubach
recalls. ``He threw me a first-pitch changeup, and I hit it right
back to the box.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a spot like this, Daubach didn't expect to see anything
but a heater from Worrell. Bases loaded, game on the line, he
figured Worrell would stick with No. 1, clearly his signature
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 1. ``A changeup,'' says Daubach. ``Up and away.'' That
gave Daubach something to think about. Count: 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 2. Fastball. Another ball. Count: 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 3. ``Another fastball. I fouled it back.'' Count: 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 4. ``He threw me another fastball for a ball. I figured by
this time that with Nomar (Garciaparra) and the bases loaded behind
me I was going to see all fastballs.'' Count: 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 5. ``A fastball down and in. I gave it a good rip and I
almost killed (first base coach) Dave Jauss.'' Count: 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 6. ``Another fastball I fouled straight back.'' Count:
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 7. ``Another fastball, I was jammed a little bit, and I
fouled it back. The crowd was screaming so loud that (catcher A.J.)
Hinch couldn't hear Worrell locate the ball for him and he got a
late start. The ball could have been caught.'' Count: 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 8. ``He threw me another fastball, and I fouled it
straight back.'' Count: 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 9. ``He threw me another fastball and I turned on it. I
hit the ball as hard as I could. It was heading down the right
field line and I remember thinking, `Hit the pole!' so there
wouldn't be any doubt. The ball went past the pole, and the umpire
called it foul. I still think it was fair. I know it was close, but
I almost lost it. I was screaming, and Jauss said, `Just don't get
thrown out!' I had to compose myself, and I remember saying
something to Nomar along the lines of, `Should I win it, or do you
want to?' I'm not sure exactly what I said, but it was almost
arrogant. But I do remember that Nomar said, `Just do your job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pitch 10. ``After eight straight fastballs, he threw me a
changeup away. I love going the other way in Fenway (editor's note:
Daubach hit five off and four over the Wall last year), and I hit
it real high off the Wall. The first two runners scored easy, and I
mean Offy (Jose Offerman) was really flying. He was crossing the
plate by the time I pulled into second.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those transcendent baseball moments, and it capped
a phenomenal stretch that earned Daubach Player of the Week honors
(13 for 26, 15 RBIs, .522 on-base percentage, 1.077 slugging
percentage). It was not just a good at-bat, or even a quality
at-bat. It was a totally professional at-bat, one that sent
Daubach's clubhouse stock, already high, to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   ``At-bats like those are very special,'' points out John
Valentin. ``Because after a while they get very personal. You want
to win the battle. We use the term `battling,' and after you foul
off a guy's best pitches two or three times, it really is a
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer it goes,'' agrees Mike Stanley, ``it's mano-a-mano.
Your senses are sharpened. You're more aware. You're heightened.
You're more acute.''
</P>
<P>
   What distinguished this particular at-bat were Pitches 7, 9, and
10. Someone long ago said, ``I'd rather be lucky than good,'' and
Daubach should have been out on the pop foul. What happened two
pitches later was electrifying. Daubach crushed, absolutely
crushed, the ball. From the instant it left the bat, the only
question was fair/foul, not distance. After the game, scores of
fans seated in the foul pole area swore it should have been a
game-winning grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the other great element of his at-bat,'' says Stanley.
``After losing the home run he had to grab hold of his emotions and
get back to work. That's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   We've all seen long-count at-bats, and we've all seen just-foul
home runs, and if there's one thing we can usually count on it's
that the batter is finished. He has just had his best chance. But
Daubach calmed himself down, stepped into the box, and smacked that
changeup off the wall in left-center to win the game. He did not
lose his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   About that changeup . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``As a catcher,'' says Stanley, ``I can tell you that in a
situation like that you want to get beaten on your best pitch.
Worrell must have decided after that near home run he'd try to
trick him. But I can tell you he would have slept much better that
night if he had lost on a fastball, rather than that changeup. He
was probably kicking himself in the ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen practically can guarantee it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to get beat,'' says Saberhagen, veteran of
many such battles, ``you want it to be with your best pitch. You
tip your cap if he beats you, but you can accept it better.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that Daubach, a guy with fewer than 300 big
league at-bats at the time, was able to make the superb adjustment
from dealing with eight consecutive fastballs, the last of which he
had tattooed, to taking a surprise changeup to the opposite field
in a clutch situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' salutes Valentin, ``a job very well done.''
</P>
<P>
   The big hit cemented his status as a minor folk hero, and it
represented his peak moment of the season. Almost immediately
thereafter, he went into slump from which he didn't emerge until
the last week or so in the season. He did some damage in the
playoffs, and now, as he starts his second big league season,
Daubach wants to be looked at as just another legitimate big
leaguer, and not the cutesy career minor leaguer, the
frog-turned-prince.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to tell the story over and over, in every city,'' he
says. ``It got old. This year I want to talk about 2000, not the 10
years in the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, if he chooses, he can talk about the best Red Sox
at-bat of the 1999 season. He's entitled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-00 2152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
