<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7022 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a FLAGSTAFFTODRAWLINEON     03-04 1683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH
</HEADLINE>
 FLAGSTAFF TO DRAW LINE ON (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY KATHLEEN INGLEY 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  Editor's note: In the stormy debate
over growth, Valley residents could look north and south for
innovative ideas. Flagstaff is drawing growth boundaries, while
Pima County is creating a desert conservation plan. Today and
Monday, The Arizona Republic looks at each strategy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   (FLAGSTAFF) - Tired of seeing rooftops replace ponderosa pines,
Flagstaff residents are about to rope in development with an urban
growth boundary.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a preview of what's ahead for communities throughout
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``People very much care about hav ing a line between where
develop ment ends and nature starts,'' said Brad Ack of the
non-profit Grand Canyon Trust.
</P>
<P>
   The worry in this college town is the same as elsewhere in
Arizona: How to make sure growth doesn't destroy a region's special
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   In Flagstaff, that means clean moun tain air, dramatic views of
the San Francisco Peaks, a small-town at mosphere, easy access to
Northern Arizona University and quick get aways to the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great values of Flagstaff is, without getting into
a car, I can walk, jog or ride a bike and get onto the Forest
Service service roads with ease,'' said astronomer Nat White,
president of the board of Friends of Flagstaff's Future.
</P>
<P>
   A growth boundary would brake the city's outward expansion by
limiting where houses and businesses were built. That's a big step
in a state known for its freewheeling, roll-out-the-welcome-mat
approach to devel opment.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a key part of competing plans to manage the number of
people flocking to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull's Growing Smarter Plus, which the Legislature
passed last month, specifically allows cities to limit how far they
extend services at public expense.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial Citizens Growth Management Initiative,
expected to be on the Nov. 7 ballot, includes strict growth
boundaries for both cities and counties.
</P>
<P>
   The tide of people rolling into Arizona is expected to raise the
population by nearly 50 percent over the next two decades. That
means the Flagstaff area will be home to 104,000 people, up from
71,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for all those people, the city and Coconino County
have been working on a land-use and transportation plan for the
past two years. Growth boundaries are a central point in the draft,
which is going through each government's approval process.
</P>
<P>
   As the residents of the Flagstaff area are discovering, the
debate over growth boundaries revolves around difficult trade-offs,
increased housing density and higher home prices.
</P>
<P>
   LIMITS MEAN TRADE-OFFS
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff has actually had a version of growth boundaries for
years, limiting the elevation to which it would extend waterlines
at public expense.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan goes a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to protect our open space,'' Flagstaff project
manager Ursula Montano said, ``and do it at a regional level, with
a unified approach between the county and city.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth boundary is drawn to include all private land in the
city and has enough room for growth over the next 20 years. It
would be reviewed periodically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if it's something that's a brick wall around the
city,'' said Earle Hoyt, a retired chemistry professor who was on
the land-use task force.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalist Ack considers the boundaries far too generous.
He prefers leaving room for just 10 years of growth, the limit set
in the Citizens Growth Management Initia tive.
</P>
<P>
   A drive through Lockett Ranch shows what planners are trying to
avoid. This stretch of meadow at the foot of Mount Elden, just
outside the city limits, is being sold off in large lots for
upscale homes. The view of abrupt mountainsides is stunning, the
scent of pine enticing.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say Flagstaff has to get away from this type of
extremely low-density growth, with each home on 3 to 5 acres,
because it gobbles up a lot of land for relatively few people.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the region's 48,000 acres of private land are
already developed. Many fear that if the rest isn't developed
efficiently, there will be pressure to take land out of the
surrounding Coconino National For est.
</P>
<P>
   Ack said there's a seldom-discussed trade-off when development
moves to the urban fringe: ``You condemn some of your inner areas
to blight, which is crazy from the point of community interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sunnyside neighborhood in east Flagstaff is a prime example,
he says. A once-thriving shopping center is now half-empty behind a
vast ex panse of asphalt. Retailers such as Kmart bailed out and
moved to the growing edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   The urban growth boundary is de signed to direct development
back into the center of town, where roads, sewers and other
services are already in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In-fill'' is planning jargon for buq5$Nj kzn vacant or
underused lots within a town rather than on raw land at the edges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to protect surrounding open spaces, growth has to
be developed in in-fill areas,'' Flagstaff planner Montano said.
</P>
<P>
   That means places that Flagstaff residents are used to seeing
empty.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan Mesa has long been a bit of green breathing space, an
undevel oped strip separating east and west Flagstaff. Now, it's
proposed to become a mixed-use neighborhood, with both homes and
business es.DENSITY DILEMMA
</P>
<P>
   An even hotter issue than where the houses go is how many are
built on each acre.
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff residents are used to an open, rural pattern in many
parts of town. More than half the existing houses are single family
homes on relatively large lots, with no more than five homes per
acre.
</P>
<P>
   The new land-use plan would set minimum residential densities of
at least five homes per acre in many places.
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing out of the ordinary in Phoenix, where new
subdivisions are typically at that density, built on lots of 8,000
to 10,000 square feet or less.
</P>
<P>
   But for northern Arizona, ``I'm not keen on it at all,''
Flagstaff developer Dale Little said. ``It pretty much directs that
all future development within the town would be at much higher
densities than we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff planners, however, point out that the housing mix is
already changing. Only a third of the houses built in the past
decade fit the old low-density pattern, while 44 percent are
apartments and townhouses.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would put a mixed-use development in southeast
Flagstaff, right next to a ``county island,'' an unincorporated
area within the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what Flagstaff is all about, to have such density,''
said resident Betsy McKellar, who lives in that area.
</P>
<P>
   The lots there are 1-acre minimum, roads are unpaved and housing
styles are so eclectic that one yard includes a teepee. McKellar
can't imagine putting a slice of suburbia up against the back fence
of her neighbor, who has horses, ducks and a vast collection of old
silverware destined for offbeat artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, she said, is that the develop ment would be so close to
Walnut Canyon National Monument, where prehistoric archaeological
sites are tucked under limestone ledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canyon would be ruined, the wildlife would be driven off,
the place would be covered with graf fiti,'' said McKellar, who is
spokes woman for Friends of Walnut Canyon. The group is lobbying to
expand the boundaries of the monu ment, which would put it less
than a mile from the planned development.
</P>
<P>
   Planning officials disagree with such predictions and say
numbers don't tell the whole story. The minimum densities apply
only to larger parcels, when a rezoning is requested.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they say, trade-offs are inevita ble. The city has gone
north about as far as it can, and there's room to the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth has to be in somebody's neighborhood,'' said Bill
Towler, director of community development for Coconino County.
</P>
<P>
   It's logical, he added, to keep urban densities in the city,
which can support them. For its part, the county has drawn rural
growth boundaries, which basically take in all the unincorporated
private prop erty near Flagstaff. Those boundaries would make
little change in the pattern of development, except to highlight
the county's desire to pre serve public lands.RISING HOME PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Jean Richmond, executive vice presi dent of the Northern Arizona
Home Builders Association, says the den sity requirements should be
a city wide average, not applied to individual sites.
</P>
<P>
   She's concerned, too, that the limits and new requirements in
the pro posal, such as more master planning, would jack up the cost
of housing.
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff already has the typical housing crunch of a college
town. Only a third of residents can afford to buy a home at the
median price of $150,000, a price tag that is 25 percent higher
than in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond said Flagstaff parents worry that high home prices,
aggra vated by low wages, will drive their kids away.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Sandi Gilbertson, whose daughter moved
to Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, last fall, where comparable houses cost a
third less.
</P>
<P>
   With another daughter already in Idaho, Gilbertson and her
husband ended up making the move, too, so they can be near their
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The couple regretted leaving Flag staff, but there's an upside:
``We can buy the same house for a lot less money.''
</P>
<P>
   If prices and densities both go up, home buyers in Flagstaff may
have to settle for smaller lots or attached units.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a plus, if it's done well, astronomer White said.
He hopes an imaginative developer will do in-fill in ways that
preserve the small-town atmosphere: perhaps with apartments above
stores and ``clus ter'' developments where dense hous ing is offset
by open space.
</P>
<P>
   White and others in Flagstaff have settled for lower salaries
than they could get elsewhere in exchange for living closer to
nature in a small-town setting.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that a compactly built city, with a well-designed trail
system, will continue to make their sacrifice worthwhile.
</P>
</TEXT>
