r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      03-04 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY TAKES FIGHT TO MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, John McCain has been crusading against the
Republican Party establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the critical Super Tuesday presidential primaries
looming, the establishment is striking back.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders are taking the battle to him on dozens of fronts
simultaneously while promoting front-runner George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, McCain's GOP colleagues, once accused in the
media of waging a ``whisper campaign,'' are turning up the volume.
Senators such as Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., and Robert Bennett,
R-Utah, depict the Arizona Republican as a pugnacious,
``polarizing'' figure who undermines his effectiveness by taking
issues personally.
</P>
<P>
   One group of senators from both parties says it even had to
develop a strategy for handling McCain's occasional explosions:
stand right next to him and get in his face until he calms down.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, governors are recording telephone messages in
Bush's behalf to be played to thousands of their constituents. Some
of the chief executives say they are insulted by McCain's railing
against state GOP ``machines.''
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota Gov. Ed Schafer said he was so motivated to help
Bush and so put off by McCain that he grabbed a flight to Arizona
on short notice to attend McCain's home state's primary on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flew down commercially. I don't even know if the (Bush)
campaign is paying for it or not,'' Schafer, chairman of the
Republican Governors Association, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, `I'm a reformer,' '' Schafer said of McCain. ``But I
don't think his negativism or his fighting or his methods _
browbeating _ get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cities, mayors are tailoring specific anti-McCain
messages they hope will resonate with their voters. For example, in
New York, the mayors of Yonkers, Rome and other towns denounced the
Arizona senator last week for voting against aid to help the poor
pay heating bills.
</P>
<P>
   New York, California and Ohio are the key states in Tuesday's
primaries, in which more than half the 1,034 delegates needed to
win the GOP nomination will be at stake.
</P>
<P>
   WAKE-UP CALL FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Bush's alarm became particularly acute after McCain's surprise
victory in Michigan when it appeared that the combined clout of
various governors was not enough to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain's campaign was struggling going into the weekend
before Super Tuesday, he has been in this situation before and
managed to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has been trying, not always successfully, to
line up all of its establishment troops in coordinated strikes
against McCain.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only senators, governors and mayors who are
concentrating their fire on McCain. A wealthy Texas businessman,
who is a big Bush contributor, paid $2.5 million for political
commercials in California, Ohio and New York that attacked McCain's
environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the Arizona primary, Bush aides sent reporters
remarks from three Republican senators calling on McCain ``to stop
the smear campaign suggesting Gov. Bush is anti-Catholic.'' Bush
had come under criticism for delivering a speech at South
Carolina's Bob Jones University, which has attacked the Catholic
Church.
</P>
<P>
   One of the senators, Ohio Republican George Voinovich, was
quoted in Bush's e-mail as saying, ``This smear campaign is beneath
contempt and beyond comprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   But Voinovich never, in fact, made the comment. His aide, Mike
Dawson, said the quote was written by a Bush campaign staff member
with the expectation that the Ohio senator would sign off on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wish that things like that didn't happen,'' Dawson said.
``Campaigns are going at 500 miles per hour.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP ON DEFENSIVE?
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Shadegg, R-Ariz., a McCain backer, says the party's
brass is tripping over itself to try to oust McCain as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican establishment fell in love with and gave the
nomination to Governor Bush long before they determined whether he
was an electable national candidate and before they realized John
McCain might be a much more compelling candidate,'' Shadegg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once McCain became a clear threat to a Bush nomination, the
establishment was forced to aggressively oppose him to protect
their early endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   In an ironic way, all of the establishment's rhetoric against
McCain may actually help him.
</P>
<P>
   He has won votes by depicting himself as a principled insurgent
raging against the machine. What better way to demonstrate his
maverick, reformist credentials than by pointing to the army of
politicians lined up against him?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got all the establishment,'' McCain said in a Virginia
speech last week that he has repeated in various forms for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got all the governors, they've got the senators and
the Congress _ they got them all. And I've got all the foot
soldiers right here,'' he said. ``I'm telling you, we're just like
Luke Skywalker headed out of the Death Star. They're shooting at us
from every direction.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT BUYING THE MESSAGE
</P>
<P>
   But some of Bush's highest profile backers believe McCain's
populist appeals ring hollow. They say McCain unsuccessfully
pursued many of the same establishment figures who ultimately
endorsed the Texas governor instead.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for example, sought the backing last year of Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., who serves with the Arizonan on the Senate
Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Gorton privately told a group of amused lobbyists
that McCain blew up at him when Gorton said he was supporting Bush.
McCain aides, however, insisted that the conversation remained
civil.
</P>
<P>
   Montana Gov. Marc Racicot says he believes McCain adapted his
campaign theme to fit his lack of party support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This didn't become a `machine' that he could opportunistically
seek to take advantage of until such time as no one was supporting
him,'' said Racicot, who has endorsed Bush. ``At that point in
time, he began these populist themes and this notion of running
against the establishment and against machines. I suspect he would
have been delighted to have some of what he describes as machines
on his side.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shadegg said McCain is a real reformer. ``McCain scares the
establishment because he is more willing to shake up Washington and
make meaningful changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's most significant reform proposal would ban ``soft
money,'' the unregulated contributions that flow into the national
Republican and Democratic parties. Soft money is supposed to build
support for parties instead of specific candidates, but both
parties bent the rules during the 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As it always does, the Republican National Committee, which
might be considered the ultimate establishment group, is remaining
officially neutral in the GOP presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   But the RNC and McCain remain deeply split over the soft-money
issue, and that disagreement is a big reason why many committeemen
around the country won't back McCain.
</P>
<P>
   At its winter meeting earlier this year, the RNC endorsed a
resolution that said McCain's campaign finance proposal ``is a
scheme that amounts to unilateral disarmament by Republicans and
their allies while leaving the Democrats, unions and liberal
special interests untouched.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
