<HEADLINE>
THE NIGHT THAT BASEBALL
 LOST ITS A-PEEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'd last spoken to Dave Bresnahan in September 1987, shortly
after he'd been tossed out of professional baseball for publicly
displaying a sense of humor, an offense more heinous to league
officials than spewing racist screeds or snorting dope.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 137th game of a 140-game season in the Class AA
Eastern League. The Williamsport (Pa.) Bulls, for which Bresnahan
was a catcher, were playing the Reading Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been talking to a lot of guys about pulling the stunt,''
Bresnahan remembers. ``It was the end of a long season and I
figured, `What the heck?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bresnahan once starred in Phoenix for Gerard High School and
Grand Canyon University. By 1987, he'd been in the minor leagues
for three years and still hoped to get into the majors with an
expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   That steamy night in central Penn sylvania, Bresnahan placed a
peeled potato inside his spare glove in the Bull's dugout. In the
fourth inning, with a man on third and two out, the young catcher
reached a crossroads in his career. He had to decide:
</P>
<P>
   Tuber, or not tuber?
</P>
<P>
   One of Bresnahan's relatives, great-Uncle Roger Bresnahan, was a
Hall of Fame catcher credited with introducing shin guards. Young
Dave's boss would later tell the`` New York Times,'' ``I guess
ingenu ity is in the Bresnahan bloodlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Bresnahan told the umpire he had a problem with his glove and
needed to get a new one. Back behind the plate, Bresnahan slipped
the potato into his throwing hand.
</P>
<P>
   After catching the next pitch, Bres nahan reared up fired the
potato over the third baseman's head. It looked like a wild
pick-off play, causing the base runner to trot home. Bresnahan, who
had the real ball in his glove, casually tagged him out.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing a potato in left field, the fans went wild. Then the
umpires went wild, tossing Bresnahan from the game. Then the team
went wild, dropping him from the roster.
</P>
<P>
   `'That was it,'' he says. ``That was my last game as a pro.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after getting fired, Bresna han delivered a bag of
potatoes to his manager with a note reading, ``This spud's for
you.'' Then, he returned to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after John Rocker's sus pension for racist remarks
was re duced, and after multiple drug abuser Darryl Strawberry was
suspended but not banned from baseball, I contacted Bresnahan.
</P>
<P>
   Painful as it may be, I asked if he'd mind rehashing the past.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since AA ball, he's sold real estate and worked as
a stockbro ker. He's married and has three young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career allows me to spend lots of time with my family,'' he
says. He's coached high school and plays in an over-30 league,
which he calls ``an excuse to drink beer.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the potato play finally yielded some gravy. Bresnahan
was asked back to Williamsport for the 10-year anniversary. That
appearance led a Japanese TV show to invite him to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I'd have liked to be remembered for something
better, baseball-wise,'' he says, ``but it was fun. I enjoyed my
time in the game. It makes me sad to see talented guys like Rocker
do such dumb things.''
</P>
<P>
   He has season tickets to the Dia mondbacks. He coaches his own
kids in peewee ball. He likes his work, his life.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, he's been called a ``catch'' potato. And, yes, he's
aware that in the grand scheme things that he's small potatoes.
And, yes, it's been pointed out to him that he's a ``cleat'' and
potatoes kind of guy. And, no, it doesn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   The man has every right but, still, doesn't have a chip on his
shoulder. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
