<HEADLINE>
RICE'S SLUMP CAUSES LITTLE CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few weeks ago, a slump by one of the Lakers' top
players might have triggered widespread panic. But a 14-game
winning streak has all but obscured the fact that Glen Rice has
recently disappeared again.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has gone three straight games without scoring in double
figures -- a first in his 88-game Lakers career -- shooting 35.7
percent (10 for 28) from the field and averaging 8.3 points during
the slide.
</P>
<P>
   But the statistical dropoff coincides with wins over Portland,
Vancouver and Indiana, and a resurgence from the Lakers' bench. So
coach Phil Jackson isn't expressing much concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really looked at that from that point of view, I
haven't really taken that as the most challeging thing,'' Jackson
said. ``We feel kind of like, if teams want to occupy themselves to
just denying Glen the ability to touch the ball, it allows other
people to be open, and it gives us greater spacing to play our
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there's situations in the game where we need him to
score, but we haven't had that since the Portland game, when we
really wanted him to score some points for us in that game. They
did a good job (defending him), and Rick (Fox) got off and hit a
couple 3s for us. So we haven't really just been focusing on that.
... He's someone we can rely on, but yet it's not so critical for
us that we feel the loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq vs. 'Zo: Shaquille O'Neal's list of capable rivals is
dwindling, but today's opponent, Miami's Alonzo Mourning, is among
them. And for added spice, the two have a history of strong mutual
dislike. O 'Neal downplays any personal differences, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal, no,'' he said. ``But on the court, we're just two
competitive big guys that are trying to win. So it'll probably look
ugly at times , but in real life, it's nothing ugly at all.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal looks forward to the rare one-on-one challenge, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great defensive player. They're probably going to play
(me) as straight up as possible and then sag, force the outside
players to make some shots,'' he said. ``When I play against the
best, it brings the best out of me, so hopefully I can have a good
game. I've been playing pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson, ``I just don't want him to get in foul trouble, if
he's too keyed up, because there's not a whole lot of resources we
have behind him to stop Mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   Streakers: A win today would all but guarantee the Lakers a
second 16-game streak this season. They play the Clippers on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the first streak died, players figured they got a bit
complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that happening this time,'' O'Neal said. ``There's
only 20-something games left, so we want to keep it real tight.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. HEAT
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 3 p.m., Staples Center
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KNBC-Channel 4; KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (48-11) update: They play 15 of their final 23 games
against probable playoff teams, starting with Miami today. The
Lakers have beaten the Heat five straight times in L.A., but the
teams haven't p layed since the 1997-98 season, when they split the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Heat (37-21) update: Miami is well-rested. The Heat hasn't
played since Thursday, giving Alonzo Mourning (left ankle) time to
heal; he is expected to play today after missing three games. The
Heat has wo n five of its last six games, but is just 15-15 on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   - Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
