<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA STUNS STANFORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD - With one shot, everything changed. With one sweet
stroke by JaRon Rush, UCLA's season - and perhaps the future of its
program - changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new season for us,'' Rush said. ``We got a big-time
win, we've got a four-game winning streak, we beat the No. 1 team
on its home court, our attitude's up, and now we're a team to be
reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll get no argument from top-ranked Stanford, which watched
its 13-game winning streak vanish Saturday when Rush buried a
last-second baseline jumper to give UCLA a 94-93 overtime victory
before 7,391 in rowdy Maples Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   At the site of its worst loss ever, UCLA - a 19-point underdog -
recorded one of its most memorable victories in years.
</P>
<P>
   This was a fabulous game, the best in the Pac-10 this season. It
was taut, intense and well-played. There were four lead changes in
the last minute of regulation and three in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It was so good, in fact, it ended twice: UCLA danced off the
court only to be recalled by the officials. When TV replays
confirmed Ray Young's jumper hit the rim with nine seconds left on
the game clock - thus resetting the shot clock - lead official
Charlie Range approved Rush's subsequent jumper and declared UCLA
the survivor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one great team, Stanford, and one team that's trying
to get back in the mix nationally,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said.
``Today was a good step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   It was giant step for the embattled Lavin, for his much-maligned
staff and for UCLA's NCAA Tournament hopes. If the Bruins (17-11,
8-8) simply beat last-place Washington State on Thursday in Pauley
Pavilion, they'll have the 18 wins necessary for an at-large berth.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's shocker wasn't about win totals or four-game
winning streaks. This was a seed victory - the kind of power-rating
push that turns a No. 9 seed into a No. 7, and that could mean
avoiding a No. 1 seed in the second round. After all, there's
nothing the Selection committee likes more than late-season road
wins over ranked teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to end the NCAA Tournament rumors,'' Bruins guard
Earl Watson said. ``Everyone predicted we'd beat Cal but lose to
Stanford. We were like, `Hold on, here.' Now, we've got the
Washington schools at home, and that's a good situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe this is the same team that lost at Arizona
State by 29 points two weeks ago. Or that lost to Arizona (without
Loren Woods) by 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's not the same. For one thing, Rush is back from
his 2-month suspension, and his impact was immediate. In 26 minutes
Saturday, he hit 7-of-10 shots and scored a team-high 19 points,
including a 3-pointer with 48 left in overtime and the game-winner.
No doubt, the Selection committee will consider Rush's return when
determining UCLA's seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told the players that we can't use (Rush's suspension) as
a cop-out for not being successful,'' Lavin said. ``But this gives
you an idea of the impact he can make on a team.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rush isn't the only difference. Since the disastrous trip to
the desert, the Bruins have practiced and played with increased
resolve. It showed Thursday, when they rallied from a 19-point
deficit to thrash Cal, and it was apparent again Saturday, when
Stanford charged to a 19-4 lead behind senior Mark Madsen, who was
playing his final home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same as Cal,'' Watson said. ``Cal prepped us for
this situation. It wasn't new territory... Where ever we go, nothin
This team is so mentally tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It took eight minutes to erase the 15-point deficit, and from
there the Bruins matched Stanford basket for basket, rebound for
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   When they weren't on the bench with foul trouble, big men Dan
Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso did as they pleased against Madsen and
the Collins twins. Moiso scored eight of UCLA's last 15 points in
regulation, including the tying shot with one second left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moiso was huge for them today,'' Jarron Collins said, ``and
unfortunately, I wasn't able to limit his high-percentage shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush made the game-winner and Moiso sent the game into overtime,
but no one played better than Watson, who had 13 assists and four
turnovers. Crafty and composed, he was the primary reason UCLA shot
54.5 percent from the field and scored on 14 of its last 17
possessions against the nation's best defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great,'' Stanford coach Mike Montgomery said. ``They
were great today, and we were good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
