<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BIGCAP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL CHALLENGE WINS BIG 'CAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- Trainer Ted H. West had just finished second in
Saturday's $1 million Grade I Santa Anita Handicap with Budroyale
when he was asked about the winner, General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Wa he surprised how well the inconsistent 4-year-old colt ran?
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprises me when this horse (begin ital)doesn't(end ital)
run good,'' West said. ``I've seen him train in the mornings, and
he does some spectacular things.''
</P>
<P>
   What General Challenge did in the 63rd running of the Big 'Cap
was pretty spectacular, laying next to last in the eight-horse
field for much of the way before uncorking a powerful move on the
outside to outfinish Budroyale by 1 1/4 lengths as the 2-1
co-favorite in front of an on-track crowd of 30,122.
</P>
<P>
   The California-bred son of General Meeting covered the 1 1/4
miles on a main track labeled good in 2:01 2/5 to give his owners,
John and Betty Mabee, their second Big 'Cap victory. Best Pal won
the race for the Mabees in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero finished third, one length behind Budroyale and 1
1/2 lengths ahead of stablemate Malek. Cat Thief, the other
co-favorite, set the early pace and faded to finish a disappointing
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge's victory also gave jockey Corey Nakatani and
trainer Bob Baffert their first Big 'Cap wins. Nakatani is 2-0 with
General Challenge after replacing Chris McCarron before last
month's Strub Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an engine in him that just doesn't stop,'' Nakatani
said. ``He took dirt and handled it just fine. He's maturing,
getting a lot better. I think maybe the confidence I have in him
might be helping a little bit. I just help him relax, let him get
in his stride.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when General Challenge wouldn't let anybody
help him relax. The big strapping colt won last year's Santa Anita
Derby and the Pacific Classic at Del Mar, but he also ran
disappointing races in the Louisiana and Kentucky Derbies and the
Breeders' Cup Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani might have discovered the secret to success with
General Challenge -- let him fall back and make one big run. He did
it in the Strub, romping home by 9 1/2 lengths, and Saturday he
handily beat one of the strongest Big 'Cap fields in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corey is going to have to ride this horse all the time now,''
Baffert joked. ``He relaxes unbelieveably for him.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was joy in the General Challenge camp, Budroyale's
connections suffered another heartbreaking loss in a Grade I race.
The 7-year-old gelding has been runner-up in the Breeders' Cup
Classic and Hollywood Gold Cup in the past eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fires his best shot every time,'' West said. ``Consistency
is his key. He ran super. I can't be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Richard Mandella comebackers, Puerto Madero and Malek,
acquitted themselves well with their third and fourth-place
finishes. For Puerto Madero, the race was a huge improvement over
his past four starts dating back to last year's Big 'Cap.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella brought Malek into the race on workouts alone after his
disappointing fifth-place finish as the favorite in last summer's
Pacific Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both ran well,'' Mandella said. ``Puerto Madero got
carried wide and I think that cost him a little bit. And Malek ran
fine too off a layoff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Laffit Pincay Jr. rode Puerto Madero, his first Big 'Cap mount
since 1996 when he finished 11th aboard Urgent Request. He said the
wide trip might have cost Puerto Madero a chance for second.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was nice to get to ride in a Big 'Cap again,''
Pincay said. ``I got very excited coming down the stretch. I
thought I had a chance. I really thought I had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be wishful thinking. General Challenge, now
9-for-14 lifetime with two seconds and 5-for-7 at Santa Anita,
inched to the lead at the head of the stretch and drew clear from
Budroyale and the fast-finishing Puerto Madero.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said it's uncertain where General Challenge will run
next, that the horse's camp will sit down and map out a strategy
that could lead to Horse-of-the-Year honors if he shows he can win
outside California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to enjoy this win, go back and give him a lot
of loving,'' Baffert said. ``It's a long year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert seems convinced that General Challenge is a
different horse, that he'll be a better shipper now that he's
matured and has a jockey who fits him like a glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we finally got him going the right way,'' he said.
``We're definitely going to go out of town again, to the Breeders'
Cup and some other races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   If General Challenge handles it like he did Saturday's Big 'Cap
field, Baffert can begin work on an acceptance speech for Horse of
the Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
