<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS PLAY SPOILERS AGAINST SABRES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Facing the final games of the season with
nowhere to go (except maybe 13th place instead of 14th), the
Islanders had a choice: they could exit quietly, or they could make
everyone else's lives miserable.
</P>
<P>
   They picked the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest victims were the Buffalo Sabres as Olli Jokinen
scored on a penalty shot and got two assists in the Islanders' 4-2
victory Saturday afternoon at Nassau Coliseum. The loss further
scrambled the Sabres' playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (26-30-10), which reached the finals of the Stanley Cup
last season, is tied for ninth in the Eastern Conference, 2 points
behind Pittsburgh and 3 behind the Rangers. The top eight teams
make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way our season is going, this is what we are playing
for,'' said center Dave Scatchard, who had two goals for the
Islanders (18-39-8). ``We're relishing the role of spoilers. You
think to yourself, if we had played this way all year, maybe it
could have been us instead of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Scatchard sacrificed part of a front tooth in the effort; he was
hit by a flying puck early in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Scatchard opened the scoring for the Islanders, beating Dominik
Hasek off a centering pass from Jokinen to tie the score at 1-1 at
13 minutes 40 seconds of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres got a penalty shot at 17:58 after Mathieu Biron
tripped Miroslav Satan on a breakaway. But with goaltender Kevin
Weekes coming out to challenge him, Satan's shot flew wide left,
missing the post by inches.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Haggerty, recalled from Kansas City last Tuesday, put the
Islanders up by 2-1 early in the second period on his first
National Hockey League goal. Mariusz Czerkawski and Zdeno Chara
assisted.
</P>
<P>
   The 13,149 fans were then treated to a rare spectacle, which
also happened to be a first in Islanders history: two penalty shots
in a single game.
</P>
<P>
   Jokinen, coming in on Hasek, was taken down from behind by Keith
Primeau and was awarded the shot.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Jokinen, who had scored three goals in the
previous four games, calmly beat Hasek with a backhander to put the
Islanders up by 3-1 at 3:09 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only move I have,'' said Jokinen, who got his
second assist of the afternoon when he fed Scatchard at 14:24 of
the same period to put the Islanders up by 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a tulip in the spring come blooming out,'' Coach
Butch Goring said. ``The last five or six games he really has
emerged as the player we thought he could be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres made it 4-2 on Vladimir Tsyplakov's second goal of
the game just 19 seconds later, and had a chance to come within a
goal midway through the final period when Stu Barnes put one past
Weekes but Primeau was called for interfering with Ray Schultz and
the goal was nullified.
</P>
<P>
   With just over a minute left, Hasek was pulled for a sixth
skater, and Scatchard had a chance for the hat trick when he took
the ice with 28 seconds left, but was unable to find the empty net.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game tells me a lot of good things about our club,''
Goring said of the Islanders, who skated to a 5-5 tie with the
Ottawa Senators Thursday night. ``We got a little bit robbed the
other night, but we played a strong game and that continued
today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
