<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-KAPLER-TE     03-04 1670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-KAPLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNG-HO GABE KAPLER GROWS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates got his
first real introduction to his new right fielder this off-season at
a YMCA in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a winter caravan stop and we were supposed to just
mingle with the kids and sign autographs,'' Oates said. ``There was
a 13-year-old kid out on the basketball court who was supposed to
be the best player in San Antonio, averaging 40 points a game. Next
thing I know, I've got my right fielder out there playing
two-on-two with 13- and 14-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting after it, too. He's wearing blue jeans and
sneakers and sweat is pouring off his face. This guy was gung-ho,
soaking wet, high-fiving the other players, saying, `Good offense,
good defense.' He was getting into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler, unfazed at the prospect of replacing Juan Gonzalez
as the Rangers' right fielder, is that way: intense, driven and
determined to succeed in everything he attempts. This is a guy who
includes Pete Rose and Charles Barkley among his on-field role
models.
</P>
<P>
   He refuses to hold back. Two innings into the Rangers' first
scrimmage of the season, Kapler was diving after a pop fly down the
right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's him,'' said pitcher Justin Thompson, who came with
Kapler from the Detroit Tigers in the Gonzalez trade. ``He'll run
through the outfield wall; it doesn't matter if it's spring
training or the World Series. He just plays all-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler considers that high praise. There's little doubt he wants
to put up big numbers, but that's not what he wants Rangers fans
talking about when they watch him play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to say, `I've never seen a guy pour his heart out
on the field,''' Kapler said. ``I want them to get chills like I
did when I saw Pete Rose play. I want them to go: I can't believe
how high he got when he dove into second base. I want them to see
how bad I want it. I want them to see how passionate I am about the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers' new right fielder is more than just intense and
passionate. Study where he came from and what he's all about, and a
complex, almost contradictory personality emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler is obsessed with winning a World Series, yet he was once
kicked off a major-college baseball team because he was totally
unfocused.
</P>
<P>
   He is a thoughtful, intelligent person who alternates reading
three books at one time _ ``Tough Jews'', ``Easy Ways to
Meditation'' and ``Science of Hitting'' _ but became adept at
forging his mother's signature so he could cut classes in junior
high school.
</P>
<P>
   He is a hard-nosed, fearless player, but he needed therapy when
he was 8 because he was hit by an automobile and developed a fear
of crossing the street.
</P>
<P>
   He has become a weightlifting and nutritional fanatic, but only
after getting over his beer-and-cigarette days of high school. He
also once considered acting as a career after finishing second in a
city-wide drama competition by playing three roles from ``Taming of
the Shrew.''
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and you have a bold-talking,
straight-shooting mixture of Rusty Greer, Will Clark, and Socrates
_ a muscular philosopher who doesn't mind speaking his mind or
getting his uniform dirty. He seems as adept at discussing cures
for cancer with teammate Chad Curtis as he is breaking up double
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm out there, but I'm not uncomfortable with that,''
Kapler said.
</P>
<P>
   Nez Balelo, owner of the West Coast Baseball School and a mentor
who helped Kapler overcome his wayward teen-age years, said: ``He's
a great individual. People who see his size and commitment don't
see the whole picture. He's a very caring person with a heart of
gold.''
</P>
<P>
   His Tigers teammates, however, had trouble seeing that. When he
unexpectedly crashed their starting lineup last season, they saw a
brash rookie who was coming off an incredible minor-league season
and seemed to have everything going for him. Having his own Web
site didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't help that his well-sculpted body was on the cover
of several weightlifting and bodybuilding magazines. When he walked
into the clubhouse at spring training, he was greeted by a sign
that said ``Welcome Mr. America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some serious grief,'' Kapler said. ``But I was a rookie,
so I had to keep my mouth shut. I'd be in bed late at night, and
I'd just twist and turn. My wife, Lisa, would say to me, `I know
you want to explode, but you have to be smart.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His first season in Detroit was rough but it fulfilled a dream
Kapler said he had since he was 5. Growing up in Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley, he would get up at 7 a.m. and spend all day at the
park playing baseball. That apparently included school days, as
well as weekends and summers.
</P>
<P>
   He was gifted in mathematics and reading, but he also had
attention-deficit disorder, and that led to trouble in the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sit there and watch the clock, break pencils in
frustration and look out the window,'' Kapler said. ``It would be
one of those beautiful California days, and I'd want to be playing
sports instead of being in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``School was miserable, so I didn't go. I'd take the bus, get
dropped off, and I wouldn't go. Any chance, I'd cut class. My mom
\RJudy\S bailed me out a billion times. One day, she went in to see
the counselor, and he had a stack of notes this big where I had
forged her signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are awesome. I owe everything to them. They really
helped me through some tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kapler said his son ``is a very intelligent person, he
just wasn't a student. He's an exceptional reader. He was
interested in learning; he just wasn't interested in the school
system. We all struggled with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball wasn't a struggle. Kapler was able to hold his own and
more among the highly competitive Southern California baseball
talent. But the guy who was taunted by his Tigers teammates as
``Mr. America'' was scrawny and didn't have much power, causing
coaches and others to doubt his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an intensity I saw in very few other people,'' his
father said.
</P>
<P>
   That intensity was transferred to weight training when Kapler
started seriously working out as a senior in high school. It was a
time when he was becoming precariously more interested in drinking
and smoking than hitting and fielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weight training was a way of getting my anger out,'' Kapler
said. ``I wasn't feeling too good about myself, and I got a lot of
compliments right away. I'd probably say that's what drove me to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler was a shortstop at Taft High School in Woodland Hills,
graduating in 1993. He wasn't the best player around, but, through
Balelo's help, he received a scholarship to Fullerton State,
coached by Augie Garrido and one of the premier programs in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't belong there,'' Kapler said. ``I was overmatched,
completely directionless and completely insecure. I was over my
head in every way, and I was trying to be something I wasn't. I was
partying a lot. All I know is when I was there, I didn't want to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I told the coach I had to miss practice because of a
family problem,'' Kapler said. ``Well, I didn't go home. I was in
the dorm watching a basketball game and drinking a beer when one of
the coaches brought in some recruits to look at the place. So I got
nabbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day, very politely, they said beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler said calling his father and telling him was one of the
hardest things he has ever done. But being kicked out of Fullerton
turned out to be one of the best things that ever happened to him,
once he enrolled in Moorpark College, a community college in the
Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   He played for head coach Ken Wagner and assistant Mario Porto.
``Those coaches were awesome. I needed firm guidance and they gave
it to me,'' Kapler said. ``They didn't give me anything. Usually
when you come back from a major university and want to play at a
junior college, they're pretty excited to have you.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys said, Tuesday practice starts. The best guys are
going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler flourished under Wagner and Porto's guidance in 1995,
hitting .337 (56-for-166) with seven home runs and 52 runs batted
in. After the season, the Tigers drafted him in the 57th round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moorpark was great for him,'' Balelo said. ``After Fullerton,
I think he really decided at that point, `I'm going to commit
myself to the game of baseball and be a major-league player.' Gabe
and I had a lot of long talks, and he just needed to understand he
had to work at it. When he got off the beaten path, I'd tell him,
you have what it takes, it's up to you to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He did it quickly with the Tigers. He started out as a
57th-round pick, but three years later he was one of the Tigers'
top prospects. He hit .322 with 28 homers and 146 RBI at Double-A
Jacksonville in 1998 and was named minor-league player of the year
by several publications.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was great until he unexpectedly made the Tigers'
Opening Day roster last season then failed to live up to his
impressive minor-league credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he was the minor-league player of the year, everybody
wanted instant results,'' Justin Thompson said. ``That just didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He was optioned back to the minors after six games, then
promoted after Brian Hunter was traded to the Seattle Mariners on
April 28. Overall, Kapler hit .245 with 18 homers and 49 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looked upon as needing to not have a good year but a
gigantic year because we weren't any good,'' Kapler said. ``That's
why it's a breath of fresh air being here. The veteran players were
great guys, but they didn't go out of their way to make me feel
comfortable as the guys here do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have come to realize that Kapler might not be Juan
Gonzalez, but he is extraordinary in his own way.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
