<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLREPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE BELFOUR SOARS, OSGOOD FALTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody wandering into the Dallas Stars' postgame locker room
in Detroit a couple of years ago had a better chance of hearing a
pin drop than a laugh. On June 5, two years will have passed since
Stars players trudged from Detroit's Joe Louis Arena with a dark
cloud of uncertainty hanging over them. Game 6, along with the
Western Conference Finals, had just been lost, and everybody seemed
to be wondering if Stars goalie Ed Belfour had what it took to
carry a team to a Stanley Cup. Wouldn't they be better building
with a young player like Red Wings goalie Chris Osgood, people
asked. Stars general manager Bob Gainey insisted ``no.'' Now,
almost two years later, you can't hear a marching band for all of
the laughing. Gainey and the Stars certainly have had the last
laugh on this one. Not only has Belfour helped them win one Cup, he
has them primed to win another. A month away from the playoffs, the
Stars have to be on the short list of Cup contenders in large part
because of the play of Belfour. He has to be considered one of the
three best goalies in the league right now, along with Toronto's
Curtis Joseph and New Jersey's Martin Brodeur. Without a doubt,
start to finish, he has been the Stars' best player this season.
When the Stars were good, he was good. When the Stars were bad, he
was better. Everybody knows good goaltending is the key to winning
in the playoffs. Not everybody has a good goaltender. We're not
talking also-rans like Pittsburgh or San Jose, either. There are
legitimate Cup candidates who have serious holes in goal. And,
maybe, the most ironic part is Detroit is one of them. Osgood, who
outdueled Belfour in 1998 on the way to the Cup, has become the
enigma that Belfour was supposed to be. The same people who
questioned Belfour have now turned their sights on Osgood. The
question isn't whether he's a good goalie. The question is whether
he's a goalie who can win a Cup for the Wings. There isn't an easy
answer. The shelf life on this team is short. Players like Brendan
Shanahan, Chris Chelios and Steve Yzerman have one, maybe two, more
Cup runs in them. This is not the same Red Wings team it was two
years ago either. They need their goalie to do more than just mind
the net. They need to have confidence that he'll be able to win
games for them. The Wings, of course, have said all season that
they have complete faith in Osgood. They did when he started the
season hot. They did when he went through a slump. They do now as
he has mirrored the team's inconsistency. He's their guy. But with
10 days remaining until the trading deadline, the brutal reality is
Osgood can't be if they want to win. Osgood was good enough to play
on a Cup winner. He hasn't proved himself to be capable of winning
a team a Cup. The irony is that Belfour has. The not-so-funny part
for Detroit is that he might just do so again this season.
Iginla carrying Flames into the playoff chase
</P>
<P>
   You hear the phrase ``win-win'' situation all the time. The
description has crept into the English language in politics and
finance and sports. But what does ``win-win'' really mean? Well, it
means that four years after the Stars traded a young, talented
Jarome Iginla to Calgary for a proven, talented Joe Nieuwendyk both
teams are saying they got exactly what they wanted. Nieuwendyk, of
course, was the playoff MVP as the Stars won the Stanley Cup last
season. Iginla, 22, has developed into the player capable of
leading the Flames to a Cup in the coming seasons. Don't think
Iginla didn't realize it would easily have been a win-lose
situation. ``I did feel pressure,'' Iginla said. ``I'm a big fan of
hockey, and I watched and I realized that Nieuwendyk was one of the
top scorers in the game, and so I did feel pressure. But the Flames
talked to me, and they took a lot of pressure off me. They just
told me to relax, and once the season started, after my first year,
I was just going out and playing, and I realized all I could do was
my best.'' Which has been pretty good lately. Iginla had 10 goals
and 11 assists in February, snagging him Player of the Month
recognition. (He's the first minority ever to win the award). In
February, he scored or assisted on half of the Flames' goals and
led the team with a plus-11 rating. His team followed, too. A
strong end to February not only snapped a 10-game winless streak
but has the Flames back in contention for a playoff spot. They're
three points out of the eighth and final spot. ``We haven't really
talked about a certain amount of points that we need,'' Iginla
said. ``But we play all the teams that, besides a few games,
directly affect us. We play Anaheim. We still have two against San
Jose. I think we still play LA again, and we have two against
Edmonton.'' Ah, a playoff race in Calgary. For a while, playoffs
and a small-market team like Calgary looked to be at odds,
especially as players such as Nieuwendyk and then Theo Fleury were
traded for younger, less expensive players such as Iginla. Not so,
says Iginla. ``This year we want to make the playoffs, but we think
there's bigger things,'' Iginla said. ``We look at the Ottawa
Senators, where they had to go through some tough times, and now
they are a legitimate contender, and that's what we feel we can do
here and what we have developing. I mean, people have written us
off. When we did lose Theo, people wrote us off, and people said we
were all a bunch of no-names and stuff.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
