<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPICNOTEBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MARATHONERS SLOW TO FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are a nation of joggers. And yet, in the ultimate 26-mile
jog, we are wheezing also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. On any given weekend, there is a marathon being
staged somewhere within a day's drive from practically anywhere in
America. There is a long-distance race, calling men's and women's
soles.
</P>
<P>
   But in the consummate run to glory, the Olympic marathon, United
States runners have been little more than roadkill since Joan
Benoit won the first women's marathon at the Los Angeles Games in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   The latest case came last weekend in Columbia, S.C., where 170
women ran for what were supposed to be three spots on the U.S.
Olympic marathon team.
</P>
<P>
   Why February, you ask? A fair question. U.S. Track and Field
organizers felt that the midwinter weather in South Carolina
approximated what the Olympic marathoners will experience when they
toe the line on Sept. 24 in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the men's Olympic Trials Marathon will take place in
Pittsburgh more than two months from now, which won't correspond to
any weather except, duh, Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the runners in Columbia last week saw temperatures
climb into the 80s as the marathon progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Libbie Hickman, who had the fastest time by a U.S. woman coming
into the trials (2 hourse, 28 minutes, 34 seconds), staggered home
eighth. Benoit, now Joan Samuelson and a married mother at age 42,
came in ninth. Anne Marie Lauck, a 1996 Olympian, carried the pace
for 20 miles and then faded desperately, collapsing as she crossed
the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the 170 runners never made it to the finish line.
And of those who did, few ran personal bests in the muggy
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But one who did, Christine Clark, a 37-year-old pathologist,
came from the edge of nowhere _ Anchorage, Alaska, actually _ to
win the trials in 2:33:31. The time was more than seven minutes
faster than she had ever run a marathon before.
</P>
<P>
   She had trained for the race by running a relatively benign 70
miles per week, with most of it coming on a motorized treadmill
because of Alaska's acute winters.
</P>
<P>
   A great story, except ...
</P>
<P>
   Except seven months ago, to weed out the sundry roadkill, the
world governing body for track and field, the IAAF, lowered the
``A'' qualifying standard for the women's Olympic marathon from
2:35 to 2:33. The U.S. governing body, in turn, decided that all of
its Olympic entrants should have to make the A standard and thus
decreed that if the trials winner didn't run 2:33, only the winner
would run in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In most U.S. track and field events, the decision wouldn't have
raised a single eyebrow. We more than capably fill our three spots
in the sprints, hurdles and field events.
</P>
<P>
   But in South Carolina, the issue boiled over. The two other
Americans who had run under the A qualifying standard coming into
the race _ Hickman and Kristy Johnston _ can't compete in Australia
now because Clark's time was too slow on an 80-degree day in
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most fair system there is,'' Craig Masback, head of
USA Track and Field, told the Denver Post, ``because there's no
bureaucratic meddling. And it's the most unfair system there is,
because inevitably in every Olympics, there is some story of
someone not making the team who people thought should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Masback is correct. Track and field's system of trials is
supposed to stifle the tribulations by removing all subjectivity.
Finish 1-2-3 and you go to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But by deciding to honor only the IAAF's A qualifying standard,
USATF opened the door to a worst-case scenario as it experienced in
Columbia. Hickman and Johnston deserve to join Clark as Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   Masback is being urged to ask the IAAF for an exemption that
would take into account the humid conditions _ relax the A standard
to 2:34, perhaps, which Clark bettered.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy underscores, however, the ongoing problems with
the marathon in this country. Since 1984, no U.S. runner has
finished better than 10th in the Olympic marathon. Since 1985, no
U.S. runner, male or female, has won the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   The theories linger. Some think that our elite runners are
opting for their weekend 10-kilometer runs because they're easier
and sometimes offer prize money. Others contend that marathoning
has simply become more serious business in other countries _ Japan,
notably.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the race last weekend in South Carolina will
only aggravate the problem.
TANGLED BUREAUCRACY
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of marathon problems, the best marathon runner in the
world wants to run for the United States _ and red tape may not let
him.
</P>
<P>
   Khalid Khannouchi of Morocco broke the world record at the
Chicago Marathon last October, covering the 26 miles, 385 yards, in
2:05:42. He wants to run for Uncle Sam and has denounced his
Moroccan citizenship because of what he claims is lack of support.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi moved to the United States in 1993, married an
American girl and lives now in Ossining, N.Y. Under normal
processing, he would have been eligible for U.S. citizenship in
September, two weeks before the Sydney marathon.
</P>
<P>
   But an immigration official who was handling Khannouchi's
application failed to complete the paperwork, and the runner was
forced to start again from square one. Khannouchi reportedly is
seeking a special exemption based upon his wife's employment
overseas. Problem is, she doesn't work overseas _ yet. TV-FRIENDLY
TRACK
</P>
<P>
   Lamine Diack of Senegal, who took over as IAAF president upon
Primo Nebiolo's death in November, wants to make track and field
more appealing to the TV-stupefied masses.
</P>
<P>
   Diack said last week that he is in favor of doing away with
false starts altogether. One premature lurch and you're gone. In
time, Diack feels, sprinters would stop training to anticipate the
starting gun.
</P>
<P>
   The IAAF head also likes the idea of limiting high jump and pole
vault attempts to six, which would eliminate the three-jump cattle
call at the lower heights. And he wants to lower the number of long
jump and triple jump attempts from six to four. AUSTRALIAN COLD
SHOULDER
</P>
<P>
   What, no ESPN?
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Morning Herald reported last week that Sydney Olympic
organizers plan to limit broadcast access to Olympic venues only to
local (Australian) television and to NBC, its affiliates and
non-U.S. rights holders.
</P>
<P>
   If enforced, it would mean that organizations such as ESPN, ABC
and FOX couldn't tape interviews from any Olympic sites. NBC paid
$3.5 billion to the International Olympic Committee for the TV
rights to every Olympics from now to 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by controversies that prompted a shake-up at the top in
recent months, SOCOG, the Sydney organizing committee, has turned a
conspicuous cold shoulder to the global media. Committee president
Michael Knight says it's time that the organizers ``get out of the
media and turn the focus elsewhere.'' EYEING 2008
</P>
<P>
   Ten cities officially remain in the running to host the 2008
Summer Games _ Bangkok, Thailand; Beijing; Cairo, Egypt; Havana;
Istanbul, Turkey; Kuala Lampur, Malaysia; Osaka, Japan; Paris;
Seville, Spain; and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing is considered the favorite, with Paris a semi-distant
second. The IOC will name the 2008 Olympic host city in July 2001.
LEARNING FROM THE GUYS
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Dragila pocketed a $50,000 bonus Friday for breaking a
world record at the USA Indoor Track and Field Championships at the
Georgia Dome in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila is the world's best woman in the pole vault, an endeavor
that not too long ago was considered a distinctly manly pursuit. As
queen of the new event, therefore, her sky is the limit.
</P>
<P>
   She jumped 15 feet, 1 3/4 inches Friday, bettering her previous
mark by a convenient one-quarter inch and thus earning the USATF's
$50,000 bonus check.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old Sergei Bubka trick. The great Ukrainian vaulter used
to travel the planet, breaking his world record in one-eighth inch
increments and, of course, pocketing bonus checks all the way up to
20-2. \Nsubheds:Forrest Gump would be proud Adrien Sawyer, who won
the USATF indoor long jump Friday with a leap of 21-5 1/2, is a
product of Texas A&AMP;M. She was born with a dislocated hip, and
doctors advised her parents to put her in leg braces. They didn't,
and she says she leaped off the table one day and hasn't stopped
running or jumping since.
DRUMMOND ENJOYS LIFE AS TRACK STAR, FATHER
</P>
<P>
   Long after he was supposed to have exhausted his shelf life, if
not his vocal cords, Jon Drummond is still a world-class sprinter.
</P>
<P>
   The former TCU All-American was among the favorites yesterday in
the 60-meter dash at the USA Indoor Track and Field Championships
in Atlanta. Drummond went into the race with a career indoor best
of 6.45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He came to TCU from Odessa College in 1988 and led off the
Horned Frogs' NCAA champion 400-meter relay team in 1991. In that
same year, the Philadelphia native made the 100-meter top-10
rankings of Track and Field News for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond became a fixture on the lists. In 1997, he was ranked
No. 3 in the world over 100 meters and No. 1 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in Culver City, Calif., and works out under the
demanding eye of Olympian John Smith. Drummond and 100 world
record-holder Maurice Greene share the same coach and the same
practice track.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is like my father,'' Drummond said by telephone last
week. ``Before, he was just my coach and later he was my friend.
But now our relationship is more like father and son. He's cautious
about overworking me. He understands that sometimes Jon Drummond
just needs somebody to say, `Come on, man, let's do this together.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Notepads and microphones have never seemed to scare Drummond. He
has been called the ``Clown Prince of Track,'' a nickname he didn't
shy from.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond was born 31 years ago with spina bifida. Doctors told
his parents that he would likely be mentally retarded and unable to
walk. ``I'm a walking miracle,'' he tells interviewers.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond was married in 1997 and has a 19-month-old daughter,
Gabriella. He said she is much harder to catch than Maurice Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in good health,'' Drummond said. ``I just take my time now
and listen to my doctors and don't rush things. A lot of times we
get caught up, pushing that envelope. But married, with a child,
I'm learning how to manage my time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also more focused now on my technique. In the past, I was
focused on running fast, not running correct. If I can do that now,
I do believe that Jon Drummond can do some amazing things. I've
already proven that I'm a man full of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Drummond missed the Olympic teams in both 1988 and 1992,
reaching the semifinals of the 100 and 200, respectively. But he
came back to finish third in the 100 and make the U.S. team for the
1996 Games. He reached the semis, finishing sixth, in Atlanta, and
ran the lead-off leg on the U.S. silver medal-winning 400-meter
relay team. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
