<HEADLINE>
RANGERS, DODGERS TEAM TO FIND SPRING HOME
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers and Dodgers have formed an
informal partnership to search for a new spring-training home
either in Las Vegas or Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But if that doesn't work out and only the Dodgers leave Florida,
the Rangers could move into historic Dodgertown at Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't go with them, Vero Beach would be an option,''
Rangers owner Tom Hicks said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' contract with Port Charlotte expires after the 2001
spring training. The Rangers, especially general manager Doug
Melvin, are happy with their current situation from a baseball
standpoint, but poor attendance remains a major concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sympathetic to what the baseball people want and intend to
listen to them,'' Hicks said. ``This place wouldn't really be all
that bad if we weren't last in attendance. I haven't figured out
why that is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are looking seriously at Las Vegas, but there are
concerns about the cool weather and the possible distractions of
the city famous for its night life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vegas would be the perfect place,'' Hicks said. ``Texans love
to go there, and there are 10 flights a day \Rfrom DFW\S into the
place. There are great golf courses and attractions. You could
build a resort around the complex. But the baseball people have
some obvious concerns; they're worried about turning players loose
there. But that could be controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   A move to Las Vegas would require three to five other teams
coming with them. The Dodgers and their Fox ownership group are
eager to move to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had a rare sellout crowd yesterday against the
Cincinnati Reds, but that was from advanced sales from the
unfulfilled expectations that Ken Griffey Jr. would make the trip
from Sarasota, Fla. HICKS GOAL STILL HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks, addressing the Rangers as a team for the first time
this spring, said his goals remain high even with the off-season
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to continue to win the West, make it farther in the
playoffs and eventually win the World Series,'' Hicks said. ``This
is the best I've ever felt about the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have cut $9-10 million from the payroll, but the
players were happy to hear Hicks say there is flexibility to add
payroll during the season if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in here thinks we're going to win the World Series,
and it's good to know he's going to help any way he can,'' first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro said. ``If we're close, he's willing to put
us over the top. That's great to hear in spring training.''
THOMPSON THROWS
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Justin Thompson threw another 25 pitches off the
mound yesterday without any trouble with his left shoulder.
Thompson, who underwent shoulder surgery in August, said, ``It
feels good, I just don't know how much to put on it. I'm just
trying to feel good and mechanically do everything right.'' nn
</P>
