<HEADLINE>
STARS FINDING WAYS TO COME FROM BEHIND IN FINAL PERIOD
</HEADLINE>
 COMEBACKS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stars rarely seemed in need of comebacks last season as they
steamrolled to the Presidents' Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   This season, they could charge opponents for clinics on the art
of the third-period comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's 4-1 victory against Pacific Division rival Phoenix
provided the Stars an NHL-leading eighth comeback victory when
trailing after two periods. That's 16 points. Sixteen points that
could be the difference between winning a division title and
opening the playoffs as the second seed in the West, and falling
back in the pack as a fourth or fifth seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sign of a good hockey team,'' said winger Aaron
Gavey, who is providing substantial depth at forward. He scored his
fifth goal of the season Friday and third in the past five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars won only one of 17 games when trailing after the
second period last season. They are now 8-15-2 when faced with that
same predicament this season. They've done it twice in the past two
weeks in critical situations.
</P>
<P>
   Before beating the depleted Coyotes on Friday, two weeks ago the
Stars put a third-period spanking on a cranky group of Red Wings
who make their way to Reunion Arena tonight for a key Western
Conference showdown.
</P>
<P>
   With 17 games remaining, the Stars hold a seven-point division
lead. And now all of a sudden they find themselves trailing the Red
Wings by only three points.
</P>
<P>
   In both of those comebacks, the Stars, the team with the fewest
goals in the Western Conference, broke loose for four third-period
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been pretty good coming into the third and realizing
whether we're up or we're down to really go after them,'' said
Grant Marshall, who notched his first goal of the season Friday to
tie the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The key has been goaltending team defense, which has enabled the
Stars to stay within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of games we've been down 1-0, 2-1, we've been right in
the games,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It hasn't been like we've
gotten blown out, we've been competitive in the game, stayed with
it and scored some goals in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go into every game now, regardless of our lineup, expecting
to win. It doesn't matter who we're playing or who is in our
lineup. We have confidence _ it's not a cockiness _ in the way that
we push each other. It's just an expectation, we're expecting to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory tonight would give the Stars the season series, 3-1,
and the edge in a head-to-head tiebreaker. By catching Detroit, the
Stars would ensure home-ice advantage should they meet the Red
Wings in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe now that is another goal for us,'' defenseman Darryl
Sydor said. ``They are right there, so let's try to catch them. I
guess you always want to keep pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars kept pushing against Phoenix thanks in part to a line
change. Hitchcock moved Jamie Langenbrunner off the checking line
with Guy Carbonneau and Mike Keane and onto the No. 1 line with
Mike Modano and rookie Brenden Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner responded with an offensive blitz. He scored the
game-winner and added an assist in the third period. Hitchcock said
he is not certain if he will keep the Modano-Langenbrunner-Morrow
line intact for tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``One of the reasons we made the
change was we didn't really have a line specifically to check. We
weren't getting enough offense, and I felt we needed to change the
mind-set. Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, everything seems to be working for Stars. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
