<SLUG> BC-BKC-UNC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TARRED CAROLINA FEELING BLUE
</HEADLINE>
 BARNHOUSE COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ Good thing Bob Knight wasn't around. He might
have thrown a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Cameron Crazies broke out Rhythmic Cheer No. 33 _ ``Who's
Your Daddy'' _ to taunt visiting North Carolina yesterday. Knight
took offense when Northwestern's fans yelled that phrase last year,
but the Tar Heels took no umbrage. It would appear they understand
completely who their daddy is.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-ranked Blue Devils (24-4) are the Atlantic Coast
Conference's patriarch. Their 90-76 victory against North Carolina
gave them a 15-1 ACC record and a 58-6 league record the last four
years that translates into four consecutive ACC regular-season
titles. Duke is a Big Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   Duke might even be in the process of ruining this rivalry, the
best in sports. It's not a rivalry when one team wins all the time.
What's most galling to the Tar Heels isn't that they're no longer
king of the hill, it's that the Dookies are.
</P>
<P>
   A telling moment. In the second half, as North Carolina tried to
shoot its way back in the game, Duke's Shane Battier (game-high 30
points) hit his second consecutive 3-pointer. Blue Devils coach
Mike Krzyzewski bounded from the bench, landing on his hands and
knees. He slapped the court, urging his team's defensive effort.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite sideline, North Carolina coach Bill Guthridge
observed the scene calmly, hands on both knees.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels (18-12, 9-7 ACC) lack passion. They have several
talented parts that don't fit together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, that's you guys saying they're struggling,'' Krzyzewski
said. ``They're a heck of a basketball team, well-coached. I don't
look at them struggling. They're good.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical Coach K class. But there's ``good'' and there's North
Carolina ``good''. These Tar Heels are generic ``good''
</P>
<P>
   A fan behind the North Carolina bench held up a chartreuse sign
with the words Guthridge's Pink Slip. Guthridge, in his third
season as Dean Smith's Successor, isn't likely to be fired. But he
knows that this season, with a senior point guard (Ed Cota), a
talented scorer (Joseph Forte) and a 7-foot center (Brendan
Haywood), has been substandard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously wanted to do better, but we've worked hard and
competed hard,'' Guthridge said.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's excuse for this season is ``injuries''. Backup
point guard//defensive specialist Ronald Curry was lost for the
season. Brian Bersticker's broken foot cost the Tar Heels another
post player, and power forward Kris Lang has played despite
numerous aches and pains.
</P>
<P>
   And yesterday, the Tar Heels lost Cota for a key stretch in the
first half when he needed five stitches to close a cut in his left
eyebrow. When he left the court with 10:57 remaining, Duke had a
15-10 lead. When he returned at 3:05, North Carolina trailed 36-18.
The Blue Devils' press had produced seven turnovers and a 21-8 run.
</P>
<P>
   (Never mind this counter point: Duke won yesterday even though
freshman Mike Dunleavy, the team's top reserve, missed his fourth
consecutive game recovering from mononucleosis.)
</P>
<P>
   Duke has won five consecutive games in this rivalry, its longest
streak over North Carolina since the early '60s. The Blue Devils
have averaged 89.2 points in those victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' said Cota, noting that the Tar Heels
shot 58.2 percent _ 69 percent in the second half _ to lose by
double digits. ``It would have been in there, it would have been a
different game. I'm not saying we would have won. ... Losing to any
teams five times is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   But you just know that for North Carolina, losing five in a row
to the Dookies is equal parts grating and galling.
</P>
<P>
   The Cameron Crazies' Cheer No. 1 in this series is ``Go to hell,
Carolina, go to hell.'' A sign in the stands put the cheer into
past tense: Gone to hell, Carolina, gone to hell. Five losses to
Duke by an average margin of 14.6 points. Carolina blue isn't just
a color, it's a mood description. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
