<HEADLINE>
RUSH QUICKLY FINDS HIS TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD - Time and again, UCLA forward JaRon Rush imagined how
his first game in three months would unfurl. How much would he
play? Would he upset the team chemistry? Would he be nervous? What
about his defense and his rebounding?
</P>
<P>
   The one thing Rush didn't worry about was his shooting touch -
not after shooting 500 jumpers a day during his suspension. When he
wasn't going to class, testifying before a grand jury or meeting
with his attorney, Rush was shooting jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I worked on the most,'' he said. ``I wanted to get
a consistent jumper. I've been shooting before practice and after,
and I was pretty comfortable with my touch.''
</P>
<P>
   He proved that Saturday, hitting 7 of 10 shots from the field
and scoring a team-high 19 points - including the game-winner - in
UCLA's dramatic 94-93 overtime victory over Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might score a few points,'' Rush said. ``But I
never imagined this.''
</P>
<P>
   His biggest baskets came when UCLA needed them most: trailing
93-89 with 48 seconds left in overtime and big men Jerome Moiso and
Dan Gadzuric on the bench with five fouls.
</P>
<P>
   First, Rush buried a 3-pointer from 23 feet to pull the Bruins
within 93-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rhythm shot,'' he explained. ``(Mark) Madsen backed
off me, and I'd been shooting well all day.''
</P>
<P>
   After a Stanford turnover and several UCLA timeouts, Ray Young
missed a difficult shot from 10 feet. A scramble for the rebound
ensued, and Stanford guard David Moseley tried to flip the ball to
teammate Casey Jacobsen.
</P>
<P>
   Rush intercepted and swished a 10-footer from the left baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fade-away jumper, a regular shot,'' he said. ``Nobody
was in my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate and longtime friend Earl Watson wasn't surprised by
Rush's last-minute heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been doing this stuff since we were 12 years old,''
Watson said. ``He's the biggest money player I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: The Bruins improved to 12-1 in the last two years
when Sean Farnham starts.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA was 10 of 15 from the foul line. Stanford was 29 of 42.
</P>
<P>
   This was UCLA's first win in Maples Pavilion since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when the Bruins last beat a No. 1 team, a UCLA official
mentioned 1980, when they upset No. 1 seed DePaul in the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
