<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY DOES IT FOR PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA - If Saturday was any indication of how easy it's
going to be for Pepperdine at the West Coast Conference basketball
tournament, then the Waves should immediately begin clearing their
schedule for March 16-19.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like they'll be dancing that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly it can't get (begin ital)any(end ital) easier for
Pepperdine, which crushed overmatched Loyola Marymount 83-49 in a
first-round victory at Santa Clara's Torso Pavilion. But if the
Waves (23-7) can play at the same level through Monday, it's hard
to imagine any other team in the conference wresting the title away
from the No. 1 seed.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament champion gets an automatic bid to the NCAA
Tournament. Pepperdine, the regular-season conference champion,
plays Santa Clara or San Francisco tonight in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves' next opponent better hope it's more effective than
LMU, which had nothing Saturday despite playing for lame-duck coach
Charles Bradley, who resigned two weeks ago but stuck around for
the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lions (2-26) were hoping to keep Bradley employed a
little while longer, they sure didn't play like it. In fact,
Bradley could have started his job search about five minutes into
the first half. That's when Pepperdine opened an 18-2 lead to get
the rout started.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Armstrong led the way with 17 points, including three
3-pointers on 3-of-4 shooting. Nick Sheppard and David Lalazarian
had 12 points apiece. Sheppard, playing one of his best games this
season, also had seven rebounds in only 14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Loyola got 21 points from Pablo Machado and 10 each from Rupert
McClendon and Curtis Slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get to them early, be aggressive and just be on
top of our game,'' said Armstrong. ``And that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of their game? The Waves took it to new heights,
especially in a scintillating first half in which they shot 57.9
percent from the field (22 of 38), hit five 3-pointers,
outrebounded LMU 22-14, forced 10 turnovers and held the Lions to
28.6 percent shooting (8 of 28) to take a 53-24 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine, which struggled to a 77-65 victory over LMU the last
time the teams met, had no trouble this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played very unselfishly, we made the extra pass - there
were four different times in transition when someone had a layup,
but they passed it to someone else,'' Pepperdine coach Jan van
Breda Kolff said. ``When you do that, it's a team that's cohesive,
a team that knows what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The ease with which Pepperdine took care of LMU allowed van
Breda Kolff to substitute freely. The Waves need two more wins
today and Monday to win the tournament, so any chance to rest
players is welcomed. No Pepperdine starter played more then 18
minutes, and reserve Al Minihan (22 minutes) played the most of
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff didn't want anyone to play !ital!that!off! much,
but backup center Cedric Suitt went down in the second half with a
hyperextended knee, forcing van Breda Kolff to change his plan.
Suitt, who had seven points, said he should be fine by today.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-point margin of victory was the second biggest in
Pepperdine-LMU history. The Waves beat the Lions 92-57 in 1962-63.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, LMU brought this trouncing on itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're our crosstown rival, we have a history and they played
us tough in their place the last time we played,'' Tezale Archie
said. ``That was enough motivation right there. We had to come in
and keep our cool. We knew it would be a war.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, a very one-sided war.
</P>
</TEXT>
