<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-KANSAS-ST.-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' KELLY BECOMES SHOOTING STAR IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ Throughout his career, Darren Kelly's shot has
been the subject of fairly animated conversation. Texas coach Rick
Barnes recalled that the first time he saw it, the result was three
air balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're guarding him, it looks like it's not going in, but
it does,'' said Texas teammate Gabe Muoneke, who has seen a lot of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Last night it went in almost continually, as Kelly popped in 33
points to lead the Longhorns (22-7, 13-3 Big 12) to a 99-70 victory
over Kansas State (9-18, 2-14) in the regular-season finale.
Coupled with Oklahoma's victory over Oklahoma State, the victory
gives Texas the second seed position for the conference tournament,
which opens Thursday in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ugly, but it drops,'' Kelly said. ``And when it does,
it's pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke, who added 27 points, said he wasn't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Darren is, he started off the season pretty
slow,'' Muoneke said. ``But tonight he was making the same shots I
watched him make all summer ... a little fadeaway, and a floater. I
don't know how he does it, but when it starts, I just say, `OK,
Darren.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything _ except for a first-half air ball _ was OK
for Kelly, loudly supported by several old teammates from his days
at Brown Mackie (Junior) College in nearby Salina, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like I couldn't miss,'' said Kelly, who hit 13 of
17 shots from the field, including 6 of 8 3-point attempts. ``After
the air ball, coach left me in, and they left me open, so I figured
he wanted me to shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both teams had foul trouble in the first half, Barnes
said he was pleased with the tuneup for the tournament _ especially
since Chris Mihm spent much of his time on the bench with foul
trouble. He still managed 17 points and seven rebounds in 23
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked some of the things we did,'' Barnes said. ``We stayed
poised and calm even when they made a run. But the main thing was,
this is the first time we won by playing a big lineup without Chris
in there. Gabe and Chris Owens and William Wyatt really played
well, and I was impressed with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he also felt better about the shape of the team at
this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I think we were just happy to win the \RBig 12\S
title, and we were tired,'' he said. ``We're a much different team
physically this time around, and I think we're feeling good.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke agreed, saying, ``Last year at this point we were worn
out. This year, we have much greater depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Shooting 58 percent, the Longhorns put up a season-high point
total, the most by a Texas team since UT scored 105 against
Nebraska in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an idea people have, that we can't win without a big
game from Mihm,'' Kelly said. ``But we have a lot of offensive
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kelly's shot, Barnes said, ``No, I never tried to change
it. You can't change that thing.''  &LR; tagtop:Whit Canning, (817)
390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
