<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-04 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-EWING-ART-NYT &LR;      03-04 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-EWING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A EWING FAN FROM THE VERY BEGINNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Philip Dine is a Washington correspondent for the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch.) 
(mk) 
 By PHILIP DINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By early afternoon, when the high school basketball players from
Cambridge Rindge and Latin School came over to practice at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology gym back in the late 1970s,
the noontime pickup games of MIT grad students, research
assistants, faculty members and employees would be winding down.
</P>
<P>
   The egghead reputation of the place notwithstanding, those were
surprisingly competitive contests, with some pretty talented and
driven players spurred by the nature of the games: First to six
baskets played on, while the losers sat until their next turn.
Sometimes you wouldn't get another shot before you had to head back
to class or desk.
</P>
<P>
   But for me, win or lose, the real lure was the chance to walk
over to the court next to the one we played on, where the high
school kids were taking warm-up shots before their practice began
in earnest. Inevitably, I'd approach the tallest player, the one I
was sure was destined for eventual stardom, and ask to go
one-on-one for a minute or two.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have been terribly exciting for him, to guard this
guy a dozen years older and 14 inches shorter, and so I was upfront
about my reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick,'' I told him the first time, ``you're going to be a
great player someday, and I'd love to tell my children I scored on
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, I never did. Day after day, he'd block my best
shot, no matter now many fakes I gave him; slap the ball off my leg
out of bounds, or simply force me into an awkward attempt that had
no chance. When he felt so inclined, he'd just catch my jump shot
and look at me.
</P>
<P>
   Still, good-naturedly, Patrick Ewing, all of 15 or 16, day after
day accepted my polite challenge.
</P>
<P>
   So I watched with some pride in subsequent years as he led
Georgetown University to the national championship. I also cringed
at times, as he was subjected to racist haranguing in Boston
arenas, the soft-spoken son of immigrants called all kinds of names
because of his supposedly suspect language skills. Actually quite
bright, he was too dignified to respond in kind.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as a native New Yorker, I was beyond thrilled when he
became a Knick. And I felt pride as he soon joined that tier of
great centers, just below Russell and Chamberlain and Jabbar, that
includes players the caliber of Reed and Cowens, Unseld and
Thurmond, Olajuwon and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, on a trip back to New York, I secured a game
pass from Knick management that admitted me to the locker room.
With some trepidation, I approached Ewing, by then a worldwide
basketball figure, and inquired whether he remembered the days on
the MIT court and my futile efforts to score a basket on him. After
a moment's reflection, he softly said, ``I think I do,'' and smiled
broadly, though I'm sure he was just being polite.
</P>
<P>
   So I was dismayed that after years and years as the bulwark of
the Knicks, Ewing was feeling unappreciated recently. Indeed, he
may well have been _ by his teammates, by the media and even by
many fans. As a result, he seemingly wanted out.
</P>
<P>
   This was unfortunate and unfair, and not just because Patrick
Ewing probably has more class and more accomplishments than any
dozen of his critics. As he is once again demonstrating, he remains
a vital part of the team; observers who say the Knicks are better
off as a fast-break team ignore that running requires a man in the
middle who can secure the rebound or, better yet, ignite a break
with a blocked shot. They also forget that playoff basketball is
often half-court basketball.
</P>
<P>
   As a suffering Knick fan from the early 1960s on, I would assert
that Patrick Ewing is the most important player in franchise
history. Almost single-handedly, he has kept the team competitive
from one year to the next, as the players _ and coaches _ around
him changed.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Knick history is defined by ineptness and no-name
players, with even the team's announcers of the mid-1960s, for
instance, having trouble articulating the movement of the ball from
Butler to Butcher to Buckner to Budd. The brief shining moment of
the late '60s and early '70s was stitched together by a coterie of
players _ the Fraziers and Reeds and DeBusscheres, the Monroes and
Barnetts and Bradleys and, of course, Holzmans. Ewing has had to
give this franchise meaning _ through management shifts and lineup
experiments and talent deficits _ for much of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with some speed and versatility around him, he should be
allowed to ride the twilight of his career as far as it takes him _
and the team.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans ought to see Ewing end his career in Madison Square
Garden. I have three little girls who all play basketball.
Actually, the 7-year-old and the 3-year-old do; the 1-year-old only
cradles a little rubber ball, but she's just a year or two away
from trying to get a shot by her father.
</P>
<P>
   I'd love to take them some day soon to the mecca of basketball
and point out the man who never let their daddy score a point, but
who graciously let him try. In the best of worlds, it will be when
Ewing is yelling and driving and scowling in the middle of it all
as the Knicks contend for a championship. They deserve that thrill.
More important, so does he.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
